<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Rave New World</TITLE></TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H1>Equinox: Rave New World</H1><IMG SRC="raving_2.gif" ALIGN=top WIDTH=520 HEIGHT=338><p>An edited transcript of the programme first shown 6 November 1994.</p><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"><p><b> NARRATOR (TOM BAKER):  </b></p><p>Pop culture has met the microchip and a strange new creature has emerged. </p><p><b>GRAHAM BROWN-MARTIN (Managing Director, Electronic Sound and Pictures):  </b></p><p>You've got this convergence of youth culture, technology culture, dance culture, to an extent drug culture as well, merging in the middle. </p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>At the heart of this techno trip is a drug called 'Ecstasy'. </p><p><b>PAUL HARTNOLL (Orbital):  </b></p><p>For thousands of years people have been banging the tribal drum and dancing for 12 hours, and often drugs were involved. Instead of having a few natural herbs that have been shot up your nostril with a blowpipe you're getting pharmaceutical things, and instead of skin over a log for a drum you're getting electrical sounds. </p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>But the pleasures of rave have their price. Ecstasy can kill. </p><p><b>DR JOHN HENRY (Consultant Physician, National Poisons Unit):  </b></p><p>Your blood-clotting goes haywire, your brain begins to dysfunction and your heart can pack up. </p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>But despite dangers known and unknown, this heady mixture of music, drugs and technology has created a brand-new experience. </p><p><b>MATT BLACK (Hex):  </b></p><p>Club culture for the last ten years or so has represented a kind of centre of energy, and it's either get with it or drown really - surf or die. </p><p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>Midsummer in Kent. An airport hanger is being turned into a beach. A quarter of a million pounds' worth of lights will sear eyeballs with lasers and strobes; 100,000 watts of sound will hammer ear-drums. Four thousand of the half million who rave every weekend will arrive here in the next few hours. They have come to dance, and only to dance - some may take drugs, many won't - but there'll be no booze, no chatting up, just non-stop dancing right through the night. </p><p><b>GUY POTTER:  </b></p><p>One evening we went - anxious build-up, all the expectancy, that anxiety element - just hoping builds you up all night. Very excited - and then walking down huge queues, worries and tensions about whether the bouncer's going to find and search you, kick you out, because if you're carrying something . . . We'd been queuing up for about two hours, and we could hear the noise coming out really thundering, and we just went in there and went straight up to the top, to the balcony section, and just glanced down and it was just absolutely incredible. And all of a sudden I was just taken away, I was just completely taken away and I didn't stop dancing all night. </p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>Rave music has virtually no lyrics or melody - it just pounds the ears with a relentless 4/4 rhythm of up to 180 beats a minute from the moment you enter. </p><p><b>JOHN:  </b></p><p>There was just this massive rush of, to me, happiness, because there was a genuine brilliant atmosphere in the club and everybody was basically feeding off each other, where everybody's shouting and screaming and dancing. </p><p><b>GUY POTTER:  </b></p><p>And all of a sudden I just got this huge whoosh running through my body and out of it, sort of thing - don't know where it went - a huge energy force almost. And then going mad again just dancing again and going crazy. </p><p><b>JOHN:  </b></p><p>And this would just build up and the whole crowd would just be like going along with it and becoming more and more frantic until you did actually feel as if you were slightly losing control. </p><p><b>GUY POTTER:  </b></p><p>It hits you and it bombards you and it breaks down any of those barriers between us. The rhythm just grabs hold of you. </p><p><b>JOHN:  </b></p><p>I actually came away from that thinking: I have just had the best night of my life, and I really thought I have never had a better time. It was just the happiest. </p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>The happiness lasts till dawn, and beyond.  </p><p>It all began in 1988, the so-called 'Second Summer of Love'. Late at night cars full of revellers packed normally deserted motorways. They gathered at service stations and waited for a tip-off - the location of an open field or a disused warehouse. It was all kept last-minute to prevent the authorities from getting there first. The police thought they might breach the peace. The kids said they just wanted to dance to a new music called 'Acid House'. </p><p><IMG SRC="raving_3.gif" ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=84 HEIGHT=53>But there was one other crucial element: the new dance music arrived at the same time as a new drug called Ecstasy. Ravers who took the drug enthusiastically reported that it made them feel warm, friendly to strangers and want to dance all night. Ecstasy is a class-A drug, which means dealing carries a maximum life sentence, but tens of thousands of doses, made mainly in illegal Dutch factories, are taken every week, and it's thought at least two million Britons have tried it. </p><BR=CLEAR LEFT><p><IMG SRC="raving_4.gif" ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=76 HEIGHT=56>The step-father of rave's favourite pharmaceutical lives in the hills behind San Francisco. In the early sixties Dr Alexander Shulgin was one of the Dole Chemical Company's top analytical chemists. He turned his skills to making psycho-active drugs. It cost him his job, but turned him into a folk hero to the rave generation. In the mid 1960s he resynthesised an obscure drug that had been patented, but then ignored by the German company E-Merc in 1911. It was called 3,4-methyln-dioxy-n-methyl-amphetamine - MDMA for short. It would later acquire the street name 'Ecstasy'. To Dr Shulgin it was just one of hundreds of mind-altering drugs he concocted and tested on himself and his close friends. </p><BR=CLEAR LEFT><p><b>DR ALEXANDER SHULGIN:  </b></p><p>Actually it's about 40 years ago I started with the drug that's an isolate from a cactus, it's called mescalin, and it was an eight-hour experience. My curiosity was if such a simple molecule can allow me this type of openness, this so-called psychedelic experience, what modifications that molecule will modify, improve, change, redirect that type of introspection, and hence that became my research search.  Ah magnificent. This is my first effort to make the product and I have starting through end product lift . . . </p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>Today in his gardener's shed laboratory Dr Shulgin is synthesising what he hopes will be a brand new psychedelic substance. In the weeks to come he will try it in larger and larger doses and assess whether or not the trips it will produce are worth taking. </p><p><b>DR ALEXANDER SHULGIN:  </b></p><p>(Reading from contemporary notes) 'I rather suspect it will be a visual distortion, maybe colour exaggeration, wiggly lines, moving patterns. I would not expect it to rob you of awareness of your reality and where you are and your relationship with it.' </p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>(Page from notebook) Around 20 years ago Dr Shulgin made these careful notes - the first recorded experience on Ecstasy. </p><p><b>DR ALEXANDER SHULGIN:  </b></p><p>This is one of the early studies on MDMA - I called it n-methyl-MDA at the time - let me get my glasses so I can read - 16 milligrams; that was in 1976. Actually the first trial in that particular guise was on a train trip going from here to Reno. There was a thing called the 'Fun Weekend with the Fun Reno Train', and I went with my late wife and two very good friends. We very often would take our own meals with us and we'd eat on the train with the fun of having our tablecloth and the candelabra and all the pleasures instead of a sandwich. And not at all uncommonly we did then have a Martini or an alcohol as a prelude to dinner, and I asked if they would mind if I tried a chemical in its place. </p><p>Twenty-five milligrams - no effect; 40 - no effect; 60 milligrams - no effect; 81 milligrams - I got a +1: '53-minute smooth shift into a light intoxication, distinct almost early-alcohol-like intoxication'. And I'd find that I would blend very nicely into the gregariousness, into the disinhibition of the cocktail hour, so I looked upon it as a possible low-calorie Martini, or no-calorie Martini. </p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>Dr Shulgin mentioned the drug's effects to a therapist friend. He and others were enthusiastic. They felt its ability to induce friendliness and empathy would be ideal for treating people with relationship problems. Dr Shulgin believes thousands were given the drug, often by qualified practitioners, until it was banned in America in 1985. </p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>At UCLA's Harbor Hospital Dr Charles Grob is head of child and adolescent psychiatry. He believes Ecstasy's reported ability to induce empathy means it still has enormous potential for therapy. After hard lobbying, he has, for the first time, permission from the US government to study the drug's effect on humans. </p><p><b>DR CHARLES GROB (Harbor-UCLA Medical Center):  </b></p><p>There has never been a prospective methodological examination examining what this drug will do on body physiology and on psychological function. </p><p><b>NURSE:  </b></p><p>Going to give your medicine now . . . </p><p>NARRATOR:  The subject is being given 75 milligrams of Ecstasy, about three-quarters of a street tab, the largest ever officially sanctioned dose in the US. </p><p>(Caption: 0 mins)</p><p><b>NURSE:  </b></p><p>The capsule, and then as much water as you can. </p><p>(Caption: 15 mins) </p><p><b>VOLUNTEER:  </b></p><p><IMG SRC="raving_5.gif" ALIGN=left WIDTH=84 HEIGHT=57>Nothing's happening to me yet. </p><BR=CLEAR LEFT><p>(Caption: 45 mins) There's nothing happening. </p><p>(Caption: 1 hr 30 mins) I don't know how to describe it - yeah, something's definitely happening. Something's definitely happening. I'm feeling little shivers running down my spine. It's not that bad (laughs). Whoops, there again - it's coming, it's something that runs up your spine. Is it a girl, is it a spider? No, it's just that little feeling. </p><p>(Caption: 2 hrs) </p><p><b>INTERVIEWER:  </b></p><p>Do you feel more aware? </p><p><b>VOLUNTEER:  </b></p><p>Yeah. I wouldn't like to do like a five times table thing, but I wouldn't mind dancing. </p><p><b>INTERVIEWER:  </b></p><p>Seriously? </p><p><b>VOLUNTEER:  </b></p><p>Yeah, seriously, yeah, I could get into loud music right now, loud music and girls. No, not really - dancing with girls, yeah. </p><p>(Caption: 2 hrs 30 mins) I did the same form earlier (shows questionnaire of emotional responses) but now I admit to being unhappy a little bit more. But it's because it's cool to be unhappy - there's nothing wrong with being unhappy and depressed and things like that. That's the kind of feeling I've got now. That you don't have to think: oh my God, there's something wrong with you if you're sad. It's cool to be sad. </p><p>(Caption: 3 hrs) I could give politicians a couple of tips. Like to meet the Pope right now and share some of my new-found wisdom with him. No, it's just a calm, really just a calm feeling. </p><p><b>DR CHARLES GROB:  </b></p><p>About an hour and a half after you took the medicine you appeared to . . . </p><p><b>VOLUNTEER:  </b></p><p>To peak. </p><p><b>DR CHARLES GROB:  </b></p><p>Very good, excellent, OK, well it's good to hear. You're feeling comfortable? </p><p><b>VOLUNTEER:  </b></p><p>I'm feeling comfortable, yeah, because I'm feeling completely calm, cool, calm and collected as the form said . . . </p><p><b>DR CHARLES GROB:  </b></p><p>From the early reports on the effects of this drug what appeared to be particularly interesting was its suggested capacity to induce an empathic experience. That is very, very unusual, even perhaps unique among drugs. </p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>How does Ecstasy work? What does it do in the brain? Thinking and feeling are the consequences of frantic electrochemical activity in the ten billion or more neurons, or brain cells, that cram our skulls. Ecstasy works mainly on one group of neurons, the serotonin system. The centre of these cells, their nuclei, are clustered at the base of our brains. From here, long, wire-like tendrils, or axons, spread throughout the brain. </p><p><IMG SRC="raving_6.gif" ALIGN=left WIDTH=88 HEIGHT=56>These are real axons seen under a microscope. Something similar to an electric current passes down the length of these axons. When it reaches the end it releases a chemical called a neurotransmitter. This substance jumps from one neuron to the next. They are the brain's internal messengers and it is these that many psycho-active drugs affect. The Ecstasy molecule, because of its shape, forces neurons to spew out large quantities of one particular neurotransmitter, serotonin, or as it's sometimes called, 5HT. </p><BR=CLEAR LEFT><p><b>BILL DEAKIN (Professor of Psychiatry, Manchester University):  </b></p><p>If you imagine my arm as a nerve terminal, when this becomes electrically active it releases 5HT, and what it then does is to suck all the 5HT up again - it sort of ducks it into this cleft, this gap between the terminal and the next cell in the chain, and then sucks it all back up again by a kind of vacuum-cleaner action. What MDMA seems to do is to reverse that sucking-up process and to squirt out 5HT from the nerve terminal. It's like connecting the hoovering pipe to the wrong end of the hoovering machine. It's squirting out rather than sucking up 5HT. </p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>In depressed and aggressive people serotonin release tends to be low. Conversely, when Ecstasy forces out large amounts, it seems to cause euphoria in normal people. But many of Ecstasy's effects are unknown, and with so many people taking it, scientists at the University of San Diego are urgently trying to understand it better. They have compared the effects of Ecstasy and a well-known stimulant, 'Speed', on rats. </p><p>(Laboratory experiment) This box is criss-crossed with invisible infra-red beams. Every movement and gesture of the rat is recorded on a computer. Undrugged animals are very curious. They rear up and explore the box and, being burrowing creatures, they investigate holes with great interest. A computer charts an undrugged rat's movements over 15 minutes. </p><p>Another rat is injected with Speed. Ten minutes later the drug takes effect. The animal becomes far more active. It does what it was doing earlier but only more so. </p><p>Ecstasy, like Speed, also produces hyperactivity, but of a repetitive kind. These rats stop rearing and looking into holes. They seem stripped of all curiosity. The computer shows the effect of the drug. </p><p><b>DR MARTIN PAULUS (Resident in Psychiatry, University of California at San Diego):  </b></p>When you look at the patterns, these patterns are vastly different. In the MDMA-treated animal they keep doing the same thing over and over again. It's just a very, very - almost stereotype pattern of repeatedly hugging the wall and repeatedly rotating. </p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>Scientists have recently begun to speculate why Ecstasy does this. As the drug forces the release of serotonin molecules, they go to several possible landing sites, or receptors. Each of these affects behaviour differently. Stimulating one of them, the 1b receptor, seems to encourage repetitive behaviour. Although Ecstasy stimulates all the receptors, the effect of this one seems to dominate. In this way Ecstasy may have found the part of the brain that makes you want to dance. </p><p><b>DR MARTIN PAULUS:  </b></p><p>One base of the rave phenomenon is the music, is synchronising people's behaviour to an underlying rhythm. When you move to that rhythm you essentially do one type of behaviour - demands on your behaviour are to do the same thing over and over again; you're taking a drug that does the same thing over and over again, and it seems to fit perfectly together. </p><p><b>JOHN:  </b></p><p>Some people listen and say it's boring, but you're getting such intense pleasure from just dancing that . . . everything else would just be second best. </p><p><b>GUY POTTER:  </b></p><p>You sort of lose track and the rhythm is very important in enabling you to lose track because it's something that moves your body, it's not something that you have to concentrate on. You have to click into it and get into the groove and the pattern and relax with it, and that is that incredible feeling. </p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>It may be an incredible feeling, but the pleasures rave and the pleasures of Ecstasy are not without their price. Ecstasy has been found mixed with chalk-dust and adulterated with other drugs like Speed and LSD. Ecstasy can be very dangerous, and it can kill.</p><p><b>DR CHARLES GROB:  </b></p><p>There are features of the way young people are using this particular drug which are very dangerous. Young people often take it with no information or education as to what the effects are, and what they should or should not do, and I'm concerned that young people, often being impulsive, may get themselves into a lot of trouble. </p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>Even when completely pure, Ecstasy has dramatic effects on normal metabolism. It switches off the body's early-warning systems and after hours of vigorous exercise there can be severe overheating. Around 25 die every year. </p><p><b>DR JOHN HENRY:  </b></p><p>(Ravers receiving emergency medical attention) These people's body temperatures were almost at the region of no return. They need urgent treatment to cool them down - mainly to fill them up with fluids and enable the body to start sweating again. If they aren't treated quickly, two or three things can go wrong: the heart may stop pumping properly, the brain can pack up and perhaps worst of all and most dramatic of all, the blood stops clotting and they can bleed from anywhere. </p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>But even more disturbing, there may be long-term dangers which will affect every Ecstasy user. </p><p>This freezer is full of thin slices of squirrel-monkey's brain. Dr George Ricaurte at the Johns Hopkins Hospital in Baltimore has uncovered alarming evidence that Ecstasy destroys brain cells. </p><p><b>DR GEORGE RICAURTE (Assistant Professor of Neurology, Johns Hopkins School of Medicine):  </b></p>(High-magnification images) This is the normal distribution of serotonin axons in the brain of a squirrel-monkey. This is an animal that was exposed to MDMA a year and a half previously, and you see that there's a marked reduction in the number of serotonin immunoreactive axons in the cortex and this effect, this loss of serotonin immunoreactive axons, is evident not only in the cortex but in a number of other regions of the forebrain of the squirrel-monkey. The data we have thus far suggests that MDMA is a highly, highly neuro-toxic substance, that if taken even in just slightly higher amounts than normal dose could result in this kind of brain injury. </p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>In his study Dr Ricaurte gave the squirrel-monkeys the equivalent of just three average street tablets of Ecstasy. </p><p><b>DR GEORGE RICAURTE:  </b></p><p>Whereas alcohol produces its neuro-toxic effect after very high, repeated doses, MDMA has the potential for producing neuro-toxic effects, at least in animals, after a single moderate dose.   OK, well let me tell you a little bit about the lumbar puncture, the so-called spinal tap . . . </p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>We can't examine our own serotonin systems directly, so Dr Ricaurte measured levels of a serotonin by-product called 5HIA in the spinal fluid of people who were regular Ecstasy users. He found that their 5HIA levels were 30 per cent lower than normal - powerful evidence that Ecstasy damages serotonin axons in the human brain. </p><p>But are there long-term effects on behaviour and mood? Dr Ricaurte's study subjects underwent a battery of tests. Serotonin damage should show up as changes in levels of hostility. It did, but not quite as expected. </p><p><b>DR GEORGE RICAURTE:  </b></p><p>We might have predicted, indeed would have predicted, that lower serotonin would result in more impulsiveness and more hostility, but in fact what we found is that people with a history of MDMA exposure, in whom we find low serotonin metabolism, report less impulsivity and less hostility, so the direction of the change was surprising. </p><p><b>INTERVIEWER:  </b></p><p>Many years later, do you feel a more kind of relaxed and less aggressive kind of person? </p><p><b>JULIE BROWN:  </b></p><p>Definitely, definitely, because before I wouldn't take things so personal, I'd be more stressed out about everything, and now I think I can just take a little bit as it is and how it comes. So I think it has helped you calm your life down.</p><p><b>DR GEORGE RICAURTE:  </b></p><p>What we don't know is what will happen to people as they age. We do know that there are changes in serotonin systems  with ageing, and one of the concerns is that if an individual doesn't have the usual amount of back-up systems, if you will, because of prior MDMA injury, if they lack that reserve, with age they may begin experiencing problems that they otherwise would not have. </p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>However good Ecstasy makes you feel, it is dangerous, it has killed. But how necessary is it? Can people listen to pounding, repetitive music without any drugs and still be ecstatic? If there's more to the experience than drugs, what is it? </p><p>The Psychology Department of Leeds University tried to find out for us. It wasn't easy. Most psychological tests would be impractical in the hot and crowded conditions of a club. A solution: an adjective checklist. Four times during the night a group of 45 ravers would be asked to mark on a line how much of a particular emotion they felt. Twenty adjectives, cross-referenced, would give a glimpse into their state of mind. There were three groups: regular ravers on drugs, regulars who weren't, and occasional clubbers as a control. The first finding was unequivocal. </p><p><b>MITCH WATERMAN (Music Psychologist, Leeds University):  </b></p><p>They're having a very good time, they're having a very, very good time. In a sense we can only assess that by their responses to the positive emotions and by comparing those responses to responses to the negative emotions - and they are, in effect, six times more positive than they are negative. </p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>People having fun usually seek out a specific emotion: excitement in a horror film, sociability at a party. But nearly all 30 regular ravers, whether on drugs or not, marked every positive emotion near maximum. They were energetic and absorbed, excited and sociable, happy in every way. </p><p><b>MITCH WATERMAN:  </b></p><p>Emotional responses are consequences - I feel happy when something good happens, but usually I can say what the good thing is. The somewhat odd thing about what seems to be happening to these people at the club is that the response seems to be without content, it's just good, it's just a massive buzz. </p><p><b>JOHN:  </b></p><p>I can never escape as much as I can when I go raving. A really good game of sport - a really good game of squash or something - is good fun, and you forget about everything else, but nothing else compares to the way you lose yourself on a night out raving. </p><p><b>MITCH WATERMAN:  </b></p><p>They don't want things with a lot of content - I don't mean content in the sense that it's empty, I mean content in the sense that they have to think about things and understand in any conscious or aware manner. If the music in these sorts of clubs had lyrics, the responses would be nothing like those that we found. </p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>The most striking conclusion was that there was no difference in the happiness level of regular clubbers on drugs and those who weren't. The real difference was between regular and occasional clubbers. Regulars were nearly twice as happy, whether on drugs or not. So the key to enjoying a rave doesn't seem to be the drugs, but how often you go. You learn to like it, and the way you do that is by going again, and again. But perhaps most surprising of all, reports of feeling sexual, across the board, were low throughout the night. They stayed at a quarter of the level of positive feelings like happiness and fulfilment. </p><p><b>MITCH WATERMAN:  </b></p><p>I'm a bit surprised, [with] this large number of young people in their late teens/early twenties, who are relatively scantily dressed - because after all the environment is very hot, very sweaty, and they're all dancing - how low the reports of them feeling sexual really are. One possibility - and this is actually borne out by talking to ravers - is that losing the tension, losing the anxiety of wanting to find a sexual partner is something that helps them to be more positive still. </p><p><b>JOHN:  </b></p><p>I thought it was much better than the sex I'd had because it was just so much happier, it was with just so many people and it was such a good shared experience that that made it much more powerful. </p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>Rave music is unique in Western pop culture. It has virtually no lyrics or melody. Where did such a sound come from? In the beginning was disco. By the late seventies, as the film Saturday Night Fever spawned imitators up and down the country, disco was already unhip. The new sound was coming from the gay clubs of New York and Chicago. Here soul and funk were blending with synthetic electro-pop from Europe - black dance music was being driven by the relentless rhythm of an electric drum machine to create a brand new beat: 'high energy'. </p><p>Then DJs began to mix records seamlessly, songs didn't stop, the beat went on and on. The turntable became a musical instrument as DJs layered sound from one record over the beat from another. 'House' music was born. </p><p><b>PHIL HARTNOLL (Orbital):  </b></p><p>That evolved almost from the early days of people taking a record and getting even a voice-over on a record and spinning the voice-over. When I used to go to hip-hop warehouse parties, that's all people used to do, you know - getting their own records made of their favourite bits and pieces and shoving it on and spinning it in. British people picked up on it and sort of mutated it and did their own versions of it. </p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>And the British mutation was called 'rave'. </p><p>An abandoned gas-holder in Amsterdam. Fifteen hundred people danced to Europe's top techno band, Orbital. Orbital put the dance rhythms of house music on to the cheap drum machines and synthesisers which hit the high-street music shops in the late eighties. Their first hit, in 1989, was the track 'Chime'. It went straight from a four-track tape-recorder in their bedroom to the top 20. </p><p><b>PAUL HARTNOLL (Orbital):  </b></p><p>Well it was ridiculous, because there I was washing dishes in the pizza restaurant, wanting to talk to the manageress and being a bit nervous about it, and having to go up and say: 'Look, I'm down on the rota for working Wednesday. I can't work Wednesday, I've got to go and do Top of the Pops. I'm sitting there with my Marigolds on saying 'Oh look, I don't think I'll be coming in again after that - I'm going to try and . . .', you know, 'Can I give up work?' And they were going, 'Yeah, yeah - go for it, go for it, we'll get someone else - but if all goes wrong you know you can always have a place back here.' And I think it still stands now. </p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>Orbital are brothers Paul and Phil Harnoll. In their London studio they demonstrate how machines rewrote the rules of Western popular music. For the first time in its history, lyrics, melody and a human voice were stripped away and the music was dominated by what machines were good at: repeating rhythmic patterns that could go on and on. </p><p>Then rhythm met the sampler. Originally intended as a device to electronically recreate the sounds of traditional instruments like violins, techno artists realised they could use the sampler to record any sound they liked and layer it over the rhythm tracks. </p><p>(Music)</p><p><b>PAUL HARTNOLL:  </b></p><p>That was a piece of Equinox once upon a time but that's been sort of messed around with within the sampler to make it sound completely different. </p><p><b>PHIL HARTNOLL:  </b></p><p>You've got the whole 30 seconds of the Equinox thing - you can take out a minuscule little sound and then synthesise that through the sampler; you can then synthesise that sound, so you evolve it into something else. </p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>But techno artists were not satisfied with sound alone. They wanted pictures too. These are images sampled and mutated by a company called Electronic Sound and Pictures (ESP), who are proving that rave generation ideas are viable business. Virgin Interactive Entertainment have just bought a stake worth millions of pounds in the company. </p><p>ESP have brought digital technology to psychedelia. They have written computer software that is inspired by drug experiences. One such programme is 'Flux'. </p><p><b>GRAHAM BROWN-MARTIN (Managing Director, Electronic Sound and Pictures):  </b></p><p>The point of Flux is very simple: basically it turns the CD-ROM drive on the Sega into a CD audio player. As the music plays, it listens to the music and then synchronises graphics of thousands of different patterns and so on. It absolutely in sync with the music. </p><p>I suppose it's come from acquired knowledge, if you like, of the use of substances such as MDMA and - so we understand - when people are under the influence of MDMA, it's not really a hallucinogen, but if they close their eyes, patterns emerge which tend to pulse to the music or are triggered by other lights in a club environment. What we're doing is taking that effect and putting it on to television screens so you can have the same effect without necessarily the use of the drugs. It doesn't have any come-down, it's not addictive, but it's an entertaining experience. </p><p><IMG SRC="raving_8.gif" ALIGN=top WIDTH=88 HEIGHT=56> <IMG SRC="raving_8.gif" ALIGN=top WIDTH=88 HEIGHT=56><IMG SRC="raving_8.gif" ALIGN=top WIDTH=88 HEIGHT=56> <IMG SRC="raving_8.gif" ALIGN=top WIDTH=88 HEIGHT=56> <IMG SRC="raving_8.gif" ALIGN=top WIDTH=88 HEIGHT=56> <p><IMG SRC="raving_9.gif" ALIGN=top WIDTH=88 HEIGHT=62> <IMG SRC="raving_9.gif" ALIGN=top WIDTH=88 HEIGHT=62> <IMG SRC="raving_9.gif" ALIGN=top WIDTH=88 HEIGHT=62> <IMG SRC="raving_9.gif" ALIGN=top WIDTH=88 HEIGHT=62> <IMG SRC="raving_9.gif" ALIGN=top WIDTH=88 HEIGHT=62> <p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>And as rave moves into the mid nineties it has begun to abandon the dance floor. More and more clubs found that after a five-hour dance people needed a room to relax in. Here DJs started playing ambient music, atmospheric sounds with little or no rhythm which people could just sit and listen to. This is the 'chill-out'. Chill-out sounds were followed by chill-out images. Disc-jockeys like Matt Black turned into video jockeys and began projecting surreal collages - a mixture of computer graphics, live TV and home video - on to the walls of the chill-out room. These were images without narrative, designed on digital technology to accompany or replicate drug-induced hallucinations. Ravers would no longer exert their bodies, they would exert their minds instead. </p><p><b>MATT BLACK (Hex):  </b></p><p>Really we want to turn people on and get inside their heads. Computers are just generally used in quite boring ways and we want to use them in more interesting, psychedelic ways. I'm kind of with McKenna and Shulgin on this one to a certain extent. The human race needs to evolve its psychic potentials by all means necessary - whether chemical materials, psychedelic computer input or whatever. I feel it's important. It's a bit like a psychedelic cinema, a bit like a games arcade, a bit like a normal club and a bit like an art gallery. We want to pump up that visual stimulation to the max and that's part of what this is about. </p><p>Also with the interactive element we want to lure people into our world so they can start playing. The best thing is when someone comes up to you and they're off their face and you give them the control to the CDI, and they play with it and they go: 'This is brilliant, man,' and they're still there two hours later playing with it, frantically waggling it away. </p><p>In a way it's like toys for trippers that we're making, and people can either be into it or not be into it. But I can just say, 'Well this is art,' because it is art. This collection of boxes - if I ramp that up that's generating 25 abstract electronic masterpieces a second. It's just an art machine, an abstract, ambient art machine, and that's one level of justification for it. I mean we're quite into - as an end in itself - just chilling out and letting the machines get on with it. That's like a big 'up yours' to all the people who think that they can tell you what art is, and they haven't got a clue - you know, modern art. I'm quite interested in kind of taking this stuff and rubbing it in the faces of people, art critics and so on, who think they know what modern art is - and saying 'No, this is modern art.' </p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>And pushing techno creativity even further are the people behind these images: FSOL, the Future Sound of London. They were acid-house pioneers back in '88. Today, FSOL describe themselves as 'master editors'. They suck the sounds and images that we're all bombarded with into their machines. They mutate and retransmit them. Anything is up for grabs - street sounds can be turned into music, frames of television into art. </p><p><b>GARY COBAIN (The Future Sound of London):  </b></p><p>The whole authorship of sounds changes. We carry on sound that we're receiving. I wasn't the girl screaming in the park, that wasn't me. There's a performance there - she did it; thanks a lot, I took it. Maybe that's why electronic music is around - if you look at the nature of the sounds that we collect, it's basically a very, very cheap way of making yourself look anything but the truth. It's a very clever way of making yourself look like the most cosmopolitan, travelled, interesting, multi-headed individual. </p><p>We're masters of the machine, and that's all, and machines aren't just made with musical intentions in mind these days. There's machines made which are going to revolutionise television. And if the TV companies don't understand it, they don't have to play it, we'll do it exactly the way we've done it with radio: we'll go through small cable-TV stations and work the peripheries until they realise it and they become addicted to it and they have to have it. </p><p>I judge it from the reactions we get. One of them is impotence - if you're becoming impotent then you've been listening to FSOL. We're just some weird illness that seems to be sweeping the country - it comes through TVs, it comes through radios and it comes through vinyl or art, or whatever. We've had stories about guys stopping midway through fornication. Now that sounds like a pretty good reaction to me, because twice I've heard so much about 'this is the perfect fornication music, baby,' you know. Sounds too ordinary to me, sounds like everybody does that, everybody makes the perfect (bleep) music. What, I mean we're not into (bleep), you know. If we can make people impotent, we're doing something. </p><p><b>MC AT WEDDING:  </b></p><p>We are gathered here today, here in this god-forsaken, stinking desert to join this man Frank and this woman Kitty in matrimony, for better or for worse, for richer or for poorer. But not for long. </p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>Rave culture has come a long way from kids dancing in dingy warehouses. Today it boldly proclaims a belief that technology can be psychedelic and even subversive. In America rave has climbed comfortably into bed with the revival of hippie values. Here in a remote part of the Nevada Desert is a gathering of techno hippies, believers in love, peace and the microchip. No longer flower-powered, when they plugged their computers into the Internet they found a new generation who wanted to tune in, log on and chill out. Present to record the event are do-it-yourself broadcasters, a duo called 'Monk'. </p><p><b>MICHAEL LANE (Monk):  </b></p><p>We've lived on the road eight and a half years, and this is kind of like a nomadic village - three days it's here and after three days it's gone. We live on the road, we write about life on the road, we're the pioneers of dashboard publishing. This is the motor home, you want to see it? </p><p><b>JIM CROTTY (Monk):  </b></p><p>This is the Monkmobile. </p><p><b>MICHAEL LANE:  </b></p><p>We do it inside the Monkmobile.</p><p><b>INTERVIEWER:  </b></p><p>What happens in there? </p><p><b>JIM CROTTY:  </b></p><p>What happens in there is we write the magazine. We write, edit, publish, design - everything you need to do for life on the road and for publishing. </p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>This is the climax of tonight's techno pagan festivities: the burning of a neon-stripped wicker man. </p><p><b>MICHAEL LANE:  </b></p><p>We're using satellite phones, we're connecting to the Internet so that people around the world can watch the burning man in real time. </p><p><b>JIM CROTTY:  </b></p><p>On their computers. </p><p><b>MICHAEL LANE:  </b></p><p>It's coming through their computer screen thanks to the cyber monks of Monkmobile magazine. </p><p><b>JIM CROTTY:  </b></p><p>That's right. It means that computers are meeting burning in the desert. It means that people painting themselves with mud are meeting high technology, digital cameras. It means that our way of thinking has evolved over the years and now we're celebrating in the desert and we're plugged in with lights and cameras. </p><p><b>MICHAEL LANE:  </b></p><p>It's a cultural convergence that really you can't name and claim yet, because we're in the middle of it. We'll know what it is when it's over. </p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>There's some way to go. The courier company failed to deliver the satellite phones and Monk were forced to postpone their broadcast on the Internet till the next day. The technology may not always work, but techno hippies are convinced that bit by bit the digital revolution will spread harmony and understanding. </p><p><b>MICHAEL LANE:  </b></p><p>The whole thinking behind Silicon Valley is 'let's create a technology so everybody can use it and everybody can participate', which is why the whole digital revolution is coming out of San Francisco - because if you look at all the events of the history of San Francisco, they're all built on inclusivity. The whole Summer of Love - what is that but an inclusive gathering. What is the beat generation but an inclusive thing? What is gay rights but saying, 'Hey, they're equal to us'? What is the digital revolution? - everybody can play together. And this really represents the high point of that because all the different tribes come together: tribal, technology . . . You could come here because that's what San Francisco is about and this is San Francisco in microcosm, in the desert. </p><p><b>NARRATOR:  </b></p><p>Dawn, and the brave rave on. In the last six years ravers have made melody irrelevant, turned computers into automatic art machines and learnt to be happy without knowing why. The rave new world may be content-free, but where else can you become instant friends with complete strangers? </p><p><b>JOHN:  </b></p><p>We normally create friendships after we've made lots of judgements, but this is being friendly to somebody you don't know and no strings attached - 'I don't care who you are, I'm still going to be as nice as possible, as nice as I can be to you.' And it's just a much better way actually to live. </p><IMG SRC="raving_1.gif" ALIGN=top WIDTH=88 HEIGHT=57><IMG SRC="raving_1.gif" ALIGN=top WIDTH=88 HEIGHT=57><IMG SRC="raving_1.gif" ALIGN=top WIDTH=88 HEIGHT=57><IMG SRC="raving_1.gif" ALIGN=top WIDTH=88 HEIGHT=57><IMG SRC="raving_1.gif" ALIGN=top WIDTH=88 HEIGHT=57><p><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"><p> Published 1994 by  Channel 4 Television, 124 Horseferry Road, London SW1P 2TX</p><p>Produced by Broadcasting Support Services to accompany <b>Equinox: Rave New World</b> (a MacDougall Craig production for Channel 4) first shown on Channel 4 in November 1994</p><p>Editor: Derek Jones</p> <p>Editorial Consultant: Peter Millson</p><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
