<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Wings </TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#124B69" LINK="#166F1A" VLINK="#77422A" ALINK="#FF00FF"><BASEFONT SIZE=4><A NAME="TOP"><DL><DD><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 CELLSPACING=1>	<TR>		<TD VALIGN TOP><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/wings.gif"  ALT="logo" ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0></TD><TD VALIGN TOP><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/eagle.gif"  ALT="eagle" ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0></TD><TD VALIGN TOP><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/watch.gif"  ALT="eagle" ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0></TD><TD VALIGN TOP><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/c4.gif"  ALT="Channel 4" ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0></TD>	</TR></TABLE><DL><DD><P>WHERE DO SWALLOWS spend the winter? Why do some birds sing and others croak? Why would anyone choose to rise at the crack of dawn, travel for miles and spend long, uncomfortable hours waiting for a glimpse of a particular type of bird? <P>With the help of professional and expert amateur ornithologists, <I>Wings</I> sets out to answer these questions, and to help us all to see British birds with new eyes. <P>These pages will build week by week, covering all the items in the series. They also contain links to <A HREF="links.html#001">other bird sites</A> on the Web and details of <A HREF="links.html#002">useful organisations</A>.<P><I>Wings</I> was made in association with the  <A HREF="links.html#003">Royal Society for the Protection of Birds</A>, who have a free information pack for anyone who wants to find out more about birds, birdwatching and the society.<P>A book based on the series, <I>The Wings Guide To British Birds</I> byDominic Couzens (HarperCollins, 12.99), is also available. Produced inassociation with the RSPB and fully illustrated in colour, it coversidentification, habitats, behaviour and flight patterns. It also containsadvice on how to get started, what equipment you need and the best placesto go. <I>The Wings Guide To British Birds</I> is available from all goodbookshops, or write to: Mail Order Dept, HarperCollins Publishers,Westerhill Road, Bishopbriggs, Glasgow G64 2QT.<P><H2><A HREF="wprog1.html">Programme 1: Making Chicks</A></H2><A HREF="wprog1.html#001">Sex and the sand martin </A><BR><A HREF="wprog1.html#002">Not so cuckoo? - fostering chicks</A><BR><A HREF="wprog1.html#003">Feathering the nest - the long-tailed tit</A><BR><A HREF="wprog1.html#004">Nesting instinct - how to encourage birds to nest in your garden</A><P><H2><A HREF="wprog2.html">Programme 2: First birds</A></H2><A HREF="wprog2.html#001">Tough ptarmigans</A><BR><A HREF="wprog2.html#002">Monarch of all surveys - the golden eagle</A><BR><A HREF="wprog2.html#003">Female of the species brighter than male: the dotterel</A><BR><A HREF="wprog2.html#004">Dun but not dull: the dunlin</A><BR><A HREF="wprog2.html#005">Gargling guillemots, guano and gannets</A><P><H2><A HREF="wprog3.html">Programme 3: Comings and goings</A></H2><A HREF="wprog3.html#001">Ringers and warblers</A><BR><A HREF="wprog3.html#002">Amber for red-breast: the stonechat</A><BR><A HREF="wprog3.html#003">Fair fowl: the pink-footed goose</A><BR><A HREF="wprog3.html#004">Sitting duck: the eider</A><BR><P><H2><A HREF="wprog4.html">Programme 4: Bird song and all that jizz</A></H2><A HREF="wprog4.html#001">Retiring virtuoso: the nightingale</A><BR><A HREF="wprog4.html#002">Plangent plagiarist: the great tit</A><BR><A HREF="wprog4.html#003">Knot hard to identify?</A><BR><A HREF="wprog4.html#004">Avocet advocate</A><BR><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/line.gif" BORDER=0></A><P>	<TR>			<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=100><A HREF="links.html"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/links.gif" ALT="Links" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100 BORDER=0></A></TD>						</TR><P><FONT SIZE=-2>Published in 1996 by Channel 4 Television, 124 Horseferry Road, London SW1P 2TX<BR>Produced by Broadcasting Support Services to accompany <I>Wings</I>, first shown on Channel 4 in January 1997.<BR>Editor: Paula Snyder<BR>Consultant editor: Peter Millson<BR>Designer: Broadcasting Support Services<BR>Broadcasting Support Services provides follow-up services for viewers and listeners and runs long-term helplines.	<P></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
