<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Beast of Bardia</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000c42" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00"ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><P><H1><A HREF="bardiahp.html">The Beast of Bardia</A></H1><P><UL>	<LI><A HREF="#001">Origins of the expedition</A>	<LI><A HREF="#002">The search begins</A>	<LI><A HREF="#003">Health hazards</A>	<LI><A HREF="#004">Dawn to dusk</A>	<LI><A HREF="#005">Mammoth task</A>	<LI><A HREF="#006">The village that never forgets</A>	<LI><A HREF="#007">The first sighting</A>	<LI><A HREF="#008">The genetic evidence</A>	<LI><A HREF="#009">Tulahati</A>	<LI><A HREF="#010">Nocturnal visitors</A>	<LI><A HREF="#011">The return of the King</A>	<LI><A HREF="#012">A glimpse of an ancient world</A></UL><P><UL>	<LI><A HREF="#013">Background</A>	<LI><A HREF="#014">Further reading</A>	<LI><A HREF="#015">Links</A></UL><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD><P><A NAME="001"><H3><B>Origins of the expedition</B></H3><DL><DD><P>It all began in 1987, when <A HREF="#cjbs">Colonel JohnBlashford-Snell</A> looked into a tale abouta mysterious creature that was said to be lurking in the jungles of westNepal (see <A HREF="#015">Links</A>).<P>'The local people talked about it as if it was a mammoth,' he says. 'Itwas supposedto be rather like an elephant, with a huge domed head and a vast body, andat night itcame out of the jungle and trampled on their crops and knocked down theirhouses anddid awful damage. And they were complaining like mad about it.<P>'Two years later I was back in London, and a young lady came to see mewho had been ona canoe trip on the Kanali River. And going down the river in this canoe ofhers, with acouple of Nepalese friends, they suddenly heard a crashing noise and out ofthe junglecame this extraordinary elephant-like creature.<P>'There were various theories about what this thing could be. But onething that everyonewas certain about was that we should go and look for it and try and findout definitely whatit was. And that was what started me on this idea of organising anexpedition to investigatethis monster of the Kanali Valley - or the "Beast of Bardia", as it was nowbeing called bythe locals.'<P>For John Blashford-Snell, the search for the giant elephants became anobsession. He'sseen them three times and named the largest animal Raja Gaj - 'King'. RajaGaj has a devotedcompanion, Kansha, a huge male like himself, but not quite as tall.Blashford-Snell wasdetermined to find out what the beasts of Bardia really are - giantelephants, mammoths,or something more mysterious.</DL></DD><P><A NAME="002"><H3><B>The search begins</B></H3><DL><DD><P>Ten <A HREF="#vol">volunteers</A> have joined the expedition to locateand identify the mysterious creature.<A HREF="#dal">Dr Adrian Lister</A> is in charge of the scientific study.An expert on the mammoth, his searchfor the giants leads to a remote pocket of dense jungle on the border withIndia.<P>The idea that a prehistoric monster could remain undiscovered until nowis extraordinary.But until 40 years ago, the Nepalese plains were covered with thick forest.<P>'So what we're left with now,' says Lister, 'is a series of islands ofremaining foresthabitat which are essentially the national parks. The one in Bardia thatwe're going tostudy is now the largest.'<P>For three days the party follow the Kaligandaki River, driven everdeeper to the southby the trail of the lost giants. At base camp 1, they find the firstconcrete evidence. Thedecaying palace at this spot was only recently rediscovered. It was built100 years ago bya prince for his bride. When she died, the building became her tomb. Giantelephants, theysay, carried the marble and stone to build the palace. And it took 13,000Nepalese toconstruct a path through the jungle to reach it.<P>The party leaves the decaying palace with its secrets. From here, ittakes them two daystravelling further west to reach Bardia. The party's new location on the bankof the Kanaliriver is called the Special Camp. It's been set up especially for JohnBlashford-Snell'steam, and will be their home for the next ten days.<P>There are five female elephants to take the party out every day, and inbetween, it'sa full-time job keeping the elephants fed. As well as giving them greenery,their keepershave their work cut out making elephant sandwiches - each animal eats 100packages of grassand meal every day.</DL></DD><P><A NAME="003"><H3><B>Health hazards</B></H3><DL><DD><P>Blashford-Snell briefs the party on the dangers ahead.<P>'I do want people to remember that we are dealing with dangerousanimals,' he says.'These are wild animals. The largest animal in the world on four feet isthe elephant,and these are wild elephants. Although we are riding on 'domestic' elephants,the wildones out there are very different, and they can be extremely hazardous toyour health.<P>'I remember some years ago being woken up by Pradeep, and lo and behold,Raja Gajhad walked in, broken [a domestic elephant's] chain, and led her away intothe jungle.And we went chasing after her, found what we thought was her. It turned outto be him.<I>We</I> then got chased, and we had a very exciting night being chasedaround andaround the jungle by Raja Gaj, which is not something I recommend.<P>'But if that happens, the place that you've got to go is the beach. Thebeach is fullof boulders - elephants don't like walking - let alone running - onboulders. If it's atiger, on the other hand, of course you're dealing with a different animal.Tigers loverunning over the beaches, and that's more of a problem.'<P>Adrian Lister needs to record every observation in detail. The creatureshave hugemounds or humps on their heads. They are said to be enormous - over 11 feet(335 cm)tall. That's bigger than any Asian elephant ever recorded.<P>'Obviously one can't just walk up to an 11-foot-high elephant with atape measure andask to measure it head,' Lister says, briefing the volunteers. 'So we'regoing to use aphotographic method. In particular I'm hoping to get photographs of each ofthe male animals,exactly square on to the side, and from the photograph it would then bepossible to takethe proportions of the head relative to the size of the animal, and so on.So please dotake as many pictures as you can.'</DL></DD><P><A NAME="004"><H3><B>Dawn to dusk</B></H3><DL><DD><P>Bardia is one of the three national parks in Nepal - 1000 squarekilometres criss-crossedby the Kanali River. The search begins at dawn. Each elephant carries awildlife expert,who stands at the rear, as well as the driver and three or four passengers.<P>The expedition is dependent on the skills of Ramdin and Pradeep. Withouttheir expertiseas trackers, the others would be lost. For them 'JBS Special Camp' is onemore chance to seeRaja Gaj, a creature whose mysterious appearances and disappearances haslent him a mysticalquality.<P>From his position on the back of the elephant, Ramdin acts as scout. Onthe way down tothe river, he spots a rare Asian one-horned rhino. The only creature therhino won't attack isthe elephant, so the party stands its ground. The rhino moves on.<P>By 9 am the sun is up, and the party is nearing its destination - anisland. Its memberskeep in touch through a series of calls - in the jungle, eye contact willbe impossible.<P>There is a pattern to each day - start at dawn, break at midday, back tothe camp at dusk.<P>'What we're looking for is signs of recent passage in the long grass,'Blashford-Snell explains.'You can see that the grass has flattened down, and of course you see signswhere they've beenfeeding - broken branches and so on.'<P>But the expedition gets off to a disappointing start - and every daycounts.<P>'I think he's probably lurking north of here,' says Blashford-Snell. 'Hecould appearanywhere. He's out there somewhere, but there are a thousand squarekilometres of jungle,and it's sort of like looking for a golf ball in a bit of rough - a rather largegolf ball,but there's a hell of a large piece of rough!'</DL></DD><P><A NAME="005"><H3><B>Mammoth task</B></H3><DL><DD><P>One of the tasks for the expedition is to identify every wild elephantin the area.Sue Hilliard is a valuable member of the team. She's a fingerprint expert -a member ofthe Merseyside Police Force.<P>'I was brought along to help identify the wild elephants by their earshapes,' sheexplains, 'which as you can see are quite ragged. And I suppose the factthat I've donea bit of fingerprint work and identifying helps.'<P>It's likely that the giant elephants the expedition is looking for areclosely relatedto Asian elephants. But whether they are a different species or asub-species, or even akind of prehistoric elephant, are key questions. Adrian Lister started hisresearch bysimply comparing the head shape of Raja Gaj with that of the mammoth.<P>'When he was first seen,' says Lister, people got pictures in side-viewof him, andin side-view he's got a very high, domed head and a rather sloping back,which actuallycorresponds to what mammoths look like, as far as we know from the cavepaintings inFrance and the frozen carcasses from Siberia. So there's a superficialresemblance thereto a mammoth, which gave some people the idea there might be a populationof mammothsstill living in Nepal.<P>On closer examination, though, we can see that that similarity <I>is</I>somewhatsuperficial, because although in side view his very high head-bump looksrathermammoth-like, when we see him from the front, you can see that that domeactually isa double dome - it comprises two bumps - and that is quite different fromthe mammoth.The mammoth does have a very high skull, but we know from the fossil skullsof themammoth that it was just a single dome. But it's not a surprisingcomparison thatpeople make, bearing in mind also the very large size of Raja Gaj.'</DL></DD><P><A NAME="006"><H3><B>The village that never forgets</B></H3><DL><DD><P>By the third day, there have been no sightings of any of the wildelephants. It'stime to change tactics. The party splits up. Lister is to continue thesearch in thejungle, while Blashford-Snell does some local reconnaissance, visiting thesettlementjust outside the park. Villagers here watch out for Raja Gaj all yearround. If anyoneknows where he is, they do. People here venerate the <I>hati</I>, theelephant, as a god,recognising his power. But they also fear him.<P>The villagers tell Blashford-Snell about one particular elephant - thebiggest of all- that gets very angry, and which has been coming to the village more andmore, breakinginto dwellings looking for food. Two people have died as a result.<P>It's clear that these village people are terrified of the beast ofBardia. The partyreturns to camp in a sombre mood, unaware that Lister's team is heading foran extraordinary meeting.</DL></DD><P><A NAME="007"><H3><B>The first sighting</B></H3><DL><DD><P>Lister has been joined by Ramdin. They're trying the elephants'favourite haunton the far side of the park.<P>After a while they spot the first wild elephant. Not Raja Gaj, orKansha, but anaggressive young bull. The older males could be just out of sight.<P>Collecting dung samples from a wild elephant in a fractious mood isrisky. Butif Lister is to prove that these animals are genetically distinct, he needsDNAfrom the living cells of the animal. Fortunately the elephant moves off andhe'sable to get his sample.<P>Then Ramdin returns with some dramatic news. He's found a 20-inchfootprint.This could be what they're looking for . . .<P>The rest of the party have long since returned to camp. As night falls,Blashford-Snell is concerned that Lister's group is still in the jungle, waybeyond the six o'clock curfew. But finally they return, and Lister can hardlywait to tell his story.<P>'We've just seen something very exciting . . . the big one was Raja Gaj, andthere was one of the smaller ones, and the two elephants approached eachother,head to head . . . sort of feeling each other's mouths with their trunks. Itstarted off very gently, just moving, then just starting to jostle a bit, [theother one] starting to put his tusks in a little bit. And then Raja Gaj pushedthe other one back . . . I think it was Bada Gaj. He was a couple of feetsmallerthan Raja Gaj . . . He may be the next leader of the gang.'<P>What Lister has seen is very rare - Blashford-Snell doesn't know ofanyone elsewho has seen this behaviour in Asian elephants. The only disappointment isthat Listerwas unable to get any pictures because it was getting dark.<P>However, the next day there's no sign of the elephants. Despite thepressure of time,Blashford-Snell keeps his nerve. Experience of Raja Gaj helps.<P>'It's amazing that an animal weighing seven tons or so can disappear offthe faceof the earth,' he says. 'But in this huge forest that's quite possible, andhe canhide in deep shadow, or behind some trees, and you can walk right past him.I oncepassed him 30 feet away. So he's bound to be in here somewhere. I don'tthink he'llhave walked off the reserve, otherwise the villagers would tell us. But themainthing is to find out where the old man's gone, because he is the real target.'</DL></DD><P><A NAME="001"><H3><B>The genetic evidence</B></H3><DL><DD><P>All of the expedition's five domestic elephants are female, called Kalior Lady.They're important for Adrian Lister - he can use them as a control groupagainstwhich to compare the DNA of the giants for genetic differences.<P>'Any part of the animal has got DNA,' he explains, '- any living part of theanimal. So we collect dung from the wild ones because that's the only thingthat'savailable to us. But since these [domestic] animals are staying here, andstandingin front of us, and they're tame, I could take saliva from their mouth, Ican takea little skin-scrape. There's a hair just plucked cleanly out - it's got a fewcells at the bottom which are called the follicle, and they'll have DNA. So I'mjust putting a few hairs of the elephant in alcohol, and we'll get the DNAout ofthose. I could have taken dung, but it's messier - and I don't like thisreputationof being Dr Dung or Professor Poop as some people know me. So I don't onlydo that!'<P>Lister's analysis clarifies what the giant elephants might be -something evenmore ancient than the last mammoths to live on this planet.<P>'Raja Gaj and his friends in this area are clearly part of the Asianelephantspecies - <I>Elephas maximus</I> is the Latin name - but also clearly anunusualpopulation within that species. One very interesting thing which I cameacross isthat there are some skulls of fossil relatives of the Asian elephant foundin thisarea, in the Suwalik hills, which are believed to be the direct ancestorsof theliving Asian elephants. These fossils are about two million years old, andthey'vebeen called <I>Elephas hysudricus</I>. And if you compare a reconstruction of<I>Elephas hysudricus</I> with Raja Gaj, there is a striking resemblance.<P>'So it seems to me that although Raja Gaj is not a mammoth, he mayactually berather similar to another fossil elephant species - a kind of throwback to hisancestor of about two million years ago. I'm not suggesting that <I>Elephashysudricus</I> has been living unchanged in this part of Nepal for the lasttwo million years. I think it's more likely that a rather ancient geneticcombination has been thrown up again, perhaps due to isolation in this area.It's quite an unusual finding.'</DL></DD><P><A NAME="009"><H3><B>Tulahati</B></H3><DL><DD><P><I>Elephas hysudricus</I>: a creature that co-existed with the mammoth.In anattempt to gather more DNA and prove his theory, Lister travelled evenfurther west,to the White Grass Plains, Sukila Phanta. These plains are home for thelast remainingherd of rare swamp deer. Lister has news that giant elephants have been seenhere,too. The most legendary of these was Tulahati, reported to be as big asRaja Gaj.<P>A first encounter with Tulahati 35 years ago changed the life of theonly manto film him, Peter Burn.<P>'I had a client down in the White Grass Plains, and we were waiting fortiger,'Burn recalls. 'We were sitting in an open jeep, and this elephant came up,and to meit was just another elephant. Normally Asian elephants, as soon as theysense a personor something like a jeep, they will stop, they will look, they will goaway. And thischap came up and stood there and looked at us. He actually stood there andlooked atus for three or four minutes, close up. It was extremely unusual for anelephant.[He was] awfully muscular, with short thick tusks, and a very heavy neck,and then,faintly at that time, the beginning of these two enormous lobes on the topof the head.So he looked different from other elephants. In fact he looked somethinglike Raja Gaj,the elephant of Bardia.<P>'And sadly, in March of 1994, he put his foot on a bomb. It blew hisfoot off,and he walked to the forest pool and lay down, and over the course of fouror fivedays died beside the pool. We were all upset about it, because of all theelephantsthat this had to happen to, it had to happen to this magnificent animal,Tulahati.'<P>The tragic death of Tulahati makes the need to identify these creatureseven more urgent.<P>Peter Burn locates the grave of a large bull elephant, but the crumblingbones itcontains provide no clue to the origin of the giants. A complete skull isneeded tomake comparisons. It's a bitter disappointment.</DL></DD><P><A NAME="010"><H3><B>Nocturnal visitors</B></H3><DL><DD><P>Back in Bardia, the days are ticking by. But then one night the camp hasvisitors.This time the party manages to follow the giant elephants, but their way isblockedby the young male earlier seen testing his strength against Raja Gaj. Againthisanimal is in an aggressive mood. Adrian Lister gives an account of whathappened next:<P>'We just encountered a mock charge by a wild elephant, which was quiteexciting.We were just watching him, and he got a little bit irritable at ourpresence andsuddenly came towards us. My heart rate certainly went up a bit. But ourelephantsand their drivers know what to do, and we moved out of the way. When hecame at usagain, we moved a bit further, and we were out of danger. But that was quiteanexciting moment.'<P>Bada Gaj, a new giant in Bardia, was determined to stand guard for theKing,Raja Gaj.</DL></DD><P><A NAME="011"><H3><B>The return of the King</B></H3><DL><DD><P>The prospects don't seem good. Even Pradeep is anxious about findingRaja Gajagain, and time is running out.<P>Elephants like to travel by road. Following a hunch, Pradeep and Ramdinsetout to discover whether Raja Gaj had bypassed the camp completely. Theyfindsome fresh elephant dung, and then a footprint.<P>The height of an elephant is calculated by multiplying the footprintmeasurementby six. With a footprint of 22 inches (55 cm), Raja Gaj is 11 foot (335 cm)to theshoulder - the largest Asian elephant in the world.<P>It turns out that Pradeep was right. Raja Gaj has outsmarted the party.He'scircled the camp, and may be heading right of out the area. Without Raja Gaj,Adrian's research would be incomplete.<P>At operational headquarters, Blashford-Snell is working on strategy withGary,the camp doctor.<P>'I have a feeling he'll move where there's more water, being the dryseason,'he says. 'I think what we'll find is that he'll come down to the Babai, wherethere is water, because elephants have to bathe every day, and they drink ahell of a lot.<P>'In the middle of a study it's rather a shame when your prime suspectsuddenlywalks off stage,' he adds. 'And that's what he's done.'<P>The search party leaves for the Babai valley. But the domestic elephantsremain.It's their first real break. Lister begins to reconcile dung and hair samplesforDNA analysis.<P>On the basis of the anatomy of the animals, traditionally it's been thoughtthat the Asian elephant is more closely related to the mammoth than is theAfricanelephant. There are several labs around the world working on this theory, andLister hopes his samples will contribute to the study.<P>For those who didn't go off with Blashford-Snell, it's a welcome break ina fairly relentless research programme. But it's all too soon over. Thereportsare that Raja Gaj, having reached Dunwatel and frightened the life out of thearmy post, has turned round and is heading back towards the camp.<P>It's good news, but the expedition is down to its last 24 hours. Then theyspot Kansha - giant number two - and another large bull. Once again the wayisblocked, this time by Kansha. For a while they are unsure of the identityof thesecond bull, but to everyone's excitement, it turns out to be Raja Gaj.</DL></DD><P><A NAME="012"><H3><B>A glimpse of an ancient world</B></H3><DL><DD><P>Two months later, the first DNA analysis at the University of London labconfirms Adrian Lister's suspicions: the elephants of Bardia are notmammoths,but are clearly within the Asian elephant group. What's more, the analysissuggeststhat his more radical guess may be right: the giants of Bardia may be athrowback tosomething more ancient than the mammoths, the result of unusual geneticcombinationsthrown up by isolation and in-breeding.<P>But it's Lister's work on measurement that provides the evidence JohnBlashford-Snellhas been waiting for. By comparing the Nepalese giants with otherelephants, and plottingthe height of their cranial humps, Lister proves that they do form a uniquegroup.<P>'We've got probably the largest body size of Asian elephant anywhere inthe world,'he says, 'including certainly the biggest bull now living, in Raja Gaj. Andsomethingin that area - whether it's the environment or the genetics or acombination of the two,we're not quite sure - something has produced this special kind of Asianelephant of avery large size . . . And a feature which is rare in other populations -the unusuallyhigh head dome - is common here. There is something very special aboutthem.'<P>Raja Gaj: a king with mysterious origins; a giant creature emerging fromour ancientpast, propelled into this century by a unique set of circumstances. Ourglimpse into aworld two million years old.<A NAME="vol"></DL></DD><P><A NAME="013"><H3><B>Background</B></H3><DL><DD><P>This expedition was organised by<A HREF="#disc">Discovery Expeditions</A> with the<A HREF="#ses">Scientific Exploration Society</A>, and led by<A HREF="#cjbs">Colonel John Blashford-Snell</A> and<A HREF="#dal">Dr Adrian Lister</A>.<P><A NAME="disc"><H4><B>Discovery Expeditions</B></H4><P>Discovery Expeditions provide opportunities for adventurous holidayscombined withpractical involvement in environmental issues. Participants have helped,for example, to observe the social behaviour of elephants, talk tonomadic people abouttheir conflictswith conservation efforts, collect data on snow leopards in Mongolia andinvestigate theeffects of gold mining on Amerindian communities in South America.<P>For further details, contact:<P><B>Discovery Expeditions</B><BR>Park House<BR>Chicksgrove<BR>Tisbury<BR>Wiltshire SP3 6NA<BR>Tel: 01722 716430<BR>Fax: 01722 716963<BR>E-mail: <AHREF="mailto:106043.2527@compuserve.com">106043.2527@compuserve.com</A><BR><P><A NAME="ses"><B>The Scientific Exploration Society</B><P>The Scientific Exploration Society aims to encouragescientific explorationworldwide, and mounts global expeditions on land and sea. It is especiallyinterested inbiological research, conservation, community and medical aid in developingcountries,education, environmental protection and the welfare of wildlife andanimals. A newsletter,<I>SESAME</I>, is regularly circulated to all members.<P>Members can be of any age or nationality. They divide into two categories:those whohelp, or take part in projects, and those who display a keen interest inthe society'sactivities mainly from an armchair. The society prefers that members shouldbe proposedand seconded by existing members.<P>Through Executive Expeditions the society also provides opportunitiesfor non-members to assist in projects in remote parts of the globe.Participants are able-bodied men and women who apply to support a projectphysically and financially.<P>For further information contact:<P><B>The Scientific Exploration Society</B><BR>Expedition Base<BR>Motcombe<BR>Shaftesbury<BR>Dorset SP7 9PB<BR>General enquiries:<BR>Tel: 01747 853353 <BR>Fax: 01747 851351<BR>Executive Expeditions:<BR>Tel: 01747 854898<BR>Fax: 01747  851351<BR><P><IMG SRC="blashford.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0"><A NAME="cjbs"><B>Colonel John Blashford-Snell</B><P>In 1968 Emperor Haile Selassie of Ethiopia invited the British Army tosend a team to makethe first descent of the Blue Nile. Captain John Blashford-Snellof the RoyalEngineers was commissioned to select, train and lead the 60-strong party.The success ofthis immense expedition led to even tougher assignments, such as the firstvehicle crossingof the complete Darien Gap in 1971-2 and, in 1974-5, the navigation ofalmost all 2,700 milesof the great Zaire River.<P>John Blashford-Snell has become one of the world's most renowned and highlyrespected explorers,and his innovative method of negotiating white water in inflatable boatshas been adopted asa world-wide sport.<BR CLEAR=LEFT><P>In 1969, following the success of the Blue Nile expedition,Blashford-Snell and hiscolleagues formed the <A HREF="#ses">Scientific Exploration Society</A>(SES) to foster andencourage scientificexploration worldwide. The SES became the parent body for severalworldwide ventures, with thesupport and involvement of HRH The Prince of Wales.<P>In 1991, Blashford-Snell set up <A HREF="#disc">DiscoveryExpeditions</A>. From his base in Dorset he continuesto organise and lead many expeditions, takingpeople of all ages andwalks of life to remote areas of the world.<P><IMG SRC="lister.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0"><A NAME="dal"><B>Dr Adrian Lister</B><P>Dr Adrian Lister is Lecturer in Biology at University College London andone of theworld's leading experts on mammoths and the evolution of elephants. He hasstudiedfossil andmodern mammal material at over 80 museums and institutes in 14 countries,and hasexcavated at many fossil sites, including the Condover mammoth site inShropshire.<P>Adrian Lister has also broadcast widely in Britain and the UnitedStates, and as well asbeingscientific co-ordinator for the Bardia elephant project, has served asscientificadviser for several major exhibitions on mammoths and the ice age, and fora BBCHorizon / NBC Nova television production called <I>The Last Mammoths</I>.<BR CLEAR=LEFT></DL></DD><P><A NAME="014"><H3><B>Further reading</B></H3><DL><DD><P><I>Mammoth Hunt</I>, John Blashford-Snell's account of the search forthe giant elephants of west Nepal, is to be published in September byHarperCollins.<P>Adrian Lister's book <I>Mammoths</I>, co-authored with Paul Bahn, ispublished by Boxtrec (1995).<P>Other books by John Blashford-Snell:<P><I>Weapons and Tactics</I> (with Tom Wintringham)<BR><I>Expeditions, the Experts' Way</I> (with Alistair Ballantine)<BR><I>Where the Trails Run Out</I><BR><I>In the Steps of Stanley</I><BR><I>A Taste for Adventure</I><BR><I>In the Wake of Drake</I> (with Mike Cable)<BR><I>Operation Drake</I> (with Mike Cable)<BR><P><I>Mysteries: Encounters with the Unexplained</I><BR><I>Operation Raleigh: The Start of an Adventure</I><BR><I>Operation Raleigh: Adventure Challenge</I> (with Ann Tweedy)<BR><I>Operation Raleigh: Adventure Unlimited</I> (with Ann Tweedy)<BR><I>Something Lost Behind the Ranges</I> (autobiography)<BR></DL></DD><P><A NAME="015"><H3><B>Links</B></H3><DL><DD><P><IMG SRC="elemed.gif" ALIGN=left><A HREF="http://www.princeton.edu/~yyodin/chang/">Friends of the AsianElephant</A>:since its launch three years ago this organisation has provided medicaltreatment for a number of neglected elephants. It also runs a scheme forrelocating 'domestic' elephants to their natural habitat. It is based inThailand.<BR CLEAR=left><P><A HREF="http://www.cftw.org.uk../elephnt.htm">Care for the Wild -Working for Wildlife</A>: a small international charity dedicated toprotecting wildlife from suffering and exploitation. This site includesinformation on the organisation's  project to relocate 500 threatenedelephants in Zimbabwe.<P><IMG SRC="mestp.gif" ALIGN=left><A HREF="http://www.si.edu/elephant/elephant.htm">The Malaysian ElephantSatellite Tracking Project</A>pages evaluate the success of a relocation project for Malaysian elephants.<BR CLEAR=left><P><IMG SRC="wwf.gif" ALIGN=left>The <AHREF="http://www.panda.org/research/country/nepal/page1.htm">WorldWide Fund for Nature</A> site contains a profile on Nepal, which includes areport on the Royal Bardia National Park conservation programme.<BR CLEAR=left><P><IMG SRC="friendshighplaces.gif" ALIGN=left><A HREF="http://www.webmart.com/icc/nepal.html">Friends in HighPlaces</A>is a Kathmandu trekking company and operates customised treks in Nepal.This good-looking site has information about Nepal's geography, culture andwildlife, as well as details of the trips.<BR CLEAR=left><P><IMG SRC="nepalhp.gif" ALIGN=left><A HREF="http://www.cen.uiuc.edu/~rshresth/Nepal.html">The Nepal HomePage</A>has a visitors' guide with comprehensive information for the tourist orexplorer.<BR CLEAR=left><P><A HREF="http://www.lonelyplanet.com.au/dest/ind/nep.htm">The LonelyPlanet pages on Nepal</A>have useful information and tips for the more adventurous traveller.<P><IMG SRC="explorers.gif" ALIGN=left><A HREF="http://www.si.edu/elephant/elephant.htm">The Explorer HomePage</A>: search for lost cities, explore ancient mysteries andseek hidden treasure around the world.<BR CLEAR=left><P>The <A HREF="http://www.jse.com/index.html">Society for ScientificExploration Web pages</A>: check out abstracts from the society's journal, plus links to other sites. (This organisation should not be confused with the Scientific Exploration  Society, which helped to organise the expedition to Bardia.)<P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"><P>Published in 1995 by Channel 4 Television, 124 Horseferry Road, LondonSW1P 2TX to accompany <I>The Beast of Bardia</I>, a Cicada Films production forChannel 4, first shown on Channel 4 in July 1996.<P>Editor: Paula Snyder<BR>Consultant editor: Peter Millson<BR>Design: Broadcasting Support Services<BR><P>Broadcasting Support Services provides follow-up services for viewersand listeners and runs long-term helplines.</FONT><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
