<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Travelog 1996 - North Korea - The gen</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><BASEFONT SIZE=4><A NAME="TOP"><P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 CELLSPACING=1>	<TR>		<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=76><A HREF="../travelog.html"><IMG SRC="../smtrav.gif" ALT="Travelog home page" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=76 BORDER=1"></A></TD>		<TD VALIGN TOP><P><FONT SIZE=6>North Korea - the gen</FONT>	</TR></TABLE><DL><DD><DL><DD>		<FONT SIZE=4><P><A HREF="#BAC">Background</A>		<BR><A HREF="#GET">Getting there</A>		<BR><A HREF="#BEI">Being there</A>		<BR><A HREF="#BOO">Books and links</A></FONT></TD>				<P><A HREF="koreat1.html">return to North Korea page</A></FONT></DL></DD></DL></DD><P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 CELLSPACING=1>	<TR>		<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=76><IMG SRC="koream1.gif" WIDTH=76 ALT="East Asia Map" ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0></TD>		<TD VALIGN TOP><IMG SRC="koream2.gif" WIDTH=440 HEIGHT=315 ALT="Korea Map" ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0></TD>	</TR></TABLE><DL><DD><DL><DD><P><A NAME="BAC"><H2><B>Background</B></H2><P>When Korea was liberated from Japan at the end of the Second World War, the USSR occupied the North and the US the South. The Democratic People's Republic of Korea was officially established in the North in 1948, under the leadership of the Workers' Party, with Kim Il Sung, the 'Great Leader', as president.<P>In 1950 the North invaded the South. The US intervened on the side of the South, and China on the side of the North, but after three years the war ended in stalemate. North Korea officially remains committed to reunification, and relations with the South are still largely tense and hostile.<P>Factories were nationalised and agriculture collectivised in North Korea during the 1950s, and unlike Communist China and Vietnam, the country has not adopted economic reforms. At the end of the Second World War the north was the more industrialised part of the country, but North Korea's economic growth has lagged far behind that of its southern neighbour.<P>Kim Il Sung died in 1994, and the presidency has devolved to his designated successor - his son, Kim Jong Il, known as the 'Dear Leader'. However, Kim Jong Il has yet to consolidate power to the extent his father did.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME="GET"><H2><B>Getting there</B></H2>A train runs from Beijing to Pyongyang four times a week; alternatively there are the rather unreliable services of Air Koryo from Beijing or Moscow. In Beijing, from which <I>Travelog</I> reached the country, visas are normally issued on the morning of travel.<P>Arranging your own trip is daunting, but a few organised tours are available. These will save you endless hours in queues for tickets or visas, but won't guarantee that you'll travel on a given date - the borders open and close without warning.<P>Operators offering tours to North Korea include <B>Regent Holidays</B> (15 John Street, Bristol BS1 2HR; tel: 0117 921 1711, fax: 0117 925 4866). Regent work in conjunction with Beijing-based <B>Koryo Tours</B> (206 Kindly Commercial Centre, 9 Jianguomenwai Dajif, Beijing 100020; tel/fax: (00 86 10) 5958357), whose staff know the destination well and who can offer such entertainments as a bicycle tour of Beijing while you're waiting to get there. <P>Combined with a trip to Beijing, the cost of a week in North Korea is around 1,900. For more information on <A HREF="beijint1.html">Beijing</A>, click here. <P><I>Travelog</I> travelled to Pyongyang on the 'soft sleeper' train, which takes 23 hours. The border crossing confirmed the need to avoid carrying printed material that could be deemed pornographic or otherwise subversive: border guards read every piece of paper. On the other hand, cameras, both video and still, didn't seem to interest them.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME="BEI"><H2><B>Being there</B></H2>Universal education, no unemployment, no crime, no advertising - it all sounds too good to be true. In an attempt to find out if it is, <I>Travelog</I> worked for 18 months to get the necessary permissions to visit and film in this extraordinary country, one of the world's most secretive and impenetrable.<P>Visitors cannot travel independently in North Korea - everyone must be guided (guarded?) by representatives of the National Directorate of Tourism. You are 'advised' to stay with guides at all times because, it is said, you may get lost, and it worries the local population to see foreigners wandering about. Some parts of the country remain closed to visitors, but in a week's tour <I>Travelog</I> managed to take in the capital, Pyongyang; Myohyangsan, the Palace of Gifts and the mountain scenery that surrounds it; Nampo and the West Sea Barrage; and Kaesong, Panmunjom and the demilitarised zone.<P>Tours include every meal: the idea of walking into a restaurant off the street is - well, foreign. The few hard-currency shops don't have a great deal to offer. But if you're interested in cultures and peoples rather than shopping and beaches, this is a truly fascinating place.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME="BOO"><B><H2>Books and links</H2></B>Not surprisingly travel books on North Korea are few and far between. <I>Lonely Planet's Korea - a travel survival kit</I> devotes 30 pages out of 300 to it. <BR CLEAR=LEFT><P><A HREF="http://www.adfa.oz.au/CS/flg/wf93/kn.html">KP/KN North Korea:</A> geography, people, government, economy, communications.<BR CLEAR=LEFT><P><A HREF="http://www.kimsoft.com/korea.htm">Korea WebWeekly:</A> a non-partisan, non-profit news magazine dedicated to Korean issues. All news summary and editorials are contributed by volunteers. <BR CLEAR=LEFT><P><A HREF="http://www.onramp.net/~hbarker/index1.htm"><IMG SRC="cd50c.jpg" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP BORDER=1><P>Korea War Project:</A> includes history, maps, North Korean Travelogue, government, related resources.<BR CLEAR=LEFT><P><A HREF="http://www.lonelyplanet.com/letters/nea/nk_pc.htm">Lonely planet postcard from North Korea</A><BR CLEAR=LEFT><P><A HREF="http://www.kimsoft.com/korea/eyewit.htm">Eyewitness: A Korean Remembers Korea 1935-1955:</A> contains photos and excerpts from recently declassified US, Chinese and Russian documents. <BR CLEAR=LEFT><P><A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/text/Regional/Countries/Korea__North/">Yahoo links for North Korea</A><BR CLEAR=LEFT><P><B>Newsgroups</B><P><A HREF="news:clari.world.asia.koreas">clari.world.asia.koreas</A>: News about North and South Korea.<P><A HREF="news:soc.culture.korean">soc.culture.korean</A>: Discussions about Korea and things Korean.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
