<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Travelog 1996 - Postcard from Korea</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><BASEFONT SIZE=4><A NAME="TOP"><P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 CELLSPACING=1>	<TR>		<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=76><A HREF="../travelog.html"><IMG SRC="../smtrav.gif" ALT="Travelog home page" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=76 BORDER=1"></A></TD>		<TD VALIGN TOP><P><FONT SIZE=6>Postcard from Korea</FONT>	</TR></TABLE><DL><DD><DL><DD> <FONT SIZE=4><P><A HREF="koreat1.html">return to North Korea page</A></FONT><P><IMG SRC="koreap2.gif" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=440 HEIGHT=321 BORDER=0><P><FONT SIZE=5><B>Found the hotel with the help of <I>Let Us Speak Korean</I>, which, fortunately, has a section on finding your hotel. Useful phrases include: 'Is the hotel far off?', 'What street is this?', 'The houses are very beautiful' and 'Let us mutilate US capitalism.' This really is an extraordinary place. The tour of the Palace of the Students' Children, a talent factory, concluded with a two-hour show the scale of which would humble Busby Berkeley. The Koreans are world leaders in what they call 'mass games' - choeographed gymnastic displays or parades of drilled spear-carriers of the revolution. But there are signs that Korea may be starting to break step just a little. The fact that the Koreans let us film here suggests that things are changing, and just before we left a government official came up and said the unthinkable: 'Please tell your country: Korea is opening its doors.'</B></FONT><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
