<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>INTRODUCTION</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H2><A HREF="-mind.html">The Mind Field</A></H2><H1>Introduction</H1>Telling people that I am a psychiatrist generally stops conversation about anything else. At parties, two things seem to happen. Either people become self-conscious, say that they fear I might see through their defences and that I am, in fact, analysing even the way they hold their drinks, or people metamorphose into ambulatory taxi-drivers and give me their opinions on how the world works. Both groups are interested in what makes them tick and the conversations are usually fascinating.<P>Many people think of psychiatrists and psychologists as all-knowing Freuds and believe that these professionals know exactly how their minds work - but do they?<STRONG> The Mind Field</STRONG> helps you answer this question for yourself on a range of subjects - lying, perception, memory, gambling, power and fear. It takes a look at current psychological theory, explains it and also sets up experiments to test it. The aim is not to deliver tablets of stone, but to give you information and to help you to decide for yourself. Few psychological theories apply to everyone - we are all different - but some of the theories might explain exactly why you do the things you do and think the things you think.<P>The programmes opened the discussion, but this on-line information goes further. As well as being packed with information, it is littered with useful telephone numbers, references for further reading and <KBD><A HREF="-mindgen.html" NAME="">Internet addresses</A></KBD> and <KBD>links to other sites</KBD> - an invaluable guide.<P>I have always thought of psychology as a journey of discovery about myself as well as other people. It's fascinating and exciting - so enjoy reading these pages. Bon voyage!<P><STRONG><A HREF="-kwam.html" NAME="">Dr Kwame McKenzie</A><BR>Department of Psychological Medicine <BR>King's College Hospital and the Institute of Psychiatry, London</STRONG><P><A HREF="-lying.html" NAME="">Lying</A>/<A HREF="-power.html" NAME="">Power</A>/<A HREF="-memory.html" NAME="">Memory</A>/<A HREF="-risk.html" NAME="">Risk-taking and gambling</A>/<A HREF="-percep.html" NAME="">Perception</A>/<A HREF="-fear.html" NAME="">Fear</A><P><hr><P>Published in 1995 by <BR>Channel 4 Television<BR>124 Horseferry Road<BR>London SW1P 2TX<BR><P>Produced by Broadcasting Support Services to accompany THE MIND FIELD (a Diverse Production series for Channel 4), first shown on Channel 4 in June-July 1995<P>Writers: Gill Adams and Chrissie Kravchenko<BR>Additional research: Deborah Catesby<BR>Editor: Derek Jones<BR>Editorial consultant: Nancy Duin<BR><P>For copies of the booklet to accompany this series (same text as on-line version with extra photos), please send a cheque or postal order for 2.50 (made payable to Channel 4 Television) to:<BR>THE MIND FIELD (www)<BR>PO Box 4000<BR>London W5 2GH or Cardiff CF5 2XT<P><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
