<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>LYING</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H2><A HREF="-mind.html">The Mind Field</A></H2><H1><A HREF="lies1.html" NAME="">Lying</A></H1><H2><EM>The lying game</EM></H2><H3> The thought of ourselves as liars is an uncomfortable one. But by the time we are adults, most of us do it extremely well, and we practise our skill on a daily basis. What's more, we teach our <A HREF="lies13.html" NAME="">children</A> to do it. If you think that's a lie, read on.</H3><KBD>Usenet <A HREF="news://alt.lies">newsgroup</A>: alt.lies</KBD><P>'Sorry I'm late - the traffic was terrible,' Stephanie tells her boss, sliding quietly behind her desk. The truth: 'I was at a party till late last night and overslept' - but how would that go down at her end of year assessment?<P>What would you do in the same circumstances? Would you own up and face the music? How would you decide? Would it depend on who you're lying to, or whether you're likely to be found out?<P>What's certain is that <A HREF="lies3.html" NAME="">we all lie</A> to survive. 'One of the things about lying that people don't understand is that it's actually part of our personal survival tool kit,' says psychotherapist Gladeana McMahon. Some lies are socially acceptable because they smooth the path to good relationships. We use them because they're kinder than the truth. We might say, 'Yes, I love the sweater you made for me, Auntie Sue,' even at the risk of getting another, similar one next Christmas.<P>We're all familiar with excuses for getting out of a tight spot. They can easily be true - but often they're not, and usually it doesn't matter. They're not meant to hurt. They're an acknowledged social skill - discreet, tactful and diplomatic. <P>In everyday life, there are pay offs for the liar. People like to be liked, so we may bend the truth to fit in with whatever group we happen to be with, and still manage to retain our integrity and basic honesty. Judging when to lie and when to tell the truth is a vital and hard won skill. It's not surprising that some people never properly learn to make such delicate judgements.They lie habitually, to themselves and to others, to the detriment of their relationships.<P>When deceit becomes a way of life, as it does for con men and compulsive liars, the stories inevitably become more and more elaborate. Often, the liar has difficulty distinguishing between fact and fantasy, which is what makes life so difficult for those who live or work with them. As the ex wife of one compulsive liar says, 'He used his lies to have control over me, or to keep me with him. In the end, I think he believed the lies himself.'<P><H4>Once upon a time ...</H4><P>Why do some people need to distort the truth so much? Are liars born or made? Let's look at <A HREF="lies12.html" NAME="">lies through a child's eye</A>s.<P>We start to lie as soon as we learn that lying may get us something we want (our parents' approval, initially) or help us avoid something we don't want (punishment). Very <A HREF="lies17.html" NAME="">young children</A> can't help lying because they make mistakes and don't want to get caught out. But it is hard to lie convincingly at first - becoming good at it takes a while. However, children quickly learn to judge whether it's riskier to lie to us or tell us the truth, and they use all sorts of <A HREF="lies6.html" NAME="">clues</A> from our behaviour - e.g. tone of voice and body language - to help them decide. <P>'In a healthy family,' says Gladeana McMahon, 'children will get told off for misdemeanours, but they know they are loved and therefore can withstand their parents' disapproval, so they're not as likely to feel the need to lie. In another family, they might experience what we call "conditional love" and come to believe that they are only loved if they do the right thing - for example, get a good mark for a spelling test, spend time with friends their parents like. In these types of families, children will be tempted to bend the truth to keep the approval of a <A HREF="lies11.html" NAME="">parent</A>, because without that, they feel unloved.' So if, as children, we were only loved for what we did rather than who we were, and punishments for doing wrong were harsh, then we are almost bound to lie habitually to survive. The pattern is set.<P>If you lie to yourself ... well, that's a different game. Everyone sometimes finds 'home truths' hard to take, but when the truth is staring people in the face and they can't see it, psychologists would say that they are in a state of 'denial'. We do it to protect ourselves from emotional pain. Only if our self deception is making us unhappy are we likely to seek the help of a counsellor or therapist. But neither of these would suggest that the way to heal an individual, or society in general, is to banish all deception.<P>If, with missionary zeal, we all embarked on a 'National Truth Day' - 'You're fat,' 'I hate you,' 'There's no Father Christmas,' 'I slept with your boyfriend in 1972' - the result would be chaos or worse. This is because the intention behind so many of the truths would be cruel rather than loving - and most of us would rather love and be loved than be right.<P>So we'll all, except Pinnochio, go to to our graves carrying a pack of lies:<BR><CITE>'How can you possibly know that I have told a lie?' asks the little wooden boy.<BR>	'Lies, my dear boy, are found out immediately, because they are of two sorts. There are lies that have short legs, and lies that have long noses. Your lie, as it happens, is one of those that has a long nose.'</CITE><P><A HREF="lies2.html" NAME="">Article</A><P><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
