<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>POWER</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H2><A HREF="-mind.html">The Mind Field</A></H2><H1><A HREF="pow3.html" NAME="">Power</A></H1><H2><EM><A HREF="pow1.html" NAME="">Power struggles</A></EM></H2><H3>What would you be like if you were really <A HREF="pow2.html" NAME="">powerful</A> - a religious leader, say, or the head of a huge corporation? Would you be kind and caring, remote behind the smoked windows of your limo, or perhaps just a bit brash, all flashy suits and gold accessories?</H3><P>'I think there are people who are naturally powerful,' says film director Michael Winner. 'My mother was one of them. I have seen her - a little white-haired woman - reduce top lawyers and accountants to dust within five minutes. Usually, though, you have to have some sort of position. A movie star, for example, has enormous power.'<P>Few of us are movie stars, though, or heads of large corporations. <A HREF="pow13.html" NAME="">We don't often meet them</A> either. The most powerful people in our lives will be our partners and managers, doctors, teachers, beautiful women, people in uniform - people we meet every day. Some of them use their power sparingly and with care; <A HREF="pow5.html" NAME="">others can impose their will in a more frightening way</A>.<P>'Rich and 'powerful' are two words that seem made for one another, but the power of a strong personality resides less in wealth or status than many of us imagine. At its simplest, power is about persuading others that your idea is the best.<P>One of the best ways to persuade people that you know best is to wear a uniform. In a simple experiment, 92 per cent of passers-by, when asked by a man in uniform, handed over 20p to a motorist for a parking meter. Asked by someone without a uniform, passers-by passed by. <P>In a famous experiment by psychologist Stanley Milgram <A HREF="http://pccvm.sycrci.pcc.edu/~sysmaint/gunquote.html/"><KBD>[go to quotes]</KBD></A> in 1963, more than 60 per cent of ordinary people were shown to be capable of administering apparently lethal electric shocks to others because they were told to do so by a 'responsible' person in a laboratory coat. The subjects themselves were later shocked by their level of compliance. It seems that most of us are eager to shelve <A HREF="pow18.html" NAME="">responsibility</A>, and so give too much power to others.<P><H4>Are you a leader?</H4>A recent, and more optimistic, piece of research showed that people who are able to sustain powerful positions and retain the admiration and respect of their employees typically show certain characteristics that most of us have to some degree. <P>'From the research that we've carried out here,' says Cary Cooper, professor of organisational psychology at the University of Manchester Institute of Science and Technology (UMIST), '<A HREF="pow4.html" NAME="">good leaders</A> need an ability to <A HREF="-risk.html" NAME="">risk</A>-take, be innovative, be extremely good time managers, very energetic and, more surprisingly, to be able to cut off and spend a lot of time with their families and have a private life.' <P>These individuals favour a management style based on reward rather than punishment. Most fascinating, according to Professor Cooper: 'The number one factor is that they have a kind of driving force which comes from an event, usually negative, which happened early in childhood. Quite a large proportion have lost a parent before the age of 16, or have been separated from a parent for a large number of years, or have been rejected by a parent. That forces them on to their own resources. But this driving force is not to gain power to control other people but to gain control over a world they had no control over when they were younger.' <P><H4><A HREF="pow10.html" NAME="">Children and power</A></H4>If power is such a good thing, why didn't our parents want us to have any?<P><KBD><A HREF="http://www.einet.net/galaxy/Community/The-Family.html">Family/parenting</A> web site</KBD><P>Babyhood is a place filled with mystery and wonder ... and huge, god-like adults. When we start to think as individuals - to talk, and to talk back - our gods can come down from Olympus like a ton of bricks, and meet our power ploys with gambits as childlike and furious as our own. <A HREF="pow11.html" NAME="">Parents</A> can find it hard during this phase to stay gently in charge, but understanding why on earth a child seems to be trying to make infanticide defensible can help.<P>'So much of what adults see as bad behaviour in children is actually the child trying to survive as a person,' says psychologist and author Dr Dorothy Rowe. 'Wise parents make sure that there are some areas in the child's life where the child wins over the parent. Unwise parents insist always that the parent is right and the child is wrong, and that attitude does terrible damage to a child. Obedient children keep me in work. They grow up to be <A HREF="pow19.html" NAME="">depressed</A> adults, guilty adults, <A HREF="-fear.html" NAME="">frightened</A> adults.' <P>What if you - now grown up - still feel frustrated by your lack of power, at home or in the workplace? For shortterm effect, you can learn conversational ploys and how to make persuasive speeches, or you could even try ostentatious use of a mobile phone, flashing a gold or platinum credit card, or buying a bigger desk and occupying a more richly carpeted office.<P>If lasting power is what you want, though, the <A HREF="pow7.html" NAME="">'soft' power qualities</A> will stand you in good stead. Assertive people take power without being aggressive and give it up gracefully when necessary. Maybe you need only enough power to get your clients to pay up on time, or get your child to school without a fight. Whether you seek power at home or at work, <A HREF="pow14.html" NAME="">assertiveness training</A> or 'people management' skills training can help you to develop useful strategies.<P><H4>When the star fades</H4>Frightening bosses, angry spouses, even people in uniform are just ordinary human beings who've borrowed a bit of power - leave it hanging around, and there's always someone ready to pick it up. Ultimately, power only exists in relationships, so people who allow others to have it are also powerful: they can take it away.<P>As Michael Winner says, 'It's so awful when a star eventually fades, and those smiles diminish on the people facing them. The handshake is less strong, nobody is there to light the cigarette. I've seen very major stars shattered by this loss of power.'<P>So if you're feeling bullied by someone who's power crazy, keep remembering that their power is only on loan and that they are as ordinary and fallible as anyone else. <A HREF="pow12.html" NAME="">Dr Dorothy Rowe</A> recommends reading the last part of Lewis Carroll's Alice in Wonderland:<P><KBD>The full text of <A HREF="ftp://ftp.std.com/obi/Lewis.Carroll/AliceInWonderl.tar.Z">Alice</A> is available at ftp.std.com/obi/Lewis.Carroll/AliceInWonderl.tar.Z</KBD><H3><EM>'Off with her head,' the Queen shouted at the top of her voice. Nobody moved. <BR>   'Who cares for you?' said Alice (she had grown to her full size by this time). 'You're nothing but a pack of cards!'</EM></H3><P><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
