<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>MEMORY</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H2><A HREF="-mind.html">The Mind Field</A></H2><H1>Memory</H1><H2><EM>Memories</EM></H2><H3>Just for starters, why don't you look at this string of characters for a few moments? Try memorising them. Now cover them up, and stop thinking about them while you read what follows. Ready? <BR><A HREF="mem1.html" NAME="">ITV1030PMORBBC21030PM</A></H3><EM>He reached out his hand, and took hold of his wife's head, tried to lift it off, to put it on. He had apparently mistaken his wife for a hat!</EM><P>This tragic tale of Dr P, told in <A HREF="mem2.html" NAME="">Oliver Sacks' now-famous book</A>, shows dramatically what can happen when a very specific part of a person's memory disappears - in this case, destroyed by a massive brain tumour. <P>Dr P lost his visual memory, so that, although he could see his wife, his brain was unable to give him accurate information about who or what he was seeing. However often he tried, he couldn't recognise his wife, or a glove, or a flower. Other senses were, however, intact. As he was a musician, he learned how to 'cue' his memory with <KBD><A HREF="http://american.recordings.com/wwwofmusic/ubl.html">music</A></KBD> rather than sight. As his wife reported: 'He does everything singing to himself.' While singing, he could do things that we don't even think of as feats of memory - such as dressing. But once his singing was interrupted, his clothes became a mystery again. <P>Not only does this show us how fundamental memory is to our functioning, but also how adaptable our minds can be. In addition, it demonstrates clearly how logical it is to fear losing our memory.<P>Have you ever 'blanked' - been suddenly unable to introduce someone you know well - or gone through a period of <A HREF="mem4.html" NAME="">forgetfulness</A>? Before you add anxiety about mental illness to your worries, know that memory, like other skills, is vulnerable to tiredness, depression, stress and, yes, ageing. But lapses don't signal dementia. Memory ages and changes just as the rest of the body does, and forgetfulness need bother most of us no more than the odd twinge of rheumatism. Like carrying heavy bags, let someone younger (or your diary) do all the weighty memory work. <P><H4>How we remember</H4>There are three basic types of memory:<P><EM>Immediate memory</EM> allows the mind to hold and let go of a sensory impression within a very short time. If you look at an image and close your eyes, you'll remember it for only about a second unless you 'decide' to store it.<P><EM>Short-term memory</EM> has space for up to seven 'items', which it will store for up to 20 seconds. This allows you to remember, say, a phone number for the amount of time it takes to dial it while writing a lunch date in your diary.<P><EM>Long-term memory</EM> is where we do all our heavy-duty, complex storing and retrieving of events, people, places, languages and other skills. To do this, we use emotions, meanings, associations, connections - a whole toolbox of <A HREF="mem16.html" NAME="">devices</A>, above and beyond words - which can make the things we want to remember more or less retrievable for life.<P>No one quite knows how brain cells form <A HREF="mem5.html" NAME="">memories</A>, but we know that they don't work like tape-recorders, faithfully taping and filing full-length features of our lives. In fact, memory is much more complicated, interesting and useful than any machine.<P>As an example, suppose you saw two snails that looked as if they were fighting. The information about those snails - size, colour, position - would register in your brain, along with your interpretation of what snails mean to you: 'Eat all the plants', 'Make silver trails', 'Slimy', 'My brother put one down my back.' This information and interpretation would then be recorded. Later, when something happens to remind you of that event - say, another snail on a wall menacing a favourite flower - you will retrieve the memory of the original snails, and you'll also add in related information about favourite flowers and walls. Then, if you tell someone else about your memory of the two fighting snails, you might forget to say that they only looked as if they were fighting.<P>The next time you see a snail, you might remember the original time you saw two snails apparently fighting, or you might remember the time you told the story of two snails fighting - along with a lot of seemingly irrelevant information about flowers and walls. The whole experience can become jumbled and inaccurate. It is therefore prudent to doubt your own detailed memory of one event.<P><H4><A HREF="mem8.html" NAME="">Improving memory</A></H4>What you can rely on is that whatever you do remember is not random but connected to something else. You can actively use the mind's almost obsessive desire to make connections to develop your 'memory muscle' or just to remember specific things.<P>For example, Jonathan Hancock, world memory champion in 1994, simply uses the mind's habit of <A HREF="mem7.html" NAME="">connecting</A> and its complex ability to imagine. He remembers a series of objects by imagining them in specific places - e.g. a key in a snake pit, a shell in a jug of water on a brown tablecloth, a pencil sharpener on a moss-covered rock in a small wood - and so on.<P>Is memory just an acquired skill that anyone can learn? The answer, as usual, is yes and no. Strategic tasks - such as <A HREF="mem3.html" NAME="">face recognition</A> or remembering numbers, words or objects - are suited to the use of tricks or techniques. Other tasks aren't so easily managed. For example, it's more difficult to store and retrieve a story with a complex plot than to commit a <KBD><A HREF="http://english-server.hss.cmu.edu/poetry.html">poem</A></KBD> to memory word for word. There are, however, 'naturals', people with exceptional memories who are particularly good at the less strategic tasks. They don't use tricks; they are just able to <A HREF="mem11.html" NAME="">remember</A> things more easily, and for longer periods, than the rest of us. <P>One way to 'tone' this <A HREF="mem9.html" NAME="">story-telling</A> ability has become very fashionable recently. Called 'oral history', it encourages people - especially the elderly - to take trips down memory lane and gives listeners unique perspectives on social history. Starch, darning, ration books, shillings - we all have memories of such things from our childhoods that would seem like Martian objects to our own children. Organisations such as Age Exchange's Reminiscence Centre actively encourage older people to remember the times they've lived through. But don't forget: these memories can be as inaccurate as any others. It can be an interesting exercise to cross-check them with other people's or with history books.<P>We know from our own experience the extraordinary power that a <A HREF="mem12.html" NAME="">taste</A> or a smell can have to evoke the past. And touching long-forgotten everyday objects can perform a similar function. <A HREF="mem10.html" NAME="">Age Exchange</A> have created a set of 'Reminiscence Boxes' which are full of triggers to set off memories. The 'Going Shopping' box, for example, has a string bag, some old money, a ration book, Co-op tokens, a typical shopping list - all to get people talking about their <A HREF="mem6.html" NAME="">pasts</A>. These boxes can also be used to help people suffering from dementia and other types of serious memory loss to make connections between past and present.<P>Most comforting for the vast majority of people who, moving into the 'Third Age', notice that recent details become strangely elusive, is this thought from <A HREF="mem13.html" NAME="">Lawrence LeShan</A>: <P><H4><EM>It is necessary in the first 40-50 years of life to remember details: 'What size transistor fits here?' 'What are the legal precedents for that?' It is the developmental time for these concerns. As life reaches the halfway point ... we turn naturally to the general, the relationships, the upper end of the spectrum.<P>I have questioned many people who complain of the 'forgetting' symptom. They have great trouble remembering the <A HREF="mem14.html" NAME="">name to go with a face</A> they have met recently. They are always surprised when they realise that they do not forget the emotional tone between them and that person at the time that they met. They remember the relationship and its meaning; they forget the details ... Because they do not understand that this change is part of development and a sign to go forward, they regard it as a loss and so it becomes one. I have never known of a mystic or a sensitive of any age with this symptom.</EM></H4><P>Young or old, we'd all do well to get family members to commit this information to their long-term <A HREF="mem15.html" NAME="">memories</A>. After all, who wants to be related to an absent-minded old codger when you can have Sunday lunch with a sage?<P><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
