<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>RISK-TAKING AND GAMBLING</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H2><A HREF="-mind.html">The Mind Field</A></H2><H1>Risk-taking & Gambling</H1><H2><EM>The gambling instinct</EM></H2><H3><A HREF="risk8.html" NAME="">We assess risk</A> every day of <A HREF="risk2.html" NAME="">our lives</A>, and most of us have the occasional flutter on the horses or the lottery. Life can be <A HREF="risk6.html" NAME="">risky</A>, but the <A HREF="risk4.html" NAME="">odds</A> are that we'll probably live to tell the tale.</H3><KBD>Gamblers <A HREF="news:rec.gambling">newsgroup</A>: rec.gambling</KBD><P><EM>'Son ... no matter how far you travel, or how smart you get, always remember this: Some day, somewhere ... a guy is going to come to you and show you a nice brand-new deck of cards on which the seal is never broken, and this guy is going to offer to bet you that the jack of spades will jump out of this deck and squirt cider in your ear. But, son ... do not bet him, for as sure as you do, you are going to get an ear full of cider.'</EM><P>So advised the father of ace gambler Sky Masterson in Damon Runyon's short story, 'The Idyll of Miss Sarah Brown'.<P>Try getting that message across to the millions who bet on the <A HREF="risk3.html" NAME="">national lottery</A> every week. 'It could be you,' says the ad. We all know it probably won't be - not the jackpot anyway - but still we queue up to play. Then for a few hours every week, while we're waiting for Mystic Meg, we escape to the land of dreams. We'll buy a holiday villa or build homes for the needy; we'll bathe in champagne or take flying lessons. If our hopes are dashed, there's no harm done. We had all that fantastic entertainment for a measly pound. <P>As a nation, we love to gamble. Bingo, football pools, the horses, <A HREF="risk5.html" NAME="">fruit machines</A>, the election results, stocks and shares - there's something for everyone. 'You can feel the adrenalin building up. It's the excitement above all else,' says one bingo player. Not all gamblers feel the same, but perhaps even bingo players have something in common with the adrenalin-hungry bungee jumpers who seek excitement through <A HREF="-fear.html" NAME="">fear</A> and risk.<P>Casino gamblers, like bungee jumpers, readily admit that they do it for the thrill. And the effect isn't all in the mind. 'Physiological arousal is very important,' says Iain Brown of Glasgow University. 'When they gamble, one division of their nervous system is very active indeed. And that tends to increase their heart rate and their blood pressure and slow down their digestive processes and so on.'<P>Some people actually seem to relish the excitement of danger. Think of mountain climbers or war correspondents - they put their need for excitement into their work. Some of the best gamblers and risk-takers are those who do it for a living - <A HREF="risk16.html" NAME="">investing</A> on the money markets in the <A HREF="risk10.html" NAME="">City of London</A>, or advising those who do. 'A <A HREF="risk11.html" NAME="">good gambler</A> is someone who works out the odds, takes a calculated risk, takes his profit and waits for his next opportunity. Someone who's cold, who's completely dispassionate about his evaluation. Luckily not too many of these people exist - or I wouldn't have a business!' says Jonathan Sparke of City Index, the pioneers of <A HREF="risk12.html" NAME="">'spreadbetting'</A>.<P><H4>Chasing losses</H4>Gambling is a particular form of risk-taking, and for those who are susceptible to <A HREF="risk14.html" NAME="">addiction</A>, it can become an illness. Not all risk-takers are addicts, but all addicts are risk-takers, as Robert Lefevre, director of the <A HREF="risk15.html" NAME="">PROMIS</A> recovery centre, points out. 'People usually have three or four outlets for addictive disease. <A HREF="risk17.html" NAME="">All addictions</A> can be equally damaging to the individuals who've got them, so gambling and risk-taking can be major problems for people who are addicts.'<P>In 1994, <A HREF="risk15.html" NAME="">compulsive gambling</A> was finally recognised as a psychiatric illness. However, the symptoms aren't all psychological - there can be physical ones, too. 'I don't eat, I don't drink. It can be six or seven hours before I use the toilet, because the [fruit] machine takes over my life. When I come home, I'm physically sick. I have diarrhoea and sleep till four or five o'clock in the afternoon,' admits one compulsive gambler. She worries about the effect of her gambling on her family, 'My little boy likes the arcade. He likes the excitement and the noises. But the other children associate the machines with upset and heartbreak. They know what goes on when I spend everything and they know they've got to go without.'<P>According to Robert Lefevre of the PROMIS centre: 'In those of us who've got addictive diseases, there's a defect in the mood centres of our brain. We feel two steps down. And we discover that these substances or processes, such as alcohol, drugs, gambling, sex or love, put us two steps up again.' <P>Happily, for most of us, gambling isn't all-consuming. Rather, it's simply entertainment, a sort of play, a ride into an imaginary world where dreams come true. We bet what we can afford to lose. Any <A HREF="risk13.html" NAME="">win</A> is just the icing on the cake.<P><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
