<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>PERCEPTION</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H2><A HREF="-mind.html">The Mind Field</A></H2><H1><A HREF="percep2.html" NAME="">Perception</A></H1><H2><EM><A HREF="percep13.html" NAME="">Seeing things</A></EM></H2><H3>Welcome to the real world, the one your mind has chosen to build. As you can see, there's more than one way of looking at things.</H3>How do you see the world? As a playground or a battleground? Perhaps it changes depending on your mood, the money in your pocket or the company you keep. Although we search out people who share our world-view, each of us experiences the world from a unique vantage point, <A HREF="percep14.html" NAME="">coloured</A> by personality, circumstance and what life has taught us. <P>Imagine leaving a cinema after watching a moving film of family life. You may be thinking: 'That poor girl, what terrible parents. No wonder she ended up as she did.' 'That poor mother,' says the chap behind you. 'What she had to put up with from that awful, selfish girl.' Same film, from different viewpoints, so <A HREF="percep8.html" NAME="">differing realities</A>.<P>How can two people arrive at such different conclusions? All of us receive information from the outside world via our senses - touch, feel, sight, hearing and smell - which is <A HREF="percep4.html" NAME="">interpreted</A> by our minds. Every day we are bombarded with messages from our senses, and we'd be overloaded if we gave each one the same degree of importance. So we are selective - we choose what is important at the time and push the rest into the background. Each mind is as individual as a fingerprint, so each of us selects differently, and from this selection, we construct a tailor-made reality. Most significantly, in healthy individuals this reality is biased towards optimism.<P>'Since the time of Freud, it's been assumed that being in touch with reality is the hallmark of mental health,' says Professor Richard Bentall of Liverpool University. 'But we now know that actually being slightly out of touch with reality is something which keeps us bright-eyed and bushy-tailed. If we spend our lives dwelling on the limitations of our own abilities, then we don't feel we're able to get up in the morning and cope with the demands which are placed on us.'<P>People who are depressed find it much harder than others to look on the bright side - to preserve this <A HREF="percep5.html" NAME="">'positive illusion'</A>, as it's sometimes called. According to a psychological theory - 'depressive realism' - these individuals are more realistic and fair-minded than non-depressed people. In an experiment set up by <A HREF="percep6.html" NAME="">Professor Bentall</A>, depressed and non-depressed people were asked to play a computer game. Unknown to them, the game had been rigged so that none of them had a chance of winning. The depressed people soon saw that their situation was hopeless. The non-depressed group remained optimistic about their chances even when they lost repeatedly. <P>You can, however, have too much of a good thing. A depressed person has, if you like, too good a grip on reality (at least in some things); most of us have a good enough grip on reality tending towards optimism; but a <A HREF="percep7.html" NAME="">paranoid</A> person has only a tenuous grip. <P>'There are people who are experts in finding somebody else to blame when things go wrong. Over a period of time, they develop theories about conspiracies which account for the bad things which happen to them. In this way, they manage to maintain to some extent a positive self-image, but at a huge price,' says Professor Bentall.<P>So what are we to do? Give in to <A HREF="http://www.cityscape.co.uk/users/ad88/dep.htm"><KBD>depression</KBD></A> or delude ourselves that things aren't as bad as they seem? Fortunately, most of us, most of the time, find a balance and hover between the two. <P><H4>Witches, monsters and fairies</H4>For children, still trying to make sense of the world, the boundaries between <A HREF="percep15.html" NAME="">what's real</A> and what's fantasy are not clear. They can build up a pretend world, where teddies need to be lovingly fed, where they become doctors or pilots, or have imaginary companions to whom they can talk. There's nothing unhealthy about any of this - quite the contrary. <P><KBD>All your favourite <A HREF="ftp://ftp.funet.fi/pub/doc/literary/etext/fairy-tale/">fairy tales</A> at ftp.funet.fi/pub/doc/literary/etext/fairy-tale/</KBD><P><KBD><A HREF="http://www.clark.net/pub/journalism/kid.html">"Kids Internet Delight"</A> - web site with links to things children and their parents might enjoy on the net.</KBD> <P>'We still don't know exactly why children do it, but it may be part of developing our ability to entertain all sorts of possibilities about our future,' says Dr Paul Harris of Oxford University. What we do know is that a well-developed <A HREF="percep10.html" NAME="">imagination</A> is an important human quality. Our imaginations help us to empathise with other people and see their points of view.<P>In one of Dr Harris's experiments, children are shown two large boxes and asked to look inside to make sure each is empty. The experimenter then encourages them to pretend that there's a fairy in one of the boxes. When the children seem involved in the fantasy, the experimenter makes an excuse to leave the room. Some children can't resist taking a peep into the box to see if there really is a fairy, but others who are more sceptical sit resolutely on their seats.<P>So it seems that even quite young children understand that the products of their imagination are not visible or real. Yet they can't completely discount the possibility that fairies or monsters may exist, and often they perceive imaginary creatures as frightening or comforting, depending on their circumstances.<P><H4>Imagine ...</H4>As adults, we can use our imaginations to daydream or visualise a different reality in order to get certain results. Some become experts, such as runner Julian Golding: 'About half an hour before my race, I lie down and mentally rehearse the race in my mind. For me, then, the ride is smooth. Instead of running, I tend to be gliding on the track.' Psychiatrist Kwame McKenzie uses a <A HREF="percep12.html" NAME="">visualisation</A> technique to convince himself that the dentist's drill won't be painful.<P>We have at our disposal, and use, all sorts of 'helpers' to alter our current reality, if only temporarily. <A HREF="http://www.health.org/ncaditop.html"><KBD>Drugs and alcohol</KBD></A> are powerful but have unwanted side-effects and can be addictive. Flotation tanks, <A HREF="percep3.html" NAME="">virtual reality</A> environments, mountain climbing and holidays are more benign. So if you don't like your current world, you can always construct a new one. Everything depends on the way you look at it.<P><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
