<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>FEAR</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H2><A HREF="-mind.html">The Mind Field</A></H2><H1><A HREF="fear1.html" NAME="">Fear</A></H1><H2><EM>Feeling afraid</EM></H2><H3>You have chosen, bravely, to think about fear. Hold tight, because no one is in control but you. You can stop at any time, of course - but you won't. Because the chance to make peace with fear is a Faustian offer, with freedom as the prize.</H3><STRONG><EM>Sleep came not near my couch - while the hours waned and waned away. I struggled to reason off the nervousness which had dominion over me. I endeavored to believe that much, if not all of what I felt, was due to the bewildering influence of the gloomy furniture of the room - of the dark and tattered draperies, which, tortured into motion by the breath of a rising tempest, swayed fitfully to and fro upon the walls, and rustled uneasily about the decorations of the bed. But my efforts were fruitless. An irrepressible tremor gradually pervaded my frame; and, at length, there sat upon my very heart an incubus of utterly causeless alarm.</EM></STRONG><P>Is he simply scared of the dark ... or is he sensing the cries of a dead woman from her tomb? Things go from bad to worse for our hero in 'The Fall of the House of Usher', a story by that master of fear, Edgar Allen Poe.<P><KBD><A HREF="ftp://ftp.funet.fi/pub/doc/literary/etext/Poe/">Poe's works</A> available at ftp.funet.fi/pub/doc/literary/etext/Poe/</KBD><P>Language has changed in the 155 years or so since Poe was writing, and so has the dominant fictional medium. One of the master fear-conjurers of our age is <A HREF="fear2.html" NAME="">Freddie Francis</A>, veteran 'Hammer <A HREF="fear18.html" NAME="">horror</A>' film-maker (as director and cameraman), who was also responsible (as cinematographer) for <EM>The Innocents</EM> (1961) and <EM>Cape Fear</EM> (1991). In his works, he has the advantages of camera angles, lighting and scary music, but the same things still keep audiences on the edge of their seats: suspense, unpredictability, knowing some dreadful thing is going to happen but not exactly what or when.<P>As a society, organised, predictable, controllable fear is something we seek. In spite of what we might think, everyday life just isn't scary enough any more, so our systems crave stimulus and use fear as entertainment. When we're tired of gripping our cinema seats, there are white-knuckle <A HREF="fear19.html" NAME="">fairground rides</A> (one man loved them so much he got married on one), pot-holing, and that new European rite of passage for <A HREF="fear3.html" NAME="">adrenalin</A>-hungry young men with money: <A HREF="fear4.html" NAME="">bungee-jumping</A>. As one jumper said with relish: 'You're pumping for hours before and after - it's a natural high.'<P>But what about fear that we can't switch off or control, the kind that gets the better of us? Let's be brave and have a closer look.<P><H4>The function of fear</H4>'Fear reactions are primarily to get you away from dangerous situations,' says Graham Davey, professor of psychology at the University of Sussex. 'Bodily reactions to fear are ones that make you more aroused and more alert and ready to run away. Avoiding dangerous things has survival benefits.'<P>Although you may want to escape from them, you don't have to (literally) run away from many of today's <A HREF="fear5.html" NAME="">adult fears</A> - negative equity, the VAT man, AIDS - but the instinct is still there. The adrenalin-rush that goes with fear-arousal may cause you to tremble and sweat even though there's nothing tangible to escape from and no obvious foe to slay.<P>Most fear is not innate. We learn, gradually, how to fear. 'We really start to fear once we start to learn,' says Dr Dorothy Einon of the Department of Psychology at the University College London. 'Then we can learn to anticipate danger or pain and that things can become frightening.'<P>One of our first anticipated fears is of losing mother, father or whoever takes care of us the most - so-called <A HREF="fear20.html" NAME="">'separation anxiety'</A>, which has a survival function. As our experience grows, we collect information about what to fear. If we were hurt or saw someone cry at the dentist's, we may fear it next time round. More subtle - and less researched - is how we 'pick up' our parents' fears, using tiny physical cues, such as clammy hands clutching us too tightly as a plane reaches the end of the runway. 'My little girl has inherited my <A HREF="fear11.html" NAME="">fear of flying</A>' is probably less accurate than 'I gave her my fear of flying.'<P><H4>How fear can go wrong</H4>The fear of ghosts and monsters typical of the pre-schooler can seem alarmingly real, and the way we respond to these can affect <A HREF="fear6.html" NAME="">children</A> for the rest of their lives. Put simply, you need to take their fears seriously. If a little boy says he feels scared, and you tell him he doesn't - or that he's stupid if he does - then he may have to separate himself either from his own feelings or from you. Either proposition could have repercussions for his relationship with himself and with the outside world.<P>One famously unkind experiment shows how easy it is for an adult to become stuck with a childhood fear. In 1919, the behavioural psychologist J. B. Watson subjected a young child known as 'Little Albert' to a loud shocking noise every time he played happily with a white rat. Eventually the boy would not only cry when he saw a white rat but, as he grew up, he remained terrified of anything white and fluffy - even Father Christmas's beard! This demonstrates our minds' tendency to <A HREF="-memory.html" NAME="">associate</A> events, feelings and so on with each other - vital to learning but also the cause of deliberate, or accidental, misunderstanding. It can result in the mind constructing a special kind of fear, which affects 30-40 per cent of the population at some time in their lives. We know it as <A HREF="fear12.html" NAME="">phobia</A>.<P><H4><A HREF="fear9.html" NAME="">Phobias</A></H4>Be grateful that we live in the 1990s as opposed to the early 1800s, when phobia was regarded as a religious affliction. In fact, the word '<A HREF="http://www.well.com/user/selfhelp/panic.htm"><KBD>panic</KBD></A>' - a feeling unfortunately familiar to many phobics - is derived from Pan, the name of a Greek god who engendered terror. By the mid-1850s, the condition was seen as a medical problem, but some sufferers still faced dreadful treatments: the knife-happy Victorians were keen on lobotomies for agoraphobia, a practice that apparently went on into the late 1940s. <P><KBD><A HREF="gopher://gopher.nimh.nih.gov">Anxiety disorders</A> - gopher.nimh.nih.gov [Directory: /Documents/NIMH/Other/Anxiety]</KBD><P>Perhaps the biggest split in treating phobias is now between the 'quick-fixers' and the psychoanalysts. The latter can take seven years of twice weekly sessions to fail to treat a phobia, saying that the removal of one would just uncover another. Says Dr Paul Salkovskis, research clinical psychologist at Oxford University's Department of Psychiatry: 'I think psychoanalysts often make some phobias more complicated than they need be. There is some evidence that psychoanalysis makes phobia worse and none that it makes it better. It's often easier and cheaper for a doctor to prescribe a drug such as Prozac rather than consider other treatments. But the drugs are often ineffective, and in any case, after treatment has ceased the problem returns.'<P>When Dr Salkovskis treats phobias, he first finds out what terrible things his patients fear will happen if they expose themselves to their specific 'phobic situation' (for instance, a supermarket or a particular object). He takes his patients' fears seriously, telling them: 'Anyone who believes that this will happen if they come into contact with X [the phobia] would feel the way you do.' Then the patients are taken into the feared situation and talked through it in a reassuring and firm but unpressured way. This <EM><A HREF="fear13.html" NAME="">cognitive behavioural therapy</A></EM>, as it's called, can often result in immediate improvements in only one session.<P><A HREF="fear14.html" NAME="">Neuro-linguistic programming</A> (NLP), which doesn't involve exposure to the feared situation, has also had some good results. Phobias often develop because of a frightening incident in childhood. NLP works by looking at how the phobia was first acquired, then 're-running' the incident in the person's imagination with a less frightening outcome.<P>Perhaps the most fearful 'outcome' we can imagine is <A HREF="fear15.html" NAME="">death</A>, yet for some people, fearing death and facing it is an everyday occurrence. Firefighters, for example, are paid to walk towards fearful situations instead of away from them. How do they learn to cope? Their trainers are not interested in fearless heroics. To them, the enemy of courage is not the lack of fear but the lack of confidence and competence. Trainee firefighters are gradually exposed to more and more danger, and are taught to work as a team, so that they do not have to be alone and unsupported with their fears. <P>Fear is a natural part of us. When it gets out of hand, however, it can seem like an enemy within. Tackling the <A HREF="fear16.html" NAME="">undesirable effects</A> of too much fear - or any other overwhelming emotion - can be difficult if we feel alone. Like the firefighters, even the seemingly impossible can be tackled if you can find and use the right kind of <A HREF="fear17.html" NAME="">support</A>.<P><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
