</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Travelog 1996 - Alexandria and the Nile delta - The gen</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><BASEFONT SIZE=4><A NAME="TOP"><P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 CELLSPACING=1>	<TR>		<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=76><A HREF="../travelog.html"><IMG SRC="../smtrav.gif" ALT="Travelog home page" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=76 BORDER=1"></A></TD>		<TD VALIGN TOP><P><FONT SIZE=6>Alexandria and the Nile delta - the gen</FONT></TD>			</TR></TABLE><DL><DD><DL><DD>		<FONT SIZE=4>		<A HREF="#001">Past</A>		<BR><A HREF="#002">Past and present</A>		<BR><A HREF="#003">Getting there</A>		<BR><A HREF="#004">Links</A>				<P><A HREF="alexat1.html">return to Alexandria and the Nile delta page</A></FONT>		</DL></DD></DL></DD><P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 CELLSPACING=1>	<TR>		<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=76><IMG SRC="alexmap1.gif" WIDTH=76 ALT="Inset map" ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0></TD>		<TD VALIGN TOP><IMG SRC="alexmap2.gif" WIDTH=440 HEIGHT=324 ALT="Main Map" ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0></TD>	</TR></TABLE><DL><DD><DL><DD><P><A NAME="001"><H2><B>Past</B></H2><P>Alexandria, Egypt's main port, was founded in 332 BC by <A HREF="http://www.lance.colostate.edu:80/auth/home/eng/Makedonia/Alexander_the_Great.html">Alexander the Great</A>, but Alexander never actually saw the city. Having ordered his architect to build Egypt a new capital, he left in search of new conquests.<P>For more than 1,000 years Alexandria was not only the capital of Egypt but the main centre of Hellenistic culture, but unfortunately comparatively few relics of antiquity remain. The Pharos - the first lighthouse and one of the seven wonders of the ancient world - has long since disappeared, and the world-famous Alexandrian library was destroyed in 641. Two obelisks, which once stood before the Caesarum temple, are now in London (Cleopatra's Needle) and New York respectively.<P>However, Pompey's Pillar (see <A HREF="alexat3.html">Postcard</A>), survives, and in recent years more of Alexander's heritage has been uncovered by accident: the catacombs were found when a donkey fell through the roof, and the Roman amphitheatre was unearthed by workers digging the foundations for yet another apartment block.<P>Tourists interested in historic remains should bear in mind that each official site charges 30 for a permit to use a video camera and 2 for a stills camera.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME="002"><H2><B>Past and present</B></H2><P><IMG SRC="alexapic4.gif" BORDER=3><P>As a tourist destination Egypt is mainly sold through its history - so much so that it comes as something of a surprise to find there's actually a living country there. But <B>Alexandria</B> - vast, busy and enticing, if rather shabby - is certainly very much alive. It's a favourite haunt for Egyptians escaping the heat and dust of Cairo in the summer, but is largely ignored by foreign tourists. Some well-known Europeans have felt its allure, however - E M Forster and Lawrence Durrell are among the writers who have found it an inspirational base. Both stayed at the elegant Hotel Cecil (00 20 3 807055), in the middle of the city. Rooms cost about 36 per person per night for a twin room.<P><IMG SRC="alexapic3.gif" BORDER=3><IMG SRC="alexapic2.gif" BORDER=3><P>Foreign tourists are still more scarce in the <B>Nile delta</B>, a flat, fertile area which is a refreshing change after the hubbub of Alexandria. <I>Travelog</I>'s guest presenter Stephanie Calman visited <B>Tanta</B>, the capital of the Gharbiya province - which incidentally is the only place in the delta with a hotel. Tanta's mosque, dedicated to a 12th-century Moroccan pilgrim who subsequently became a Muslim saint, is visited by present-day pilgrims from across Egypt, and each April and August religious festivals are held in his honour. The mosque is a magnificent sight, and visitors are welcome.<P><A HREF="http://gds.esrin.esa.it/C0xc1cce622_0x0000e9c6;sk%3D4BE3DE97">Image of the Nile River Delta</A><P>The nearby colonial town of <B>Ismailiyia</B> is, like Alexandria, a popular holiday destination for Egyptians. It is named after Khedive Ismail, one of the men behind the creation of the Suez Canal. The canal was controlled by an international council of 33 (including 10 British representatives) until it was forcibly nationalised by President Nasser of Egypt in 1956. From the beach on Lake Timseh you can watch convoys of ships preparing to make the 125-mile voyage - 76 ships a day now come through the channel, paying tolls upwards of $70,000 each. <P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME="003"><H2><B>Getting there</B></H2><P>British passport holders require a visa to enter Egypt. It costs about 15 and is available through the Egyptian Embassy. Visas can also be arranged by tour operators.<P>There are no direct flights to Alexandria from the United Kingdom, but Cairo is only three or four hours away by road. <B>Egyptair</B> (0171 437 6309) fly twice weekly to Cairo from London Heathrow. Return flights start at 250 plus airport tax.<P><B>British Airways</B> (0181 897 4000) fly daily from Heathrow. They currently have a 'World Offer' fare starting at 429 plus tax, which runs until 31 March. After 31 March the cheapest fare is 525 plus tax.<P>The Nile delta is not promoted as a tourist destination. If you want to travel through it you'll have to insist, or you'll be taken around it by the unattractive but faster desert roads. No tour operators offer tours through the delta, so you'll need to travel independently or use a company that offers tailor-made tours. <B>Misr Travel</B> (0171 255 1087), the government travel agency, offer both tailor-made and basic package tours to Egypt.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME="004"><H2><B>Links</B></H2><P>This following only a brief selection of the wealth of related sites on the Web:<P><A HREF="http://pharos.bu.edu/Egypt/Alexandria/"><IMG SRC="alex_title.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP BORDER=1">Alaa Ashmawy's Alexandria:</A> excellent guide to the city past and present.<BR CLEAR=LEFT><P><A HREF="http://its-idsc.gov.eg/tourism/">Egypt Tourist Authority home page</A>: links to information about the Red Sea, Cairo, Luxor, Aswan, Sinai, Alexandria and oases.<P><A HREF="http://163.121.10.41/tourism/docs/alex/">Egypt Tourist Authority - Alexandria</A>: includes map, history and tourist information.<P><A HREF="http://www.idsc.gov.eg/">Egypt's Information Highway</A>: information on culture, the environment, health and tourism.<P><A HREF="http://www.eecs.uic.edu/~khaggag/egypt.html">Guide to Egypt</A>: land, people, places and historical background. Includes information on Alexandria.<P><A HREF="http://www.channel1.com/users/mansoorm/index.html">Egypt Interactive</A>: religion; culture; travel; language; online museums, displays, etc.; sites in Egypt.<P><A HREF="http://pages.prodigy.com/G/U/N/guardian/egypt.htm">Guardian's Egypt Page</A> - links for Egypt and Egyptology.<P><A HREF="http://santos.doc.ic.ac.uk/~mmg/VisitEgypt.html">Planning your visit to Egypt</A> - good links for tourists.<P><A HREF="http://www.colostate.edu/Orgs/MSA/docs/holidays.html">Islamic Holidays and Observances</A><P><A HREF="http://santos.doc.ic.ac.uk/~mmg/EgyptianInfo.html">Index to Egyptian Information on the Internet</A><P><A HREF="http://www.mordor.com/hany/egypt/egypt.html">The Egyptian Gallery</A>: pictures, music and songs - real-time and downloadable.<P> <A HREF="http://santos.doc.ic.ac.uk/~mmg/recipes.html">Egyptian Recipes</A><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
