<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Travelog 1996 - Postcard from Alexandria</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><BASEFONT SIZE=4><A NAME="TOP"><P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 CELLSPACING=1>	<TR>		<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=76><A HREF="../travelog.html"><IMG SRC="../smtrav.gif" ALT="Travelog home page" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=76 BORDER=1"></A></TD>		<TD VALIGN TOP><P><FONT SIZE=6>Postcard from Alexandria</FONT>	</TR></TABLE>		<DL><DD><DL><DD> <FONT SIZE=4><P><A HREF="alexat1.html">return to Alexandria and the Nile delta page</A></FONT><P><IMG SRC="alexapc1.gif" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=440 HEIGHT=359 BORDER=0><P><FONT SIZE=5><B>Egypt's history is one of its main selling points, but some relics are reluctant to reveal their secrets. Pompey's Pillar is a case in point. The guide at the site explained he couldn't be filmed doing his routine because he was a government employee, and unfortunately <I>Travelog</I>'s own researches only seemed to thicken the fog. Apparently Pompey's Pillar was so named because the Crusaders thought that Pompey was worshipped here - but he wasn't. The pillar was in fact erected to honour the Roman emperor Diocletian for saving the city from famine - but it turns out Diocletian's siege caused the famine in the first place. Thankfully there's an inscription at the bottom of the pillar. It's to Ptolemy's wife, who seems to have had nothing to do with any of it.</B></FONT><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
