<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Trial and Error: Chowdhary</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000c42" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H1><A HREF="trial.html">Trial and Error</A></H1><P><IMG SRC="chowdhary.gif" ALIGN=top><P><H3>On 27 June 1996 Channel 4's <I>TRIAL AND ERROR</I> looked at the conviction of Jamil Chowdhary for a brutal murder carried out during a raid on a petrol station on 1 February 1991. This is an edited transcript of the programme which raised serious questions about the evidence used to convict Chowdhary - and used the latest technology to demonstrate he could not have been the killer.</H3><P><A HREF="#001">False number plates</A><BR><A HREF="#002">Nazir's false accusations</A><BR><A HREF="#003">Jamil the womaniser</A><BR><A HREF="#004">Independent witnesses</A><BR><A HREF="#005">Nazir changes his story</A><BR><A HREF="#006">Jury directed to disregard evidence</A><BR><A HREF="#007">The doubts creep in</A><BR><A HREF="#008">Jealous girlfriends</A><BR><A HREF="#009">Pressure on interviewees</A><BR><A HREF="#010">Who benefited from Chowdhary's conviction?</A><BR><A HREF="#011">Marlene 'told police lies'</A><BR><A HREF="#012">Gaps in police log</A><BR><A HREF="#013">A lot of inaccuracies</A><BR><A HREF="#014">Crucial evidence</A><BR><A HREF="#015">'I couldn't have picked him out'</A><BR><A HREF="#016">300 for helping in the case</A><BR><A HREF="#017">Security camera evidence</A><BR><A HREF="#018">Virtual reality</A><BR><A HREF="#019">Technology convinces the expert</A><BR><A HREF="#020">An unsolved crime</A><BR><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"><B><P>The Hampshire village of Phoenix Green is split in two by the busy A30. There's not much to it - the Phoenix Inn provides a sandwich for the hungry traveller. And the petrol station next door caters for thirsty engines on the long drive from London to the south west and back.<P>By night the traffic flashes by more urgently, hurrying home. You would only stop at the service station for a good reason - if petrol was running low. Or, as was the case five years ago, for an especially evil purpose.<P>Sophie Ashworth was on the garage till, chatting with two friends, on the night of 1 February 1991. At a quarter to nine, she saw a man come into the kiosk. He helped himself to a soft drink and went as if to pay. At the same time an accomplice darted in. He told Sophie to empty the till and her friends to lie on the floor.<P>Suddenly there was the sound of a shot and the air was full of feathers. For a few stunned seconds, Sophie thought it was a terrible practical joke. But the feathers were from the eiderdown jacket of one of Sophie's friends, as the gun exploded into his back. 17 year old Raymond Kelly was dead.<P>At that very moment Alexandra Bridgeman pulled up on the forecourt, with her ten year-old passenger. 'Roy was in the back seat banging on the window saying robbers, robbers, go, go!,' she remembers. 'So I look up and I see them in the shop. I threw the petrol pump flying and jumped in my car. I started my car up and they ran out of the shop and were running down the road.'<P>Sophie Ashworth dialled 999 and the police immediately threw a cordon round the area. At least seven police cars took up stationary positions, monitoring the passing traffic. Details flashed to these so-called statics grew more specific by the minute. Nineteen minutes after the killing, the control room radioed descriptions of the two suspects.<P><DL><DD><I>...white male, 6'3", thin build, black jeans, white trainers... suspect two: white male, 6'3", slim build but heavier... black woolly hat and balaclava...</I></DL></DD></B></DL></DD><P><A NAME="001"><B><H3>False number plates</H3></B><DL><DD><P>PC Keith Gibson was manning one of the static points. At four minutes past nine, he logged a red car - an Escort XR3i, he thought - with the distinctive number-plate - JAB9. But JAB9 isn't just a distinctive number plate. It's a false number plate. At least it is when it's attached to a red Escort XR3i.<P>What's more, JAB9 had been stopped by the police as a suspicious vehicle just thirty-six hours earlier. Its details had been fed into the police national computer. The driver had also given the police a false name - Michael Smith.<P>The man driving JAB9 that day was Womiq Nazir, who often uses the name Michael Smith. Nazir's light skin fits the white murder suspect the police were looking out for. Nazir was from a tough criminal set in Slough; he was lying low in the relative quiet of Reading.<P>This is how Jamil's friend Bobby Chowdhary (no relation) describes Womiq Nazir. 'He didn't fit into our way of life. When he came on the scene he started to mingle with us, but no-body would accept him because of his character. He was a hardened criminal. He would talk about things, like I mean guns and heavy drugs, which was not our scene at all. I mean the worst we thought we were being was smoking cannabis, you know, and we were trying to keep that under control.'<P>Nazir was in prison on another charge just six weeks after the garage killing, awaiting trial for slashing a man whose house he'd broken into.<P>Interviewed in jail, and hoping to do a deal on this charge, he hinted he could help the police about the Phoenix Green murder. His own involvement doesn't surprise those who know Nazir as a man with a hair-trigger temperament who often went out with a gun.<P>This is what one former associate of Nazir has to say. 'He knew he couldn't handle himself so he'd always have a tool or something, do you know what I mean? I went out with him once and we got into a nice car, it was a few years ago now, obviously. Got into a car and took out a double barrelled shot-gun and we were cruising around in the car. And he was in the back seat and I remember exactly what it was on the back seat, it was a samurai sword on the back seat and the gun was in the boot, you know? If we wanted a war we would have got a war. If we had somebody looking for us or if he had someone looking for him, we wouldn't have had any problems. Know what I mean?'</DL></DD><P><A NAME="002"><B><H3>Nazir's false accusations</H3></B><DL><DD><P>In prison, Nazir began to spin the police who came to see him a web of self-serving deception. He first named as accomplice a young woman called Marlene Thomas. This was doubly treacherous. Marlene was his lover and he had even got her to burn his clothes when he came home the night of the murder.<P>According to Nazir's former associate, 'You couldn't trust him. Once you're arrested you don't know what he's going to say, do you know what I mean? That's why when I came back on the streets I wasn't too quick in running back to the person I used to make money with. I didn't want to know him.'<P>The next person Nazir falsely accused was his flatmate, Rajinder Dhaliwal. The police went to the flat they shared in Reading to arrest him.<P>'He was evil. I always said that from day one,' says Dhaliwal. 'Even my friends that used to come round, they all used to say that there is something funny about him. I couldn't even believe they were arresting me for murder. I was just laughing it off. I was saying no, because I didn't have anything to hide. I knew where I was. I knew I was working. I was just glad I had an alibi.'<P>Dhaliwal thinks a great deal about what might have happened without that alibi. 'I don't know how to put it. Whenever I feel bad or sometimes I think things aren't going right for me then I think back and I think to myself, well, you know what I mean. I could have been in a different place today.'<P>After accusing Rajinder Dhaliwal, Nazir also accused Rajinder's brother Abdul. 'Well, I heard a knock on the door and I opened the door and there was about 20 policemen there. They just burst through the door. And they said you and your brother are under arrest for the murder of so and so. And I don't know what I said - are you serious, you know? I didn't know what was going on. They took me and my brother to the police station and questioned us. They questioned me for about seven hours before they let me go and my brother came out about five hours after that.'<P>After a series of evidently false accusations, the police would have had good reason to be cautious about the integrity of Nazir's word. But Nazir came up with yet another name - the name of someone else who shared the flat in Reading - Jamil Chowdhary.<P>Nazir said Chowdhary was with him at the Phoenix Green garage. Nazir even accused him of another murder, which the police knew he couldn't have committed.<P>When he was arrested three months afterwards Jamil Chowdhary just couldn't remember where he had been on the Friday night of the murder. As likely as not, he had been hanging out at a club - Scruples in Reading, the Majestic or even Martine's of Basingstoke.<P>His friends Bobby Chowdhary and Rajinder Dhaliwal said that most days they would go out nightclubbing with Jamil, such a lively guy who always made people laugh. Once they had driven all the way to Swansea at 9 o'clock at night just to go to a club.</DL></DD><P><A NAME="003"><B><H3>Jamil the womaniser</H3></B><DL><DD><P>Chowdhary liked to have fun, and he liked others to have it, too. But though he was generous with his money, he was spendthrift in his affections.<P>Bobby Chowdhary describes Jamil as a womaniser. 'He had so many woman, so many girlfriends. We envied him for that in some instances. But he was always the leader figure when it came to going out and having a good time.'<P>One of Jamil's conquests was Marlene Thomas, the girlfriend of Nazir - the man who falsely accused him. While Nazir was behind bars Chowdhary, a fast worker, had added Marlene to his string of lovers.<P>As a letter to Marlene shows, Womiq Nazir was not happy about this breach of criminal etiquette. As for Jamil Ahmed Chowdhary - Nazir would get get even somehow. And what could be a deadlier revenge than a false accusation of murder?<P>Both men were charged with the murder. Womiq Nazir admitted he had been there - eye witness descriptions of what he'd been wearing that night, and the security videotape, supported the Crown's case that he was the first man to go into the service station. The Crown accepted Nazir's claim that it was Chowdhary who followed him and Chowdhary who pulled the trigger.<P>Marlene Thomas seemed to corroborate Nazir's story that Chowdhary was his accomplice. The 17-year-old had admitted she'd got rid of the gun for Nazir and so was herself vulnerable to a charge of being an accessory to murder.<P>The tape recording of her police interview provided confirmation that the two men were together on the fatal night, as this transcript shows.<I><DL><DD><P>MARLENE THOMAS: The night that it happened, Jamil and Womiq, they went about in a white car, and they took the gun. I didn't know where they was going or what they was doing. Jamil was there at the petrol station and...<P>DETECTIVE: Now, when you say the petrol station, are we talking about the one where Raymond Kelly was shot?<P>MARLENE THOMAS: I don't where it is, but the petrol station, and they went there.<P>DETECTIVE: What did they go there for?<P>MARLENE THOMAS: Well, after they had done it, Womiq told me that they went there to get some money, to hold the petrol station up...<P>DETECTIVE: Cast your mind back and tell me what happened when they came back...<P>MARLENE THOMAS : ...Womiq came in first and... he just said, 'Leave me alone,' so I left him. I went back in there and he said 'I've just done something really bad' and that he was going away and he couldn't come and see me but I could go and see him and that's when he meant prison...<P>DETECTIVE: What about Jamil, because we're still skirting around Jamil, aren't we?<P>MARLENE THOMAS: I didn't see Jamil. At that time I was in the bathroom with Womiq.<P>DETECTIVE: But you've been...but you are aware that they have gone out to work.<P>MARLENE THOMAS: Yeah.</I></DL></DD><P>The police case depended on the word of Nazir, a liar and a thief - and his girlfriend, a woman who had helped to get rid of the murder weapon. The evidence against Chowdhary needed independent support, and that came from witnesses who'd seen two men loitering at another garage nearby that same night.</DL></DD><P><A NAME="004"><B><H3>Independent witnesses</H3></B><DL><DD><P>One of them, John Cole, later identified Chowdhary. 'They were acting very suspiciously. There was a hole in the fence near to where they were standing which offered a very good vantage point of the front of the garage and of the garage forecourt. I'd say they were looking through that hole to sus it out really.'<P>But the final, clinching clue in the case against Chowdhary only came to light when the police raided the minicab office which Chowdhary ran. When the police went to Chowdhary's office, they were to find the fatal JAB9 number-plate which the static officer had registered within a few miles of the murder and within minutes of it taking place.<P>If Jamil Chowdhary is the killer, it's odd that he should use a car with such a distinctive number plate, and a car that had actually been stopped by the police just the day before. It's odd that having used the car in a killing he should hold onto the number plates and display them like some grim trophy. And yet it was all beginning to fit - provided Nazir could be believed.<P>At trial, the case was completed with two statements from prisoners that Chowdhary had admitted the murder while on remand at Winchester prison. But there was another reason why the odds of justice were stacked against Jamil Chowdhary.</DL></DD><P><A NAME="005"><B><H3>Nazir changes his story</H3></B><DL><DD><P>After first telling the police Chowdhary was his accomplice, Nazir then denied he'd ever been at Phoenix Green himself. Extraordinarily, on the very first day of his trial in Winchester he switched his story yet again, this time admitting his part in the robbery, but still denying any guilt for the shooting. This prevarication inevitably wrong-footed Chowdhary's defence.<P>Chowdhary's solicitor, John Wroe, said that they arrived in court with no indication that he was going to change his plea. 'He'd served a notice of alibi only a few days earlier saying, I think, that he was in Slough and suddenly out of the blue he changed his plea at the door of the court. It caught us by surprise because Nazir's position was obviously fundamental to the case.<P>'If Mr Chowdhary had been tried on his own there would have been very few witnesses. But because he was tried jointly with Nazir there were a large number of witnesses who were called to give evidence against Nazir. Unfortunately through the back door they also gave evidence against Chowdhary. If Chowdhary had been tried alone that evidence would not have been admissible. Our QC asked for a re-trial on the basis that that was unfair to Chowdhary.'</DL></DD><P><A NAME="006"><B><H3>Jury directed to disregard evidence</H3></B><DL><DD><P>The judge then directed the jury to disregard evidence which was admissible against Nazir but not admissible against Chowdhary. In other words, the jury had to put out of their minds completely anything that might have come up in the same case against Nazir when they were dealing with Chowdhary. John Wroe describes this as 'asking them to perform mental gymnastics which they're not qualified to perform.'<P>But another factor was to count against Jamil Chowdhary. The judge at his trial said Chowdhary had the morals of a tomcat. And it's fair to say that he had a pretty approximate view of sexual fidelity. He wasn't just sleeping with the girlfriend of his accuser but at one stage he had up to eleven girls on the go. The case against Chowdhary was built partly on the jealous resentment of unsuspecting girlfriends - and partly on police evidence which itself was not always above suspicion.<P>Chowdhary was always a man on the move. He had to be with so many different girlfriends on the go. That's one reason why Chowdhary's account of his whereabouts on any one day can be a little approximate. He would tell one girl he was just off with the lads - but he'd more likely be round with any one of a dozen other girls.<P>The mother of his child, Sharon Chowdhary, had a lot to put up with. 'He did have a lot of other women, mainly because he was a good-looking guy and the women used to go for him,' she says. 'I think it was a challenge to him.'<P>Jamil's job running a taxi firm gave him the chance to flit between assignations, and be somewhere else before anyone had even noticed he'd left. Rajinder Dhaliwal said he had never met a womaniser like his friend Jamil. Another friend, Bobby Chowdhary (no relation) says, 'There's one girl knocking on the door and he's hiding one in one bedroom and then another girl knocks and he's hiding in the back room and there's one phoning up and, you know, there's so many of them.'<P>Rajinder used to provide Jamil with an alibi when he wanted to go out to meet another girlfriend. 'He used to say Jinda, you want to go to the petrol station to get a drink or something or want to go to the shop. So I'd give him a lift and he'd disappear.'<P>But one person took a stern view of Chowdhary's wild ways - Jamie Chowdhary, Jamil's elder brother, a wealthy and respected businessman who manufactured electronic equipment. 'Morally, I totally disapproved. The behaviour pattern can only lead one way and I'm sad it did it lead him into very serious problems. Nobody wants to say, there you are I was right.<P>'Sadly I was infuriated, annoyed, upset and so therefore when he was arrested and the subsequent trial took place I refused to have any part in it. I walked away. My answer to all this was, I told him so, he didn't listen and so therefore he must pay the price.'</DL></DD><P><A NAME="007"><B><H3>The doubts creep in</H3></B><DL><DD><P>Jamie Chowdhary's perspective on his younger brother owes a lot to his own past. In earlier days, he was one of the first non-white policemen recruited into London's Metropolitan force.<P>'Eventually, and I think this must have been about a year and a half later, I did go and visit him, under some pressure I must admit. The pressure being the family saying, look you must listen to him he wants to talk to you. So I went and I didn't say an awful lot. It was about a two hour visit. And it was when I came back out and drove back home to Reading for about two hours that I did an awful lot of thinking. I minced over what he'd told me and the doubt started to creep in.'<P>The raw material of the evidence which put Chowdhary behind bars for life included taped interviews with a series of Chowdhary's girlfriends - interviews sometimes conducted under the threat of a murder charge, and the explicit prospect of a life sentence in Holloway. Most of what they say does nothing to link him to the crime - but at trial the parade of Chowdhary's lovers was to leave a damning impression of a an unscrupulous liar and cheat.<P>Police arrested Heather Gale when she was just 18 and told her she was being held in connection with murder. This extract from the tape shows the police are understandably anxious to find the man responsible for this terrible crime - but how can they expect to find the truth in such a weak and impressionable witness, under such obvious pressure?<I><DL><DD><P>POLICEMAN: Let's have the lot now. Let's get it over with. Get it done because I don't want to see you in that dock at the end of the day as an accomplice to murder. You've been nicked for murder, you're here for murder. You've got your family; you've got everyone else to think of - you've got your life to sort out; you've got your whole life in front of you. Don't throw it away in Holloway Prison, sweetheart. Alright.<P>POLICEMAN: He's been different since that.	<P>HEATHER GALE: I know, I know he's been... he hit me.<P>POLICEMAN: He's been different since that.<P>SECOND POLICEMAN: The violence has started even more since then.<P>POLICEMAN: I bet he has because he killed someone, that's why.<P>(GALE weeps.)</I></DL></DD><P>From another tape it's clear that the girlfriend Chowdhary had taken from Nazir, Marlene Thomas, was exasperated to the point of a patently false confession.<I><DL><DD><P>MARLENE THOMAS: There is nothing for me to worry about. I never done it; I wasn't there. I haven't done it.<P>POLICEMAN: You haven't done it?<P>MARLENE THOMAS: I wasn't there. I haven't done it.<P>POLICEMAN: I would have hoped if you were there, driving the car, maybe, sat in the car...<P>MARLENE THOMAS: Alright, I was driving the car, I done it, I went in there. Happy now?</I></DL></DD></DL></DD><P><A NAME="008"><B><H3>Jealous girlfriends</H3></B><DL><DD><P>The tape of Heather Gale's interview certainly shows the police exploited that most unreliable of emotions - jealousy.<I><DL><DD><P>POLICEMAN: There's some things you don't know about Jamil... You've been taken for a ride and this is going to upset you. What do you think I'm talking about?<P>HEATHER GALE: I don't know.<P>POLICEMAN: Where do you think Jamil went Saturday night when he left you? I'll tell you what he did. He went to pick Marlene up and they went to Liverpool... that's where Jamil and Marlene were arrested this morning. That's where he went with Marlene. Now I told you it would hurt and I told you we'd be honest with you. I'm sorry, sweetheart, but you've heard that much and I'll tell you something else. He's been seeing Caroline English. I can tell you he's been ringing Caroline English after ringing you because we've looked at the phone accounts. I'll tell you something else. He's been seeing Alison Blight.</I></DL></DD><P>Says Jamie Chowdhary, 'If you listen to those tapes and you hear these young girls, most of them quite young, being threatened or being charged with murder and then being told things like, do you know he was with such and such a girl last night and playing one off against the other. It didn't take them an awful lot of coaxing to get these girls to perform exactly how they wanted them to.'</DL></DD><P><A NAME="009"><B><H3>Pressure on interviewees</H3></B><DL><DD><P>Solicitor John Wroe says, 'Sometimes they simply put pressure on the particular interviewee by reminding them they were on suspicion, being arrested on suspicion of murder. Sometimes it was done in a rather different way. In one situation they actually had a photograph of a girl who was one of Jamil's girlfriends, taken in bed, clearly partly naked and from time to time as other girlfriends were interviewed they were shown a copy of that photograph.<P>'One of the ways in which the prosecution sought to discredit him was to simply say, well, here is a man with six girlfriends, clearly immoral and there was a place to draw really a rather large conclusion from the fact that he had rather a large number of girlfriends.'<P>Sharon Chowdhary believes it was this that really did for Chowdhary. 'All the different women, the police were really playing them against each other. Like one of the girls, they said to her, was he with you on New Year's? Oh no, he was with such and such wasn't he, to make her think, well he told me he was working or he told me he was here. And she would get angry and think to herself, right I'm going to tell them what they want me to say.'<P>As Jamie Chowdhary points out, 'I think if I was a 17, 18 or 19 year old girl, first time ever in police custody, then I would say anything under that pressure to just get out of the place.'<P>These days the police are being re-educated about how they conduct interviews. They're being told not to interrogate people on the basis that they already know the answers. This isn't soft policing, it's intelligent policing. Because the police, like all of us, can make mistakes. It just matters more when the police act on a conviction which is unshakeable but which also happens to be mistaken.</DL></DD><P><A NAME="010"><B><H3>Who benefited from Chowdhary's conviction?</H3></B><DL><DD><P>But as well as questioning the interviewing techniques, <I>Trial and Error</I> asked about the extraordinary number of people in this case who seem to have benefited from their accusations against Jamil Chowdhary.<P>A month after Chowdhary's conviction one of the prisoners who testified to his so-called cell-block confession came up for trial. Maurice Nedd is a multiple rapist. But the judge clearly recognised the help he'd given in Chowdhary's conviction when he said he was lightening Nedd's sentence for the rape of a 20 year old student 'to take account of his assistance.' It was his Nedd's conviction for rape.<P>Other prisoners say they were asked to help build the case against Chowdhary. Letters from two convicted criminals claim that they were manipulated and induced to say that Chowdhary had also made admissions to them.<P>And, while many of Chowdhary's girlfriends were arrested on suspicion of being accessories to murder, none was charged. Not even Marlene Thomas, who admitted handling the shotgun and burning Nazir's clothes afterwards.<P>Marlene's evidence was more damning than that of the other girls. They had portrayed Chowdhary as a rogue - Marlene identified him as Womiq Nazir's accomplice on the night of the murder.<P>Chowdhary's solicitor John Wroe says her evidence was absolutely fundamental to the case. 'Because without Marlene Thomas the prosecution wouldn't have been able to show that on the night in question, Chowdhary allegedly left the flat together with Nazir and also that he returned shortly after.'<P>Marlene Thomas says she wants to put that part of her life behind her now. She says she's forgotten almost everything anyway. Given the drugs she used to take, life for Marlene Thomas was never in very sharp focus. The threat of a life sentence must have concentrated her mind.<P>'It was a lot of stress for me to cope with at the time,' she remembers. 'I didn't have my family around me, you know, because I'd left home and I'd left Womiq. I didn't have anyone to support me or to back me up so to speak. I felt a bit lost you know? And most of it... I'd go along with anything...'<P>Marlene says she sometimes gave the police the answers she felt they were looking for. 'Because I thought if I said, I don't know, certain things then probably I could go home. I didn't think, you know that I'd be kept in there for that length of time. So I thought keep them sweet, you know, and then I can go home, just get on with it.'<P><I>Trial and Error</I> asked Marlene if Womiq and Jamil actually went out together, as if they were going to do something together, and then came back together as though they had done something together.<P>Marlene replied that she couldn't say for certain that they did and said it was possible the two had gone out at different times from each other. 'I don't know, they might have gone together, they might not have gone together. I mean they might not have even been together.'<P>When <I>Trial and Error</I>'s David Jessel pressed the point, reminding Marlene how important her evidence had been at trial - when she had said they left together and they came back together, she replied, 'But I'm saying I can't remember. Like I said it was a long time ago.'<P>Jamil Chowdhary's solicitor John Wroe described how Marlene's integrity was questioned at the trial. ' I think one of the comments that she made was that she told lies and deliberate lies and to be fair she didn't distinguish between the two, but clearly those remarks were to suggest that she was unreliable.</DL></DD><P><A NAME="011"><B><H3>Marlene 'told police lies'</H3></B><DL><DD><P>'Somewhat unusually she contacted my office. When I say she, I can't say for certain that it was Marlene Thomas, but certainly somebody claiming to be Marlene Thomas telephoned me to say she wanted to make an appointment to see me. I explained to her that if she was a prosecution witness I wouldn't able to see her. I didn't ask her anything about the case but she did volunteer that what she told the police was all lies and she also suggested that they effectively had told her what she should say.'<P>John Wroe was not able to follow this up as it could have been suggested that he was attempting to influence a key prosecution witness.<P>But what about the tangible evidence that the police found when they raided Chowdhary's cab office? Chowdhary has never denied having those number plates, nor that he knew they were false.<P>They were on a car of one of his many girlfriends - a car used at different times by both Chowdhary and Nazir, a car apparently logged by PC Gibson at the Swallowfield Roundabout close to the murder scene and soon after the shooting.</DL></DD><P><A NAME="012"><B><H3>Gaps in police log</H3></B><DL><DD><P>PC Gibson's log was obviously a crucial document in the case, but it's far from straightforward. Indeed, the log seems to pose more questions than it answers.<P>Why, for instance, should PC Gibson note the description of the robbers as coming through at 21.00, when we know the police radio room doesn't record the message as being sent until four minutes later? And what about that JAB9 entry which was so central to the case against Chowdhary?<P>Why was there a gap underneath this key entry, when all the others are in a continuous list? Or - on a busy road - the eight minutes that seem to have passed between cars? Or the apparent variation in the layout of the entries?<P>But the biggest problem is what isn't in the document. PC Gibson's job was to keep a comprehensive log, but it's not a complete record. Details are missing. Or destroyed. In fact Gibson himself threw them away next day - he said he hadn't thought them relevant.<P>According to John Wroe, 'The curious thing about it is how did the officer know which numbers were relevant, because of course Chowdhary wasn't arrested until three months later. It was only three months later that the police were trying to establish that JAB9 was involved and was relevant.<P>'So that on the evening in question the officer would have had no means at all of knowing which entries on those lists were relevant. But what the officer was effectively saying was, I destroyed some numbers and I can assume I destroyed them because they weren't relevant. But at that stage he couldn't have known which numbers were relevant and which weren't. It's certainly worrying.'<P>Dave Burden was twenty-five years with the Essex police and is an expert on police procedures. He also pioneered the development of HOLMES - the Home Office computer system used to investigate major murders.</DL></DD><P><A NAME="013"><B><H3>A lot of inaccuracies</H3></B><DL><DD><P>'I find it to be incomprehensible. I just don't understand what he's playing at at all. One would have thought that any vehicle passing that point would have been of some interest to the incident room, be it the number of persons in the vehicle or be it the times that vehicle that actually passed that point. <P>'There seem to be a lot of inaccuracies on either side. There are inaccuracies in what was written down by the officer. There are inaccuracies in respect to the log showing the sequence of events in respect of what was happening at the scene. There are anomalies which really need to be clarified.'<P>Hampshire police wrote to <I>Trial and Error</I> saying that since they'd been advised that Chowdhary was pursuing an appeal, their own participation in the programme would be inappropriate.<P>But this log is at the core of the case, and much of it is still a mystery. And a murder case is too important to have inexplicable evidence at its heart.</DL></DD><P><A NAME="014"><B><H3>Crucial evidence</H3></B><DL><DD><P>A lot of things in this case aren't quite right. Too often evidence seems to be the result of pressure or apparent inducement. And yet, as <I>Trial and Error</I> has established, there was one independent piece of evidence which was staring the police in the face.<P>They either ignored it or misunderstood it - either way that was a pity, because it would have proved to the police that Jamil Chowdhary was not their man.<P>How would you begin to describe yourself? How do witnesses almost invariably begin to describe people they've seen? It's not the faces they begin with, or the clothes. It's the height. Tall, short or middling, it's the major characteristic which differentiates the face in the crowd.<P>Nick Reynals almost certainly saw the killers casing another garage earlier in the evening before they got to Phoenix Green. His sighting was in the dark, and positive identification was difficult. Reynals had been cycling down the lane and by the light of his Tilley lamp he'd seen a man who looked as if he needed some help. When he asked if he was all right, the man said he'd lost his wallet.<P>Nick Reynals stopped to help him try to find his wallet and a little while later, according to what he told the police, they were joined by another man, obviously an accomplice of the first.<P>This second man must have been Nazir - he was wearing a distinctive jacket and a Palestinian-style scarf like the one we know Nazir was wearing that night.<P>But what about the first man? The man claiming to be looking for his wallet, who according to the police case must therefore have been Chowdhary. Renals described him as 5' 8 to 5' 10. But Chowdhary is more than 6 foot.<P>This discrepancy must have worried the police. They took Mr Reynals back to the scene with a policeman, an officer considerably taller than he was. By photographing the two from various positions, they convinced Mr Reynals that in certain circumstances he could well have mistaken a six-footer like Chowdhary for someone shorter.<P>But Nick Reynals wasn't the only person to witness events that night. John Cole was coming down the lane in a car. He saw his friend Nick Reynals and helped in the search for the non-existent wallet.<P>Mr Cole saw both men, and months after the murder when Chowdhary was arrested he was asked to identify him as the man who had supposedly lost his wallet.<P>He says, 'Yeah, it was a bit embarrassing really because, you know, I was taken to Aldershot police station where they said they were going to do a cell identity parade which is confront me with the man they had in custody. And I was to say yes or no.</DL></DD><P><A NAME="015"><B><H3>'I couldn't have picked him out'</H3></B><DL><DD><P>'I went down to the cell with the police man and the cell door opened and there was a man standing there. Who looked similar to the man who I seen here but if it was in an identity parade I couldn't have said, I couldn't have picked him out as sworn alone. It wasn't an identity parade. It was just one man in a cell. I said, yes that looks like the man.'<P><I>Trial and Error</I> asked John Cole how certain he was that it was the man. He replied, 'I couldn't say. I was in the grip of the police, not in the grip of the police but in the whole... they said I was being slip-streamed and the whole thing was out of my hands. I was in police hands and they knew what the score was and how to run it and I was just being taken along, caught up in the wind so to speak.'<P>This ID evidence wasn't heard at trial - it wouldn't have stood up to scrutiny. But what about the matter of height. Nick Reynals had been persuaded that the short man he saw was in fact a six footer. What is Mr Cole's opinion?<P>'Well him and Nick were standing next to each other and I said they were basically the same height. That's about 5' 8 or 5' 9.' In the <I>Trial and Error</I> programme John Cole correctly estimated the height of presenter David Jessel as 5' 9 or 5' 10.<P>Jessel then asked him about the height of the other person that came to join in, the person with the scarf on? Cole replied, 'He was appreciably taller. About my height I would say. I'm 6' 1 or 6' 2.'<P>Cole then repeated that the man with the scarf round the bottom half of his face and with a woolly hat on his head was considerably taller than the person in the ditch. The man believed to be Nazir.<P>Now the puzzle began to make sense, why this question of height was such an issue for the police. Because if Mr Cole is right, and the man he saw pretending to look for his wallet was shorter than Nazir, then Nazir's accomplice could not have been Chowdhary. Because Chowdhary isn't shorter than Nazir. He's taller.<P>No wonder the police were concerned. But as for Mr Cole, there was an unexplained and inexplicable postscript to the story. 'I'd moved into a house at that stage and they came and gave me some money for my part in the trial.'</DL></DD><P><A NAME="016"><B><H3>300 for helping in the case</H3></B><DL><DD><P>Questioned by <I>Trial and Error</I>, Cole said he had been given 300 in cash in a brown paper envelope delivered by a man in a suit.<I><DL><DD><P>DAVID JESSEL: Did you sign for it?<P>JOHN COLE: No.<P>DAVID JESSEL: So a bloke comes along and says here's 300 for helping us in the case?<P>JOHN COLE: Yeah.<P>DAVID JESSEL: What did you say?<P>JOHN COLE: Thank you.</I></DL></DD><P>But what about the heights of the men responsible for the murder at the garage later that same evening? Statements from survivors of the dreadful attack are clear that the second man to enter the garage, the gunman, was shorter than Nazir.<P>So <I>Trial and Error</I> went back to the evidence of the security video camera on which the tragedy is so dispassionately enacted. We know that this man at the counter is Nazir. He admits it, and is wearing the right clothes. We don't see much of the killer. He darts right through the shot, and does his dreadful business out of frame.</DL></DD><P><A NAME="017"><B><H3>Security camera evidence</H3></B><DL><DD><P><I>Trial and Error</I> went to the experts to get the video enhanced. But there are limits to the process. There comes a stage when enhancing a blur just makes a bigger blur. This method, we concluded,would never produce the exact measurements of the two men at Phoenix Green. But then we realised we didn't need to know how tall each man was. All we needed to find out was how the heights of the two men compared with each other.<P>Because we know that the man at the counter is Nazir - and that Chowdhary is taller than he is. So if the gunman in the background is shorter, the killer just can't be Chowdhary.<P>We took the tape to Geoffrey Oxlee, an expert in video images. Apart from work with the police, Oxlee advises banks and other agencies on closed-circuit security systems.<P>Oxlee did two types of measurement. 'The first measurement was taken when both people came in through the door and I measured them from the top of the frame of the picture because I knew that to be constant, because I knew the camera was static and remained static right the way throughout the scene,' says Oxlee.<P>'So I measured the distance between the top of the frame to the top of the first man's head and the same for the second man and saw in fact the man that went to the counter came out to be taller than the man that subsequently went behind the counter.'<P>Oxlee did this first of all by reference to their heights as they came in through the door then he double checked it with another point of reference.<P>'There was another stage where both of them went quite near to a card rack. This enabled me to estimate - and it was an estimate in this case that they were standing on roughly the same spot. So I could measure them both at the same spot and get a difference in image size for the two and again I found that the man that came in and went to the counter was taller than the second man that came in.<P>'I'm bound to say, however, that because the imagery is relatively poor that means that these measurements that I made will have inaccuracies, they're not things that you could, if you like in a legal sense, fall on your sword about.'<P>That qualification is, in a legal sense, a problem. Recent experience of the Appeal Court suggests that the judges will attach much more weight to Oxlee's minor reservation than to his major calculation which effectively rules out Chowdhary. <I>Trial and Error</I> needed to go the extra mile, to make Chowdhary's innocence obvious to all.</DL></DD><P><A NAME="018"><B><H3>Virtual reality</H3></B><DL><DD><P>Our search for a clearer and unarguable conclusion took us into the realms of higher electronic technology. Didier Madoc-Jones and his company are pioneers in the field of virtual reality.<P>Architects and builders commission a virtual version of their two-dimensional blueprints so that they can virtually walk through the buildings they plan, virtually see what they look like... and feel the experience of being in them.<P>Recently, the technique has acquired an extra dimension. In forensic examinations, such as the Channel 4 <I>Dispatches</I> investigation into the Marchioness riverboat sinking on the Thames, virtual imaging built a chilling picture of the accident which killed 51 people.<P>Madoc-Jones explains, 'Any image you actually ever see is only two dimensional, but the data that has been used to manufacture that image is three dimensional.'<P>But could virtual reality provide the actual truth? Could it prove the relative heights of the men at the scene of the murder? More importantly, could our expert, already almost certain, be made fully sure?<P>Images from the security video were factored into a range of statistical information by Madoc-Jones to build a three dimensional computer model of the garage. Accuracy was guaranteed by checking the pictures against measurements taken by the police themselves.<P>For instance the video showed a cold drinks dispenser which is exactly 6' 6 high. Other dimensions were plotted with the same accuracy. Says Madoc-Jones, 'So when we digitised each individual image of the two intruders caught on the scene of crime video, we could place them with absolute accuracy within the model of the garage.<P>Geoffrey Oxlee asked about the relatively few images available and Madoc-Jones explained, 'Well, by taking as many positions as possible within the environment that begins not to eliminate the inaccuracies but even them out so we get a more accurate average.'<P>Using this technique, it becomes clear as we move around the computer model - indeed it becomes blindingly obvious - that the first man to enter the garage, Nazir, is taller than the gunman who enters later. Whatever way you look at it, and whatever way he's standing, he's always taller.<P>Taking the average apparent height of both men it becomes clear that the second man simply cannot be Chowdhary. Not if he's in fact taller than Nazir, which we know he is.</DL></DD><P><A NAME="019"><B><H3>Technology convinces the expert</H3></B><DL><DD><P>This is what Geoffrey Oxlee had to say. 'I think this is an aid to understanding because it's using technology at its very best to try and authenticate or deny a scientific thought about the actual scene that we're seeing. So from that point of view I think it's a good use of technology.'<P><I>Trial and Error</I> asked Oxlee if Didier Madoc-Jones had been able to put his worries to rest. He said yes. 'I think the worry is that you're dealing with a very poor image to start with and that means that any measurements you can make from it are bound to have some inaccuracies.<P>'But these largely, I think, been satisfied by the fact that they've used all of the images that were available and by averaging out, that would average out the systematic errors and the human errors that are actually inherent in the world.'<P>Oxlee was then asked if beyond any doubt it could be said that the man at the counter is taller than the man with the gun.<P>'Yes, I think that's an assumption that we can come to, at the end of the day. I think that the perception that the man is taller is certainly authenticated by all the work we've done and I would say in terms of probability that it's highly probable, if nothing else, that the man is taller. The man that came to the counter is taller than the man that went to the back of the garage.'</DL></DD><P><A NAME="020"><B><H3>An unsolved crime</H3></B><DL><DD><P>The cars still flash by Phoenix Green on their urgent journeys. And some will stop for petrol at the garage - most of them unaware of the tragedy played out here that night five years ago. A tragedy, however, missing the final scene - a crime still left unsolved.<P>Because of course that's the logic of this new evidence. If an innocent man is in prison then there's a guilty man still free, a man who had no trouble in getting a gun, and no conscience in taking a life.<P>Jamil Chowdhary's self-evident innocence means two things - that the Home Office should refer his case back to the Court of Appeal. And that the police should reopen the file on the Phoenix Green murder. Justice demands that both be done.<P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"><FONT SIZE=2><P>Published in 1996 by Channel 4 Television, 124 Horseferry Road, London SW1X 2DP to accompany <I>Trial and Error: Chowdhary</I>, a Just Television production for Channel 4.<P>Editor: Paula Snyder<BR>Design: Broadcasting Support Services<BR>Broadcasting Support Services provides follow up services for viewers and listeners and runs long-term helplines.<BR><P><I>Trial and Error: Chowdhary</I><P>Just Television, 11-15 Emerald Street, London WC1N 3QL<P>Written and Presented by	DAVID JESSEL<BR>Camera	INGRID DOMEIJ<BR>Assistant	NICHOLAS HOLMAN<BR>Sound	BILL LEWIS<BR>Graphic Design	STEVEN PICARD<BR>News Archive	BBC TV<BR>Title Music	ALAN COATES, KIM GOODY<BR>Original Music	ANDREW MORTON<BR>Film Editor	JURIS EKSTS<BR>On-Line Editor	NIGEL WILLIAMS<BR>Dubbing Mixer	NIGEL READ<BR>Production Team	LEONARD FIELD, SAM RAVENSCROFT<BR>Production Assistant	GLORIA MORRIS<BR>Production Manager	OLWYN SILVESTER<BR>Assistant Producer	DANNY ROSENBAUM<BR>Associate Producer	BOB DUFFIELD<BR>Executive Producer	STEPHEN PHELPS<BR>Produced and Directed by	STEVE HAYWOOD<BR></FONT><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
