		<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=140><IMG SRC="xpconn5gifs/xphirp3.gif"ALT="Photograph" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=140 HEIGHT=107 BORDER=0></A></TD>		<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=140><IMG SRC="xpconn5gifs/xphirp5.gif"ALT="Photograph" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=140 HEIGHT=107 BORDER=0></A></TD>				</TR>				<P><A NAME="001"><H2><B>Reining in the dogs of war</B></H2><P>South Africa can ill afford to turn down export earnings, but the success ofthe innocently named company Executive Outcomes is of a sort that the new SouthAfrica could well do without. <P>In recent years Executive Outcomes has mounted major operations in Angola and Sierra Leone, and is said to be negotiating several other multi-million-pound contracts. The company says it is a force for stability, providing a military advisory service to 'legitimate' governments. However, governments involved in a civil war have clearly failed to establish their legitimacy to everyone'ssatisfaction and may - as in the case of Sierra Leone -  have no mandate at all. InSouth Africa many believe that Executive Outcomes' 'advisers' are simply upmarket mercenaries, and that their activities actually fuel conflict.<P>William Sass, deputy director of Johannesburg's Institute for Defence Policyand a retired brigadier, says that Executive Outcomes' employees are true mercenariesin the sense that they are motivated by money, not nationalism or idealism. But headds thatthey are 'more like a managerial organisation offering services than a privatearmy' - although in Angola, as well as training and planning operations, they 'flew planes and might even have gotten involved in someshooting'.<P>Executive Outcomes won its first Angolan contract in 1992, when two oilcompanies hired the company to protect their installations. Then in 1993 the Angolangovernment awarded the company a 25 million contract to help defeat rebel UNITA forces.Fourteen hundred personnel were flown in to train the Angolan army. The government wasclearly impressed, signing another contract worth 60 million in 1994. William Sassconfirms that from the government's point of view it was money well spent: 'EO certainlyplayed a major role in shifting the military balance in favour of the MPLA.'<P>Since arriving in Sierra Leone, Executive Outcomes have helped secure a numberof areas against rebel forces. One of the first was the area containing the diamond mines, and this was made a priority, director Eeben Barlow admits, 'because thatdoes give us an insurance that there will be funds to pay us'.<P>As Executive Outcomes' role in Africa has become more public, political embarrassment in South Africa has intensified, and ministers say they are now determined to block the legal loopholes that have enabled the company to operate.'You cannot have peace and stability while mercenary or mercenary-type activitiescontinue,' says Aziz Pahad, the minister for foreign affairs. Unfortunately it's probably also true that while war and instability persist, so will the dogs ofwar.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME="002"><H2><B>Links</B></H2><P><A HREF="http://www.mg.co.za/mg/news/oct6denard2.html">Mail & Guardian - BobDenard:</A> rather romantic feature written by the biographer of the infamousmercenary at the beginning of his last coup attempt in the Comoros Islands.<P><AHREF="http://www.africaonline.com/AfricaOnline/cgi/postnews.cgi%3F960209%2Bsadcnews">AfricaOnline - Southern Africa:</A> daily news reports by local African news networks,and from various NGOs.<P><AHREF="http://neal.ctstateu.edu/history/world_history/archives/archive371.html">WorldHistory Archives: South Africa</A><P><A HREF="http://www.anc.org.za/"><IMG SRC="xpconn5gifs/ancflag.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP BORDER=1">African National Congress home page:</A>  includes news from South Africa and related Internet resources.<BR CLEAR=LEFT><P><A HREF="http://www.und.ac.za/und/trans/current.html">Transformation:Critical Perspectives on South Africa:</A> a quarterly South African journal thatprovides a forum for academic debate, discussion and review of current social,political and economic issues in Southern Africa (subscription).<P><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8BORDER=0></A></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
