<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Africa Express 1996 - Channel 4 Programme Support Online</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00"ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><BASEFONT SIZE=4><A NAME="TOP"><DL><DD><DL><DD><P><IMG SRC="xplogo.gif" WIDTH=440 HEIGHT=174 BORDER=0><P><I>Africa Express</I> uses Africa-based correspondents to seek outthe real stories behind the superficial coverage of the continent in thenews. Nigerian journalist Toyin Fani-Kayode covers West Africa;Joseph Warungu, a former news reporter and presenter for Kenya TelevisionNetwork, has East Africa as his home patch; South African TV journalistBeathur Baker joins the series to report on what is happening in SouthernAfrica.<P>These pages, which will be built on week by week, provide backgroundinformation on each report and resources for those wishing to find outmore.<P><A HREF="xpconn.html"><IMG SRC="xpconn.gif" ALT="Express connections" ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=88 HEIGHT=50 BORDER=0></A></TD><P><A HREF="xpconn.html"></A> <DL><P>Programme schedule with links tobackground information on each report, including suggestions for reading, contacts for further information and links to related Internet sites<BR CLEAR=LEFT></DL>		<P><A HREF="xplinks/xplinks.html"><IMG SRC="xplink.gif" ALT="Africa Links" ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=88 HEIGHT=50 BORDER=0></A></TD><P><DL> Links to and contacts for furtherinformation on Africa in general: politics, economics, culture and travel<BR CLEAR=LEFT></DL><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><P><FONT SIZE=2><P>Published 1996 by Channel 4 Television,124 Horseferry Road, London SW1P 2TX<P>Produced by Broadcasting Support Services to accompany <I>AfricaExpress</I>, made for Channel 4 by Barraclough Carey Productions. Withspecial thanks to Vincent Gasana/Barraclough Carey. Book research byAnthony Zurbrugg/The Africa Book Centre<P>Editor: Paula Snyder<P>Consultant editor: Peter Millson<P>Designer: Broadcasting Support Services<P>Maps: Norman Barnfather<P>Broadcasting Support Services providesfollow-up services for viewers and listeners and runs long-term helplines.</FONT><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8BORDER=0></A></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
