REF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME=001><B><H2>Programme 1</H2></B><P><A NAME=002><AHREF="xpconn1/xpcurt1.html"><H3><B>Loadsamoney</B></H3></A><IMG SRC="xpcurps.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0"><P>Zaire has probably the highest inflation rate in the world - up to 9,000per cent a year. Your need boxes of local currency to buy an air ticket,for instance. Oneconsequence is that the capital Kinshasa now functions on a US dollareconomy. What is itlike trying to live in the middle of this sort of inflation? Only a countrythat hastotally lost confidence in its own currency could have an Association ofBlack MarketCurrency Dealers, whose President believes they perform a vital social andpoliticalfunction.<BR CLEAR=LEFT><P><A NAME=003><A HREF="xpconn1/xptaxt1.html"><H3><B>TaxiWars</B></H3></A><IMG SRC="xptaxps.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0"><P>New black entrepreneurship has been at its sharpest in the rivalrybetweenminibus taxi firms carrying commuters between the townships andJohannesburg. Butcompetition has got wildly out of control: there has been a rash ofshoot-outs at taxi-stops between rival firms, and many peoplehave been killed. For South Africans, it's another reflection of the hottestissues of the day - crime, violence and the widespread availability ofweapons. South Africanow has the highest homicide rate in the world.<BR CLEAR=LEFT><P><A NAME=004><A HREF="xpconn1/xpaidt1.html"><H3><B>Rap AgainstAIDS</B></H3></A><IMG SRC="xpaidps.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0"><P>Makerere University students Lillian Butele and Brenda Z'obbo formUganda'sleading female pop group, Prim and Propa. They signal a new approach toclean-living among the AIDS-conscious youth of Kampala. For them AIDS isalso afeminist issue, and in their songs and contacts with young fans theyemphasisethe need for a different way of life. As elsewhere in Africa, AIDS inUganda is aheterosexual phenomenon. Since promiscuous men infect their faithfulwives,AIDSraises women's issues ranging from rights within marriage to questions ofproperty inheritance.<BR CLEAR=LEFT><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME=005><B><H2>Programme 2</H2></B><P><A NAME=006><A HREF="xpconn2/xptret1.html"><H3><B>The Boers AreBack</B></H3></A><IMG SRC="xptreps.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0">With South Africa back in the international fold, Afrikaner farmers areresuming the great trek northwards. In private enterprise arrangements andgovernment-to-government deals, farmers are leaving their marginalagricultural lands in Transvaal and heading for black Africa. <I>AfricaExpress</I> profiles the role of Sadevco, a Pretoria-based company that hassent farmers to the Congo, where they live in crumbling mansions abandonedbythe French a generation ago.<P><A NAME=007><A HREF="xpconn2/xparmt1.html"><H3><B>DictatingTerms</B></H3></A><IMG SRC="xparmps.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0"><P>Spurred to action by the execution of Ken Saro-Wiwa and his Ogonicolleagues,at their recent summit Commonwealth leaders insisted that progresstowardsdemocracy should be monitored in Nigeria, Sierra Leone and The Gambia.Thingsdon't look good: the Nigerians have not even allowed the monitors into thecountry; Sierra Leone has just had another coup, further consolidating thepower of the army; the Gambians are way behind in their timetable fordemocracy. <I>Africa Express</I> interviews Captains Yahya Jammeh, theGambiandictator, who explains that military rule is good for people.<P><A NAME=008><A HREF="xpconn2/xpmedt1.html"><H3><B>The MedicalMan</B></H3></A><IMG SRC="xpmedps.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0">Throughout Africa there is a growing relationship between traditional andWestern medicine. The cultural cross-over is at its most advanced in SouthAfrica, where there are white medicine men and where even the healthinsurancecompanies and the big trade unions are planning to pay for traditionalconsultations. Traditional medical practitioners are also extensivelyinvolvedin the fight against AIDS. But not everyone sees this as a wholesomedevelopment.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME=009><B><H2>Programme 3</H2></B><P><A NAME=010><A HREF="xpconn3/xpshat1.html"><H3><B>Licence toDrink</B></H3></A><IMG SRC="xpshaps.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0"><P>With the changes in South Africa, the Black middle classes have startedmovinginto the white northern suburbs of Johannesburg. With them they've broughtshebeens - the private home / drinking houses that were the centre of muchsocial and political life in the townships. Unfortunately the shebeens areoutraging many white residents, who object to all the noise and the traffic.<P><A NAME=011><A HREF="xpconn3/xpadwt1.html"><H3><B>A FamousVictory</B></H3></A><IMG SRC="xpadwps.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0"><P>Nineteen ninety-six is the centenary of the battle of Adwa, in northernEthiopia - the most significant defeat ever inflicted on a European army byAfricans. Italy was forced to recognise Ethiopian independence as a result.The celebrations will take on particular significance because Adwa is inTigr&eacute, whose Popular Liberation Front helped to free Ethiopia from amorerecent quasi-imperialist power - the Soviet-backed Mengistu regime.<P><A NAME=012><A HREF="xpconn3/xpsapt1.html"><H3><B>FashionNotes</B></H3></A><IMG SRC="xpsapps.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0"><P>Sapeurs are the dandies of the Zairean pop scene - the most sophisticatedinAfrica. Their lives revolve around the clothes they buy and show off.What's thelatest in Sapeur fashion for 1996, and how on earth can they keep it upwith theZairian economy collapsing around them?<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME=013><B><H2>Programme 4</H2></B><P><A NAME=014><A HREF="xpconn4/xpbent1.html"><H3><B>CeasefireLine</B></H3></A><IMG SRC="xpbenps.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0"><P>Peace of a sort has returned to Angola after 20 years of ruinous civilwar, and there are now plans to reopen stretches of the Benguela railway -the line that once linked the Atlantic coast with Africa's mineral-bearinginterior. One stretch of the line - from Lobito to Benguela - has keptrunning throughout the conflict, but there remain severe problems on theinland stretch, with blown bridges and Angola's ubiquitous landmines. Theprospects for the railway sum up those for Angola itself - is the peacesufficiently durable to persuade the aid-givers to make reconstruction areality?<P><A NAME=015><A HREF="xpconn4/xpcolt1.html"><H3><B>ColourBar</B></H3></A><IMG SRC="xpcolps.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0"><P>The Moslem army officers who run The Gambia have banned skinlighteners,which are increasingly used in Africa and are causing medical problems.This is part of a growing trend in Africa. On health grounds, theTanzanians are on the point of introducing legislation to the same end.<P><A NAME=016><A HREF="xpconn4/xphott1.html"><H3><B>HotSeating</B></H3></A><IMG SRC="xphotps.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0"><P>The practice of beating school children is alive and well in Zimbabwe.Corporal punishment was outlawed for a time after independence, but thenreintroduced - along with hanging. More and more cases of brutality arecoming to light in Zimbabwean schools, and a campaign is under way tooutlaw corporal punishment once again. But the traditionalists insist thatcaning is good for school children and the best way to avoid the sort ofyouth problems that have engulfed the West.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME=017><B><H2>Programme 5</H2></B><P><A NAME=018><A HREF="xpconn5/xphirt1.html"><H3><B>HiredHelp</B></H3></A><IMG SRC="xphirps.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0"><P>It's the South African company that claims to bring stability to theContinent. Its 'advisers' have helped restore the military fortunes of theGovernments of Sierra Leone and Angola. but Executive Outcomes is seen byits critics as a dangerous mercenary outfit in business for profit alone.Their spokesmen argue that their role should by appreciated in a continentplagued by civil war. But in Sierra Leone, the first thing they did was tosecure the diamond-bearing regions of the East so then they could get paid.<P><A NAME=019><A HREF="xpconn5/xpmbit1.html"><H3><B>MusicalSpirit</B></H3></A><IMG SRC="xpmbips.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0"><P>Mbira makes the beautiful, traditional music of Zimbabwe. It is also theinstrument that raises the ancestral spirits, and as such was frowned uponby the missionaries as the devil's music. The country's Christianestablishment has been so antagonistic towards Mbira that there was adanger that the music and the instrument would die out altogether. It's nottaught in schools, and doesn't figure in the National Anthem. Now, though,there's a revival - thanks not to African interest, but to the interest ofwesterners in Mbira music.<P><A NAME=020><A HREF="xpconn5/xperit1.html"><H3><B>FishyStory</B></H3></A><P><IMG SRC="xperips.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0">What do you do if you fight a protracted liberation struggle and inherit an800 mile coastline? learn to fish, that's what! Dedicated toself-sufficiency, the Eritreans are developing a fishing fleet in thebombed-out port of Massawa, and a cooperative of former women guerrillasislikely to set up the first big fish market in Asmara. But the Eritreanauthorities must also convert their meat-eating compatriots into actuallyliking fish in the first place. Television advertisements are playing theirpart.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME=021><B><H2>Programme 6</H2></B><P><A NAME=022><A HREF="xpconn6/xpnigt1.html"><H3><B>ImageMatters</B></H3></A><P><IMG SRC="xpconn6/xpconn6gifs/xpnigps.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOPBORDER=0>Under attack for the Ogoni executions and anxious to counter its grim imagearound the world, the Nigerian military government has come up with a videoentitled <I>Not In Our Character</I>. It was intended primarily to deal withNigeria's reputation as a nation of swindlers. Toyin Fani-Kayode tacklesuncomfortable questions about her country and discusses them with topNigerianofficials.<P><A NAME=023><A HREF="xpconn6/xpnamt1.html"><H3><B>WhoseTourists?</B></H3></A><P><IMG SRC="xpconn6/xpconn6gifs/xpnamps.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOPBORDER=0>The Brandberg, a 3,000-foot mountain in Namibia, is the Ayers Rock ofSouthernAfrica. It's becoming a significant tourist attraction, offering trekking,campingand spectacular scenery as well as spiritual significance, Stone Age rockpaintingand ancient bush culture. But now the government must decide who will gettheconcession to exploit the mountain. Will it be the local community -already at workon the tourist front - or will it be outside commercial interests?<P><A NAME=024><A HREF="xpconn6/xpcont1.html"><H3><B>AwayDay</B></H3></A><P><IMG SRC="xpconn6/xpconn6gifs/xpconps.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOPBORDER=0>The Congolese prison service is in a desperate state. It's run out of money,even to feed prisoners, and prisoners have been suffering from seriousmalnutrition.The minister responsible has appeared on television to appeal forinternationalassistance. Meanwhile prisoners have been allowed out of jail on a dailybasisto scavenge and beg for food.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME=025><B><H2>Programme 7</H2></B><P><A NAME=026><H3><B><A HREF="xpconn7/xprevt1.html">RevenueMen</A></B></H3><P><IMG SRC="xpconn7/xpconn7gifs/xprevps.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOPBORDER=0>Uganda is getting back on its feet, and the best evidence is that thetax-men areback in business, cracking down on errant businesses and getting the armyto takeon smugglers. The Revenue Authority has a Ghanaian in charge. He raised bigtaxesin Ghana, and was asked to do the same in Uganda. His success has beenphenomenal,and is helping to realise the government's aim of reducing and eventuallyeliminatingthe country's dependence on foreign aid.<P><A NAME=027><H3><B>Strictly Ballroom</B></H3><P><IMG SRC="xpconn7/xpconn7gifs/xpbalps.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOPBORDER=0>After football and boxing, South Africa's top leisure activity is - waitfor it -ballroom dancing. <I>Africa Express</I> follow preparations for a majorcompetitionin Johannesburg, and see who goes home to the townships with the large andcovetedsilver trophies.<P><A NAME=028><H3><B><A HREF="xpconn7/xpbtbt1.html">Back toBarracks</A></B></H3><P><IMG SRC="xpconn7/xpconn7gifs/xpbtbps.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOPBORDER=0>One of the curses of modern Africa is the overblown, overpaid andoverbearingmilitary. Congo has come up with the obvious answer - give soldiers aproper job!The government is seeking European Union backing for training them to bebuildersand farmers. Militiamen are already at work on a range of civilian projects.One question remains - is this an authentic political initiative, or is thegovernment acting out of fear of military power?<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME=029><B><H2>Programme 8 </H2></B><P><A NAME=030><H3><B><A HREF="xpconn8/xpnigt1.html">ShellOut</A></B></H3><P><IMG SRC="xpconn8/xpconn8gifs/xpnigps.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOPBORDER=0>Shell's image has recently taken a battering in the West following theexecution of environmental campaigner Ken Saro-Wiwa. But what is thecompany's reputation in Nigeria itself? Shell has a series of communityprogrammes in place, but do Nigerians think it has done enough in returnfor its oil profits? Or do they blame their own government for not havingspent the oil money wisely?<P><A NAME=031><H3><B><A HREF="xpconn8/xpangt1.html">CarnivalTime</A></B></H3><P><IMG SRC="xpconn8/xpconn8gifs/xpangps.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOPBORDER=0>Angola's peace is uncertain; its economy collapsing. But even after twodecades of civil war, a sense of fun triumphs over strife during the annualcarnival. Surprisingly, carnival's roots are entwined with colonisation andthe slave trade. Such associations might seem unwelcome at a party, butcarnival time in Angola is all about the resilience of a people and of thehuman spirit.<P><A NAME=032><H3><B>Living Ads</B></H3><P><IMG SRC="xpconn8/xpconn8gifs/xpadsps.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOPBORDER=0>Zimbabwe has found a way of advertising products that is better than TV,press and billboards. Manufacturers are funding theatrical roadshows thattour the country playing to large audiences in cities, towns and villages.The sketches and plays use local idioms - particularly local humour - tosell products such as toothpaste and soapsuds.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8BORDER=0></A><P>		<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=88><A HREF="xphome.html"><IMGSRC="xphome.gif"ALT="Africa Express Home Page" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=88 HEIGHT=50BORDER=0></A></TD>		<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=88><A HREF="xplinks/xplinks.html"><IMGSRC="xplink.gif" ALT="Africa Links" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=88 HEIGHT=50BORDER=0></A></TD>		</DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
