<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Africa Express: ␀␀␀␀Fashion Notes - background</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><BASEFONT SIZE=4><A NAME="TOP"><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 CELLSPACING=1>	<TR>				<TD VALIGN TOP><P><FONT SIZE=6>␀␀␀␀Fashion Notes - background</FONT></TD>			</TR></TABLE>		<FONT SIZE=4>		<BR><A HREF="#001">Soukous, The African Elvis and the Papa of Sapeurs</A>		<BR><A HREF="#002">Further reading</A> 		<BR><A HREF="#003">Links</A>						</FONT>				<TR>		<P><TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=88><A HREF="xpsapt3.html"><IMG SRC="../xpfact.gif" ALT="Factfile" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=88 HEIGHT=50 BORDER=0></A></TD>				<P><TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=88><A HREF="../xphome.html"><IMG SRC="../xphome.gif" ALT="Africa Express Home Page" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=88 HEIGHT=50 BORDER=0></A></TD>		<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=88><A HREF="../xplinks/xplinks.html"><IMG SRC="../xplink.gif" ALT="Africa Links" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=88 HEIGHT=50 BORDER=0></A></TD>		<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=88><A HREF="../xpconn.html"><IMG SRC="../xpconn.gif" ALT="Express Connections" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=88 HEIGHT=50 BORDER=0></A></TD>				</TR>		</DL></DD></DL></DD><P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 CELLSPACING=1>	<TR>		<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=76><IMG SRC="../xpconn1/xpconn1gifs/xpcurm1.gif" WIDTH=76 ALT="Inset map" ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0></TD>		<TD VALIGN TOP><IMG SRC="../xpconn1/xpconn1gifs/xpcurm2.gif" WIDTH=440 HEIGHT=312 ALT="Map of Zaire" ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0></TD>	</TR></TABLE><DL><DD><DL><DD><TR>				<P><TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=140><IMG SRC="xpconn3gifs/xpsapp3.gif" ALT="Photograph" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=140 HEIGHT=107 BORDER=0></A></TD>		<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=140><IMG SRC="xpconn3gifs/xpsapp4.gif" ALT="Photograph" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=140 HEIGHT=107 BORDER=0></A></TD>		<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=140><IMG SRC="xpconn3gifs/xpsapp2.gif" ALT="Photograph" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=140 HEIGHT=107 BORDER=0></A></TD>				</TR>				<P><A NAME="001"><H2><B>Soukous, The African Elvis and the Papa of Sapeurs</B></H2><P>'A Sapeur is someone who lives to dress,' says the Zairean designer Ali Babason. But the Sapeur also dresses to be seen, and the place to be seen is at a soukous concert.<P>Strictly speaking, soukous is a style of music and dance that originated in Zaire in the 1980s, but the term is now used for modern Zairean pop music in general, and for similar music from as far away as Zimbabwe and Togo.<P>Papa Wemba, the original Sapeur, was one of the originators of 'rumba rock' - a fusion of soukous, Zairean dance music and Western blues. Now resident in Paris, Wemba readily acknowledges his pop aspirations, but Zairean influences are still predominant.<P>One such influence is the 'African Elvis' Tabu Ley Rochereau, one of the pioneers of Zairean pop. Many soukous stars, including Papa Wemba, once played in Rochereau's band. It was Rochereau who first introduced Europeans to urban African pop in 1970 with a run of 26 performances at the Paris Olympia, followed by dates at the London Palladium.<P>Rochereau also now lives in Paris, and is reluctant to return to Zaire. He and the Zairean guitarist, singer and composer Franco Luambo Makiadi were at one time courted by President Mobutu, and Rochereau once sang Mobutu's praises, but he has been harshly critical of the military regime in recent years. (For more about Mobutu and the history and economy of Zaire, see <A HREF="../xpconn1/xpcurt1.html">Loadsamoney</A>.) Rochereau has returned home only once since 1988, to attend Franco's funeral.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME="002"><H2><B>Further reading</B></H2><P>Graeme Ewens, <I>Congo Colossus: The life and legacy of Franco and OK Jazz</I> (Buku Press 1994)<BR>Includes photos, discography and 19 pages of lyrics.<P>Graeme Ewens, <I>Africa O-Ye!</I> (Guinness 1991)<BR>An exploration of African musical styles ancient and modern. Includes notes on clubs, festivals and magazines.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME="003"><H2><B>Links</B></H2><P><A HREF="http://www.ina.fr/music/index.fr.html">Afro-Caribbean Music home page:</A> has links to record details for Papa Wemba, Zaiko Langa Langa and other soukous stars.)<P><A HREF="http://matisse.net/%7Ejplanet/afmx/wemba.htm"><IMG SRC="xpconn3gifs/wemba.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0">Music from Africa and the African Diaspora:</A> includes profiles of Papa Wemba and Tabu Ley Rochereau.<BR CLEAR=LEFT><P><A HREF="http://www.soton.ac.uk/~pelham/music.htm">Zaiko Langa Langa and soukous:</A> brief personal introduction.<P><A HREF="http://www.AfricaOnline.com/AfricaOnline/music/soukous/soukous.html"><IMG SRC="xpconn3gifs/soukous.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0">Africa Online - Soukous Corner</A><BR CLEAR=LEFT><P><I>For details of African music suppliers, see <A HREF="../xplinks/xplinks.html">Africa links</A>.</I><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
