<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Equinox 1995 - Questions and Answers</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><A NAME="TOP"><H1>Equinox: Questions and Answers</H1><P>If you have further questions on any of the topics below or general questions about science, technology, engineering and medicine, call Science Line on 0345 600 444 or visit <A HREF="http://www.campus.bt.com/CampusWorld/pub/ScienceNet/">ScienceNet</A>.<H2>1995 Schedule</H2><P><I>Please note: transmission dates are subject to change - check listings nearer the time.</I><P><A HREF="#XFILE">The Real X Files</A> (27.8.95)<BR><A HREF="#CYB">Cybersecrecy</A> (3.9.95)<BR><A HREF="#GURU">Gurubusters</A> (10.9.95)<BR><A HREF="#MED">Sharks in the Med</A> (17.9.95)<BR><A HREF="#FIRE">Under Fire</A> (24.9.95)<BR><A HREF="#WEIGH">State of Weightlessness</A> (1.10.95)<BR><A HREF="#COMM">Commanding Heights</A> (15.10.95)<BR><A HREF="#DNA">DNA in the Dock</A> (22.10.95)<BR><A HREF="#ELEC">Electric Skies</A> (29.10.95)<BR><A HREF="#BOOM">Kaboom!</A> (5.11.95)<BR><A HREF="#AVA">Avalanche</A> (12.11.95)<BR><A HREF="#GOD">God Only Knows</A> (19.11.95)<BR><A HREF="#GLOR">Gloria's Toxic Death</A> (26.11.95)<BR><A HREF="#JUP">On Jupiter</A> (3.12.95)<BR><A HREF="#DREAM">Designing Dream Machines</A> (10.12.95)<BR><A HREF="#RUN">Running on Water</A> (17.12.95)<BR><A HREF="#ANIM">Animal Thoughts</A> (20.12.95)<BR><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><B><H3><P><A NAME="XFILE">The Real X Files (27.8.95)</H3></B><B><P>The cloak-and-dagger world that led the US government to join a psychic arms race with the Soviet Union.</B><I><P>How did the US intelligence forces use psychics for high-level spying missions?</I><P>During the Cold War, the paranoid President Nixon, convinced he was being 'zapped' by communist enemies, decided intelligence forces needed to harness the powers of US psychics to counter the threat. The general in charge of Army Intelligence set up a 'remote viewing' unit. Another two-star general, in charge of 30,000 personnel, became so obsessed with New Age phenomena that he sent snipers to train in Zen archery and officers to undergo out-of-body experiences. <BR>During the 1981 hostage crisis a well-known psychologist was invited to join the psychic unit to 'remote view' his way into the US embassy in Tehran.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><B><H3><P><A NAME="CYB"><A HREF="../cybersecrecy/cyber000.html">Cybersecrecy</A> (3.9.95)</H3></B><B><P>As the Internet grows and more and more transactions are made via modem, the debate about privacy, secrecy and encryption is hotting up.</B><I><P>Why are some people worried about the use of code to keep computer communications private?</I><P>They argue that encryption will protect those using the Internet to promote illegal activities - child pornographers, drug dealers, racist groups and the like. Advocates of privacy say that the alternative is a technology infrastructure designed for surveillance, which, they believe, has frightening implications for democracy and civil liberties.<I><P>How is the US government trying to control encryption?</I><P>Congress will soon be trying to enforce use of the 'Clipper Chip', which will enable individuals to keep their computer transactions secret - from everyone but the FBI. At least, that's the principle. But 'Cypherpunks' have already come up with their own secrecy chips, which the FBI can't read.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><B><H3><P><A NAME="GURU">Gurubusters (10.9.95)</H3></B><B><P>A fascinating study of an ideological fight for hearts and minds between gurus and rationalists in India. </B><I><P>What is fire-walking?</I><P>Fire-walking, or 'taking a coal stroll', as it is known in North America, involves striding barefoot across searingly hot coals spread out on the ground. The walkers, who often follow in the wake of their shaman or guru, apparently suffer no burns. In addition sometimes their clothes are not singed, seeming to enjoy the same protection as their feet.<I><P>How hot are the coals?</I><P>The coals can reach many hundreds of degrees centigrade - typically 700. Human skin can be damaged at temperatures as low as 100 degrees.<I><P>How do scientists think that fire walkers protect their feet from burns?</I><P>For a long time the most popular explanation was that fire-walkers were protected by the thick skin on the soles of their feet, which they had developed by walking barefoot all their lives. But more recently American gurus have shown that they can teach anyone to fire-walk. <P>There is no evidence that fire-walkers have any special psychic powers. It has been suggested that fire-walkers often stand on cool, damp ground in bare feet immediately before they dash across the coals, and that moisture on their feet (even sweat) takes the brunt of the heat and turns to a layer of steam, offering further insulation.<P>A more likely explanation is that fire-walkers just walk quickly, so their feet are not in contact with the coals for long enough to cause any damage. This was what <I>Equinox</I>  producer Robert Eagle and some of his film crew thought - until they attempted to fire-walk on location in India. The blisters on their feet proved that busting the gurus can be a painful business.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><B><H3><P><A NAME="MED">Sharks in the Med (17.9.95)</H3></B><B><P>Evidence of a major breeding ground for the great white shark between Malta and the Mediterranean. Have reports of shark attacks been covered up?</B><I><P>What kind of animals are sharks?</I><P>Sharks are fish, not mammals, so they don't hold their breath underwater as whales and dolphins do. They must constantly swim so that oxygenated water can pass continuously through their gills - they swim when they are asleep!<I><P>How many different species of shark are there, and are they all dangerous?</I><P>Only seven years ago biologists thought there were roughly 350 living species of sharks, but deep-sea trawling has revealed that there are probably over 400. Only five or six of these are known to bite swimmers. Three of these - the white, the bull and the tiger shark - may not be man-eaters, but are simply inquisitive. As they don't have hands to explore floating objects on the surface, they use their mouths. It's just unfortunate, say biologists, that they have such sharp teeth.<I><P>Where are sharks found?</I><P>Most of the big sharks are found in warm tropical and subtropical waters, typically off the coasts of Australia, Indonesia, Central and North America and Africa. But there is evidence of about 50 cases of shark attacks on humans this century in the Mediterranean, 44 per cent of them off the coast of Italy.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><B><H3><P><A NAME="FIRE">Under Fire (24.9.95) <A HREF="../../paperbkup/bstequn.html">(booklet)</A></H3></B><B><P>An analysis of the behaviour of fire and how a greater understanding of the physical laws controlling it could help fire-fighters.</B><I><P>How do fires spread?</I><P>Bonfires in open spaces behave quite predictably - they increase in size and temperature more or less steadily until the fuel runs out, then they die away. Enclosed fires are a different matter. In an enclosed space a fire can develop in several ways. It may consume just one object and then die out without doing any more harm. But things become more dangerous when the blaze is powerful enough to heat up surrounding sources of fuel, such as tables, chairs and carpets. Flammable gases released can then combust further, raising temperatures to over 1100 degrees centigrade, with catastrophic results. <I><P>Why do we need to use computers to model fire?</I><P>The trouble with enclosed fires is that they involve complex physics and chemistry, but they don't usually leave any evidence behind. Accident investigators simulate fires to find out how they spread. They can do this with experimental test fires or with mathematical models on computers. Test fires using scale models are unsatisfactory because they don't behave in the same way as full-scale fires, and building full-size models is not practical. Mathematical modelling on computers offers a cheaper and more realistic method.<I><P>What are the problems of modelling fires on computers?</I><P>Scientists used to divide fires into zones for modelling purposes, but this isn't really how a fire burns. 'Field' modelling is an alternative technique.<P>Field modelling divides the fire into thousands of small volumes or computational cells, the number depending on the type of fire and where it is. The approach involves one of the most difficult areas of mathematics - computational fluid dynamics. Equations describing the physics of fire are solved simultaneously in each cell, to work out temperature, pressure, gas velocities and smoke concentrations, and each cell affects the calculations in all the others. This requires an enormous number of calculations, and far more computing power than zone modelling. Japanese researchers trying to crack this maths in the past spent one and a half years with a mechanical desk calculator - today such calculations are performed in minutes.<I><P>Are these models accurate?</I><P>The combustion process is extremely complex. The change from reactants to final products includes many intermediate reactions involving intermediate chemical products. These intermediate products and their rates of creation and destruction are rarely known. Turbulence complicates things still further. Consequently these models only consider burning as a simple, one-stage process with a reactant and a product. This approach, whilst only approximating the real combustion process, still gives satisfactory results for relatively simple fuels such as methane and polyurethane foam.<I><P>What are the outcomes of this research?</I><P>Mathematical field models have demonstrated that they can simulate the spread of smoke and heat within a variety of enclosures. Architects and engineers are beginning to use the technique in the early stages of building design to examine a structure's response to fire and its associated hazards. They can also use it to reduce the threat to life in the event of fire in existing structures.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><B><H3><P><A NAME="WEIGH">State of Weightlessness (1.10.95)</H3></B><B><P>The daily realities of life for men and women in the Russian space programme.</B><P>Here former cosmonaut Helen Sharman, the first Britain to go into space, answers questions about her experience on board the MIR space station.<I><P>What does the Earth look like from space?</I><P>The first time that I saw the Earth was 160 seconds into the launch when the protective fairing around the rocket was jettisoned. All I could say was 'Wow!'<P>The Earth is mostly blue (owing to the seas) and white (owing to the clouds). Countries show up very clearly - grey-brown, brown or brick-red - and look exactly as they do on a globe. Because I was only 220 miles above the Earth I could not see the Earth all at once, as we do in pictures from the Moon, but I could see that it was curved, and in one glance out of a window I could see all of western Europe.<I><P>Would you like to live on the Moon?</I><P>I would prefer to live on Earth because there are many more people on Earth at the moment! I like to see many different people both at work and in leisure-time, and I can't imagine being able to take all of my friends to the Moon with me.<I><P>Did you miss anything when you were in space?</I><P>I was in space for eight days, so I did not have time to miss anything. If I were in space for longer I think I'd miss my friends most, and the variety of things that we can do on Earth. It would often not be actually doing something that I would crave, but having it available if I wanted to do it.<I><P>Did you always want to be an astronaut?</I><P>When I was at school, I did not think that it was possible to be an astronaut. I always wanted to use science or technology somehow, so I studied science and then worked as a technologist in industry. I heard of the chance to go into space on my car radio as I was driving home from work.<I><P>Would you want to go into space again?</I><P>I would love to go into space again, as there was so much to discover there. You can do experiments that are impossible on Earth, and see space from outside our atmosphere, which makes it clearer and easier to understand. You can also learn a great deal about the Earth from space.<I><P>What was the best thing about being in space?</I><P>Feeling weightless. I could not sit down or stand up. It feels a bit like floating on top of a swimming pool, except that there's no water around you. If you put your arms out in front of you, your body moves backwards. At night, you can sleep on the ceiling if you want to! <I><P>What was it like to take off in a rocket?</I><P>The launch is rather bumpy and jerky. As the rocket accelerates you feel the g-forces increasing and pushing you into your seat. I experienced 3.5g during my launch, so I felt three and a half times heavier than I do normally on Earth. The launch lasted for 530 seconds, and finished when we jettisoned the final rocket stage, and this was when we felt weightless for the first time.<I><P>What did you eat in space? Do you like space food?</I><P>I do like space food. I went into space with the Russians, so I ate Russian space food - we had tins of fish and meat, packets of dried cabbage soup and vegetable puree, and tubes of cream cheese and fruit juice.<I><P>Did you ever get bored in space?</I><P>I was never bored. We had a guitar, a small keyboard, books, magazines and a video player. But mostly if we had any spare time we just looked out of the window.<I><P>Are there any problems in being weightless?</I><P>Feeling weightless is easy to get used to mentally, but the body takes time to adjust. Half of all astronauts feel space-sick because the balance system in the ears is not giving the brain signals of what is up and what is down any more. Fortunately none of my crew was sick, or else there might have been a chain reaction! Fluids in the body also change. On Earth we are adapted to feeling gravity, which pulls body fluids down towards our feet. Weightless, this does not happen, and more body fluids than normal accumulate in the upper body and head. It takes two or three days before the body excretes this 'extra' fluid as urine.<I><P>Do you get paid to be an astronaut?</I><P>I was paid a salary during my training and space flight, in the same way as you are for many jobs on Earth.<I><P>Was being in space the highlight of your life?</I><P>There are 'highs' all through life, and because they're all so different it's difficult to say whether one is any more high than another. Being in space was pretty good though!<I><P>How did you feel when you came back from space, and what have you been doing?</I><P>I felt very heavy! There was much to do, with all of the debriefings and press conferences, and then I started to work to make science fun and a part of our everyday lives.<I><P>Do you think there is life on other planets in the universe?</I><P>There must be. There are so many stars - we would be arrogant to think that the only intelligent life is on Earth.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><B><H3><P><A NAME="COMM">Commanding Heights (15.10.95)</H3></B><B><P>The technology, engineering, architecture, psychology and anthropology of the lift.</B><I><P>When was the first lift invented?</I><P>From ancient times to the thirteenth century, man- or animal-power was traditionally used in hoisting devices. By 1850 steam and hydraulic elevators had been introduced. In 1852 the world's first 'safety elevator' was built by Elisha Graves Otis. Otis went on to install the first passenger lift in 1857 in New York. Today there are over 2000 Otis lifts in use in offices, hotels and other buildings all over the world.<BR>Today, lifts almost show an artificial intelligence. The cunning use of micro-electronics has enabled them to operate more efficiently, responding to calls more quickly.<I><P>Which came first, the skyscraper or the elevator?</I><P>It was the invention of the passenger lift in 1857 that allowed architects and engineers to design and build tall buildings for the first time. Today the Empire State building, the World Trade Centre, the Toronto CN tower and Chicago's John Hancock Centre wouldn't exist without lifts.  <I><P>Why are some people scared of lifts?</I><P>A lift phobia, like any other phobia, is an irrational fear, often born out of a negative experience of the object or animal in question, which range from the bizarre (cutlery, toilet seats or door knobs) to the more reasonable (dangerous snakes or spiders). Lift phobias are often combined with fear of enclosed spaces - claustrophobia. Phobias can be cured through hypnotherapy and other psychological treatments.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><B><H3><P><A NAME="DNA">DNA in the Dock (22.10.95)</H3></B><B><P>How reliable is 'genetic fingerprinting'? What are the civil liberties implications of the police's new DNA database? Are we overly willing to accept scientific evidence in court?</B><I><P>What exactly is DNA?</I><P>Each of our cells has a <I>nucleus</I>  containing instructions that the cell obeys. The only way a cell can remember instructions is to record them in a pattern of chemicals. These patterns of chemicals are called <I>chromosomes</I>, and are made up of a single molecule of DNA. This DNA molecule is in fact a chain of many connected <I>genes</I>. The sequence in which the genes are arranged contains the instructions for the cell.<I><P>Who invented 'genetic fingerprinting'?</I><P>In 1984 Professor Alec Jeffreys, of the University of Leicester, was studying a particular gene when he discovered a part of the DNA that did not seem to be doing anything. Further investigation found such pieces of redundant DNA in other parts of cells. Stranger still, the patterns turned out to be different in each individual. Everyone has these unique regions of their DNA - half comes from the mother and half from the father. Only identical twins end up with the same sequences of DNA.<I><P>How does DNA fingerprinting work?</I><P>The test works by taking a sample of hair or blood found at the scene of the crime, and dissolving these in solution. The DNA strings are broken into pieces. A little of the solution is dropped onto a nylon membrane, which acts like a large sheet of blotting paper. The large bits of DNA do not travel very far, whilst the smaller pieces are more mobile and move further. This separates the solution into bands or lines down the paper - each containing different-sized pieces of DNA. Because certain parts of our DNA are unique, each person's DNA produces a different pattern. The nylon membrane is treated with radiation and the bands can then be seen on X-ray film, and compared with other DNA extractions.<I><P>Are there any problems with this method?</I><P>Errors can creep into the procedure at each stage:   <UL>	<LI>The samples of DNA can be new or old, and each responds differently	<LI>There is no way of knowing for sure if a DNA sample is damaged or broken up before the test is carried out	<LI>Breaking up the DNA is a haphazard process, and each time it is cut differently	<LI>The quality of the nylon membrane changes the distance that the DNA pieces can travel	<LI>The radiation treatment can sometimes fail to show up all the bands or lines of DNA.	<LI>The results can be very easily contaminated by microscopic specks of dust, hair or skin in the lab at any stage. </UL><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><B><H3><P><A NAME="ELEC">Electric Skies (29.10.95)</H3></B><B><P>A repeat of <I>Equinox</I>'s close-up examination of the power of lightning. </B><I><P>What causes thunder and lightning?</I><P>Thunderstorms form when a particular patch of warm, moist air rises into cold air above land or sea. As the humid air rises to a great height, water vapour condenses, forming huge cumulo-nimbus clouds. Water droplets and ice crystals in the cloud bump together and break up. This action builds up positive charges at the top of the cloud and negative charges at the base. When the charge at the base of the cloud gets to a certain strength, electrical energy is released and passes through the air to another point on the ground with the opposite charge.<BR>This release of energy is called the 'leader' stroke and forms a path of charged air for the main stroke to travel along. The main stroke travels back up to the cloud and produces a flash of lightning - which reaches a temperature of several thousand degrees centigrade. This heats up the air very quickly, causing it to expand, which produces a sound wave. This is what makes a clap of thunder.<BR>If the storm is overhead, the thunder and lightning are seen at the same time; otherwise there is a delay between the lightning and the thunder, due to the difference between the speed of light and the speed of sound. Each 1-second delay represents about 1 mile from the storm. <BR>Thunderstorms continue until the charge between the ground and the cloud has equalled out.<I><P>What is the structure of the Earth's atmosphere?</I><P>There are six main layers. The <I>troposphere</I>  is the lowest, rising to a height of 18 kilometres above the Earth's surface. Its temperature cools towards the top. The <I>stratosphere</I>  rises from 18 to 50 kilometres. It contains the protective ozone layer and is where most aircraft travel. The <I>mesosphere</I>, from 80 kilometres upwards, also cools towards the top. The <I>thermosphere</I>, from 450 kilometres upwards, can reach 2000 degrees centigrade at the top and contains gases that absorb harmful solar radiation. From 900 kilometres upwards is the <I>magnetosphere</I>. It contains no gases at all and is where most weather satellites orbit. <I><P>Why are clouds different shapes?</I><P>Clouds are made up of millions of tiny droplets of water or ice crystals which form when the air is cooled. There are three main types of cloud recognised by their shapes. <I>Cirrus</I>  clouds are found at a high level - 6000 metres - and are made up of ice crystals. They have a feathery, wispy appearance. <I>Cumulus</I>  clouds have a flat base at about 1500 metres; the upper part is rounded and extends to about 2000 metres. They are often seen on dry, sunny days, and are caused by air heated at ground level rising quickly, cooling and condensing. <I>Cumulo-nimbus</I>  clouds have their base at much the same level, but can extend up to 6000 metres. It is these clouds that are associated with thunderstorms. <I>Stratus</I>  clouds form a layer or sheet across the sky. They are found at lower levels (500 metres) and often produce light rain or drizzle.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><B><H3><P><A NAME="BOOM">Kaboom! (5.11.95)</H3></B><B><P>A scientific, historical and poetic exploration of the enduring fascination of explosions.</B><I><P>Who invented gunpowder?</I><P>Gunpowder was discovered accidentally by Chinese alchemists in the ninth century, while they were looking for the elixir of life. Paradoxically, the chemical they discovered was destined to end the lives of millions of people, and its applications in warfare were soon being exploited. By the time gunpowder appeared in the West, the Chinese developed its use through many stages, perfecting the barrel gun and the cannon. <I><P>What does gunpowder contain?</I><P>There are three main ingredients in gunpowder: saltpetre, (potassium nitrate), sulphur and carbon. But they have to be mixed in exactly the right proportions.<I><P>What is an explosion?</I><P>An explosion is essentially a rapidly exothermic (heat-generating) reaction which produces large quantities of gases. The large amount of heat given off speeds up the reaction and also means that the gases expand. <I><P>What makes something explosive?</I><P>Many nitrogen-containing compounds are explosive. The reason for this is that they contain a large bond between two nitrogen atoms which is packed with energy. As this bond breaks, the energy is given out as heat and nitrogen gas forms and quickly expands explosively - kaboom! <P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><B><H3><P><A NAME="AVA">Avalanche (12.11.95)</H3></B><B><P>An investigation into the physics of one of nature's most dangerous forces, which claims hundreds of lives each year.</B><I><P>What causes an avalanche?</I><P>Snow collecting on a mountain slope can become unstable when lower levels of snow start to melt, removing support. Eventually the upper snow layers will collapse, cascading down the slope. <BR>Alternatively an avalanche can be triggered by explosives or loud noises. These shock-waves are often used to get rid of unstable snow fields before natural avalanches happen.<I><P>How much snow can be carried by an avalanche?</I><P>As much as a million tonnes of snow can be carried by a big avalanche, and galloping ahead of this white wave is an invisible shockwave of air, blasting almost everything in its path.<I><P>What should you do if you're caught in an avalanche?</I><P>If you feel the ground suddenly slipping away from you in a cloud of surging snow, try to stay on the surface by paddling your hands and arms underneath your body. If you are buried by an avalanche you will suffocate within about half an hour.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><B><H3><P><A NAME="GOD">God Only Knows (19.11.95) <A HREF="../../paperbkup/bsteqgo.html">(booklet)</A></H3></B><B><P>A look at how, in seeking to answer questions to do with the origin of the universe, the nature of time and the unification of the laws of physics, scientists have found themselves trespassing on territory that for centuries has been mainly the preserve of theologians.</B><I><P>What happened before the Big Bang?</I><P>In the world we live in, everything we observe is caused by something else. If nothing happens without a cause, it is argued, then something must have caused the universe to appear. But what? And if God created the universe, who created God?<BR>One way of getting round this question is to hypothesise that the universe has always been here, so there was no beginning and no pre-beginning to concern ourselves with. But it's not as simple as this. Given an infinite amount of time, anything that can happen will already have happened, so everything in the universe should have run its course and be almost over. However, observations of the age of stars suggest that we certainly aren't near the end yet. What's more, there is plenty of evidence to show that there was once a Big Bang about fifteen billion year ago and that the universe is still expanding.<BR>Paul Davies, who won this year's Templeton Prize for Progress in Religion, suggests that the answer to this question was actually spotted a long time ago, by Augustine of Hippo - a Christian saint who lived in the fifth century. The world he claimed was made not 'in time' but simultaneously 'with time'. In other words, the Big Bang was not the sudden appearance of matter in an eternally pre-existing universe, but the coming into being of time itself. So in this neat theory there was no 'before'. One thousand five hundred years later this is pretty much the conclusion which science has come to.<I><P>So is that it? </I><P>Well, not really. This still prompts the question: why should time suddenly turn itself on? But is an explanation of this really necessary? Does there really have to be a cause for everything? In the sub-atomic world this is not always the case - particles appear and just as quickly disappear, with no apparent reason. A good example is the decay of a radioactive nucleus, which throws out particles randomly. It is not that we haven't found a cause - there isn't one.<P>There is a big jump from these quantum observations of the creation of particles to the creation of the universe, but the relatively new science of quantum cosmology is working on it. <P>But these are still only <I>how</I> questions - what about the <I>why</I>s? Perhaps the employment prospects of philosophers and theologians aren't so bad after all.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><P><B><A NAME="GLOR"><H3>Gloria's Toxic Death (26.11.95)</H3></B><B><P>A fascinating chemical forensic detective story. Why did a young woman leak a nerve gas as she lay dying in a hospital in California? </B><P><I>Who is Gloria?</I><P>Gloria was a woman in America who was rushed into a casualty ward last year suffering from heart palpitations, nausea and fainting fits. But her condition was far more complex than these symptoms suggested. Emergency workers took a blood sample and noticed that her blood appeared to contain crystals and smelt of ammonia. Within minutes several ER staff collapsed and an emergency was declared. Gloria was pronounced dead thirty five minutes later.<P><I>What had caused this toxic degassing from Gloria's body?</I><P>There were a number of theories which were put forward to explain what had happened. They ranged from poisoning by noxious pesticides to mass hysteria brought about by the 'smell of death'. Gloria's autopsy and an analysis of the air in the emergency room showed nothing abnormal. But then a team of forensic chemists from the Lawrence Livermore Labs found traces of a curious chemical called <I>dimethyl sulphoxide</I> (DMSO) in Gloria's body.<P><I>What's so special about dimethyl sulphoxide? </I><P><I>Dimethyl sulphoxide</I> has been used for a number of medical applications in the past. In the 1950s it was used as a cellular antifreeze for organ transplants, but it has also been advocated as a cure for arthritis, herpes and gout to mention a few. In the United States it is freely available in chemists and often used by athletes to treat muscle pain.<P><I>How had dimethyl sulphoxide caused the problems? </I><P>In the emergency room, Gloria had been pumped full of oxygen. Under these conditions, the Livermore chemists think that <I>dimethyl sulphoxide</I> can be turned into a deadly relative chemical called <I>dimethyl sulphate</I> - which they argue would be responsible for the deaths.<P><I>So is that the answer? </I><P>Other chemists disagreed that the <I>dimethyl sulphoxide</I> would react in this way, to release the quantities of <I>dimethyl sulphate</I> needed to cause the effects witnessed that day in the hospital. You can read more about their scepticism on the <A HREF="http://www.ch.ic.ac.uk/">Imperial College Chemistry Department web pages</A>. They also argue that in blood, the <I>dimethyl sulphate</I> is likely to be changed to sulphuric acid during a two stage reaction which you can see as a <A HREF="http://www.ch.ic.ac.uk/equinox/">molecular animation on the Imperial College pages</A>. Based on their evidence it does seem unlikely that the Livermore lab explanations are correct. Many chemists still consider the <I>dimethyl sulphoxide</I> a wonder medicine that the government and regulatory bodies wish to keep under wraps - by trying to blame it for Gloria's death. <I>Equinox</I> attempts to clear the name of <I>dimethyl sulphoxide</I> by uncovering the real reasons behind Gloria's toxic death.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><B><H3><P><A NAME="JUP">On Jupiter (3.12.95)</H3></B><B><P>The Galileo probe's quest to reveal the secrets of Jupiter and its moons. </B><I><P>What are conditions like on Jupiter?</I><P>Jupiter is a 'gaseous giant' - a planet with a thick atmosphere many thousands of kilometres deep. It consists mostly of hydrogen (89 per cent) and helium (11 per cent). The average surface temperature is 150 degrees centigrade, although the word 'surface' is misleading, as Jupiter is gaseous - though the vast volumes of gas create such pressures that it probably has a solid centre, perhaps of solid metallic hydrogen. Jupiter's axis is not tilted very much, so it doesn't have any seasons. <I><P>What is a big red spot seen on Jupiter?</I><P>The Great Red Spot, perhaps the most famous marking on Jupiter, was fist discovered by Robert Hooke in 1664. Since then it has shown variations in both intensity and colour, and at times it has been invisible, but it always returns after a few years. It is probably a long-lasting storm in Jupiter's turbulent atmosphere, preserved by its own immensity. And this really is a big storm, covering a surface bigger than that of the Earth. <I><P>How big is Jupiter?</I><P>Jupiter is the largest planet in the Solar System, and with a diameter of 143,500 kilometres it's 11 times larger than the Earth. Cosmologists think that if it was a little bit bigger it would produce enough internal energy to be classed as a star! <I><P>Does Jupiter have any moons?</I><P>There are 16 known moons. Many of these are quite small - less than 100 kilometres in diameter - but there are four bigger moons, which seem to be curious worlds in their own right. Colourful Io is a volcanic world of sulphur-rich lava flows. In contrast, Europa, Ganymede and Callisto are cold, icy worlds.<I><P>How far is Jupiter from the Sun?</I><P>Jupiter is about 770 million kilometres from the Sun, but it's still one of the brightest objects in our night sky. Jupiter is best seen in the summer months, low down in the sky to the south. <I><P>How long does a day last on Jupiter?</I><P>Jupiter spins surprisingly quickly for such a large planet. A day lasts about ten hours. As it spins so fast, its thick atmosphere gets drawn into bands which give the planet a streaked, stripy appearance.<I><P>What does this latest mission to Jupiter hope to achieve?</I><P>The Galileo mission to Jupiter will arrive in January 1996, when the satellite will split into two parts as it nears the planet. A probe will plunge through Jupiter's clouds, transmitting data for an hour before heat and pressure destroy it. The other part, an orbiter, will explore Jupiter and its Moons for two years.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><B><H3><P><A NAME="DREAM">Designing Dream Machines (10.12.95)</H3></B><B><P>Nine months in the life of Britain's most prestigious technological design company, Seymour and Powell, as they work on three different motorcycle design contracts.</B><I><P>Who invented the motorcycle?</I><P>The first powered cycle was built in 1868 in France. But it wasn't really a motorbike in the true sense of the term - the patent describes it as a bicycle running off steam and coal! A year later the Americans came up with their own bicycle driven by charcoal and steam. In England, in 1885, Daimler went a stage further, putting the first petrol engine on a wooden bicycle. The first purpose-designed motorbike didn't come till 1901.<I><P>How does a motorcycle engine work?</I><P>There are two kinds of engine: the two-stroke and the four-stroke. In two-stroke engines, the pistons move down once and up once between each spark. The petrol-air mix is introduced into the top of the cylinder containing the piston and a spark ignites it. The explosion forces the piston down, rotating the crank and turning the wheel. The piston then moves up again, compressing the gas, and another spark ignites it. In a four-stroke engine, the piston moves up and down twice between each spark. <I><P>Why does a motorcycle not fall over?</I><P>Bicycles and motorcycles work on the gyroscope principle. A gyroscope is a quickly spinning wheel or disc which seems to defy gravity. The faster the disc spins, the more it resists being tipped over. This is simply because you need more energy to change the angle of the spinning wheel - than a wheel that's not spinning. The energy of gravity which will tip over a stationary wheel is not great enough to change the angle of the spinning wheel by tipping it over.<I><P>What are the stages in creating a new motorcycle? </I><P>Motorcycles start life as experimental prototypes which are ridden mercilessly over specific test tracks. The aim is to discover any weak points and correct the bike's design accordingly. Next the assembly lines for mass production are prepared. The first bikes off the line are pre-production models, and these too are thoroughly tested. When the manufacturers are finally satisfied with the design, actual production begins.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><P><H3><B><A NAME="RUN">Running on Water (17.12.95)</B></H3><P><B>Everyone knows that you can't get something for nothing, or to put it more scientifically - you can't get more energy out of a reaction than you've put in - the first law of thermodynamics. Or can you? <I>Equinox</I> attempts to turn science on its head with an investigation of a number of inventors around the world who claim to have produced machines that do just that.</B><P><I>What exactly is the first law of thermodynamics?</I><P>The science of thermodynamics takes a mathematical look at the relationship of heat to mechanical and other forms of energy. The first law of thermodynamics states that the energy in a system remains constant although it may be transformed from one form to another, e.g. from the electrical potential energy in a thunder cloud to the heat, light and sound energy of a thunder bolt.<P><I>What do the machines in the programme do?</I><P>The energy machines, known as 'over-unity devices', appear to produce more energy than is put into them - breaking the first law of thermodynamics. <I>Equinox</I> follows five inventors who claim to have produced 'over-unity' devices. Despite such reports stretching back over centuries, the machines have either been ignored or laughed out of court. <P><I>Will we ever really get something for nothing?</I><P>Probably not, although we can come close - by using water as a fuel! Energy from water seems inconceivable, but it is the storehouse for one of the most powerful and volatile fuels in the universe - hydrogen. Weight for weight the constituents of water have 2.5 times the explosive power of petrol. And whilst petrol will produce 42 mega joules of energy per kilogramme, hydrogen will generate 140 mega joules of energy per kilogramme.<P><I>Why is water a potentially good fuel?</I><P>Water is a potentially good fuel because when you release the hydrogen from it - there are no waste products and when hydrogen is burnt you get water again - the ultimate environmentally friendly fuel.<P><I>So is this really something for nothing?</I><P>Well, not really. You still have to put energy into the process to get hydrogen out. Conventionally, water is split into hydrogen and oxygen using electrolysis. The energy needed to break up the water is the same as you get back when the hydrogen is burnt. So the trick is to get your energy for the process from something else that's already generating energy - like sunlight, or even algae. Energy that is so far largely unused in society. Using such sources to generate hydrogen from water <I>Equinox</I> suggests that the oil, gas and coal economy could be replaced by a hydrogen-based economy. Could this be the end of the petrochemical and nuclear industries, or is it all just pie-in-the-sky?<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><P><H3><B><A NAME="ANIM">Animal Thoughts (20.12.95) <A HREF="../../paperbkup/bstbrut.html">(booklet)</A></B></H3><P><B>This special edition of <I>Equinox</I> sets out to explore the intriguing question - what do animals think about? Do they rationalise about decisions they have to make or are they more like sleepwalkers - simply programmed by evolution to survive and reproduce?</B><P><I>Do animals think?</I><P>The question 'what is it like to be another animal' has always fascinated human beings, but how do we discover the answer. We can dissect the animals in question to learn what their sensing systems are like. Using special cameras we can even mimic the vision that horses, birds, insects and other animals probably have, through physiological studies of their eyes. But we still don't know what they think about these images, largely because we still don't understand how a bunch of chemicals - the brain - develops consciousness.<P><I>What is the current thinking in this area?</I><P>Two hundred years ago in Europe, animals were considered responsible for their actions, and were arrested, tried, convicted and executed for crimes they had committed. Today many people think that most non-human animals are simply hard wired by evolution to reproduce and survive; lacking any emotions. Somewhere between these extreme beliefs is the common sense view that dogs look forward to their owners coming home, cats do prefer some types of food to others and mosquitos don't matter!<P><I>How will we ever know?</I><P><I>Equinox</I> meets zoologists, ethnologists, psychologists and animal lovers in a quest to discover whether animals are controlled by emotions. Gerald Wilkinson spent months in a hollow tree in Costa Rica to decide whether or not vampire bats share their food with friends who've fed them in the past when their luck's been down. Dorothy Cheney and Robert Seyfarth are trying to understand baboon grunts in Botswana and Irene Pepperberg introduces us to her parrot Alex, who can count and tell the difference between shapes and colours. But however many species you examine and behaviours you document, we only have one case to really go on - our own.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
