<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Hidden Hands</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><P><H1>Hidden Hands</H1><P><B>Modernism in art and architecture - practised by such giants as Mondrian, Le Corbusier, Picasso and Pollock - developed at the turn of the century from a willingness to disrupt the status quo, expose contradictions and probe myths. With Modernism, artists and architects entered a heroic age in which they struggled for a complete rupture with the past.</B><P><B>However, the movement's roots are shrouded in mystery, and as it developed it acquired some startling influences and patrons. By revealing these 'hidden hands' over the weeks, these pages, an edited on-line version of the fully illustrated <A HREF="../../paperbkup/bamhidd.html">Channel 4 booklet</A> - and the television series they accompany - will offer a new history of Modernism, and question its ostensibly liberal ethos.</B><P><B><A HREF="hhandintro.html">Introduction</A></B> by Waldemar Januszczak, commissioning editor, arts and music, Channel 4<P><B><A HREF="hhand1.html">Is Anybody There?</A></B> - the influence of the occult on Mondrian, Kandinsky and others<UL>	<LI> The birth of Theosophy	<LI> Modernism, Mondrian and mumbo-jumbo	<LI> An embarrassing secret - Mondrian's Evolution 	<LI> Theosophy and abstraction	<LI> Kandinsky - the artist as messiah	<LI> The colour of thought, the geometry of the divine	<LI> Mazdaznan at the Bauhaus	<LI> Further reading</UL><P><A HREF="hhand2.html"><B>Art and the CIA</B></A> - The involvement of The Central Intelligence Agency in the establishment and dissemination of American Abstract Expressionism.<UL>	<LI>Modernism goes West	<LI>Pollock, booze and the 'triumph of American art'	<LI>Patriots and patsies	<LI>Advancing American Art	<LI>Covert Institute for the Arts	<LI>An abstract expression of the American myth	<LI>Millionaires in museums - MOMA and the CIA	<LI>Artists' response to the rhetoric	<LI>Modernism's swan-song	<LI>Further reading</UL><P><A HREF="hhand3.html"><B>Clean White World</B></A> - Modernist architecture and design...formal innovation or body fascism? <UL>	<LI>War, flu and a new artistic imperative	<LI>Shit, sex, viscera, chaos: Dada and Expressionism	<LI>Le Corbusier cleans up	<LI>The Bauhaus and the new Age of Reason	<LI>Healthy houses: the Weissenhof Siedlung	<LI>New Man, New Woman, New Body	<LI>The tyranny of order	<LI>Nazism and Modernism: hygiene and the art of the insane	<LI>Compromise and betrayal	<LI>Further reading</UL><P><B><A HREF="hhand4.html">Painting with the Enemy</A></B> - the persecution of Modernism in France during the Vichy years<UL>	<LI>A war on two fronts	<LI>Decadence and degenerates	<LI>Signing up for the aesthetic pogrom	<LI>Picasso: discreet resistance	<LI>Matisse: the refuge of a dream	<LI>Further Reading</UL><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
