</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Cybersecrecy</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H1>Cybersecrecy:<BR>Code-makers and code-breakers</H1><B>The obscure science of cryptography - code-making and code-breaking - is at thecentre of a hot political debate about the social implications of digitaltechnology. The advocates of privacy say that people should be able tocommunicate over the telephone and over computer networks in code - even ifthat makes it harder for the police to catch child pornographers and the like.They say that the alternative is a technology infrastructure designed forsurveillance, which, they believe, has frightening implications for democracyand civil liberties. Meanwhile, governments throughout the world say that thethreats of terrorism, drugs and so on are so serious that they must maintaintheir ability to eavesdrop on communications. Science, it would seem, is on theside of privacy.<B><P><OL>	<LI><A HREF="cyber010.html">A short history of encryption</A><UL>	<LI><A HREF="cyber020.html">Black magic and executions</A>	<LI><A HREF="cyber030.html">Signals over wires</A>	<LI><A HREF="cyber040.html">Interceptions and Enigma</A></UL>	<LI><A HREF="cyber050.html">Cracking codes</A><UL>	<LI><A HREF="cyber060.html">Public and private keys</A></UL>	<LI><A HREF="cyber070.html">The new information age</A><UL>	<LI><A HREF="cyber080.html">Government surveillance</A>	<LI><A HREF="cyber090.html">Threats against private encryption</A>	<LI><A HREF="cyber100.html">The Cypherpunks strike back</A></UL>	<LI><A HREF="cyber110.html">Resources</A><UL>	<LI><A HREF="cyber110.html#reading">Further reading</A>	<LI><A HREF="cyber110.html#finding">Finding out more on the Internet</A></UL></OL><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
