<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Travelog 97</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#E7C46C" VLINK="#BA7335"><BASEFONT SIZE=3><A NAME="TOP"><DL><DD><DL><DD><P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 CELLSPACING=12><TR><TD VALIGN TOP><IMG SRC="graphics/4logo.gif" BORDER=0></TD><TD VALIGN TOP><A HREF="gen-info/gen-info.html"><IMG SRC="graphics/travlink.gif" ALT="Traveller's links" BORDER=0></A></TD><TD VALIGN TOP><A HREF="travelog97.html"><IMG SRC="graphics/smtrav97.gif" BORDER=0></A></TD><TD VALIGN TOP><A HREF="../travelog96/travelog.html"><IMG SRC="graphics/smtrav96.gif" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR></TABLE><P><H2>Programme 1 (15 January, 8.30 pm)</H2><P><A HREF="vanuatu/van1.html"><IMG SRC="graphics/thumbnail/van.gif" ALIGN=left border=0>Vanuatu</A> was the inspiration for the film <I>South Pacific</I>. Today it is one of the most stable independent countries in the Pacific, so Pete McCarthy thought he was dreaming when he heard there had been a coup. Fortunately the 'coup' turned out to be little more than an over-egged industrial dispute.<P>Vanuatu has 107 different languages, making it one of the most linguistically confused nations on earth. And in the inhabited interior of the islands, which are framed with idyllic beaches and coral reefs, beliefs and values are equally diverse. Protestant and Catholic missionaries have left their mark, but many traditional ways and beliefs also survive. However, one ancient tradition, it is said, <I>has</I> recently died out: the last act of cannibalism probably happened about 13 years ago on the island of Malakula.<BR CLEAR=left><P><H2>Programme 2 (22 January, 8.30 pm)</H2><P>Madrid is a city with no cathedral; a city where the main river is so pathetic they have to pump water into it; a city that only became a capital on a king's whim. It's also a city famous for its night-life, and Madrid is becoming a very popular destination for weekend breaks. Sam Norman reports.<P>The second destination this week is Andalucia.<P><H2>Programme 3 (29 January, 8.30 pm)</H2><P>Bordering on China and only opened to visitors from 1991, Kyrgyzstan is known as Asia's 'Switzerland'. Andy Kershaw relishes its oddity.<P>Clare Gorham, meanwhile, visits Switzerland itself. Clare was adopted as a child and later discovered that her mother was a Swiss lawyer. It didn't add up, as her image of the Swiss didn't match her flamboyant character. However, people in the Ticino Canton have been known to smile once in a while . . .<P><HR WIDTH=80%></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
