<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Wings: Resources</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#124B69" LINK="#166F1A" VLINK="#77422A" ALINK="#FF00FF"><BASEFONT SIZE=4><A NAME="TOP"><P><DL><DD></FONT>			<TABLE>		<P><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/resources.gif" ALT="Resources" ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0>	</TABLE>		</DL></DD>	<DL><DD><DL><DD>		<TABLE>		<P>	<TR><TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=100><A HREF="wingshome.html"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/home.gif" ALT="Home" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100 BORDER=0></A></TD>				<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=100><A HREF="rspb.html"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/rspb.gif" ALT="RSPB" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100 BORDER=0></A></TD>						</TR>	</TABLE><P><A NAME="001"><H2><B>Links</B></H2><P><A HREF="http://www.abdn.ac.uk/~nhi019/intro.html">Bird Web</A><BR>Links to online bird resources plus an open noticeboard to which you can submit any bird-related question, inviting answers from any visitor to the site.<P><A HREF="http://www.aber.ac.uk/~dbswww/bird/birding.html">Birding and Natural History Links</A><BR>UK sighting information and links to other sites organised by country.<P><A HREF="http://www.birder.com/">Birding on the Web</A><BR>A resource of birding information, merchandise and fun and games, plus a gallery of bird photos donated by visitors to the site.<P><A HREF="http://compstat.wharton.upenn.edu:8001/~siler/birding.html">Birding on the Web (US)</A><BR>A fairly comprehensive site focusing on American ornithology. Includes daily updates on birds to spot, organised by date and region.<P><A HREF="http://www.mth.uea.ac.uk:80/~h055/headings/birdlinks.html%0D">Birdlinks</A><BR>Based at the University of East Anglia, this site has lots of links to bird-related sites categorised both under their location and under the specific species they focus on.<P><A HREF="ftp://rtfm.mit.edu/pub/usenet-by-group/rec.birds/">Birds newsgroups</A><BR>These two newsgroups, although American-based, have some very handy hints for the birdwatcher. For example, the answer to the question 'What field guide should I get?' is that it's advisable to go for one with paintings and not photos, as paintings pose the birds to convey more information.<P><A HREF="http://www.nhbs.co.uk/booknet/srchops.html">BookNet - the Natural History Book Service</A><BR>Search this UK-based Booknet for the bird book of your choice.<P><A HREF="http://www.netlink.co.uk/users/ag/ebn/">EuroBird Net - UK</A><BR>This site includes reports on rare bird sightings, invasions and migration in the UK, and news from birdwatchers around the world. It also provides an arena for discussion on bird identification and any information useful to the birdwatcher.<P><A HREF="http://www.abdn.ac.uk/~nhi019/intro.html">North Sea Bird Club</A><BR>The latest news on bird sightings from around the world, plus links to Web sites and newsgroups.<P><A HREF="http://isit.com/bird/index.htm">Ornithological WebSite</A><BR>Includes discussion area as well as information and links. This is a good place to start looking for online information on specific types of birds - you'll find this in the section called Ornithological Resources On & Off the Web<http://www.isit.com/bird/resource/index.htm>.<P><A HREF="http://weber.u.washington.edu/~dvictor/other.html">Tweeters' birding links</A><BR>A comprehensive set of birding links for American birds and birding organisations.<P><A HREF="http://www.wildlifetrust.org.uk">Wildlife Trusts</A><BR>Web site of the UK-wide network of trusts working to protect wildlife in town and country. Includes details of all the trusts, as well as news and events, campaign information and links to related sites.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/line.gif" WIDTH=440 BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME="002"><H2><B>Useful organisations</B></H2><P><B>Birdlife International</B><BR>Wellbrook Court<BR>Girton Road<BR>Cambridge CB3 0NA<BR>Tel: 01223 277318<BR>E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:birdlife@gn.apc.org">birdlife@gn.apc.org</A><BR><I>Global partnership of bird protection organisations worldwide - the RSPB is the British member organisation. Runs World Bird Club. Write or phone for more information.</I><P><B>British Ornithologists' Union</B><BR>c/o The Natural History Museum<BR>Akeman Street<BR>Tring<BR>Hertfordshire HP23 6AP<BR>Tel: 01442 890080<BR><I>Association of professional ornithologists, but with some amateur members. Encourages the study of birds throughout the world. Produces the scientific journal </I>Ibis<I>. Also makes research grants, organises conferences and publishes checklists.</I><P><B>British Trust for Ornithology</B><BR>National Centre for Ornithology<BR>The Nunnery<BR>Thetford<BR>Norfolk<BR>IP24 2PU<BR>Tel: 01842 750050<BR><I>The UK's largest bird research organisation. Its 15,000 members and supporters collect information on birds that live in a variety of habitats. The BTO is looking for more participants for its garden bird survey - contact the Garden Birdwatch<http://home.sol.no/tibjonn/surveys/britain.htm> organiser at the address above for more information. The organisation is also launching National Nest Box Week in 1997 (14-21 February). For an information pack, please send 2.95 (made payable to National Nest Box Week) to Tony Soper, NNBW, Freepost 1155, Canterbury, Kent CT3 4BR (no stamp required).</I><P><A HREF="rspb.html">Royal Society for the Protection of Birds (RSPB)</A><P><B>Scottish Ornithologists' Club (SCO)</B><BR>21 Regent Terrace<BR>Edinburgh<BR>EH7 5BN.<BR>Tel: 0131 556 6042<BR><I>Primarily concerned with Scottish birds, the SCO has 14 branches across Scotland and runs the largest ornithological library in Scotland. Members receive a bi-annual journal and an annual report. Adult membership costs 15. Concessionary rates are available. Write or phone for more information.</I> <P><B>The Wildlife Trusts</B><BR>Royal Society for Nature Conservation<BR>The Green<BR>Witham Park<BR>Waterside South<BR>Lincoln LN5 7JR<BR>Tel: 01522 544400<BR>Web site: <A HREF="http://www.wildlifetrust.org.uk">http://www.wildlifetrust.org.uk</A><BR><I>A UK-wide network of 47 Wildlife Trusts, 50 Urban Wildlife Groups and Wildlife Watch (the junior branch) working to protect wildlife in town and country. Manages 2,000 nature reserves. Visit the Web site or write enclosing a stamped addressed envelope for details of your nearest trust or group.</I><P><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/line.gif" WIDTH=440 BORDER=0></A><P>	<TABLE>		<P>	<TR><TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=100><A HREF="home.html"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/home.gif" ALT="Home" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100 BORDER=0></A></TD>				<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=100><A HREF="rspb.html"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/rspb.gif" ALT="RSPB" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100 BORDER=0></A></TD>						</TR>	</TABLE>		</DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
