<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Wings: Making Chicks</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#124B69" LINK="#166F1A" VLINK="#77422A" ALINK="#FF00FF"><BASEFONT SIZE=4><A NAME="TOP"><P><DL><DD></FONT>			<P>		<IMG SRC="wingsgifs/1chicks.gif" WIDTH=440 ALT="Making chicks" ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0></TD>	</TR><DL><DD>	<TABLE>		<P>	<TR><TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=100><A HREF="wingshome.html"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/home.gif" ALT="RSPB" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100 BORDER=0></A></TD>				<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=100><A HREF="rspb.html"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/rspb.gif" ALT="RSPB" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100 BORDER=0></A></TD>	<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=100><A HREF="Links.html"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/links.gif" ALT="Links" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100 BORDER=0></A></TD>						</TR>	</TABLE><P><UL><LI><A HREF="#001">Sex and the sand martin</A><BR><LI><A HREF="#002">Not so cuckoo? - fostering chicks</A><BR><LI><A HREF="#003">Feathering the nest - the long-tailed tit</A><BR><LI><A HREF="#004">Nesting instinct - how to encourage birds to nest in your garden</A></UL><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/line.gif" BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME="001"><H2><B>Sex and the sand martin</B></H2><P><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/sand.gif" HEIGHT=150 ALIGN=RIGHT ALIGN=TOP>WHEN IT COMES to breeding, pretty much anything goes for some bird species. The sand martin <I>(Riparia riparia)</I> is a good example. <P>David Bryant and a group of students from Stirling University have discovered that 'the commonest behaviour is for the male from one nest to mate with the female from another'. And if a female thinks her nest is getting too crowded, she may dump some of her eggs in another sand martin's nest. This isn't too difficult, because sand martins nest in colonies. <P>The nests themselves consist of horizontal burrows two to three feet long, with chambers at the ends. These are dug mainly in sand- and gravel-pits, railway cuttings, coastline cliffs and the banks of rivers.<BR CLEAR=RIGHT><P>Despite the probability of a brood being of mixed parentage, both male and female help to dig the burrow and feed the young. The chicks generally hatch in late May or June.<P>Sand martins are very sociable, and outside the breeding season often roost in large numbers in reed-beds and swamp vegetation.<P>The sand martin is about 11 cm long - smaller than the swallow and the house martin - and has a slightly forked tail. Its upper parts are brown; its lower parts white, with a wide brown band across the chest. Its song is a harsh twitter.<P>The sand martin visits the UK during the summer, arriving from about mid March, and moving south from the second half of June - though some stragglers don't leave till November. Though its numbers have been greatly depleted since the 1960s, the sand martin is widely distributed throughout the UK, except in Scotland. It can be seen at many RSPB reserves, including the one at Minsmere, Suffolk (off the B1125 from Westleton to Dunwich or via East Bridge north from Leiston), between April and August.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/line.gif" WIDTH=440 BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME="002"><H2><B>Not so cuckoo? - fostering chicks</B></H2><P><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/cuckoo.gif" HEIGHT=150 ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP>THE CUCKOO <I>(Cuculus canorus)</I> is well known for the male's distinctive call and for the female's distinctive approach to parenting. The female lays her eggs in the nests of birds of other species and leaves the foster parents to get on with it. As amateur naturalist and cuckoo expert Mike Bayliss points out, this may not be an admirable strategy from the human point of view, but it isn't a silly one either. <P><I>Wings</I> observes a female cuckoo carefully watching a reed warbler's nest. The cuckoo waits until the warbler leaves the nest for a moment and then swoops in, taking one of the warbler's eggs and replacing it with one she lays herself. (The cuckoo's eggs tend to resemble those of the fosterer, ranging widely in colour and pattern.) All this is done within ten seconds. It's then up to the chick, which finishes the job when it hatches by pushing the warbler's own eggs or fledglings out of the nest. Cuckoos can foster up to 25 chicks per season in this way.<BR CLEAR=LEFT><P>More than 50 species are known to be selected by the cuckoo as fosterers, including the dunnock, robin, magpie, pied wagtail and sedge warbler. <P>Alighting and on the ground, the cuckoo is rather awkward, and in flight it is hurried and direct, with rapid wing movements. Its upper parts and breast are blue-grey; the rest of its under parts are whitish, with dark bars. The tail is long and graduated, with feathers tipped with white. The wings are pointed. It is about 32 cm long.<P><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/cuckchick.gif" HEIGHT=150 ALIGN=RIGHT ALIGN=TOP> <FONT SIZE=-1><FONT COLOR="#000000"><I>A cuckoo chick struggles to push its host's egg out of the nest.</I> </FONT><P>Cuckoos winter in central and southern Africa. The male's 'cuckoo' song is heard in April, May and most of June, and occasionally in July. The female's song is quite different - a sort of bubbling chuckle. <P>The cuckoo is distributed throughout the UK, though it is rare in Orkney and Shetland. It can be seen in many RSPB reserves, including those at Blacktoft Sands, Humberside (half a mile east of Ousefleet, off the A161 from Goole) and Minsmere, Suffolk (off the B1125 from Westleton to Dunwich or via East Bridge north from Leiston).<P><I>There's a brief discussion of how cuckoos get away with planting their chicks on magpies in the US radio programme</I> <A HREF="http://www.earthsky.com/1996/es960227.html">Earth and Sky site</A>.<BR CLEAR=RIGHT><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/line.gif" WIDTH=440 BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME="003"><H2><B>Feathering the nest - the long-tailed tit</B></H2><P>IN THE PROGRAMME <I>(Aegithalos caudatus)</I>, Mike Hansell reveals the 'amazingly beautiful' and intricate structure of the nest of the long-tailed tit. The nest's upright, ovoid shell is made of moss, lichen and tiny twigs, bound together with spider's silk, and has an entrance hole at the top. The nest is lined with an astonishing average of 1,500 feathers, of various kinds. <P><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/longtit.gif" HEIGHT=150 ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP> <FONT SIZE=-1><FONT COLOR="#000000"><I>A long-tailed tit puts the finishing touches to its luxury home.</I> </FONT><P>Both male and female help to build the nest - in thorn bushes, brambles or furze, and also in trees - and to feed the young. In the breeding season, the birds main habitat is hedgerows, thickets and bushy places or outskirts of woods. Outside the breeding season it is also commonly found deeper in woods.<P>The long-tailed tit is very small - about 14 cm long, and more than half of that is tail. The head is off-white with a broad dark band over the eyes and back of the head; the upper parts are blackish with some pink; the under parts are dull white shading to pink; the wings and narrow tail blackish with white in the outer tail feathers. As with other tits, the flight of this species is rather laboured and erratic. The long-tailed tit mixes freely with other tits, but visits gardens less frequently.<P>The long-tailed tit is a UK resident, and is widely distributed. It can be seen in many RSPB reserves, including The Lodge in Bedfordshire (off the B1042 Sandy to Cambridge road, one mile from Sandy).<BR CLEAR=LEFT><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/line.gif" WIDTH=440 BORDER=0></A><P><P><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/nest.gif" HEIGHT=150 ALIGN=RIGHT ALIGN=TOP><A NAME="004"><H2><B>Nesting instinct - how to encourage birds to nest in your garden</B></H2><P>CHRIS MEAD, whose reputation is such that he is known by some within the birding fraternity as 'God', tells <I>Wings</I> viewers how to encourage birds to nest in their gardens.<P>In the long term, the best strategy is to plant native trees, hedges and climbers, such as rowans, crab apples, hawthorns, pyracanthias (not the yellow-berried type), elders, ivies and female varieties of holly. More immediately, you can encourage blackbirds and song thrushes by providing a platform in a sheltered position, such as behind a bush against a wall. Robins choose all sorts of nesting places - try placing an old kettle, spout down for drainage, in a sheltered place. You can also put up nest boxes. There's more information on this in the free RSPB information pack<link to RSPB page>.<BR CLEAR=RIGHT><P></FONT><P><P><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/line.gif" BORDER=0></A><P>			<TABLE>		<P>	<TR><TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=100><A HREF="wingshome.html"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/home.gif" ALT="RSPB" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100 BORDER=0></A></TD>				<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=100><A HREF="rspb.html"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/rspb.gif" ALT="RSPB" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100 BORDER=0></A></TD>	<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=100><A HREF="Links.html"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/links.gif" ALT="Links" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100 BORDER=0></A></TD>						</TR>	</TABLE>		</DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
