<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Wings: Making Chicks</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#124B69" LINK="#166F1A" VLINK="#77422A" ALINK="#FF00FF"><BASEFONT SIZE=4><A NAME="TOP"><P><DL><DD></FONT>			<P>		<IMG SRC="wingsgifs/prog2.gif" WIDTH=440 ALT="Programme 2: First birds" ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0></TD>	</TR><DL><DD>	<TABLE>		<P>	<TR><TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=100><A HREF="wingshome.html"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/home.gif" ALT="RSPB" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100 BORDER=0></A></TD>				<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=100><A HREF="rspb.html"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/rspb.gif" ALT="RSPB" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100 BORDER=0></A></TD>	<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=100><A HREF="Links.html"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/links.gif" ALT="Links" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100 BORDER=0></A></TD>						</TR>	</TABLE><P><UL><LI><A HREF="#001">Tough ptarmigans</A><BR><LI><A HREF="#002">Monarch of all surveys - the golden eagle</A><BR><LI><A HREF="#003">Female of the species brighter than male: the dotterel</A><BR><LI><A HREF="#004">Dun but not dull: the dunlin</A><LI><A HREF="#005">Gargling guillemots, guano and gannets</A></UL><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/line.gif" BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME="001"><H2><B>Tough ptarmigans</B></H2><P>AFTER THE LAST ice age, 80,000-10,000 years ago, the first birds to recolonise the UK were Arctic species such as the ptarmigan <I>(Lagopus mutus)</I> - tough characters equipped to survive severe cold and sparse food.<P>These Arctic birds are still found amongst the high Scottish mountains, and Kevin Shepherd, a professional ornithologist, has been hired by <A HREF="http://www.hmsoinfo.gov.uk/hmso/document/r-scot/c3b1.htm">Scottish Natural Heritage</A> to survey them. The ptarmigan, golden eagle, dotterel and dunlin are amongst the birds Kevin's team has been studying.<P>The ptarmigan is about 33-35 cm long and rather like the grouse in flight and appearance, but its plumage is distinctive, varying in colour and pattern from season to season. In winter it is pure white, except for black tail-feathers tipped with white and, in the male, black patches on the side of the head. In summer the upper parts, breast and flanks are grey with thin black stripes; the wings remain white. In summer the male is darker, the female yellowish; in autumn the female is darker than the male. <P>Ptarmigans are often reluctant to fly, and crouch when nervous, their plumage blending into their surroundings. They tend to flock together outside the breeding season, particularly in winter.<P>Ptarmigans build their nests amongst short vegetation or on stony ground sheltered by rocks. The female incubates her eggs alone, though the male stays nearby. The chicks hatch from June onwards, and are brooded by the female and guarded by the male.<P>Ptarmigans can be seen at the RSPB's Loch Garten reserve, Abernethy, Highland (signposted off the road between Boat of Garten and Nethybridge).<P><A HREF="http://www2.northstar.k12.ak.us/schools/upk/here/ptarmigan.html">Alaska - what it's like here: ptarmigan picture.</A><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/line.gif" WIDTH=440 BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME="002"><H2><B>Monarch of all surveys - the golden eagle</B></H2><P><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/eagle2.gif" HEIGHT=130 ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP><P>The magnificent golden eagle <I>(Aquila chrysaetos)</I> is king of the high mountains. Approximately 75-90 cm long, with broad wings and wide-spread, upward-curving primary feathers, it can glide effortlessly for long periods without beating its wings, and soars to great heights. Its plumage is brown, with a yellow tint on the head.<P>Golden eagles often perch motionless for hours on cliff ledges or in trees. When hunting, they flies low over the hillsides and swoop down on their quarry - usually blue hares, red grouse and ptarmigan, though young lambs are known to have been taken. Golden eagles are normally solitary, though they sometimes hunt in pairs during the winter. <BR CLEAR=LEFT><P>Male and female jointly build large nests, usually on cliff ledges or in Scots pine trees. The eggs are normally laid in early April, and the female incubates them alone. However, both parents feed the young, which don't fly until they are at least 11 weeks old.<P>The golden eagle is resident in the <A HREF="http://www.hebrides.com/">Inner and Outer Hebrides</A>, the Highlands and (in very small numbers) in south-west Scotland. It is hardly ever found south of Yorkshire, but can be seen all year round at the RSPB's Haweswater reserve in Cumbria (turn off the A6 at Shap, follow the signs to Bampton and turn left in the village).<P><A HREF="http://www.raptor.cvm.umn.edu/raptor/rfacts/golden.html">Raptor facts - golden eagle:</A> includes identifying characteristics, range, habitat, etc.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/line.gif" WIDTH=440 BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME="003"><H2><B>Female of the species brighter than male: the dotterel</B></H2><P><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/dotterel.gif" HEIGHT=150 ALIGN=RIGHT ALIGN=TOP><P>THE DOTTEREL <I>(Charadrius morinellus)</I> is a comparatively rare summer visitor, inhabiting the mountain tops of the Cairngorms and Grampians, and perhaps of the Lake District. It often seems quite tame, allowing the observer to approach closely. Its markings are striking: it has a broad, white eye-stripe; its cheeks and throat are whitish; its upper parts blackish-brown; its brown upper breast is separated by a white band from its lower breast and flanks, which are chestnut in colour. Its belly is black and its tail edged with white. It is about 22 cm long.<BR CLEAR=RIGHT><P><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/cairngorns.gif" HEIGHT=130 ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP> <FONT SIZE=-1><FONT COLOR="#000000"><I>Kevin Shepherd scans the Cairngorms for birdlife</I> </FONT><P>Kevin Shepherd explains that the species is unusual in that the female's plumage is usually much more brightly coloured than that of the male, and each female has several mates. What's more, the males incubate the eggs and tend the young. <P>Dotterels nest on the ground, hollowing out a depression, which may be unlined or thinly lined with mosses, grasses and lichens.<P>Dotterels can be seen at the RSPB's Loch Garten reserve, Abernethy, Highland (signposted off the road between Boat of Garten and Nethybridge).<BR CLEAR=LEFT><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/line.gif" WIDTH=440 BORDER=0></A><A NAME="004"><H2><B>Dun but not dull: the dunlin</B></H2><P>The dunlin <I>(Calidris alpina)</I> is a small wader, about 17-19 cm long, with a distinctive round-shouldered appearance. In winter its breast is grey and its upper parts brownish grey. In summer its back is brown and black and it has a black patch on its lower breast. A whitish bar is noticeable on its wings in flight. <P>Dunlins are very gregarious, mixing both in small groups and in large flocks. Dunlin flocks fly with amazing unity, changing shape and colour as they tilt to reveal different parts of the birds' plumage. <P>Dunlins feeds on insects, molluscs, crustaceans and worms. They hunt on flats after the tide has gone out, but also wade into shallow water and can swim if necessary. They nest on the ground near shallow water in a hollow made in a tussock of grass, lined with dried grass stalks and leaves. Both male and female incubate the eggs.<P>The dunlin is one of Britain's commonest and most widespread shore-birds. It can be seen at many RSPB reserves, including those at Snettisham, Norfolk (signposted from the A149 King's Lynn to Hunstanton road in Snettisham village) and Titchwell Marsh, Norfolk (off the A149 half-way between Thornham and Titchwell).<P><A HREF="http://suze.ucs.usl.edu/~pec8774/dunlin.html">Picture: two dunlins moulting into alternate plumage</A><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/line.gif" BORDER=0></A><A NAME="005"><H2><B>Gargling guillemots, guano and gannets</B></H2><P><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/bass.gif" HEIGHT=150 ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP> <FONT SIZE=-1><FONT COLOR="#000000"><I>The rugged cliffs of Bass Rock are a haven for seabirds</I> </FONT><P>Bryan Nelson spent the first three years of his married life living among the seabirds on Bass Rock, off the coast of East Lothian. He confesses his wife got a bit fed up with it after a while, but explains 'A lot of us are just hooked on seabirds . . . the wildness of the islands, the smell of guano and rotten fish, the noise of the guillemot gargling and the kittiwake calling.' Can't argue with that. <P>Bryan is one of the world's leading authorities on the gannet <I>(Sula bassana)</I>, and shares his knowledge and enthusiasm with <I>Wings</I> viewers.<BR CLEAR=LEFT><P><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/gannet.gif" HEIGHT=150 ALIGN=RIGHT ALIGN=TOP>Gannets are very large (about 90 cm long) and very distinctive, with a white body and long, narrow, black-tipped wings, a pointed tail and a pointed beak. They are also instantly recognisable from their spectacular headlong dives for fish. Unfortunately, they're not so good at getting back into the air, flapping over the surface of the water for some distance before taking off. <P>Gannets only come onto land in the breeding season, nesting on cliff ledges in colonies, which are sometimes very large. Their eggs are laid in April or May in a nest built of seaweed or grass. Both male and female incubate the eggs and feed the chick (there is usually only one egg), but after about two months the parents let the chick go hungry for about ten days, at which point it takes the hint, flies down to the sea and, after two or three weeks, begins to fish for itself.<P>Gannets are UK residents, breeding on islands around Scotland and Ireland. There is also a large colony on the RSPB reserves at Grassholm, Dyfed (not easily accessible) and a smaller one at Bempton Cliffs, Humberside (take the cliff road from Bempton village on the B1229 from Flamborough to Filey).<BR CLEAR=RIGHT></FONT><P><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/line.gif" BORDER=0></A><P>			<TABLE>		<P>	<TR><TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=100><A HREF="wingshome.html"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/home.gif" ALT="RSPB" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100 BORDER=0></A></TD>				<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=100><A HREF="rspb.html"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/rspb.gif" ALT="RSPB" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100 BORDER=0></A></TD>	<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=100><A HREF="links.html"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/links.gif" ALT="Links" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100 BORDER=0></A></TD>						</TR>	</TABLE>		</DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
