<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Wings: Comings and goings</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#124B69" LINK="#166F1A" VLINK="#77422A" ALINK="#FF00FF"><BASEFONT SIZE=4><A NAME="TOP"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/prog3.gif" WIDTH=440 ALT="Programme 3: Comings and goings" ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0></TD>	</TR><DL><DD>	<TABLE>		<P>	<TR><TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=100><A HREF="wingshome.html"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/home.gif" ALT="RSPB" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100 BORDER=0></A></TD>				<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=100><A HREF="rspb.html"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/rspb.gif" ALT="RSPB" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100 BORDER=0></A></TD>	<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=100><A HREF="Links.html"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/links.gif" ALT="Links" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100 BORDER=0></A></TD>						</TR>	</TABLE><P><UL><LI><A HREF="#001">Ringers and warblers</A><LI><A HREF="#002">Amber for red-breast: the stonechat</A><LI><A HREF="#003">Fair fowl: the pink-footed goose</A><LI><A HREF="#004">Sitting duck: the eider</A></UL><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/line.gif" BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME="001"><H2><B>Ringers and warblers</B></H2><P><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/hitech.gif" WIDTH=160 ALIGN=right ALIGN=TOP><P>In the third programme of the series, professional ornithologist Kevin Shepherd is shown ringing and releasing a garden warbler <I>(Sylvia borin)</I>. Ringing enables ornithologists to determine birds' migration patterns. <P>Garden warblers are summer visitors to Europe, spending the winter in Africa. They first arrive in the UK in April or May, and these early arrivals remain in Britain for the summer. More garden warblers arrive at the end of May or in early June, and these birds are probably on their way to Scandinavia.<P>The garden warbler is plump and about 14 cm long. Its plumage is pale buff below and darker brown above. It is very secretive, spending most of its time in the cover of foliage.<P>The garden warbler nests in shrubs and brambles, and sometimes in trees. The nest, which is made of grass stalks, is built by both male and female, and both sexes help to feed the young.<P>Garden warblers can be found in woodland throughout the UK, except in the Highlands, Grampian and most of Ireland, between April and September.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/line.gif" WIDTH=440 BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME="002"><H2><B>Amber for red-breast: the stonechat</B></H2>	<P><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/stonechat.gif" WIDTH=160 ALIGN=left ALIGN=TOP><P>The stonechat <I>(Saxicola torquata)</I> is on the 'amber' list of birds of conservation concern in Europe. Most stonechats remain in the UK for the winter, and many die if the cold is severe, but numbers should recover in mild winters. However, since the early 1970s the overall population has declined steadily. <P>Most stonechats breed in the west and south of England, but there are also populations in north and west Scotland and in west Wales. There are almost none in the east of Britain between Aberdeen and Norfolk.<P>The stonechat is rather like the robin in general appearance, with a large, rounded head and long legs. The male has a bright red breast, black head and white collar; prominent white patches are clearly visible on the wings and rump in flight. The female is less distinctly marked. The stonechat is about 12.5 cm long.<P><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/bagchat.gif" WIDTH=160 ALIGN=right ALIGN=TOP><P>Stonechats usually nest on the ground. The nests, which are built by the female only, are made of grass and lined with hair and sometimes feathers. Both female and male feed the young.<P>Look out for stonechats in open country with gorse and near the coast.<BR CLEAR=right><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/line.gif" WIDTH=440 BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME="003"><H2><B>Fair fowl: the pink-footed goose</B></H2>	<P><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/raidgeese.gif" WIDTH=160 ALIGN=left ALIGN=TOP><P>The pink-footed goose <I>(Anser brachynhynchus)</I> is probably the most attractive of the geese species found in the UK. As well as pink legs and feet, its distinguishing features include a white front, a barred, greyish back and a very dark, rounded head. It is 60-75 cm long.<P>In winter about 20,000 pink-footed geese spend the winter at Loch Leven, in Kinross, Scotland, where <I>Wings</I> filmed them. These birds are part of a huge winter population of about 225,000, which come from Iceland and east Greenland. Other flocks winter in Lancashire and Norfolk. <P><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/migrating.gif" WIDTH=160 ALIGN=right ALIGN=TOP><P>It's thrilling to watch streams of honking pink-footed geese returning from their inland feeding grounds to their roosts. In addition to Loch Leven, sites at which flocks can be seen include the Vane Farm RSPB reserve, Tayside; the Snettisham RSPB reserve, Norfolk; the Caerlaverock Wildfowl and Wetland Trust reserve, Dumfries; and the Martinmere Wildfowl and Wetland Trust Reserve, Lancashire.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/line.gif" WIDTH=440 BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME="004"><H2><B>Sitting duck: the eider</B></H2><P><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/countducks.gif" WIDTH=160 ALIGN=left ALIGN=TOP><P>The UK has as many as 70,000 eider ducks in winter, and the Firth of Tay, featured in the programme, is an internationally important site, hosting about 20,000 of them. Other significant wintering areas include Shetland, Orkney and the Western Isles, the Firth of Forth and Morecambe Bay.<P>Even at long range, an adult drake eider is easy to identify, being uniquely white on top and black beneath. The female is brown and barred, with a pale line over the eye.<P>In spring and summer eiders spend a lot of time resting and preening on rocks and sandbanks. They are often placid and approachable.<P>Like many wildfowl, eiders begin courtship in late winter. Females nest singly or in loose colonies, often in crevices between big rocks. Many also nest in gull and tern colonies, benefiting from their neighbours greater aggressiveness towards predators. The nests are made of grass and seaweed, and lined with down and feathers. The chicks are taken down to the water soon after they hatch. They are independent of their parents, but tend to attach themselves to a nearby adult.<P><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/birdersflock.gif" WIDTH=160 ALIGN=left ALIGN=TOP><P>In addition to the Firth of Tay, sites at which eiders can be seen include the Ythan estuary, Grampian; Aberlady Bay, Lothian; the Farne Islands National Nature Reserve, off the coast of Northumberland; and the Titchwell Marsh RSPB reserve, Norfolk.<BR CLEAR=left></FONT><P><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/line.gif" BORDER=0></A><P>			<TABLE>		<P>	<TR><TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=100><A HREF="wingshome.html"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/home.gif" ALT="RSPB" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100 BORDER=0></A></TD>				<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=100><A HREF="rspb.html"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/rspb.gif" ALT="RSPB" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100 BORDER=0></A></TD>	<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=100><A HREF="links.html"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/links.gif" ALT="Links" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100 BORDER=0></A></TD>						</TR>	</TABLE>		</DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
