<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Wings: Bird song and all that jizz</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#124B69" LINK="#166F1A" VLINK="#77422A" ALINK="#FF00FF"><BASEFONT SIZE=4><A NAME="TOP"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/prog4.gif" WIDTH=440 ALT="Programme 4: Bird song and all that jizz" ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0></TD>	</TR><DL><DD>	<TABLE>		<P>	<TR><TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=100><A HREF="wingshome.html"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/home.gif" ALT="HOME" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100 BORDER=0></A></TD>				<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=100><A HREF="rspb.html"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/rspb.gif" ALT="RSPB" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100 BORDER=0></A></TD>	<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=100><A HREF="Links.html"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/links.gif" ALT="Links" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100 BORDER=0></A></TD>						</TR>	</TABLE><P><UL><LI><A HREF="#001">Retiring virtuoso: the nightingale</A><LI><A HREF="#002">Plangent plagiarist: the great tit</A><LI><A HREF="#003">Knot hard to identify?</A><LI><A HREF="#004">Avocet advocate</A></UL><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/line.gif" BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME="001"><H2><B>Retiring virtuoso: the nightingale</B></H2><P>If you're in a wood, you may be able to hear a bird long before you can see it. Identifying birds from their songs has been made much easier by enthusiasts such as Pat Sellar, whose hobby is to record them. 'For anyone who is interested in the countryside, a walk can be enormously enhanced if they are able to identify the various sounds they hear,' says Pat. <P><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/recording.gif" WIDTH=391 ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP> <FONT SIZE=-1><FONT COLOR="#000000"><I>Pat Sellar, kitted out in his recording gear, points the microphone in the direction of the bird he is stalking for its song</I> </FONT><P>Male birds stick mainly to love songs, which they use to attract females. The male of the nightingale species <I>(Luscinia megarhynchus)</I> is a particularly fine exponent of the serenade. Though famous for singing at night, nightingales also sing during the day. <P>The nightingale is a good example of a bird that tends to be heard and not seen - it is quite plain in appearance, with brown upper parts and a russet tail, and often skulks in dense foliage.<P>Female nightingales build their nests in undergrowth and incubate their eggs alone. Both sexes feed the young.<P>The nightingale is a summer migrant, mainly found in the east Midlands, East Anglia, the Severn valley and south of the line between the Severn and Thames estuaries, though it is rare in Devon and never seen in Cornwall. Its population has declined by more than 25 per cent over the last 25 years and now consists of about 5,000-6,000 breeding pairs.<P>Nightingales can be heard or seen at several RSPB reserves, including those at Minsmere, Suffolk (off the B1125 from Westleton to Dunwich or via East Bridge north from Leiston) and Blean Woods, Kent (off Rough Common, 500 yards from the A290, a mile and a half north-west of Canterbury).<BR CLEAR=LEFT><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/line.gif" WIDTH=440 BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME="002"><H2><B>Plangent plagiarist: the great tit</B></H2>	<P>The great tit <I>(Parus major)</I> is also a skilled songsmith, though of a rather different sort. It has a very wide repertoire of calls, and is an accomplished mimic. The tone of its song tends to be rather metallic.<P>Despite its name, the great tit is quite small (about 14 cm long). It has a black crown, white cheeks and a yellow-green back; its under parts are yellow with a broad black stripe. It lives in woods, copses, hedgerows and gardens.<P>Great tits nest in holes in trees or walls, and are quite happy to use nest boxes or flower pots if there's nothing else available. Males help to build the nests and feed the young.<P>The great tit is a UK resident, and is widely distributed.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/line.gif" WIDTH=440 BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME="003"><H2><B>Knot hard to identify?</B></H2>	<P><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/hide.gif" WIDTH=158 HEIGHT=390 ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP> <FONT SIZE=-1><FONT COLOR="#000000"><I>A determined birder uses a makeshift hide to camoflage his presence and pokes the long-range lens through the canvas walls to capture these Godwits circling the estuary</I> </FONT> <P>The wide open spaces of estuaries present a particular identification problem - either the birds are too far away to be seen clearly or they are swirling round in a confusing mass. Experienced birdwatchers therefore have to rely on 'jizz' - a rather wayward acronym for 'general impression and size' - to establish the species and numbers of large flocks.<P>The knot <I>(Calidris canulus)</I>, which forms flocks of thousands on large sand- and mud-flats, is a case in point. If you can get a good look at an individual, it is recognisable by its grey-and-white plumage, stocky build and straight bill. It has fairly short legs for a wader and is about 25 cm long.<P>Nearly 300,000 knots winter in Britain. The Wash and the Thames, Humber and Ribble estuaries have the largest populations. Knots feed mainly on mud-flats between the tides, taking small bivalves, molluscs and invertebrates.<P>Good places to see the knot, along with the <A HREF="wprog2.html#004">dunlin</A> and the bar-tailed godwit, also featured in the programme, include the RSPB reserves at Snettisham, Norfolk (signposted from the A149 King's Lynn to Hunstanton road in Snettisham village) and Morecambe Bay, Lancashire (off the A5105 Morecambe-Carnforth road), and also Aberlady Bay in the Firth of Forth and the Severn estuary.<BR CLEAR=LEFT><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/line.gif" WIDTH=440 BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME="004"><H2><B>Avocet advocate</B></H2><P>The avocet <I>(Recurvirostra avosetta)</I> is the emblem of the RSPB. It was extinct as a breeding species in the UK for nearly a century, but now about 500 pairs breed here - most of them in the coastal reserves of East Anglia. The species remains very rare elsewhere in the UK.<P>Like the knot, the avocet is a very gregarious bird, though its thin, upcurving bill and the striking pattern of its black and white plumage make it easier to identify. It is about 42 cm long. <P>Avocets feed on mud-flats or in shallow water, taking insects, molluscs, crustaceans, worms and fish spawn. They nest in colonies on the ground, close to water. Both male and female incubate the eggs and tend the young.<P>A good place to see the avocet is at the Minsmere RSPB reserve in Suffolk (off the B1125 from Westleton to Dunwich or via East Bridge north from Leiston).</FONT><P><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/line.gif" BORDER=0></A><P>			<TABLE>		<P>	<TR><TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=100><A HREF="wingshome.html"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/home.gif" ALT="HOME" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100 BORDER=0></A></TD>				<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=100><A HREF="rspb.html"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/rspb.gif" ALT="RSPB" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100 BORDER=0></A></TD>	<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=100><A HREF="links.html"><IMG SRC="wingsgifs/links.gif" ALT="Links" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=100 BORDER=0></A></TD>						</TR>	</TABLE>		</DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
