<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Cutting Edge: White Death</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#006B10" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><DL><DD><CENTER><P><A HREF="../reports.html"><IMG SRC="../backtoindex.gif" border=0></A><BR CLEAR=left><H1>Cutting Edge: White Death</H1><H2>Monday 28 October 9pm</H2><HR WIDTH=40% SIZE=1><H3>Script of Dial and Listen Service<BR>Run for Channel 4</H3><HR WIDTH=40% SIZE=1></CENTER><P>Thank you for calling this recorded message after the Channel 4 Cutting Edge programme which was about the rise of new drug-resistant strains of TB.    <P>Tuberculosis, or TB as it is more usually known, is an infection caused by a bacterium that can affect any part of the body but most commonly infects the lungs.  Like colds and flu, TB is spread through the air by coughing, sneezing or via sputum or on food.  Infection usually causes no immediate problems but illness may develop a few months or even years later.  <P>Worldwide, TB is responsible for more disease and death than any other organism.  <P>In Britain, it was believed the disease had almost died out as a result of improved living conditions, but since 1987 there has been a rise in the number of reported cases.  The pattern is similar in other European countries and in the United States.  <P>Possible reasons for the rise in TB include increasing deprivation amongst certain sections of the population, the fact that people are living longer, the arrival of individuals from areas where TB is more common, such as the Indian sub-continent and HIV infection.<P>But new drug resistant strains of TB, like the ones mentioned in the programme are still extremely rare and represent only 1 per cent of all reported cases.  The vast majority of infections are completely cured through safe and effective drug treatment.<P>People most at risk from TB are homeless people and those living in poor social conditions.  Young children, pregnant women and people with HIV, the virus that causes AIDS may also be vulnerable.  <P>Nearly all children will have had a vaccination against TB, called the BCG, either in the first few weeks after birth or at about the age of 12.  This doesn't completely protect against TB, but can help the body to fight off infection.  If you or a member of your family has not a BCG vaccination you can ask your GP to give you one.  <P>The symptoms of TB include coughing, sometimes accompanied by sputum, which may be bloodstained.  There may also be chest pains, loss of appetite and weight and a fever with sweating, particularly at night.  If the disease has affected the lymph glands, these may appear as lumps in the neck.<P>If you have had a cough or sore throat which has not disappeared after six weeks, or if you are concerned that you might be at risk of contracting TB, you should ask your GP for a check up.  Your GP may arrange for you to have an X-ray.  Children and younger teenagers will be offered a simple skin test and possibly a BCG vaccination.    <P>If you have been in contact with someone who has TB, there is no need to worry.  A comprehensive nationwide tracing service will ensure that you are contacted if it is thought that you might be at risk.<P>If you would like more information about TB and its treatment, you can contact the British Lung Foundation on 0171 831 5831, that's 0171 831 5831.<P>Because TB was thought to have virtually died out, many GPs, particularly younger ones are not alert to its symptoms when patients arrive complaining of a long standing cough.  If you are a doctor, and have not come across TB before, you can find out more information about the disease and affected riskgroups from the British Lung Foundation on 0171 831 5831, that's 0171 831 5831.  For doctors working in hospitals the Department of Health have issued guidelines on the best ways of protecting patients from infection.<P>This message was provided by Science Line, the scientific question and answer service.  Science Line is open every weekday between 1.00pm and 7.00pm on 0345 600444, 0345 600444.  All calls are charged at local rates.<P><HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=center SIZE=5 ><P></BODY></HTML>
