<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Nothing but the Truth: Should Margaret be helped to kill herself?</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#006B10" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><DL><DD><CENTER><P><A HREF="../reports.html"><IMG SRC="../backtoindex.gif" border=0></A><BR CLEAR=left><H1>Nothing but the Truth:<BR> Should Margaret be helped to kill herself?</H1><H2>13th OCTOBER 1996</H2><HR WIDTH=40% SIZE=1><H3>Report on Support Services Run for Channel 4<BR>by<BR>Broadcasting Support Services</H3><HR WIDTH=40% SIZE=1></CENTER><P><H3><A NAME="S"></A><CENTER>SUMMARY</CENTER></H3>	<P>Channel 4 Television commissioned BSS Manchester to set up a free and confidential helpline after <I>Nothing But The Truth</I>,  on euthanasia, on 13 October 1996.<P><CENTER><TABLE>	<TABLE BORDER WIDTH=45%><TR><TD>No of lines available</TD><TD><CENTER>20</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>No of hours helpline open</TD><TD><CENTER>3</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>No of helpline hours</TD><TD><CENTER>60</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Effective calls (of which 15 were silent)</TD><TD><CENTER>183</CENTER></TD></TR></TABLE>	</CENTER><P>The programme was a controversial one, and consequently the helpline could have been quite difficult, as advisors were not able to discuss issues around euthanasia, as a result of BSS's and channel 4's policy on the subject.  About a third of callers did want to talk about euthanasia amongst other issues, but most fully understood the advisors' position.<P>Well over half the callers wanted to talk about terminal illnesses, many having cared for or currently caring for a parent or relative.  Half of these calls were about Motor Neurone Disease.  Many callers had feelings of guilt at not having helped to relieve the suffering, or at not having been able to care for the sufferer personally.<P>53% of callers wanted to comment on the programme - 4 times as many positive comments as negative comments.  Whether positive or negative the programme evoked some very strong feelings. <P><HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=center SIZE=5 ><P><CENTER><H2>CONTENTS</H2></CENTER>								<P><H3>1.0 <A HREF="#1.0">BACKGROUND</A></H3><P><H3>2.0 <A HREF="#2.0">HELPLINE OBJECTIVES</A></H3><P><H3>3.0	<A HREF="#3.0">FUNDING</A></H3>	<P><H3>4.0	<A HREF="#4.0">THE PROGRAMME</A></H3>	<P><H3>5.0	<A HREF="#5.0">SUPPORT SERVICES</A></H3>	<UL>	<LI>5.1	<A HREF="#5.1">The Helpline</A>								<LI>5.2	<A HREF="#5.2">Helpline Advisors</A>							<LI>5.3	<A HREF="#5.3">Information Resources</A>							<LI>5.4	<A HREF="#5.4">Call Record Form</A></UL>	<P><H3>6.0 <A HREF="#6.0">NOTHING BUT THE TRUTH HELPLINE CALLS</A></H3>	<UL>	<LI>6.1	<A HREF="#6.1">Who called?</A>		<LI>6.2	<A HREF="#6.2">What was the call about?</A>		<LI>6.3	<A HREF="#6.3">First time sought help</A>		<LI>6.4	<A HREF="#6.4">Referrals</A>		<LI>6.5	<A HREF="#6.5">Length of call</A>	</UL><P><H3>7.0	<A HREF="#7.0">SAMPLE CALLS</A></H3><P><H3>8.0 <A HREF="#8.0">OBSERVATIONS</A></H3>						<P><H3><A HREF="#A">APPENDIX: Important Information For Telephone Advisors</A></H3><P><HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=center SIZE=5 ><P><CENTER><H2><B><A NAME="1.0"></A>1.0 BACKGROUND</B></H2></CENTER><P><A NAME="1.0"></A><H3>1.0 BACKGROUND</H3>Channel 4 commissioned Broadcasting Support Services to provide a free and confidential helpline for viewers after one programme in the series <I>Nothing But The Truth</I>,  entitled <I>Should Margaret Be Helped To Kill Herself?</I>, a debate on the legalisation of euthanasia, on Sunday 13 October 1996.  <P><HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=center SIZE=5 ><P><CENTER><H2><B><A NAME="2.0"></A>2.0 HELPLINE OBJECTIVES</B></H2></CENTER><P>The helpline was designed for viewers who had personal experience of any of the issues raised in the programme.  These included the legal issues around euthanasia, motor neurone disease, and caring for the terminally ill.  The objectives were:<P><UL>	<LI>to provide some immediate support to viewers who were in similar situations to those people featured in the programme;	<LI>to give accurate information about other organisations which may be able to offer more long term support, both on a local and a national level;</UL><P>whilst being very clear on the legal position regarding euthanasia.<P><HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=center SIZE=5 ><P><CENTER><H2><B><A NAME="3.0"></A>3.0 FUNDING</B></H2></CENTER><P>The cost of the helpline was met in full by Channel 4 Television.<P><HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=center SIZE=5 ><P><CENTER><H2><B><A NAME="4.0"></A>4.0 THE PROGRAMME</B></H2></CENTER><P><I>Nothing But The Truth</I> is an 8 part series shown on Sundays from 8.00pm to 9.00pm.<UL>	<P><I>Individuals at the crux of an emotive dilemma are 'put on trial' before the studio courtroom in an attempt to get to the heart of the day's pressing matters.  Protagonists and their witnesses are cross-examined by advocates: evidence is introduced and analysed and finally a 12-person jury who have heard the case deliver their verdict.</I>  (Channel 4 Press Release)</UL><P>In the fourth programme in the series, the question which was debated was Should Margaret Be Helped To Kill Herself?  <UL>	<P><I>The case centres around Margaret who suffers from motor neurone disease.  Most cases of euthanasia involve people with motor neurone disease, terminal cancer, multiple sclerosis and AIDS - but not the elderly.  She wants her husband to help her to die when the time is right.</I>  (Judge's brief)</UL><P>In the programme, Margaret, the witness for voluntary euthanasia, appears in the witness box, giving a very articulate account of her reasons for believing that she should have the right to die when she chooses, with the help of her husband.  The prosecutor calls as witnesses two sufferers of motor neurone disease to put forward their arguments against the motion.  At the end of the programme, the jury, having heard all the arguments delivered their verdict that Margaret should be helped to kill herself.<P>The announcement at the end of the programme was as follows:<UL>	<P><B>"If you would like to talk to someone in confidence about motor neurone disease or terminal illness, you can call our free helpline on 0500 220 210.  Lines will be open for the next three hours.  That's 0500 220 210."</B></UL><P>There was no reference made to euthanasia in the announcement as BSS agreed with Channel 4 that it would not be appropriate for advisors to discuss euthanasia with callers.  See <A HREF="#9.0">APPENDIX: Important Information For Telephone Advisors.</A><P><HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=center SIZE=5 ><P><A NAME="5.0"></A><CENTER><H2><B>5.0 SUPPORT SERVICES</B></H2></CENTER><P><A NAME="5.1"></A><H3>5.1 The Helpline</H3><P>The free and confidential helpline was open from 9.00pm until midnight on Sunday 13 October on 20 at BSS Manchester.<P>When the helpline had closed, a message was left on the answering machine, giving the Motor Neurone Disease Association's helpline number and the Samaritans' 24 hour number.<P><A NAME="5.2"></A><H3>5.2 Helpline Advisors</H3><P>The helpline was staffed by a team of advisors with wide ranging experience.  The team included general and psychiatric nurses and health visitors with experience of caring for people with terminal illnesses, Samaritans, welfare officers, volunteers from the George House Trust (HIV/AIDS), a law centre co-ordinator, general counsellors, and a healer.  The Motor Neurone Disease Association were asked if they would like to provide any advisors but felt it would be better if we referred callers wanting to talk specifically about motor neurone disease directly to their helpline.<P>All advisors had extensive experience of working on BSS helplines, and were sent details of BSS's policy on handling calls about euthanasia in advance of the helpline.  See <A HREF="#9.0">APPENDIX: Important Information For Telephone Advisors</A>.<P>Advisors were encouraged to work as a team, transferring calls to the advisor with the most relevant experience to help the caller.<P>The debriefing at the end of the helpline gave the advisors the much needed opportunity to seek support from each other, and to give BSS valuable feedback on the information resources provided.<P><A NAME="5.3"></A><H3>5.3 Information Resources</H3><P>Advisors were provided with details of the Motor Neurone Disease Association, the Scottish Motor Neurone Disease Association, the Samaritans, the Voluntary Euthanasia Society, the Human Right Society, bereavement organisations, and organisations supporting carers and sufferers of other terminal illnesses.  Also available were copies of the Telephone Helplines Directory and the Voluntary Agencies Directory.<P><A NAME="5.4"></A><H3>5.4 Call record form</H3><P>Advisors completed a call record form at the end of each call.  The information collected referred to the caller and their reason for calling.  No reference to the identity of the caller was recorded.<P>Advisors were asked to record word for word requests for information about euthanasia.<P><HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=center SIZE=5 ><P><A NAME="6.0"></A><CENTER><H2><B>6.0 NOTHING BUT THE TRUTH HELPLINE CALLS</B></H2></CENTER><P>The total number of working calls handled was 168.  <P>There were also 15 silent calls which could have either been people testing the service or losing their confidence to speak at the last moment.<P><A NAME="6.1"></A><H3>6.1 Who called?</H3><P>(Audience profile based on total viewers of <I>Nothing But The Truth</I> 13 October 1996 [852,000]. Information provided by Channel 4.)<P><CENTER><TABLE BORDER WIDTH=40%><TR><CENTER><TD><B>GENDER</B></TD></CENTER><TR><TD></TD><TD>Helpline callers</TD> <TD>Viewers</TD><TR><TD>Female</TD> <TD>67%</TD><TD>56%</TD></TR><TR><TD>Male</TD> <TD>33%</TD><TD>43%</TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER><P>As is usual on helplines, most callers were women; disproportionately more than there were viewers.<P><CENTER><TABLE BORDER WIDTH=40%><TR><TD><B>AGE</B></TD><TR><TD></TD><TD>Helpline callers</TD> <TD>Viewers</TD><TR><TD>Under 16</TD> <TD>-</TD><TD>-</TD></TR><TR><TD>16-24</TD> <TD>3%</TD><TD>4%</TD></TR><TR><TD>25-34</TD> <TD>20%</TD><TD>15%</TD></TR><TR><TD>35-44</TD> <TD>13%</TD><TD>13%</TD></TR><TR><TD>45-54</TD> <TD>21%</TD><TD>16%</TD></TR><TR><TD>55-64</TD> <TD>21%</TD><TD>14%</TD></TR><TR><TD>Over 65</TD> <TD>22%</TD><TD>35%</TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER><P>	The programme attracted a relatively older audience, with over a third being over 65 years.  However fewer of the over 65 age group rang the helpline.<P><A NAME="6.2"></A><H3>6.2 What was the call about?</H3><P>NB. Callers often rang about a number of issues, so the percentages add up to more than 100. <P><CENTER><TABLE BORDER WIDTH=40%><TR><TD>Euthanasia</TD> <TD>30%</TD></TR><TR><TD>Motor Neurone Disease</TD> <TD>26%</TD></TR><TR><TD>Cancer</TD> <TD>20%</TD></TR><TR><TD>Multiple sclerosis</TD> <TD>4%</TD></TR><TR><TD>Other illnesses</TD> <TD>13%</TD></TR><TR><TD>Bereavement</TD> <TD> 6%</TD></TR><P><TR><TD>Programme comment - positive</TD> <TD>43%</TD></TR><TR><TD>Programme comment - negative</TD> <TD>	11%</TD></TR><P><TR><TD>Other</TD> <TD>6%</TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER><P>Other issues raised were mainly about the availability of Living Wills.<P>Many of the callers were either currently nursing parents with terminal illnesses or had done in the past.  Of these some were carers or bereaved looking for support, some were questioning the treatment their parents had been given and others wanted to discuss euthanasia.  Most of the callers who wanted to discuss euthanasia accepted that the advisors could not do so.  One caller had made an agreement with her friend 40 years ago that if either was in a bad way the other would help them to die.  The situation had now arisen.  Several callers expressed the view that not enough support was available for sufferers of terminal illness and their families.  Several callers talked about their guilt at not being able to look after their parents themselves.<P>A handful of callers raised religious issues and were surprised that this angle has not been mentioned at all in the programme.<P>If callers made comments about the programme, they tended to be either very positive or very negative.  It is more likely that advisors referred the callers who's comments were negative on to the Duty Office, so the Duty Log may not reflect the weight of positive feelings about the programme.<P>Negative comments tended to be about the fear that the programme would open the floodgates for people to kill for financial gain, the lack of religious perspective, the fact that humour was used in the programme, minimising the seriousness of the issue and the illness, or that it was not made clear that people could live long and healthy lives with Motor Neurone Disease.<P>Positive comments outweighed the negative comments by 4:1.  Callers' comments varied: some felt that the programme treated both the case for and the case against in a sensitive manner, others wanted to register their support for voluntary euthanasia, others just wanted to say they enjoyed watching the programme.  Several callers wanted to contact Margaret to offer her their support.  One caller said that the programme had given her the confidence to find out more about her illness and where she could get support.<P>See <A HREF="#7.0">7.0 SAMPLE CALLS</A>.<P><CENTER><TABLE BORDER WIDTH=40%><TR><TD><B>CALLING:</B></TD> </TR><TR><TD>On their own behalf</TD> <TD>83%</TD></TR><TR><TD>For someone else</TD> <TD>15%</TD></TR><TR><TD>Professional</TD> <TD>2%</TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER><P><A NAME="6.3"></A><H3>6.3 First time sought help</H3><P><CENTER><TABLE BORDER WIDTH=40%><TR><TD>First time</TD> <TD>74%</TD></TR><TR><TD>Tried elsewhere</TD> <TD>26%</TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER><P>As we usually find, most callers had never spoken to any one before about the issue that concerned them.<P><A NAME="6.4"></A><H3>6.4 Referrals</H3><P>The referrals that were made included: the Motor Neurone Disease Association, GP, the Channel 4 Duty Office, the Samaritans, CRUSE Bereavement Care, the Voluntary Euthanasia Society, Human Rights Society, the Terence Higgins Trust, MIND, and local Community Health Councils. <P>However many callers did not want to be referred elsewhere, but just wanted to be able to tell someone about their own circumstances, or to register their opinions on the euthanasia issue.<P>The Moter Neurone Disease Association provided a brief report on the calls they received as a result of the programme and helpline.<P><A NAME="6.5"></A><H3>6.5 Length of call</H3><P><CENTER><TABLE BORDER WIDTH=40%><TR><TD>Up to 10 mins</TD> <TD>76%</TD></TR><TR><TD>11 -20 mins</TD> <TD>23%</TD></TR><TR><TD>21 - 30 mins</TD> <TD>-%</TD></TR><TR><TD>Over 30 mins</TD> <TD>1%</TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER><P>Most calls were fairly short.  The shortness of some calls is attributable to advisors not being able to discuss euthanasia with callers.<P><HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=center SIZE=5 ><P><A NAME="7.0"></A><CENTER><H2>7.0 SAMPLE CALLS (Fictionalised)</H2></CENTER><P>Caller in her 80's who's husband died 30 years ago of a terminal illness.  She wishes now that she had helped him to die as he was in such pain.<P>Caller has MND and has considered euthanasia.  Since her diagnosis she has had several different sorts of treatment and has already lived longer than expected.<P>Caller's mother died of MND 20 years ago.  She is as distressed today as she was then and feels she needs help to come to terms with her mother's death.  Strongly in favour of euthanasia.<P>Caller has breast cancer and has been told there is nothing more that can be done.  She feels she has been given a death sentence.  She wants to be able to choose when to die.<P>Caller's daughter was helped to die by her husband.  Caller distressed because she did not get the chance to say goodbye.<P>Caller's husband has MND.  They had not been told that MND is incurable and wanted more information.<P>Caller has MS and wanted to discuss euthanasia.<P>Caller felt he had evidence of euthanasia happening in the hospital where he works, wanted to know what he could do about it.<P><B>Programme comments</B><P>Caller felt the programme was informative and well balance, the best television he had seen for a long time.<P>Caller well and happy at the moment but would certainly consider euthanasia if she was terminally ill.  Thought the programme was wonderful.<P>Caller enjoyed the programme and thought the NHS should buy the machine shown immediately.<P>Caller wanted to praise the programme, feels the government wastes too much money on long term care for terminally ill patients.<P>Caller very much against euthanasia, feels her father was killed off recently in an NHS hospital, feels the programme did a lot of harm in encouraging mercy killings.<P>Caller has had MND for 12 years and thought the programme was unfairly presented.<P>Caller concerned that no comments about the teachings of the bible were made in the programme.<P><HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=center SIZE=5 ><P><A NAME="8.0"></A><CENTER><H2>8.0 OBSERVATIONS</H2></CENTER><P>There was some anxiety about running this helpline; that we may be putting advisors at risk of being misinterpreted if the subject of euthanasia was raised.  It was very important that the advisors were carefully briefed on how to deal with these calls, that they understood clearly the role of the helpline, and the legal position regarding aiding another person to die.<P>Some callers will have been disappointed that they were not able to discuss euthanasia with advisors, but the majority understood and accepted the reasoning.  The opinions and reasoning that callers gave about the legalisation of euthanasia reiterated the complicated nature of this debate.<P>However, the decision to run the helpline meant that many distressed callers were able to get support and information about other organisations who would be able to help them, over three quarters of callers never having sought help before.<P><B>Lissa Davenport<BR>Project Manager<BR>October 1996<BR></B><P><HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=center SIZE=5 ><P><A NAME="A"></A><CENTER><H2>APPENDIX: IMPORTANT INFORMATION FOR TELEPHONE ADVISORS</H2></CENTER><P>Channel 4 has commissioned BSS to run a helpline after Nothing But The Truth on Sunday 13 October 1996.<P>Channel 4's description of the series is as follows:<P><I>Individuals at the crux of an emotive dilemma are 'put on trial' before the studio courtroom in an attempt to get to the heart of the day's pressing matters.  Protagonists and their witnesses are cross-examined by advocates: evidence is introduced and analysed and finally a 12 person jury who have heard the case deliver their verdict.</I><P>Channel 4 have given us this information about next Sunday's programme:<P><I>The case centres around Margaret who suffers from Motor Neurone Disease.  Most cases of euthanasia involve people with motor neurone disease, terminal cancer, multiple sclerosis and AIDS - but not the elderly.  She wants her husband to help her die when the time is right.</I><P>Obviously euthanasia is a very delicate issue and BSS has strict policies on how to handle callers who may wish to discuss euthanasia.  I have included the relevant part of BSS's policy below.  For this helpline we anticipate that we will get calls from viewers with Motor Neurone Disease or other terminal illnesses, or from those who are caring for sufferers. Our objective will be to provide support to these callers without entering into any debate about euthanasia.  This may be very difficult if callers are angry that these issues are being discussed in this way on television.  Comments about the programme will be passed on to Channel 4's Duty office in the usual way.<P>Excerpt from BSS's policy statement on suicide and euthanasia:<P>It is illegal in the UK for a person to aid, abet, procure or counsel the death of another person.  The law says we must not incite, instruct, authorise or put someone up to taking their own life, however impossible their circumstances might be.  It is possible that replying to an apparently simple question asked by a caller who appears determined to take their own life, could mean that we have broken the law.  BSS does not therefore run helplines designed primarily to give information about euthanasia.<P>We do run helplines and other services around death and terminal illness.  Care is still needed in such circumstances.  If a caller on a bereavement or related helpline asks specifically about euthanasia then the BSS helpliner must explain that we cannot discuss euthanasia.  If asked, BSS helpliners can read out the details of organisations who do discuss euthanasia, from public listings such as NCVO's Directory of Voluntary Organisations.  More than one organisation should be given.  Always give the Samaritans.<P><B>We are very grateful to you for agreeing to work on this helpline, and especially at such short notice, but if you feel you cannot work within BSS's policy on this subject we must ask you to let us know and withdraw from the helpline.</B><P><HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=center SIZE=5 ><P></BODY></HTML>
