<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Citizen's Arrest - Bad News Bank</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#006B10" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><DL><DD><CENTER><P><A HREF="../reports.html"><IMG SRC="../backtoindex.gif" border=0></A><BR CLEAR=left><H1>Citizen's Arrest - Bad News Bank</H1><H2>8th October 1996</H2><HR WIDTH=40% SIZE=1><H3>Report on Support Services Run for Channel 4<BR>by<BR>Broadcasting Support Services</H3><HR WIDTH=40% SIZE=1></CENTER><H2>Dial and Listen Service</H2><P>Tariff 0345<BR>Number of Calls 1,125<BR><H2>Bakground</H2><P>Channel 4 broadcast the Bad News Bank documentary on Tuesday Octoer 8th at 8pm and Paula Snyder, Channel 4 Suppor Services asked BSS Wales to arrange a Dial & Listen service and write the script.<H2>Programme</H2><P>Bad News Bank was a half hour documentary n the Citizen's Arrest series in which members of the public who have a grievance against an prganisaiton relate their story to reporter Joe Layburn. Togehter, with a camera crew, they then confront the organisation. In Bak News Bank Barclays Bank is the target of the programme. Keith, who started a car business in 1977, claims that the bank pulled out of a loan agreement which resulted in the collapse of his business, his health and his marriage.<H2>The Announcement</H2><P>The post-programme announcement said:<P><I>There's a special Channel 4 information line which gives sources of help for people with banking problems, on</I> 0345 59 10 12<P><I>Calls will cost no more than 16 pence and lines are open for the next month. That's</I> 0345 59 10 12<H2>The Script</H2><P>Thank you for calling the Channel 4, Citizens Arrest information line on business banking problems.<P>The message lasts for 4 minutes and will cost you 16p during the daytime and 6p after 6pm. You will need pen and paper to take down addresses.<P>We are unable to comment on, or offer advic on specific cases . The folowing informatio may help you to access the informed advice you need.<P>Every effort should be made to negotiate a reasonable settlement with your bankers. If however your problem cannot be sorted ot with them and you think you have been bakly treatd you may need to contact the banking or Building Society Ombudsman.<P>Their role is to act independently to resolve disputes over unfair treatment or maladministration. The ombudsman will not intervene where a lender has make a legitimate financial decision. Contact:<P>The Banking Ombudsman at<BR>70 Grays Inn |Road<BR>London WC1X 8NB<BR>0171 404 9944 or out of London callers can ring<BR>LoCall number 0345 66 09 02<BR><P>The Building Societies Ombudsman at<BR>Millbank Towr<BR>Millbank<BR>London SW1P 4XS<BR>0171 931 0044<BR><P>The Securities and Investment Board is the chief regulatory body for the financial services industry. You can contact SIB at<P>Gavrelle House<BR>2-14 Bungill Row<BR>London EC1Y 8RA<BR>0171 638 1240<BR><P>The Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales are at:<BR>PO Box 433<BR>Chartered Accountants Hall<BR>Moorgate Place<BR>London EC2P 2BJ<BR>0171 920 8682<BR><P>For Scotland ring: 0131 225 5676<P>For Northern Ireland ring: 01232 321 600.<P>If your business problems are causing you and your family personal financial problems you can discuss this with an advice worker at Citizens Advice Bureaux, who will help you sort out a plan of action including letters to creditors and budgeting.<P>Look in your telephone directory for you local bureau.<P>The National DebtLine offers advice and information to anyone with debt problems. Their independent helpline is open Mondays and Thursdays 10am to 4pm and Tuesdays and Wednesdays 2pm to 7pm. The number is 0121 359 8501.<P>Worries over financial problems, legal tangles and the consequent stress can sometimes seem an intolerable burden. There are people who are willing to listen and this is sometimes what you need to help you through the most stressful periods. The Samaritans are open 24 hours every day. You can ring them from anywhere on a LoCall number 0345 90 90 90.<P>It is easy to be wise after the event but the following gerneral points may help in the future:<P>Never sign up for any scheme or loan until you understand exactly how it works and the best and worst that can happen.<P>Always take independent financial advice<P>Always ask "What if?"<P>Keep original documents safely, copy all agreement letters or contracts<P>Make your own notes of verbal agreements made in meetings and send a copy to all present at that meeting.<P>This information line has been prepared for Channel 4 by Broadcasting Support Services.<H2>The Response</H2><P>1,125 callers rang the Dial & Listen service. 733 (65%0 of them rang on the first night, 165 (15%) the next day and the rest, 227 (20%) during the following minth.<H2>Conclusion</H2><P>From the response, many people identified with the subject and felt the need for help in dealing with bsiness banking problems.<P><HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=center SIZE=5 ><P></BODY></HTML>
