<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Citizen's Arrest: Terry's Tale</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#006B10" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><DL><DD><CENTER><P><A HREF="../reports.html"><IMG SRC="../backtoindex.gif" border=0></A><BR CLEAR=left><H1>Citizen's Arrest: Terry's Tale</H1><H2>Tuesday 22nd October 1996</H2><HR WIDTH=40% SIZE=1><H3>Report on Support Services Run for Channel 4<BR>by<BR>Broadcasting Support Services</H3><HR WIDTH=40% SIZE=1></CENTER><H2>Contents</H2><A HREF="#Summary">Summary</A><P><B>Background</B><BR><UL><LI><A HREF="#Broadcast">The Broadcast</A><BR><LI><A HREF="#DialandListen">The Dial and Listen / Helpline</A><BR><LI><A HREF="#Advisors">The Advisors</A><BR><LI><A HREF="#BriefingSession">The Briefing Session</A><BR><LI><A HREF="#ReferralMaterials">The Referral Materials</A><BR><LI><A HREF="#DualService">Aim of the Dual Service</A><BR><LI><A HREF="#Announcement">Announcement</A><BR><LI><A HREF="#Response">Response</A><BR><LI><A HREF="#Referrals">Referrals</A><BR><LI><A HREF="#Observations">Observations</A><BR></UL><H2><A NAME="Summary">Summary</H2><P>Broadcasting Support Services provided and ran a helpline to support the Channel 4 programme, Citizen's Arrest: Terry's Tale.  The programme focused on Terry Campbell and her ten year old son John who was expelled from his school two years ago for truanting.  John's problem was actually dyslexia, not disruptive behaviour.<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=2 CELLPADDING=4><TR><TD>Calls to Dial and Listen  service</TD><TD align=right>1,025</TD></TR><TR><TD>Tariff for Dial and Listen</TD><TD align=right>0345</TD></TR><TR><TD><HR></TD></TR><TR><TD>Tariff for helpline service</TD><TD align=right>0800</TD></TR><TR><TD>Number  of lines on helpline service</TD><TD align=right>16</TD></TR><TR><TD>Number of hours helpline open</TD><TD align=right>3</TD></TR><TR><TD>Number of effective helpline calls</TD><TD align=right>108</TD></TR><TR><TD>Ineffective calls to helpline </TD><TD align=right>809</TD></TR>           </TABLE> <H2>Background</H2><H3><A NAME="Broadcast">The Broadcast</H3><P>Terry's Tale is the sixth programme in the series Citizens Arrest which takes up the causes of ordinary citizens who believe they have suffered injustice from big business or bureaucracy.  Terry is the mother of ten year old John who was expelled from school two years ago for truanting.  Terry claims that John was running away because of bullying. His older brother had been bullied and had committed suicide.  The local education authority started a process of statementing and recommended a school for emotionally disturbed children but Terry refused to send John.  Eventually John was diagnosed as dyslexic - misunderstood rather than disruptive.  Terry is angry that the LEA denied John those two years and that they failed to listen to her.<H3><A NAME="DialandListen">The Dial and Listen / Helpline</H3><P>A dual service of Dial and Listen and a helpline was commissioned by Paula Snyder, Support Services Editor, Channel 4.<P>The programme finished at 8.30pm and the dial and listen number was announced (0345 59 10 11) on screen.  This message contained the names and addresses of relevant organisations but the helpline number was also given for people who desperately wanted to speak to an advisor.  The helpline was open for three hours until 11.30pm on a 0800 free call service, with 16 lines provided by BSS Wales. <P><B>The Dial and Listen service</B>(*...* was deleted after 00.15am Wednesday October 23)<P>Thank you for calling the Channel 4 Special Educational Needs information line.  This message lasts for four minutes and you will need pen and paper to take down some information.<P>* There is also a free, confidential Channel 4 helpline on 0800 600 444 open from 8.30 to 12.30 tonight.  Please listen to the whole of this message first as the information you need could be here.  The helpline will be very busy and is open for a limited time only. *<P>Some children who have special educational needs or have learning or behavioural problems may be subject to exclusion from their school.  If you are the parent or guardian of a child who has been excluded or statemented and would like to know more about you and your child's rights, the following information may be of use to you.<P>Your local education authority - LEA -  should be able to help in the first instance, and in the case of children under five years old, social services should be your first source of help and advice.  You can find both telephone numbers in your local telephone directory.<P>There's a special guide for parents, which gives a comprehensive overview of assessments and statementing, useful addresses and telephone numbers, and most important, information about the Special Educational Needs Tribunal.  This free guide can be ordered by phoning the Department for Education on 0171 51 00 150 during office hours.<P>For parents and guardians, as well as professionals, The Centre for Studies in Inclusive Education publishes a large number of free and inexpensive leaflets and reports on a number of disabilities and learning difficulties.  They run a free advice service and support parents' groups, families, schools and LEA's.  The CSIE can be contacted at 1 Redland Close, Elm Lane, Redland, Bristol BS6 6UE.<P>Parents of children with special educational needs can get a second professional opinion on learning difficulties from the Independent Panel for Special Education Advice.  They also offer a representation service for those wishing to appeal to the Special Educational Needs Tribunal.  The IPSEA can be contacted at 22 Warren Hill Road, Woodbridge, Suffolk, IP12 4DU.<P>If your child has suffered from bullying or other forms of harassment at school, contact Kidscape who produce books, leaflets, video programmes and free parents' guides.  They can be contacted at 152 Buckingham Palace Road, London SW1W 9TR, or you can ring their helpline on 0171 730 3300, Tuesdays to Fridays, between 10am and 4pm.<P>Childline is the free, national helpline for children and young people.  It offers a 24 hour counselling service.  The trained counsellors offer support and refer children in danger or distress to the relevant organisations.  childline's number is 0800 1111.  The lines are very busy so please keep trying.<P>This message was compiled by Broadcasting Support Services and will be available until mid November.<P>The dial and listen service received a total of 1,025 calls to date with 675 (66%) taken on the evening of the helpline.<H3><A NAME="Advisors">The Advisors</H3><P>The Advisors were mainly education specialists and general counsellors.  Nearly all had staffed BSS lines in the past.  Their areas of expertise covered :<P><UL><LI>Bullying<LI>Special educational needs<LI>Child psychology<LI>Community health care<LI>Social work<LI>LEA Parent Support<LI>Legal support</UL><H3><A NAME="BriefingSession">The Briefing Session</H3><P>During the briefing session the advisors watched the programme, discussed the types of call most likely to be received and the best responses.    There was an opportunity for the advisors to familiarise themselves with the phone system and call record forms, as well as the resources prepared for their use.<H3><A NAME="ReferralMaterials">The Referral Materials</H3><P>The referral materials available were :<P><B>1. At each phone position.</B>  <P>	Referral lists including agencies for:<P><UL><LI>	All Directors of Education in Wales, England, Scotland, Channel <LI>	Islands, Isles of Scilly, Isle of Man.<LI>	The Department for Education			<LI>	Centre for Studies on Inclusive Education<LI>	Advisory Centre for Education (ACE)<LI>	Children's Legal Centre<LI>	Network 81<LI>	Independent Panel for Special Education Advice (IPSEA)<LI>	AFASIC<LI>	Parentline<LI>	British Dyslexia Association<LI>	ChildLine<LI>	Kidscape<LI>	Careline<LI>	Child Death Helpline<LI>	Cruse Bereavement Line<LI>	Compassionate Friends<LI>	Samaritans.</UL><P>2.	Available for reference:<UL><LI><P>		Mental Health Directory<LI>		British Association of Counsellors Directory<LI>		Social Services Yearbook<LI>		Citizens Advice Bureaux<LI>		BSS Wales library of reference material.</UL><H3><A NAME="DualService">Aim of the Dual Service</H3><P><B>Dial & Listen</B><BR>To provide as many callers as possible with sources of  support and advice.<BR><P><B>Helpline</B><BR>To provide a personal service for  callers who felt the need to talk through their problems.<BR><H3><A NAME="Announcement">Announcement</H3><P>The Presentation Department at Channel 4 made the following announcement at the end of the broadcast:<P>THERE'S A SPECIAL INFORMATION LINE WITH SOURCES OF HELP - INCLUDING A FREE CHANNEL 4 HELPLINE - FOR FAMILIES OF CHILDREN WITH SPECIAL EDUCATIONAL NEEDS ON: 0345 59 10 11<P>CALLS WILL COST NO MORE THAN 16 PENCE AND LINES ARE OPEN FOR THE NEXT MONTH.  THAT'S 0345 59 10 11.<H3><A NAME="Response">Response</H3><P><B>Dial & Listen</B><BR>There was a total of 1025 calls. (675 calls on the night)<BR><P><B>Helpline</B><BR>There were 93 calls answered by the helpline advisers.  The lines were very busy for the first hour then it was very quiet for the remainder of the session.<BR><P>Many callers were angry about their situations in regard to Special Education Needs and Statementing. Although most had already explored the appropriate avenues -  LEA, ACE etc.,  they were grateful for the chance to discuss their situations and receive further information from the sympathetic advisers.<P><B>Who called the helpline?</B>   <BR>The table of statistics (see appendix) gives the details of callers and the subjects of the calls.  However some of the more interesting points from the 93 working calls are:<BR><UL><LI><P>88% of the callers were calling about their own child.<LI>84% of callers were calling about special educational needs.<LI>25% of callers were trying for help for the first time.<LI>13% of callers offered positive comments on the programme.</UL><H3><A NAME="Referrals">Referrals</H3><P>Callers were referred to the following:<UL><LI><P>	Independent  Panel for Special Education<LI>	Local Education Authorities<LI>	Department for Education<LI>	Advisory  Centre for  Education<LI>	Children's Legal Centre<LI>	British Dyslexia Association<LI>	Channel 4<LI>	Network 81<LI>	Parentline<LI>	School or School Governors<LI>	AFASIC (Association For All Speech Impaired Children)<LI>	GP<LI>	Hospital<LI>	ChildLine<LI>	Solicitors<LI>	Local Benefits Office<LI>	ADHD (Attention Deficit & Hyperactivity Disorder) Association</UL><H3><A NAME="Observations">Observations</H3><P>The calls showed that many people who rang had tried most options, and were angry and very dissatisfied with the education system.  Despite the fact no easy solution can be offered to parents experiencing similar problems to Terry the advisers were able to point out new approaches to the education authorities,  reinforce the callers'  confidence in their rights and encourage them to persevere. <P>Lynne Reynolds<BR>Project Manager<BR>BSS Wales<BR><P></HTML>
