<P><HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Witness: Love Child</TITLE></HEAD><P><BODY BGCOLOR="#006B10" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><DL><DD><CENTER><P><A HREF="../reports.html"><IMG SRC="../backtoindex.gif" border=0></A><BR CLEAR=left><H1>Witness: Love Child</H1><H2>September 24 and 25 1996</H2><HR WIDTH=40% SIZE=1><H3>Report on Support Services Run for Channel 4<BR>by<BR>Broadcasting Support Services</H3><HR WIDTH=40% SIZE=1></CENTER>			<H2>Contents</H2><P><UL>	<LI><A HREF="#1.0">1.0 Background</A>	<LI><A HREF="#2.0">2.0 Aims and Objectives</A>	<LI><A HREF="#3.0">3.0 The Broadcast</A>	<LI><A HREF="#4.0">4.0 Support Services Design</A>	<LI><A HREF="#5.0">5.0 Information Resources</A>	<LI><A HREF="#6.0">6.0 The Helpline</A>	<LI><A HREF="#7.0">7.0 The Response</A>	<LI><A HREF="#8.0">8.0 Who called</A>	<LI><A HREF="#9.0">9.0 Observations and Conclusion</A>	<LI><A HREF="#10.0">10.0 Caller Summary</A></UL><P><A NAME="sum"><H2>Summary</H2><P>The Editor, Channel 4 Support Services, commissioned Broadcasting Support Services to set up and run a freephone 0800 confidential helpline to support the programme Lovechild.  The programme was part of Witness , Channel 4's documentary series on contemporary moral issues.  It followed the three separate stories of Doreen Ward, Leslie Swire and Sue Marples who were pressured into  giving up their illegitimate children for adoption in 1960's Britain.  Twenty lines were open on a single site in London immediately after the programme for three hours. Ten lines were open at the same site the following day for an extended period of four and a half hours.  The lines were staffed by post-adoption counsellors from various agencies and  social workers from local authority adoption and fostering teams.  The advisors were chosen in order to provide a wide range of help, information and advice to callers on a wide range of issues arising from the programme.<P>A total of 504 calls were received, 315 calls on Tuesday 24 September and 189 on Wednesday 25 September.  Most female callers were responding to what they saw as a moving documentary that contained  stories which mirrored their own experiences.  The majority of the male callers felt that as adoptees, they could begin to sympathise with their birth mothers predicament.  The response on the whole was tremendously positive. Although some callers had found the documentary disturbing and upsetting it had actually in many cases spurred them into action. <P>There was an instant and sustained response to the trail for the helpline which continued throughout both sessions. The response was very big, with the Channel 4 duty office inundated with calls during the interim between the two sessions on Tuesday and Wednesday.I feel that this sort of response to a programme requires a larger number of lines. It was obvious from the majority of callers on the Wednesday session that many had wanted immediate help and would have happily waited all night in order to get it.<P>As is obvious with an issue such as adoption, many callers although happy to have the chance to talk about their feelings, in some cases for the first time, wanted to be reassured of the confidentiality of the service.<P><A NAME="1.0"><H2>1.0 Background</H2><P>	Lovechild was a Channel 4 documentary transmitted on September 24 1996. It was part of Channel 4's Witness 	documentary series, on contemporary moral issues. It followed 	the stories of three women who as young women in the 	60's had been forced to give up their children for adoption.  The 	three women told their often harrowing stories highlighting their 	feelings of abandonment and isolation. Although two of the 	subjects Lesley Swire and Doreen Ward had since been reunited with their children, the third subject Sue Marples who had 	eventually married the birthfather of the child she had given up, was still looking for her son. Although all three women were still upset by this event in their lives, it was obvious that it had affected Sue in a far more traumatic way. 	<P>	Paula Snyder, Editor of Programme Support at Channel 4 commissioned BSS to provide a helpline as the back-up to the programme. <P><A NAME="2.0"><H2>2.0 Aims and Objectives</H2>  <P>	The Helpline aimed to provide <UL>	<LI><P>A referral service for those seeking information on tracing a child or birth parent. 	<LI>To offer support and advice on the wide range of issues arising from the programme.</UL><P><A NAME="3.0"><H2>3.0 The Broadcast</H2> <P>	The programme was produced and directed by Jane Beckwith for Real Life productions. It transmitted at 9.00pm on Tuesday 24 September, as part of the Witness series on contemporary social issues. The programme detailed the stories of three women who had been forced to give up their children for adoption in 1960's Britain at a time when the themes of 'sex drugs and rock'n roll' were very much part of  youth culture but still taboo to the rest of society.<P>The programme was trailed:<UL>	<LI><P><B>If you would like to talk to someone about because of your own 	experiences with adoption or teenage pregnancy you can ring the free Channel 4 helpline on: 0800 767 800	<LI>Lines are now open until 1.00am tonight and again tomorrow 	afternoon from 12.00pm to 3.00pm. That's 0800 767 800</B></UL><P><A NAME="4.0"><H2>4.0 Support Services Design</H2><P>The twenty line 0800 freephone service opened on a single site 	for three hours after the programme and for four and a half 	hours the following day at the same site. The second day 10 line service was extended by an hour and a half due to demand.<P>The lines were staffed by post adoption counsellors from various agencies and social workers from local authority adoption and fostering teams.<P><A NAME="5.0"><H2>5.0 Information Resources</H2> <P>	Resources made available to the telephone advisors included contact information on :<UL>	<LI><P>post adoption counselling centres and therapists	<LI>tracing information for adoptees,birth parents,siblings	<LI>missing persons	<LI>specific contact information on the nursing homes featured in the programme	<LI>pregnancy advisory organisations specific to teenagers</UL><P><A NAME="6.0"><H2>6.0 The Helpline</H2><P>The evening began with a briefing during which advisors watched a video of the programme. A discussion took place on the types of calls  expected and what the responses should be. The general briefing notes covered guidelines to advisors on how to answer :<UL>	<LI><P>subject enquiries	<LI>difficult/abusive/silent calls	<LI>comments about the programme	<LI>how to complete call record forms</UL><P>Advisors were also asked to specify any areas related to the subject of adoption in which they had specialist knowledge in order to be able to help with any calls that demanded special attention  and specific information.  <P>The details of all the calls were recorded on call record forms 	designed specifically by BSS, for use in report writing and statistical analysis. The information recorded included gender, age and more specific caller information. Each caller was also asked where they were calling from.<P>The helpline closed on the first evening with an answerphone message giving information on the service opening time for the following day. The information lines finally closed with an answerphone message giving information about post adoption services available to callers.<P><A NAME="7.0"><H2>7.0 The Response</H2> <P>	Total calls answered: 504<P><B>Tuesday 24 September</B><BR>Male calls:	78<BR>Female calls: 237<BR>    <P><B>Wednesday 25 September</B><BR>Male calls:	34<BR>Female calls: 155<BR>	<P>Total Female calls: 315<P>Total Male calls: 189<P>There was a tremendous response. The lines opened at 10.00pm and closed at 1.00am. The lines were as busy at the end of the 	first session as they had been at the beginning of it. The second service session proved to be equally 	as popular and due to the amount of calls made to the Channel 4 duty office, the service 	was extended by an hour and a half, from 12 noon to 4.30pm.<P>Data from BT confirms the demand. The I/E ratio of ineffective to effective calls, BSS standard measure of the pressure on helplines was 74. On the basis of previous research, suggesting people try calling between ten and twenty times, this suggests that a helpline with at least five times the capacity of this one was needed to meet the demand.     <P>On a more personal note, many callers were distressed at the unhappy memories that the programme brought back to them. <P><A NAME="8.0"><H2>8.0 Who called</H2><P>77.7% of callers to this line were female. In relation to other similar helplines, this type of figure is quite typical.<P>There was however a need to distinguish between the male 	callers from the female callers in order to show a more realistic statistical picture because the majority of female callers were 	birth mothers while the majority of male callers were adoptees(see 10.0). There was no marked difference in subject matter of calls between the two sessions. <P>Callers were referred to a variety of organisations including NORCAP, Social Servcies, local post-adoption counselling agencies and adoption agencies, Salvation Army, Parent to Parent Information on Adoption Services, OPCS and various pregnancy advisory organisations.<P><A NAME="9.0"><H2>9.0 Observations and Conclusion</H2><P>This helpline met the objectives of providing appropriate information and the correct referrals on the issues raised in the programme.<P>	The mix of advisors in the phoneroom ensured that there was no problem in finding someone with the appropriate expertise to deal with a difficult call. For most callers the programme seemed to have a profound effect, the greater percentage of callers were in an emotional state.<P>	The advisors commented that many of the callers who phoned 	on the second day had been unable to or had had very little sleep. Despite previous similar helplines, when caller response lessened considerably after 12pm, it seems that on this occasion the lines could have remained open for considerably longer such was the response and a larger capacity of call intake was definitely needed.<P>	The caller response to this helpline was remarkable, resulting in a decision to keep the helplines open for an extra hour and a half on the second day and thereby increasing the three hour 	service to four and a half hours. We can credit the production company for making a very good programme, which was also 	very well publicised.  But the response reflects the number of people affected by adoption and the great need for information, help and support.   <P><B>Yvonne Michael<BR>September 1996</B><BR><P><HR WIDTH=40% SIZE=1><A NAME="10.0"><H2>10.0 Caller Summary</H2>	<H3>FEMALE CALLERS</H3><P>Total Female Callers: 392	<P><TABLE BORDER=2 CELLSPACING=2 CELLPADDING=4 ><TR><TH colspan=2>Who the caller was</TH></TR><TR><TD>Birth parent</TD><TD><CENTER>40%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Adoptee</TD><TD><CENTER>49%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Adoptive parent</TD><TD><CENTER>1%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>other</TD><TD><CENTER>10%</CENTER></TD></TR></TABLE><P><TABLE BORDER=2 CELLSPACING=2 CELLPADDING=4 ><TR><TH colspan=2>Subject of Call</TH></TR><TR><TD>Tracing<BR></TD><TD>95%</TD></TR><TR><TD><align=right>of which Child<BR>of which Birth parent<BR>of which Sibling</TD><TD><CENTER>33%<BR>64%<BR>3%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Other</TD><TD><CENTER>5%</CENTER></TD></TR></TABLE>						<P>Of the above figure 32% were seeking support and 68% were referred onto relevant organisations.<P><B>Asking for help for the first time:</B> 40%<P><B>Sought help before:</B> 60%<P><TABLE BORDER=2 CELLSPACING=2 CELLPADDING=4 ><TR><TH colspan=4>Age of caller by percentage</TH></TR><TR><TD>under 16</TD><TD><CENTER>0%</CENTER></TD><TD>17-24</TD><TD><CENTER>3%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>25-34</TD><TD><CENTER>33%</CENTER></TD><TD>35-44</TD><TD><CENTER>29%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>45-54</TD><TD><CENTER>27%</CENTER></TD><TD>55-64</TD><TD><CENTER>5%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>65-74</TD><TD><CENTER>2%</CENTER></TD><TD>over 75</TD><TD><CENTER>1%</CENTER></TD></TR></TABLE><P><TABLE BORDER=2 CELLSPACING=2 CELLPADDING=4><TR><TH colspan=2>Programme Comment</TH></TR><TR><TD>Positive</TD><TD><CENTER>98%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Negative</TD><TD><CENTER>2%</CENTER></TD></TR></TABLE><P><TABLE BORDER=2 CELLSPACING=2 CELLPADDING=4><TR><TH colspan=2>Area calling from by percentage</TH></TR><TR><TD>Scotland</TD><TD><CENTER>9%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>North</TD><TD><CENTER>5%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>North East</TD><TD><CENTER>12%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>North west</TD><TD><CENTER>9%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>East Midlands</TD><TD><CENTER>10%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>West Midlands</TD><TD><CENTER>10%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>East Anglia</TD><TD><CENTER>5%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>South East</TD><TD><CENTER>33%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>South West</TD><TD><CENTER>8%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Wales</TD><TD><CENTER>8%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Northern Ireland</TD><TD><CENTER>0%</CENTER></TD></TR></TABLE><P><H3>MALE CALLERS</H3><P><B>Total Male Callers:</B> 112<P><TABLE BORDER=2 CELLSPACING=2 CELLPADDING=4><TR><TH colspan=2>Who the caller was</TH></TR><TR><TD>Birth parent</TD><TD><CENTER>2.9%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Adoptee</TD><TD><CENTER>86.4%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Other</TD><TD><CENTER>11.3%</CENTER></TD></TR></TABLE>					<P><TABLE BORDER=2 CELLSPAC