<P><HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Citizen's Arrest: Selectron</TITLE></HEAD><P><BODY BGCOLOR="#006B10" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><DL><DD><CENTER><P><A HREF="../reports.html"><IMG SRC="../backtoindex.gif" border=0></A><BR CLEAR=left><H1>Citizen's Arrest: Selectron</H1><H2>Tuesday 24th September 1995</H2><H2>Radiotherapy Accidents</H2><HR WIDTH=40% SIZE=1><H3>Report on Support Services Run for Channel 4<BR>by<BR>Broadcasting Support Services</H3><HR WIDTH=40% SIZE=1></CENTER><H2>Contents</H2><P><UL>	<LI><A HREF="#Summary">Summary</A>	<LI><A HREF="#Background">Background</A>	<LI><A HREF="#Programme">The Programme</A>	<LI><A HREF="#Helpline">The Helpline</A>	<LI><A HREF="#Aim">Aim of Helpline</A>	<LI><A HREF="#Announcement">Announcement</A>	<LI><A HREF="#Response">Response</A>	<LI><A HREF="#Who">Who Called the Helpline?</A>	<LI><A HREF="#Referrals">Referrals</A>	<LI><A HREF="#Observations">Observations</A>	<LI><A HREF="#Statistics">Statistics</A>	<LI><A HREF="#Call">Call Record Forms</A></UL><P><H2><A NAME="Summary">Summary</H2><P>Broadcasting Support Services Wales provided and ran a confidential helpline after the Channel 4 programme <I>Selectron</I> in the Citizen's Arrest  documentary series, on Tuesday 24th & Wednesday  25th September 1996. The helpline was open on Tuesday evening for two and a half hours after the programme (21.00 - 23.30) and for four hours on Wednesday afternoon (12.00 - 16.00).<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=2 CELLPADDING=4><TR><TD>Effective Calls</TD><TD><CENTER>452</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Number tariff used</TD><TD><CENTER>0800</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Number of lines on helplines</TD><TD><CENTER>15/9</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Number of  working helpline calls</TD><TD><CENTER>228/184 (412)</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Ineffective calls to helpline</TD><TD><CENTER>5221</CENTER></TD></TR></TABLE><P>Of the 412 calls taken only 92 were calling about cancer treatment and only 38 of those had suffered from cervical cancer. The rest rang about various other medical grievances or programme comments. The vast majority of callers praised the programme highly. <P><A NAME="Background"><H2>Background</H2><P><I>Selectron</I> was the second programme in The Citizen's Arrest documentary series, broadcast on Tuesdays at 8.00pm. The series features members of the public who confront the people, and organisations, who have caused them hardship or distress. With the presenter, Joe Layburn, and a camera technician each subject seeks out their adversaries in an attempt to air their grievances, and have them acknowledged. <P>Paula Snyder, Support Services Editor, Channel 4, decided that there was a need for support and information for viewers for some of the programmes in the series. She commissioned BSS to provide a helpline service for <I>Selectron</I>.<P><A NAME="Programme"><H2>The Programme</H2><P>Vicky, who had radiotherapy for cervical cancer in 1982, returns to Christie's Hospital in Manchester to find out  why she was never informed that she was a guinea pig for the, then new, Selectron therapy machine. The dosages of radiation used were experimental and have left her with such extensive visceral damage that she now has a colostomy and a urostomy. She was one of many treated in this way and has set up a self-help group, Radiotherapy Accidents Group Exposure (RAGE). The investigative television camera visits another ex-radiotherapy patient and a member of the ethics committee that wasn't consulted. The consultant radiologist and chief executive administrator responsible for the Christie's unit  refuse to be interviewed but  interviews with other radiological consultants in London and Cambridge confirm Vicky's belief that Christie's  is culpable.<P><A NAME="Helpline"><H2>The Helpline</H2><P>The programme finished at 20.30 and the  helpline was open for four hours until 23.30 and was open again on the following day from noon until 16.00. It was agreed to provide 15 lines on a 0800 free service from the BSS Wales office after the programme and eight the following day. As the programme featured a woman, and was initially concerned with cervical cancer, it was decided to staff the lines with female advisors only.<P>The Advisors were mainly medical staff  who had experience of cancer patients and/or patients with colostomies. More than half of them had staffed BSS lines in the past. Their areas of expertise covered:<UL>	<LI><P>Gynaecological Cancer Support  Counselling	<LI>Macmillan Nursing	<LI>Cancer  Therapy  Counsellors	<LI>Community Nursing	<LI>Cancer Information Centre Counselling		<LI>Ileostomy / Colostomy / Urostomy Organisations Helplines		</UL><P>During the briefing session the advisors watched the programme, discussed the type of calls most likely to be received and the best responses.    <P>They familiarised themselves with the phone system and call record forms as well as the resources prepared for their use.<P><B>The referral materials available were:</B><P>At each phone position there was a list of the main UK addresses and telephone numbers for the following support agencies.  <UL>	<LI><P>AVMA  (Action For Victims Of Medical Accidents)	<LI>CANCERLINK 		<LI>COLOSTOMY ASSOCIATION (The British..) 	<LI>HOSPICE INFORMATION SERVICE	<LI>ILEOSTOMY & INTERNAL POUCH SUPPORT GROUP	<LI>RAGE (Radiotherapy Action Group Exposure)	<LI>RIPS (Radiotherapy-Injured Patients' Support)	<LI>UROSTOMY ASSOCIATION</UL><P>At hand were the directories with lists of UK contacts, by area, for:<UL>	<LI><P>The British Colostomy Association	<LI>The Ileostomy & Internal Pouch Support Group	<LI>The Urostomy Association	<LI>Hospices and Palliative Care centres</UL><P>Also available was a large collection of referral sources for all helpline topics. <P><A NAME="Aim"><H3>Aim of Helpline</H3><P><UL>	<LI><P>To provide callers with support, advice and referral as appropriate.	<P><LI>To provide the service for as many callers as possible given the limitations of the helpline hours and the difficult nature of the calls.</UL><P><A NAME="Announcement"><H2>Announcement</H2><P>The suggested announcement was: <P><UL>If you have had a similar experience to Vicky's and would like to talk to someone, there's a special Channel 4 helpline where you can find out about sources of help.  Lines are now open until.........etc.</UL><P>The Presentation Department at Channel 4 made the following announcement at the end of the broadcast:<P><UL>IF YOU WOULD LIKE TO TALK TO SOMEONE IN CONFIDENCE BECAUSE OF MEDICAL PROBLEMS LIKE THOSE RAISED IN THIS WEEK'S CITIZENS' ARREST CALL</UL><P><CENTER>0800 600 444</CENTER> <P><UL>LINES ARE OPEN UNTIL 11.30 TONIGHT, AND AGAIN TOMORROW FROM NOON TO 3.00PM. LINES WILL BE BUSY FOR THE FIRST HOUR BUT DO KEEP TRYING. THAT'S</UL><P><CENTER>0800 600 444</CENTER> <P>It was felt that the re-wording of the announcement gave the impression that any medical grievances could be aired and this was reflected in the content of the calls.<P><A NAME="Response"><H2>Response</H2> <P>On Tuesday 24th, because of telephone configuration problems, the lines were not available until half an hour after the announcement was made. From then on the lines were constantly busy. 228 calls were answered of which there were three silent / hoax / too upset to talk calls.<P>Because of the lost half-hour on the previous day an extra adviser agreed to work on the second session. The lines were again busy from the beginning but lessened during the extra hour the advisors stayed. (This  had not been announced.) The nine advisers took a total of 184 calls.<P>The calls were fairly long with BT statistics showing that the average call length was just over 7.5 minutes, with  109 calls lasting for over 10 minutes.<P>There were 3959 ineffective calls to the helpline on Tuesday and 1262 on Wednesday, a total of 5221 ineffective calls during the helpline service. This figure does not represent the number of individuals who tried to reach the helpline, it is accepted that callers will try an 0800 number many times. The callers were asked about the number of times they had called  before reaching the helpline and the answers varied greatly between one and 45!<P>Between the helpline sessions an answerphone message told the caller that the lines would be open again on the Wednesday. After the lines closed on Wednesday the answerphone message gave the <B>Cancerlink</B> main number and the <B>AVMA</B> contact number . <P><A NAME="Who"><H2>Who Called the Helpline?</H2>   <P>Information was gathered from the <A HREF="#Call">call record forms</A>. The <A HREF="#Statistics">table of statistics</A> give the details of callers and the subjects of the calls.  However some of the more interesting points from the 412 working calls are :<UL>	<LI><P>34%  of callers were complaining about medical problems unrelated to radiotherapy.	<LI>only 9% of callers had cervical cancer while 19% had other cancers.	<LI>9%  were treated at Christie's Hospital, 13 % at other radiotherapy centres.	<LI>74% of the callers were calling on their own behalf.	<LI>73% of callers were female, 25% male and 2% silent/hoax/too distressed to speak.	<LI>15% commented on the programme. All but a few praised it and those four callers spoke in defence of Christie's hospital and/or medical staff everywhere.</UL><P><A NAME="Referrals"><H2>Referrals</H2><P>All callers were given the name of at least two organisations. <P><UL>	<LI>28% were angry about problems they had encountered whilst being treated for a medical condition, they were referred to AVMA. 	<LI>18% were given  RAGE's address as they wanted either to join their support network or to help its cause.	<LI>17% to other cancer support groups.	<LI>17% to Health Committees / Authorities	<LI>8% of callers were given the Channel 4 Duty Office address.	<LI>The other call referrals were to other medical support groups and various sources of legal and medical rights advice.</UL><P><A NAME="Observations"><H2>Observations</H2><P>The lines were constantly busy after the programme and the following day. Four of the answerers agreed to stay an extra hour on Wednesday afternoon and  during this time the calls dwindled off. <P>Although many of the callers identified with Vicky's frustration and distress at the consultant and hospital administrator, it was apparent that very few shared her experience of being an uninformed guinea pig for radiotherapy treatment. This was probably due to the wording of the announcement. The callers main concerns were with getting acknowledgement of, or compensation for, their own various forms of  mistreatment - whether it be the wrong drugs or unsuccessful operations.<P><B>Lizzie Perkins<BR>Project Manager</B><BR><P><HR WIDTH=40% SIZE=1><P><A NAME="Statistics"><H2>Statistics</H2><P>There were 224 calls - 221 were working calls.<P><TABLE BORDER=1 CELLSPACING=2 CELLPADDING=4><TR><TH>Helpline</TH><TH colspan=2>Monday 20 November</TH><TH colspan=2>Tuesday 21 November</TH></TR><B><TR><TH>Gender of caller</TD><TD><CENTER>Female</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>Male</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>Female</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>Male</CENTER></TD></TR></B><TR><TD>Working Calls</TD><TD><CENTER>128</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>33</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>39</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>21</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Self</TD><TD><CENTER>70</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>20</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>30</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>15</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Partner</TD><TD><CENTER>2</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>3</CENTER></T