<P><HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Cutting Edge: Provocation</TITLE></HEAD><P><BODY BGCOLOR="#006B10" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><DL><DD><CENTER><P><A HREF="../reports.html"><IMG SRC="../backtoindex.gif" border=0></A><BR CLEAR=left><H1>Cutting Edge: Provocation</H1><H2>13th June 1996</H2><HR WIDTH=40% SIZE=1><H3>Report on Support Services Run for Channel 4<BR>by<BR>Broadcasting Support Services</H3><HR WIDTH=40% SIZE=1></CENTER><P>Described quite broadly in publicity materials as a programme exploring the tragedy of domestic violence leading to the death of a partner, <I>Provocation</I> was in fact entirely focused on the case of Sara Thornton who killed her violent husband in 1989.<P>The helpline ran for 2 hours on 20 lines immediately after the programme was broadcast on Thursday 13 June from 21.55 to 24.00.<P>As can be forecast with a programme about domestic violence, the majority of callers were female (90%).  Viewers called in equal number about current and past domestic violence, including physical, emotional and sexual abuses by their partners, as well as a handful suffering at the hands of parents or children. With a great many callers in a very distressed state, this helpline also proved emotionally demanding on advisors some of whom spent an hour at a time supporting crying and desperately upset women.<P>Sara Thornton has engendered strong feelings in the general public and built something of a love-hate relationship with the media. The programme itself was generally well-received by those who called the helpline, and the auto-biographical angle prompted a number of women to express how closely they identified with Sara Thornton; a few however conveyed feelings of anger and even resentment - they felt had suffered more than her and were unhappy with her behaviour and character.<P><P><H3><CENTER>SUMMARY</CENTER></H3><CENTER>	<TABLE BORDER WIDTH=50%><TR><TD>No. lines</TD><TD><CENTER>20</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>No. hours open</TD><TD><CENTER>2</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Effective calls to helpline</TD><TD><CENTER>100</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Working calls to helpline</TD><TD><CENTER>98 (2 silent)</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Ineffective calls to helpline</TD><TD><CENTER>5294</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Calls to answerphone after closure</TD><TD><CENTER>100+</CENTER></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER><P><HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=center SIZE=5 ><P><CENTER><H2>CONTENTS</H2></CENTER>								<P><H3>I. <A HREF="#1">GENERAL INFORMATION</A></H3><UL>	<LI>1.0	<A HREF="#1.0">Background</A>									<LI>2.0	<A HREF="#2.0">Objectives</A>								<LI>3.0	<A HREF="#3.0">Funding</A>								 	<LI>4.0	<A HREF="#4.0">The Broadcast</A>							</UL><P><H3>II. <A HREF="#II">SUPPORT SERVICES</A></H3><UL>	<LI>5.0	<A HREF="#5.0">The Helpline</A>									<LI>5.1	<A HREF="#5.1">Opening hours</A>								<LI>5.2	<A HREF="#5.2">Telephone advisors</A>							<LI>5.3	<A HREF="#5.3">Information resources</A>							<LI>5.4	<A HREF="#5.4">Call record form and future programmes form</A>	<LI>5.5	<A HREF="#5.5">Future programmes</A>	<LI>5.6	<A HREF="#5.6">Who called?</A>								<LI>5.7	<A HREF="#5.7">Subject of call and assistance required</A>				<LI>5.8	<A HREF="#5.8">Length of call</A>		<LI>5.9	<A HREF="#5.9">Getting through to the helpline</A>							<LI>5.10 <A HREF="#5.10">Referrals</A>								<LI><P>6.0 <A HREF="#6.0">When Women Kill: Comparison</A></UL><P><H3>III.	<A HREF="#III">OBSERVATIONS</A></H3>							<P><H3>IV. <A HREF="#app">APPENDICES</A></H3><UL>	<LI><A HREF="#sta">Statistical breakdown of calls</A></UL><P><HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=center SIZE=5 ><P><CENTER><H2><B><A NAME="1"></A>I. GENERAL INFORMATION</B></H2></CENTER><P><A NAME="1.0"></A><H3>1.0 Background</H3><P>Channel 4 screened Provocation a fortnight after a similar programme in the <I>Witness</I> series, <I>When Women Kill</I>, a documentary based on the cases of three Canadian women who had killed violent partners. BSS Manchester ran helplines to support viewers of both programmes.  Comparisons between the two helplines are made where relevant in section 5.0; see also section 5.10 for further observations.   <P><A NAME="2.0"></A><H3>2.0 Objectives</H3><P>We aimed to offer viewers the following help:<UL>	<LI>i.) immediate support and a 'listening' ear for those upset by issues raised in the programme	<LI>ii.) details of organisations offering practical and emotional support to people experiencing domestic violence, including women, men and children	<LI>iii.)details of organisations supporting men trying to change violent behaviour	<LI>iv.)details of organisations supporting women imprisoned for killing violent partners, and organisations campaigning for changes to the laws affecting such women.</UL><P><A NAME="3.0"></A><H3>3.0 Funding</H3><P>Funding was provided by Channel 4.<P><A NAME="4.0"></A><H3>4.0 The Broadcast</H3><P>Following her earlier conviction with a life sentence given for the murder of her husband, Sara Thornton was released on 31 May this year after retrial and conviction of manslaughter.  Although she was given a 5 1/2 year sentence, she had already served this time since her trial in 1989.  Hers is a case which has received a vast amount of publicity, partly as a result of the efforts of the campaigning group <I>Justice for Women</I> and partly through Sara Thornton's own willingness and interest in speaking about what led to her killing her husband. Unsurprisingly, the case and its central character have been surrounded by some controversy, and the <I>Cutting Edge</I> programme had attracted advance publicity through mention in various newspaper articles.  Below are two extracts from newspapers' television previews.<P>"<I>A gripping in-depth investigation of the case of Sara Thornton, the woman who killed her husband and was recently released from prison in a blaze of publicity, her murder conviction reduced to manslaughter.  The testimony of friends, family and onlookers gives a strong impression of a woman who might be labelled 'mad, bad and dangerous to know'.  Even those who helped Thornton have plenty of unflattering things to say about her.  One of her leading feminist supporters says she drove her to the edge of a breakdown</I>".<BR>  <B>The Daily Mail 13.6.96</B><BR><P>"<I>Based on extensive interviews with Thornton herself, her family and friends, and Malcolm's son by a previous marriage, it reveals a character more troubled, and less sympathetic than a simple heroine of the feminist movement.  Thornton says the root of her difficulties was an inability to live up to clever parents. She developed a lack of self-esteem which nearly drove her to suicide and carried her unstable personality into a disastrous marriage with Malcolm Thornton.  He was an alcoholic and he beat her, but she was hardly blameless.  Even those who supported her campaign to overturn her murder conviction found her capricious and ungrateful</I>".<BR>  <B>The Times 13.6.96</B><BR><P><HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=center SIZE=5 ><P><A NAME="II"></A><CENTER><H2><B>II. SUPPORT SERVICES</B></H2></CENTER><P><A NAME="5.0"></A><H3>5.0	The Helpline</H3><P>The helpline details were offered directly after the programme.<P><A NAME="5.1"></A><H3>5.1	Opening hours and calls</H3><TABLE BORDER WIDTH=87%><TR><TD><CENTER>Date</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>Broadcast time</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>Opening hours</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>Lines open</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>Working calls</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>Silent or hoax calls</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>TOTAL CALLS</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD><CENTER>13.6.96</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>21.00-21.55</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>21.55-24.00</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>20</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>98</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>2</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>100</CENTER></TD></TR></TABLE><P>In addition three return calls were made by one of our advisors with legal expertise to complement other help given by advisors who had originally taken the call.<P><A NAME="5.2"></A><H3>5.2	Telephone advisors</H3><P>The helpline was staffed by a similar group to that which worked on <I>When Women Kill</I> a fortnight earlier, including counsellors, refuge workers, health visitors and people with paid or voluntary experience of working for the following organisations: Rape Crisis, ChildLine, Domestic Violence Helpline, Samaritans, Victim Support and Partners of Prisoners.  A number of advisors also had personal experience of domestic violence.  Since the majority of victims of domestic violence are women, we recruited an all-women team to ensure that callers would not be put off by a man answering the phone.  There was however a male advisor available for any callers preferring to speak to a man; he took one call and helped provide support to advisors.<P><A NAME="5.3"></A><H3>5.3	Information resources</H3><P>Advisors were provided by BSS with a comprehensive range of information and referral materials, enabling a quick and appropriate response to callers' enquiries and needs.  Information was provided in the following areas:  <P><UL>	<LI>I.) organisations supporting women experiencing domestic violence, offering practical advice and moral support	<LI>II.) support for male victims of domestic violence	<LI>III.) campaigning organisations working to change the law affecting women who kill violent partners	<LI>IV.) organisations working to help violent men change their behaviour	<LI>V.) miscellaneous others including organisations helping people with alcohol problems, survivors of sexual abuse, relationship/marital problems, prison-related support, etc.</UL><P>In addition a variety of other resources were available from BSS' helpline library including the BSS-produced <I>Survivors' Directory</I>, directories of general support organisations and details of counsellors and psychotherapists around the UK.<P><A NAME="5.4"></A><H3>5.4	Call record form</H3><P>Advisors completed a call record form for each call taken, in order to enable us to gauge who was phoning and what help they required.  As always, no reference to the caller's identity was made and all forms were destroyed after the helpline.<P><A NAME="5.5"></A><H3>5.5	Future programmes</H3><P>Whilst recognising that the principal aim of helplines is to support viewers on issues raised in a broadcast, Paula Snyder, Channel 4 Editor of Programme Support, has perceived that they also offer a prime opportunity for feedback to programme makers for future productions.  Helplines are of course a unique way of attracting relevant people to issues.  In the future, where appropriate, BSS helpline advisors will ask callers if they would be interested in involvement with future programmes on the same subject matter.  <P>Due to the delicate nature of the issues in <I>Provocation</I>, it was expected that some callers would be in an intense emotional state, so they were only asked if the advisors felt they would not be upset by the request.  Callers offering their contact details were told they could change their mind at any time and pull out beforehand by contacting the Editor of Programme Support.  14 out of 98 (1 in 7) calls resulted in completed forms; 12 were female victims of domestic violence and 2 were related to women imprisoned for killing violent partners.<P><A NAME="5.6"></A><H3>5.6 Who called?</H3><CENTER><TABLE BORDER WIDTH=20%><TH>Gender</TH>	<TR><TD><CENTER>Female = 90%</CENTER></TD><TR><TD><CENTER>Male = 10%</CENTER></TABLE></CENTER><P>The gender and age of callers was very similar to <I>When Women Kill</I>, with the majority of callers in their mid-twenties to mid-forties.  During both helplines, only a few calls were received from male victims of domestic violence, probably because the majority of victims particularly of physical and sexual violence are women.  But it is also worth remembering that, whatever their problem, people often think they are the only one to have suffered it, and can be reticent to contact a helpline unless the programme specifically refers to their type of case.  Therefore male victims of domestic violence might have felt they could or should not approach a helpline which they perceived to be for female victims.<P><A NAME="5.7"></A><H3>5.7 Subject of call and assistance required</H3><CENTER><TABLE BORDER WIDTH=40%><TR><TD>Current domestic violence</TD><TD>45%</TD></TR><TR><TD>Past domestic violence</TD><TD>49%</TD></TR><TR><TD>Domestic violence</TD><TD>help for</TD></TR><TR><TD>Perpetrators</TD><TD>1%</TD></TR><TR><TD>Child sexual abuse</TD><TD>7%</TD></TR><TR><TD>Other issue</TD><TD>9%</TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER><P>Most callers phoned about one subject, but a handful rang about more than one distinct issue (eg current domestic violence and past sexual abuse arose a few times).  Again, the pattern is very similar to that of <I>When Women Kill</I>.<P>Callers currently in a violent relationship were often seeking help to leave; many had already tried unsuccessfully and some had left but were still being harassed and abused by their ex-partners.People who had managed to extricate themselves from the violent relationship - some over 20 years ago - wanted help with various practical and emotional matters. The practical help being sought included re-housing, legal advice, information on custody issues, and so on.  There was a strong need for emotional support across the board, with many callers weeping and speaking about themselves in very negative terms.  Some callers were so worn down by the abuses, they thought they would never be safe.<P><A NAME="5.8"></A><H3>5.8	Length of call</H3><P>Calls after <I>Provocation</I> were longer than after <I>When Women Kill</I>. Callers seemed more distressed, possibly wanting to tell their stories at more length copying the biographical nature of the programme that had prompted them to call.  During many calls it took some effort on the telephone advisors behalf to terminate the call, with people at the other end clinging to the call.  As well as being given details of organisations which could offer practical help and information, many of these callers were advised that they could phone the Samaritans 24 hours a day if they needed to speak to someone.  Unfortunately, for financial reasons, most support organisations do not have freephone numbers so calls would appear on itemised bills, and may therefore be more difficult for people to phone confidentially.<P><A NAME="5.10"></A><H3>5.10 Getting through to the helpline</H3><P>This was the first Channel 4 helpline for which we attempted to gather data on how easily callers could get their call answered.  This was done in order to further help us improve our matching of capacity to demand.  British Telecom makes available figures on call attempts, however these reflect how many times the helpline number was dialled, not how many people have dialled the number.  On this occasion advisors were required to ask callers the following questions:<TABLE><TR><TD>Approximately how long did it take to get through?	______</TD></TR></TABLE><TABLE WIDTH=40%><TR><TD>Did you try constantly during that time?</TD><TD>yes</TD><TD>no</TD></TR><TR><TD>Did you use a re-dial button?</TD><TD>yes</TD><TD>no</TD></TR></TABLE><P>Data was collected from 78 of the 98 working calls.  However some of it was quite sketchy; for example, rather than a figure for length of time to get through, the advisor has written "ages" or "it took quite a while", and in some instances gaps were left.  Any comments should only be considered on an anecdotal level, rather than being scientific evidence of the nature of getting through to a television helpline.<P><TABLE BORDER WIDTH=87%><TR><TD><CENTER><B>How long it took to get through</B></CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER><B>No. of callers</B></CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER><B>Tried continuously</B></CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER><B>Used re-dial button</B></CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Immediately</TD><TD><CENTER>13</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>-</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>-</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>5 minutes or less</TD><TD><CENTER>11</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>yes = 2, no = 3</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>yes = 2, no = 2</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>6-20 minutes</TD><TD><CENTER>18</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>yes = 14, no = 1</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>yes = 11, no = 3</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>21-40 minutes</TD><TD><CENTER>8</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>yes = 9, no = 0</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>yes = 4, no = 1</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Over 50 minutes</TD><TD><CENTER>16</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>yes = 11, no = 1</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>yes = 8, no =	1</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Time not known</TD><TD><CENTER>4</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>yes = 4, no = 0</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>yes = 2, no =	1</CENTER></TD></TR></TABLE><P>Most of those who took a long time to get through had tried continuously, and more of them appear to have used a re-dial button than not.  It does seem that viewers wanting to contact the helpline were prepared to persevere.  Only one person specifically said that they decided to wait until later on as they thought it would be easier to get through, so it may well be worth Channel 4 Presentation spelling this out to people when a helpline is expected to be busy. Only one person who took over 30 minute to get through had not used a re-dial button and had tried continuously.<P>As we are trying to get a more acurate picture of the number of callers as opposed to call attempts, we are attempting to fill the gap between attempted call figures received from BT and calls taken, we would to be stricter about the information being completed on each call record form and need to ask callers to estimate how many times they dialled (or used re-dial facility).  However we should also be alert to the fact that this adds a little time to the call and to the completion of the call record form and therefore will marginally affect how many calls each advisor takes (and of course it adds time to report writing).<P>See also comments in <A HREF="#6.0">Section 6.0</A> in relation to the calls attempts being higher and calls being longer on this helpline than on <I>When Women Kill</I>.<P><A NAME="5.11"></A><H3>5.11	Referrals</H3><P>Although some callers were talking for the first time about their ordeals, a higher proportion (50%) than usual had already sought help elsewhere.  Callers had variously looked to the authorities (police, social services, GPs) and the voluntary or private sector (refuges, support organisations, counsellors) for help.  There were mixed comments from those who had approached the police, with negative feedback about lack of assistance as well as praise for some police stations special domestic violence units.  Many women faced a dilemma where they desperately wanted to receive police protection but felt unable to go through with taking formal action which (they felt) could lead to further anger from their violent partner.<P>Helpline staff advised callers of a broad range of organisations to approach, generally attempting to give at least two choices to increase likelihood of accessing suitable help.  Organisations included the following.<P>Alcoholics Anonymous<BR>Campaign Against Domestic Violence<BR>Channel 4 Duty Office<BR>ChildLine<BR>Citizens Advice Bureaux<BR>Cruse Bereavement Counselling<BR>Drinkline<BR>Family Service Unit<BR>GPs<BR>Housing Departments<BR>Justice for Women<BR>Law Centres<BR>NSPCC Child Protection Line<BR>Organisations for men trying to change their violent behaviour<BR>Organisations for survivors of sexual abuse<BR>Parentline<BR>Re-unite (to search for abducted children)<BR>Refuge<BR>Relate<BR>Rights for Women<BR>Samaritans<BR>Social Services<BR>Solicitors<BR>The Eating Disorders Association<BR>The Male Helpline, for male victims of domestic violence<BR>Victim Support<BR>Women's Aid Federation (England, Scotland, Wales, N. Ireland)<BR><P><A NAME="6.0"></A><H3>6.0	When Women Kill: Comparison</H3><P>A simplistic guess at the numbers of viewers who would want to call the <I>Provocation</I> helpline could give a lower figure than to <I>When Women Kill</I>, the previous fortnight.  <I>Provocation</I> was broadcast only two weeks after a programme on the same subject, at the same time, on the same channel and with similar audience figures(1).  In fact there were 1500  more call attempts for the second programme.  Also notable is that we were able to take 20% more calls during the previous programme.  Since we were able to deal with less calls, those still attempting to get through will have bumped up the numbers of attempted  calls.  We can only guess at whether this reflects attempts by the same individuals or more people wanting help.  However collecting data on length of time callers took to get through may help us gauge this information in the future (see section 5.10).<P><I>Provocation</I> received no calls from violent men trying to change their behaviour(2) - 4% of calls on <I>When Women Kill</I> fell into this category.  This is not surprising in view of the fact that the impetus for violent men to phone after <I>When Women Kill</I>  would have been the programme's coverage of  a session of a group run for men trying to overcome their violent behaviour.<P>More callers disclosed that they themselves had committed violent acts or had urges to do so after this programme.  Three calls related to women imprisoned for killing violent partners (one had committed suicide in jail).  Four callers spoke about how close they had come to trying to kill their assailant and two had slept with a knife under their pillow which they felt they might have used.  These callers tended to express strong empathy with Sara Thornton and 3 or 4 actually articulated the fear that they could attempt to kill if someone tried to attack them again.<P>(1) Overnight audience ratings for <I>When Women Kill</I>: 1.6 million; <I>Provoacation</I>: 1.9 million. Figures from Channel 4 Research Department.<P>(2) One call was received from a woman who wanted formal help for her partner, but he did not participate in the call.<P><HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=center SIZE=5 ><P><A NAME="III"></A><CENTER><H2>III.	OBSERVATIONS</H2></CENTER><P>People working on the helpline were struck by how emotionally low callers were and how some had a seemingly unshiftable sense of worthlessness and hopelessness.  One advisor said that when her gut reaction was surprise and frustration that women could remain with partners who caused intense physical and psychological pain, she had to remind herself that she had done the same for 10 years of her life.  Things seem simpler in hindsight or if they are other people's problems.  But we cannot overestimate the difficulties women face in making a permanent split from an abusive relationship.  There are practical issues such as housing and income, family ties including well-being of children, and of course the disabling effects of the abuse on self-confidence.  The fact that half the people who called the helpline had separated from their partners demonstrates the long term struggles survivors of domestic violence are faced with.  Women can not only be made to live in fear of the potential violence of their partners and ex-partners, but sometimes live with the added fear of how they might one day react to that violence.<P><B>Danielle Lowy	<BR>Project Manager<BR>June 1996</B><BR><P><HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=center SIZE=5 ><P><A NAME="sta"><A NAME="app"><CENTER><H2>APPENDIX A: Statistical breakdown of calls</H2></CENTER></A></A><CENTER><P><B>13 June 1996</B><P></A><H3><B>Gender</B></H3>	<TABLE BORDER WIDTH=20%><TR><TD><CENTER>Female 90%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD><CENTER>Male 10%</CENTER></TD></TR></TABLE><P><HR WIDTH=30% SIZE=1 ALIGN=center >    <P><H3><B>Age</B></H3><TABLE BORDER WIDTH=30%><TR><TD><CENTER>Under 16 </CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER> 0%</CENTER></TD></TR>		<TR><TD><CENTER>17-24</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>13%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD><CENTER>25-34</CENTER></TD><TD> <CENTER> 34%</CENTER></TD></TR>    	<TR><TD><CENTER>35-44</CENTER></TD><TD> <CENTER>  26%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD><CENTER>45-54</CENTER></TD><TD> <CENTER> 16% </CENTER></TD></TR>   	<TR><TD><CENTER>55-64</CENTER></TD><TD> <CENTER> 8% </CENTER></TD></TR>           <TR><TD><CENTER>Over 65</CENTER></TD><TD> <CENTER> 3%</CENTER></TD></TR></TABLE><P><HR WIDTH=30% SIZE=1 ALIGN=center ><P><H3><B>Subject of call</B></H3><TABLE BORDER WIDTH=35%><TR><TD>Current domestic violence</TD><TD><CENTER>45%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Past domestic violence</TD><TD><CENTER>49%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Domestic violence</TD><TD><CENTER>help for</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Perpetrators</TD><TD><CENTER>1%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Other abuse</TD><TD><CENTER>7%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Other issue</TD><TD><CENTER>9%</CENTER></TD></TR></TABLE><P><HR WIDTH=30% SIZE=1 ALIGN=center ><P><H3><B>Calling on behalf of</B></H3>	<TABLE BORDER WIDTH=35%><TR><TD>On own behalf</TD><TD><CENTER>90%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>For someone else</TD><TD><CENTER>8%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Professional enquiry</TD><TD><CENTER>2%</CENTER></TD></TR></TABLE><P><HR WIDTH=30% SIZE=1 ALIGN=center ><P><H3><B>Seeking help</B></H3>	<TABLE BORDER WIDTH=30%><TR><TD>First time</TD><TD><CENTER>50%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Tried elsewhere</TD><TD><CENTER>50%</CENTER></TD></TR></TABLE><P><HR WIDTH=30% SIZE=1 