<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Witness: When Women Kill</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#006B10" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><DL><DD><CENTER><P><A HREF="../reports.html"><IMG SRC="../backtoindex.gif" border=0></A><BR CLEAR=left><H1>Witness: When Women Kill</H1><H2>30th MAY 1996</H2><HR WIDTH=40% SIZE=1><H3>Report on Support Services Run for Channel 4<BR>by<BR>Broadcasting Support Services</H3><HR WIDTH=40% SIZE=1></CENTER><P>Channel 4 commissioned BSS to run a helpline to support <I>When Women Kill</I>, a programme in the <I>Witness</I> series. This programme about domestic violence investigated the cases of three Canadian women who had killed violent partners and filmed a session of a group for batterers, also in Canada. Coincidentally (or by clever scheduling?), <I>When Women Kill</I> was broadcast on the same day as Sara Thornton was released following over 5 years in prison for killing her violent husband.  A high profile case, Sara Thornton was one of about 70 women in prison in the UK for killing violent partners (see 4.0	<A HREF="#4.0">The Broadcast</A> and <A HREF="#new">Appendix B</A> for further comments).<P>The helpline ran for 2 hours on 20 lines immediately after the programme was broadcast on Thursday 30 May from 22.00 to 24.00<P>95% of calls concerned domestic violence, with slightly more about current - rather than past - domestic violence and a minority from men seeking help to change their behaviour (4%).  The majority of callers were women (90%) as would be expected with a programme about domestic violence; and about half of the calls from men related to their concerns for female victims.  Advisors taking the calls commented on how much fear was expressed by people who spoke to them, including callers who had supposedly escaped from their violent partners as well as those currently trying to deal with their situation.<P><H3><CENTER>SUMMARY</CENTER></H3><CENTER>	<TABLE BORDER WIDTH=45%><TR><TD>No. lines</TD><TD><CENTER>20</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>No. hours open</TD><TD><CENTER>2</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Effective calls to helpline</TD><TD><CENTER>121</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Working calls to helpline</TD><TD><CENTER>119 (2 silent)</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Ineffective calls to helpline</TD><TD><CENTER>3900</CENTER></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER><P><HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=center SIZE=5 ><P><CENTER><H2>CONTENTS</H2></CENTER>								<P><H3>I. <A HREF="#1">GENERAL INFORMATION</A></H3><UL>	<LI>1.0	<A HREF="#1.0">Background</A>									<LI>2.0	<A HREF="#2.0">Objectives</A>								<LI>3.0	<A HREF="#3.0">Funding</A>								 	<LI>4.0	<A HREF="#4.0">The Broadcast</A>							</UL><P><H3>II. <A HREF="#II">SUPPORT SERVICES</A></H3><UL>	<LI>5.0	<A HREF="#5.0">The Helpline</A>									<LI>5.1	<A HREF="#5.1">Opening hours</A>								<LI>5.2	<A HREF="#5.2">Telephone advisors</A>							<LI>5.3	<A HREF="#5.3">Information resources</A>							<LI>5.4	<A HREF="#5.4">Call record form</A>	<LI>5.5	<A HREF="#5.5">Who called?</A>	<LI>5.6	<A HREF="#5.6">Subject of call and assistance required</A>								<LI>5.7	<A HREF="#5.7">Length of call</A>				<LI>5.8	<A HREF="#5.8">Referrals</A>	</UL>					<P><H3>III.	<A HREF="#III">OBSERVATIONS</A></H3>							<P><H3>IV. <A HREF="#app">APPENDICES</A></H3><UL>	<LI><A HREF="#sta">Statistical breakdown of calls</A>	<LI><A HREF="#new">Newsclips</A></UL><P><HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=center SIZE=5 ><P><CENTER><H2><B><A NAME="1"></A>I. GENERAL INFORMATION</B></H2></CENTER><P><A NAME="1.0"></A><H3>1.0 Background</H3><P>BSS has run helplines for previous programmes in the Witness series, including most recently, <I>The Choirmaster</I>, about the sexual abuse of choirboys by a choirmaster, also a Canada-based programme.<P>This time last year, BSS ran a package of support for a long-running storyline in <I>Brookside</I> which featured a family's domestic violence experiences.  The wife/mother, a long-standing victim of physical abuse and emotional cruelty by her husband, plunges a knife into his back as he beats up their daughter. He has also sexually abused both daughters. Although initially imprisoned for murder, she is released on appeal. Channel 4 commissioned BSS to set up a dial-and-listen (3000 calls), produce a campaign document (full 1000 print run despatched) and run two helplines (311 calls, many long ones).  Our experience of running these support services for the <I>Brookside</I> storyline provided useful background for this similar, but factual programme, and had also alerted us to the great demand there is for help in this area.<P><A NAME="2.0"></A><H3>2.0 Objectives</H3><P>We aimed to offer viewers the following support:<P><UL>	<LI>i.) immediate support and a 'listening' ear for those upset by issues raised in the programme<BR>	<LI>ii.) details of organisations offering practical and emotional support to people experiencing domestic violence, including women, men and children<BR>	<LI>iii.) details of organisations supporting men trying to change violent behaviour<BR>	<LI>iv.) details of organisations supporting women imprisoned for killing violent partners, and organisations campaigning for changes to the law affecting such women.<BR></UL><P><A NAME="3.0"></A><H3>3.0 Funding</H3><P>Funding was provided by Channel 4.<P><A NAME="4.0"></A><H3>4.0 The Broadcast</H3><P><I>When Women Kill</I> documented the cases of three women who killed their partners after years of physical, and sometimes also mental and sexual, violence.  Two of the women were given custodial sentences.  News snap shots about domestic violence were shown including women who have been killed by their violent partners.  A solicitor and an author/campaigner discussed the problems of women being trapped with violent partners and look at how the law deals with these women, as well as how the law treats women who have killed a violent man.  The programme included filming of a group run for men trying to overcome violent behaviour, including perpetrators who have been convicted for violent acts. <P>In relation to the recent release of Sara Thornton, UK-based pressure groups made similar comments to those of the programme makers with respect to the charge of manslaughter on the ground of diminished responsibility; that is, that the law can only accept that a woman is not guilty of murder if she is found to be insane, not that years of violence can lead women to genuinely believe that they have no way out of the relationship than to kill their assailant or be killed themselves; or that years of violence can be regarded as provocation to kill.<P><HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=center SIZE=5 ><P><A NAME="II"></A><CENTER><H2><B>II. SUPPORT SERVICES</B></H2></CENTER><P><A NAME="5.0"></A><H3>5.0	The Helpline</H3><P>The helpline details were offered directly after the programme.<P><A NAME="5.1"></A><H3>5.1	Opening hours and calls</H3><P><TABLE BORDER WIDTH=87%><TR><TD><CENTER>Date</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>Broadcast time</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>Opening hours</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>Lines open</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>Working calls</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>Silent or hoax calls</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>TOTAL CALLS</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD><CENTER>30.5.96</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>21.00-21.55</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>21.55-24.00</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>20</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>119</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>2</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>121</TD></TR></TABLE><P><A NAME="5.2"></A><H3>5.2	Telephone advisors</H3><P>The helplines were staffed by a mix of professional advisors, including counsellors, refuge workers, health visitors and people with paid or voluntary experience of working for the following relevant organisations: Rape Crisis, ChildLine, Domestic Violence Helpline, Samaritans, Victim Support and Partners of Prisoners. A number of advisors also had personal experience of domestic violence.  Since the majority of victims of domestic violence are women, we recruited an all-women team to ensure that callers would not be put off by a man answering the phone.  There was however a male advisor available for any callers preferring to speak to a man; he took two calls.<P><A NAME="5.3"></A><H3>5.3	Information resources</H3><P>Advisors were provided by BSS with a comprehensive range of information and referral materials, enabling a quick and appropriate response to callers' enquiries and needs.  Information was provided in the following areas:  <P>organisations supporting women experiencing domestic violence, offering practical advice and moral supportsupport for male victims of domestic violence campaigning organisations working to change the law affecting women who kill violent partners organisations working to help violent men change their behaviour miscellaneous others including organisations supporting for survivors of sexual abuse, Relate, prison-related support, etc.<P>In addition a variety of other resources were available from BSS' helpline library including the BSS-produced <I>Survivors' Directory</I>, directories of general support organisations and details of counsellors and psychotherapists.<P><A NAME="5.4"></A><H3>5.4	Call record form</H3><P>Advisors completed a call record form for each call taken, in order to enable us to gauge who was phoning and what help they required.  As always, no reference to the caller's identity was made and all forms were destroyed after the helpline.<P><A NAME="5.5"></A><H3>5.5 Who called?</H3><CENTER><TABLE BORDER WIDTH=20%><TH>Gender</TH>	<TR><TD><CENTER>Female = 90%</CENTER></TD><TR><TD><CENTER>Male = 10%</CENTER></TABLE></CENTER><P>See comments on gender under Summary and Observations.<P><B>Age:</B>In comparison to the similar helplines run for <I>Brookside</I> last year, the callers were probably slightly older (possibly because <I>Brookside</I> attracts a younger age group), but in both cases they peaked in the 25-34 age group, perhaps when women are most likely to be trapped in a relationship due to children's perceived needs.<P><A NAME="5.6"></A><H3>5.6	Subject of call and assistance required</H3><CENTER><TABLE BORDER WIDTH=40%><TR><TD>Current domestic violence</TD><TD>49%</TD></TR><TR><TD>Past domestic violence</TD><TD>42%</TD></TR><TR><TD>Domestic violence</TD><TD>help for</TD></TR><TR><TD>Perpetrators</TD><TD>4%</TD></TR><TR><TD>Sexual abuse</TD><TD>5%</TD></TR><TR><TD>Other issue</TD><TD>8%</TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER><P>Most callers phoned about one subject, but a handful rang about more than one distinct issue (eg current domestic violence and past sexual abuse arose a few times).<P>Most calls were from women who had experienced domestic violence and the vast majority concerned physical violence from a male partner.  There were also mentions of mental cruelty and sexual violence and about 4 or 5 women mentioned physical abuse by male children.  Nearly half the callers were currently experiencing violence, however probably about 10% of these were separated from their partners but continued to be harassed by them (eg smashing windows, being beaten up, denied access to possessions in ex-marital home) and wanted to find ways of making themselves safe.  A handful of women had managed to successfully press charges against their violent partners but feared for their safety on their release from prison*.  Even women who had not had contact with their violent ex-partner for a number of years often remained terrified of the possibility of something occurring.<P>Those in violent relationships required a mix of assistance, including practical information on how to leave the relationship as well as help to make it work.  A number of advisors were asked the unanswerable "Will he change?" as though the caller needed someone to give her a definite 'yes' or 'no' before she could carry on with her life.<P>A few women expressed fears about the effects their partner's violence to them would have on the children, both generally and also in specific relation to the children's own potential for violent behaviour.<P>A small number of men (4%) phoned to ask for help to change their violent behaviour, and a couple of them had been watching the programme with their partners who encouraged them to ring.  One had asked his partner to phone as he could not believe that the service would offer assistance to someone like him.  He then made successful contact with an advisor who referred him to an organisation running programmes to help violent men change their behaviour.<P>We often find that many callers to helplines are speaking for the first time about their experiences and although this was the case for some, 50% of callers had actually sought help previously.  The most common resort had been the police, but also approached were GPs, counsellors, social workers, Women's Aid, the Samaritans, Relate and the legal system.  This showed that a number of steps - and a number of different sources of help - are needed to solve the problems which domestic violence can cause.<P>* One of the many spine chilling parts of the documentary included this (approximate) conversation between a prisoner on parole following conviction for beating his partner and the leader of the anti-violence therapy group:<BR>He says, "When I came yesterday my partner told me that our relationship was over"<BR>"Is she safe now?", asks the group leader<BR>Silence, followed by a simple "No".<BR><P><A NAME="5.7"></A><H3>5.7 Length of call</H3><P>Many callers wanted to speak for a relatively long time, however advisors were aware of the volume of callers trying to get through and so attempted to move on to another call with a minimum of delay.  Obviously it was not always appropriate to rush callers, particularly if they were very upset, disclosing for the first time or if it seemed that there was little on offer as referral.<P><A NAME="5.8"></A><H3>5.8 Referrals</H3><P>Referrals were made to a wide variety of organisations, as detailed below.<P><TABLE WIDTH=55%><TR><TD>Women's Aid Federation</TD><TD>GPs</TD></TR><TR><TD>Refuge</TD><TD>Solicitors</TD></TR><TR><TD>Justice for Women</TD><TD>Law Centre</TD></TR><TR><TD>Organisations for survivors of sexual abuse</TD><TD>Social Services</TD></TR><TR><TD>Southall Black Sisters</TD><TD>Citizens Advice Bureaux</TD></TR><TR><TD>Victim Support</TD><TD>Family Service Unit</TD></TR><TR><TD>Relate</TD><TD>Channel 4 Duty Office</TD></TR><TR><TD>The Male Helpline, for male victims of domestic violence</TD><TD>Various publications</TD></TR><TR><TD>Organisations for men trying to change their violent behaviour</TD><TD></TABLE>	<P><HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=center SIZE=5 ><P><A NAME="III"></A><CENTER><H2>III.	OBSERVATIONS</H2></CENTER><P>It has been said by some in the media and in politics that change to the law which made justice less harsh on women who kill violent partners could be a 'license to kill'.  However no women who called this helpline expressed any desire to kill their violent partner, or even retrospective desire to have killed.  It was quite the opposite: some callers said they had never entertained the thought of killing their assailant but having seen the predicament of the women in the <I>Witness</I> programme, they  now realised with some anxiety that they too could find themselves in that position.<P>Despite the catalogue of abuse related by callers (broken limbs, broken jaw, blindness in one eye, inability to have further children, strangulation, rape and other physical offences, apart from the emotional and financial torment), few seem to fight back physically.  Only two callers mentioned doing so, one stabbed her partner (not fatally) and the other attempted to kill her father.<P>As would be expected, only a few calls were received from male victims of domestic violence.  Although it is known that men can be affected by domestic violence, including emotional and physical violence it would probably need a programme entirely focused on their plight to really draw in calls.  Women experiencing domestic violence can have a hard time being believed, but men seeking help (eg from GP) can be taken even less seriously, with the idea of their victimisation by a female partner seen as something of a joke (picture Punch and Judy type scenes).  In previous helplines, BSS advisors have taken calls from male victims who have felt quite indignant at the lack of cover of their plight.<P><B>Danielle Lowy	<BR>Project Manager<BR>June 1996<BR></B><P><HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=center SIZE=5 ><CENTER><P><A NAME="app"><A NAME="sta"><CENTER><H2>APPENDIX A: Statistical breakdown of calls</A></A></H2></CENTER><P><B>30 May 1996</B>	<P></A><H3><B>Gender</B></H3>	<TABLE BORDER WIDTH=20%><TR><TD><CENTER>Female 90%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD><CENTER>Male 10%</CENTER></TD></TR></TABLE>     <P><HR WIDTH=30% SIZE=1 ALIGN=center >    <P><H3><B>Age</B></H3><TABLE BORDER WIDTH=25%><TR><TD><CENTER>Under 16 </CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER> 0%</CENTER></TD></TR>		<TR><TD><CENTER>17-24</CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER>7%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD><CENTER>25-34</CENTER></TD><TD> <CENTER> 36%</CENTER></TD></TR>    	<TR><TD><CENTER>35-44</CENTER></TD><TD> <CENTER>  27%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD><CENTER>45-54</CENTER></TD><TD> <CENTER> 18% </CENTER></TD></TR>   	<TR><TD><CENTER>55-64</CENTER></TD><TD> <CENTER> 8% </CENTER></TD></TR>           <TR><TD><CENTER>Over 65</CENTER></TD><TD> <CENTER> 4%</CENTER></TD></TR></TABLE><P><HR WIDTH=30% SIZE=1 ALIGN=center ><P><H3><B>Subject of call</B></H3><TABLE BORDER WIDTH=30%><TR><TD>Current domestic violence</TD><TD><CENTER>49%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Past domestic violence</TD><TD><CENTER>42%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Domestic violence</TD><TD><CENTER>help for</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Perpetrators</TD><TD><CENTER>4%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Other abuse</TD><TD><CENTER>5%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Other issue</TD><TD><CENTER>8%</CENTER></TD></TR></TABLE><P><HR WIDTH=30% SIZE=1 ALIGN=center ><P><H3><B>Calling on behalf of</B></H3>	<TABLE BORDER WIDTH=35%><TR><TD>On own behalf</TD><TD><CENTER>84%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>For someone else</TD><TD><CENTER>14%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Professional enquiry</TD><TD><CENTER>3%</CENTER></TD></TR></TABLE><P><HR WIDTH=30% SIZE=1 ALIGN=center ><P><H3><B>Seeking help</B></H3>	<TABLE BORDER WIDTH=25%><TR><TD>First time</TD><TD><CENTER>50%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Tried elsewhere</TD><TD><CENTER>50%</CENTER></TD></TR></TABLE><P><HR WIDTH=30% SIZE=1 ALIGN=center ><P><H3><B>Length of call</B></H3>	<TABLE BORDER WIDTH=25%><TR><TD>Up to 10 mins</TD><TD><CENTER>36%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>11-20 mins</TD><TD><CENTER>36%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>21-30 mins</TD><TD><CENTER>16%</CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD>Over 30 mins</TD><TD><CENTER>12%</CENTER></TD></TR></TABLE><P><HR WIDTH=75% ALIGN=center SIZE=5 ><P></BODY></HTML>
