<P><HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Breast Cancer Workshop Report</TITLE></HEAD><P><BODY BGCOLOR="#006B10" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><DL><DD><CENTER><P><A HREF="../reports.html"><IMG SRC="../backtoindex.gif" border=0></A><BR CLEAR=left><H1>Breast Cancer Workshop</H1><HR WIDTH=40% SIZE=1><H3>A report on the workshop organised by Channel 4 on 17 January 1996 to explore the issues faced by women with secondary breast cancer and those who support them.</H3></CENTER><P>Channel 4 commissioned this report as a record of the workshop and as a working document for those who want to move forward from the day. It is also being sent to all the participants, the main cancer organisations in the field including those involved in palliative care, health professionals, political parties and pressure groups, the Department of Health, Health Authorities and Trusts and the medical media.<P><HR WIDTH=40% SIZE=1><P><H3>Contents</H3><UL><LI><A HREF="#1.0">Introduction</A><LI><A HREF="#2.0">Aims of the day</A><LI><A HREF="#3.0">Why people came to the workshop</A><LI><A HREF="#4.0">A definition of secondary breast cancer</A><LI><A HREF="#5.0">Living with secondary breast cancer</A><LI><A HREF="#6.0">One group's personal experience</A><LI><A HREF="#7.0">An overview of existing cancer services</A><LI><A HREF="#8.0">Identifying the gaps in the provision of cancer services</A><LI><A HREF="#9.0">Outcomes from the day</A><LI><A HREF="#100">Conclusion</A></UL><P><H3>Appendices</H3><UL><LI><A HREF="#110">Appendix 1     Workshop Programme 17 January 1996</A>        <LI><A HREF="#120">Appendix 2     Working Party Members</A><LI><A HREF="#130">Appendix 3     Useful Resources</A>               </UL>		<P><A NAME="1.0"></A><H2>Introduction</H2><P>In October 1995 as part of its Gimme Health series Channel 4 Television screened <I>Alive and Kicking</I>, a programme which highlighted the value of breast cancer support groups for women with secondary breast cancer. Through the experience of one woman, Alison McCartney, the programme promoted how the quality of life, and indeed the length of life, could be enhanced by getting together with other women who were going through similar experiences.<P>As part of Channel 4's commitment to raising awareness of breast cancer, it published a short information booklet listing organisations that offer support. A second booklet Alive and Kicking was published to accompany the programme on secondary breast cancer. This booklet was written by Alison McCartney and tells not only her story, but that of the group for women with secondary breast cancer that she started at St Thomas' Hospital, London. <P>Channel 4 is interested in supporting new initiatives and a workshop following the programme seemed an ideal way to generate discussion on how the needs of women with secondary breast cancer might be better served.<P>A number of people contacted Channel 4 following the programme to request the Alive and Kicking booklet. They were asked if they would like to meet together to discuss the needs of women affected by secondary breast cancer. The response was immensely positive.<P>The workshop took place at Channel 4 on 17 January 1996.<P>Fifty-five people responded to the initiative following the programme and only one of these wrote in during early January to say she would be unable to come. On the day 47 people out of the 55 attended. (All of those unable to be there on the day had described themselves as patients and many rang in to give their support.) The commissioning editor of the programmes, the film producer and members of Channel 4 support services also came to the workshop. A few late applicants could not be accommodated but will receive copies of the report and other relevant information.<P>To help plan the workshop, people were asked if they would fill in details about their experience of cancer on the original application forms. They were invited to describe themselves as either patients, partners/relatives or friends, or as health professionals.  Fifteen described themselves as patients, 12 as patient/health professionals (mainly volunteers who had been or were also patients), 7 as partners or friends and 21 as health professionals. The health professionals included staff from Breast Cancer Care, BACUP and CancerLink.<P>This report is an account of what happened during the day.<P><A NAME="2.0"></A><H2>Aims of the day</H2><P>'<I>The workshop is the beginning of a process not an end in itself</I>.' Participant<P>The aims of the workshop were to:<P><UL><LI>Clarify the needs of women affected by secondary breast cancer.<LI>Identify how those needs can be met.<LI>Consider setting up a working party to take forward the ideas of those attending the workshop.</UL><P><A NAME="3.0"></A><H2>Why people came to the workshop</H2><P>'<I>In May 1994 I found I had secondary cancer in my liver and bones. These tumors had spread from a previously unrecognised breast primary cancer.....I felt very lonely. I longed to talk to someone else who knew what it was like, someone who had "been there" before me.</I>'  Alison McCartney<P>The aim of this session was to find out from participants what they wanted from the workshop.<P>The following list was compiled from the broad range of needs expressed by women with secondary breast cancer and those of the families and professionals who support them.<P><UL><LI>To learn from each other, exchange and pool ideas.<LI>To meet other women with secondary breast cancer.<LI>To meet other people who are offering support, professionally or voluntarily.<LI>To identify and discuss ideas for developing support for women affected by secondary breast cancer, their families and friends.<LI>To explore good practice guidelines for support groups.<LI>To exchange experiences.<LI>To clarify the needs of women with secondary breast cancer.<LI>To access information.<LI>To get a 'feel' for what's available.<LI>To explore how to deal with death and dying including the physical, psychological, spiritual and social aspects.<LI>To acknowledge the change from primary cancer to secondary cancer and to identify the needs of women at different stages of the disease.<LI>To explore local funding possibilities.<LI>To formulate a plan for taking ideas from the day forward into action.</UL><P>This list reflects concerns raised during the session about some of the practical difficulties which women face, as well as some of the painful emotional issues experienced by women and their families. <P>This agenda, provided by the participants, became the focus of discussion during the day.<P><A NAME="4.0"></A><H2>A definition of secondary breast cancer</H2><P>The aim of this session was to define what we mean by secondary breast cancer.  <P>Rosemary Burch, a breast cancer counsellor from St Thomas' Hospital, London, gave a short presentation to clarify the meaning of secondary breast cancer. She described the four stages of breast cancer.<P><UL><LI><B>Stage 1.</B> A cancerous lump in the breast<LI><B>Stage 2.</B> A cancerous lump in the breast with some lymph node involvement<LI><B>Stage 3.</B> Advanced local disease<LI><B>Stage 4.</B> Breast cancer that has spread to other areas of the body such as bones, lung and liver</UL><P>She noted that Stages 3 and 4 are considered secondary or advanced breast cancer.              <P>Rosemary also outlined the different common treatments available, emphasising that cancer is a very individual disease. She invited questions from participants. Their questions and comments ranged from differences in treatment, availability of some tests and the progression of the disease.<H2><A NAME="5.0"></A><P>Living with secondary breast cancer</H2><P>The aim of this session was to give participants the opportunity to identify the emotional and practical issues that affect women with secondary breast cancer, whatever their lifestyle.<P>Several discussion groups felt that, although there were lots of similarities in the emotional experiences of women, their lifestyles had an affect on how they coped and what kind of practical and emotional support was needed. Some of the differences in lifestyle were identified as listed over the page.<P><UL><LI>Women with children<LI>Women without children<LI>Lesbians<LI>Older women<LI>Women with physical disabilities<LI>Women with mental health problems<LI>Women in partnerships<LI>Women on their own<LI>Women with close extended families <LI>Women without families<LI>Women who had first been diagnosed with a primary breast cancer<LI>Women first diagnosed with secondary breast cancer (although a much smaller group).</UL><P><I>'Secondary breast cancer is an issue which is not addressed and has for far too long been steeped in an atmosphere of doom, gloom, and negativity.'</I>  Participant<P>The groups then expressed what they saw as the emotional and practical differences for women with secondary breast cancer as opposed to women diagnosed with primary breast cancer.<P><B>On the emotional side these included:</B><P><UL><LI>'It feels worse second time around', was a common feeling amongst the participants.<LI>Experiencing again fear, anger and guilt.<LI>Facing the fact that life becomes unpredictable.<LI>Acknowledging that life is shortened, even though many women live with secondaries for an increasing length of time.<LI>Having to face your own death.<LI>Feeling an increased isolation, more so than when diagnosed with a primary.<LI>Needing to talk to people also facing a progression of the disease.<LI>Coming to terms with treatment being 'palliative' rather than 'curative', as it can seem to be first time around.<LI>Feelings of shame at letting family and even the medical profession down by seeing oneself as poor role model for not 'beating' cancer.<LI>Calling upon the support of family and friends over what, for some, will be a long period of time and being worried about the affect that might have on those relationships.<LI>Feeling devastated and being full of questions like, How long will I live? Am I going to die? How will I cope? What will happen to my family?<LI>Wondering whether I have the right to form new relationships. Will people want to get to know me if my life is shortened?<LI>Concern about how the family will survive and who will support them.</UL><P>It was also noted that this experience was one of 'endless learning' and it was important that women felt empowered and in control. Having fun was mentioned in more than one small discussion group and the notion of choice was seen as important in all aspects of living with the disease.<P><H3>On the practical side issues included:</H3><P><UL><LI><B>Needing information about</B> - the disease and its progression; tests and treatments; support available; how to get hold of information.<LI><B>Finance</B>	-  benefit information; housing; travelling expenses; prescriptions; childcare; loss of earnings; complementary therapy costs.<LI><B>Change of roles</B>	- job; within the home; within the woman's wider family, where she may be already caring for a relative.<LI>Help with cleaning, shopping and dog walking.<LI>Choosing a 'mother' for the children.<LI>Arranging a funeral.<LI>Making a will.<LI>Counselling for children.<LI>Supporting and supervising the professionals involved in cancer care.</UL><P><A NAME="6.0"></A><H2>One group's personal experience </H2><P>Several members of the group for women with secondary breast cancer based at St Thomas' Hospital, London, spoke about setting up the group and why they felt the group was important to them.<P>Members felt that the group gives them opportunities:<P><UL><LI><P>To give and get support.<LI>To make new friends.<LI>To meet with women who are interested in and will listen to the difficult issues they face.<LI>Sharing physical problems caused by treatment.<LI>Helping each other to be assertive with doctors.<LI>Talking through the effects of the disease and prognosis on family members.<LI>Sharing the best way to explain to small children what is happening to their mothers.<LI>Talking on the telephone between meetings.<LI>Visiting each other in hospital.<LI>Having fun!</UL><P>Some members emphasised the importance of such groups having a professional facilitator. (This one is facilitated by the breast cancer counsellor.) Others wondered whether the facilitator should be a therapist because of the nature of the issues which affect this kind of group. It was noted that other kinds of cancer support groups are run by the members alone, in non-medical settings.<P>Discussion took place regarding how often a group should meet. This one meets once a month and most felt it could meet more frequently. They acknowledge that the facilitator should also have support from outside the group. <P>The session led to a wider discussion about groups. They were felt to be potentially excellent forms of support and research in the US has shown that they can significantly increase the quality of life for women. As one woman put it, 'time matters'. The pros and cons to setting up and running a group were raised.  <P><I>'Groups are a place where I can say things I feel unable to say to my family and friends.'</I>  Participant<P><I>'Groups can be stressful. They can raise anxiety for some members while reassuring and lifting others' spirits and the group effect does not end when you leave the room.'</I>  Participant<P>It was noted that CancerLink, a national charity supporting people with cancer, can advise on setting up groups and offers a small grant towards the initial costs (75).<P><A NAME="7.0"></A><H2>An overview of existing cancer services</H2><P>The aim of this session was to give some background information to the participants on what cancer services already exist.<P>Carolyn Faulder, chairwoman of Breast Cancer Care and a founding member of the UK National Breast Cancer Coalition, gave an overview of services with particular mention to those in the voluntary sector and emphasised the importance of information and the role of support groups and networks.<P>Participants were now able to assess the relevance of these services to women with secondary breast cancer and in the next session identify where they thought gaps in provision might exist.                           <P><A HREF="#130">Appendix 3</A> provides details of many of the organisations and sources of information discussed in this session.<P><A NAME="8.0"></A><H2>Identifying the gaps in the provision of cancer services</H2><P>The aim of this session was to identify those resources needed to make a difference, not only to the quality of women's lives, but where possible the length of a woman's life.<P><I>'When you have children, to have an extra few months means a lot in the lives of those children.'</I>  Participant<P>Some general points were made.<P>Women need to become more political in order to access sources of funds and women need to campaign effectively for improvements in existing cancer services. However women with secondary breast cancer can feel physically and emotionally exhausted. It will be important to remember this in terms of what they could or couldn't do to add their voice to improving cancer services at any particular time.<P>Participants discussed how services could be developed. Taking into account the emotional and practical needs of women identified in the earlier sessions, the group agreed the following areas for further action and research.<P><H3>Cancer support groups</H3><P>There are about 500 cancer support groups in the country.  Some of these are specifically for women with breast cancer. There is a need for groups especially for women with secondary breast cancer as they have different needs. Some women have not felt wanted by a group when they are diagnosed with secondaries because it has frightening implications for other group members.<P><B>For action and further exploration:</B><P><UL><LI><P>Research the benefits of cancer support groups specifically for women with secondary breast cancer.<LI>Use this research to campaign for funding to set up and support groups across the country.<LI>Produce guidelines which focus on good practice for groups working with	people at this stage of the cancer journey.<LI>Produce information on free accommodation locally.<LI>Encourage some of the smaller hospitals to link up to establish a group between them.</UL><P><H3>Telephone networks</H3><P>Telephone networks are one way to keep in touch over a large geographical area or around a particular experience like secondary breast cancer. For some women who do not wish to join a group or who live too far away from any groups, being supported over the telephone could help them to feel less isolated.<P><B>For action and further exploration:</B><P><UL><LI><P>Establish a national telephone network support system. (The Lymphoedema Network provides an excellent model for this kind of development. Breast Cancer Care has a lot of experience of offering support over the telephone from volunteers who have experienced breast cancer.)<LI>Run a group over the telephone, like a conference call. (CancerLink produces a booklet describing how to do this, called Running a Telephone Cancer Support Group.)<LI>Campaign for funds to support the costs of these initiatives.<LI>Challenge the hours that helplines are open. Do they coincide with need?</UL><P><H3>Information</H3><P>All suggestions in this section relate to the NHS as well as the private health care sector.<P><I>'My experience of having breast cancer and bone metastases is one of a constant struggle to find out information, help myself, and keep a check on the medical profession!'</I> Participant<P>Information plays a large role in supporting women with secondary breast cancer.<P>Several general points were made, including the importance for women with a progressed disease to establish a relationship with their clinicians; wanting to be able to ask a range of medical professionals about their condition; wanting honesty even when the doctor is unsure or does not have an answer.<P>A flow of information on secondary breast cancer, treatment, research, emotional and financial support were identified as essential means of support for women. It is also important for women to get help to access the information, understand it and be able to use it.<P><B>For action and exploration:</B><P><UL><LI><P>Ensure that there are enough breast cancer nurses nationally.<LI>A national oncology service formed to co-ordinate information on all aspects of cancer care.<LI>Encourage national cancer services (voluntary sector) to play an important role in distributing information, via helplines, newsletters, networking groups for secondary breast cancer.<LI>Investigate the use of the internet for sharing information.<LI>Provide information on 'living with secondary breast cancer' from women who have personal experience.<LI>Educate the public and the medical profession about the needs of women with secondary breast cancer.<LI>Use television, radio, magazines and newspapers to reach women.</UL><P><H3>Other suggestions</H3><UL><LI><P>To educate and campaign for funding at both national and local level.  <LI>To campaign for more breast care nurses and cancer counsellors.<LI>To support the provision of counselling supervision for breast care nurses and cancer counsellors in their one-to-one work and as facilitators of cancer support groups for women with secondary breast cancer.<LI>To encourage the provision of free complementary therapies.</UL><P><A NAME="9.0"></A><H2>Outcomes from the day</H2><P>The workshop had identified the needs of women with secondary breast cancer. It had identified how cancer services might be developed to focus more on the needs of these women, their partners and families and how new technology like the internet might benefit this group.<P>There was a lot of support for the development of support groups and networks for secondary breast cancer.  It was acknowledged that running a successful group to meet everyone's needs is skilled, whether it is facilitated or run by the members themselves.  The benefits to women belonging to such groups is known, but it was felt that some research would add to the credibility of such claims. One member pointed out that it is a comparatively cheap way of offering very substantial and effective support.<P>So with lots of good ideas the workshop members needed to decide how to take these forward to action.<P>It was agreed to set up a working party made up of people affected by secondary breast cancer or working in the field. One member suggested its name should be C4Ward.  This derives from an acknowledgment of Channel 4's contribution, with the notion of taking the outcomes of the day forward into action.<P>The working party will:<P><UL><LI><P>Prioritise the ideas for action as identified during the day.<LI>Agree on how it will take these ideas forward into action.<LI>Find ways to report back, not only to the wider group who attended the workshop, but also to all those who may be interested or who can bring about change.</UL><P>The working party is also open to those who were unable to attend the workshop.  A list of members appears in this report as Appendix 2.<P><I>'I felt that by the end of the day we had arrived at some concrete suggestions that something practical and even effective may stem from the working party.'</I> Participant<P>Perhaps the most significant outcome of the day was the formation of this working party to turn talk into action.  However, it seemed for many the importance of the day was in meeting each other and sharing ideas, swapping telephone numbers and giving and getting some support. This may mean that a network for women with secondary breast cancer has already begun to emerge amongst this group.<P><I>'I found the workshop inspiring, informative, and effective.'</I>  Participant<P><I>'I thoroughly enjoyed the day which both increased my awareness of the needs of such women and has motivated me to look at ways of improving the quality and holistic approach to the Breast Cancer Service where I work.'</I>  Participant<P><I>'I wasn't sure what to expect. What I got was a brilliant day. Terrific food which enabled us to get on with the business!'</I> Participant<P><A NAME="100"></A><H2>Conclusion</H2><P>This was the first time Channel 4 Television had followed up a programme with a workshop in this way. There is no doubt that the participants of the workshop would like to encourage further initiatives like this one, whatever the subject matter.<P>The importance of the programme, the booklets and the workshop are that they have given a large group of women the opportunity to have a voice. Facing as they do a life threatening illness, not only have they been able to meet each other to gain support and exchange ideas, but they have been part of forming a group whose remit is to bring about change in the care of women with secondary breast cancer. As one woman told us, THINK BIG!<P><I>'It has focused our thinking as a group. I think we are clearer what the problems and the strengths are.'</I> Member of the St Thomas' group at a meeting after the workshop.<P><I>'The group feels more focused and we have moved on in several positive ways.'</I>  Rosemary Burch reflecting on the group after the workshop.<P>We would like to thank all those who were involved in planning the day, all those who attended or who sent their support and also Vicky Parnacott from Wandsworth Cancer Support Centre who offered two relaxation sessions during the day to keep us going! Thanks are also due to Dr F Parkinson who was happy that his donation following the Gimme Health season should go towards the cost of the workshop.<P>Finally, our thanks go to Alison McCartney who was instrumental in bringing about this important day for women with secondary breast cancer.<P><CENTER><B>Alison McCartney died on 8 March 1996.</B></CENTER><HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=center SIZE=2 ><P><A NAME="110"></A><H2>Appendix 1</H2><P><H3>Workshop Programme 17 January 1996</H3><P><TABLE><TR><TD><B>9.30</B></TD><TD></TD><TD><B>Arrival and coffee</B></TD></TR><TR><TD><B>10.00</B></TD><TD></TD><TD><B>Welcome to Channel 4:</B> Karen Brown, Channel 4 commissioning editor, education</TD></TR><TR><TD></TD><TD></TD><TD><P>Introduction to the day:</B> Melanie Lockett, workshop facilitator</TD></TR><TR><TD><B>10.30</B></TD><TD></TD><TD><B>Who are we and how do we want to work together?:</B> Small group discussions with feedback</TD></TR><TR><TD><B>11.15</B></TD><TD></TD><TD><B>Secondary breast cancer:</B> A presentation by Rosemary Burch, breast cancer counsellor, St Thomas' Hospital, London</TD></TR><TR><TD><B>11.30</B></TD><TD></TD><TD><B>BREAK</B><TR><TD><B>11.45</B></TD><TD></TD><TD><B>Living with secondary breast cancer</B>		Working in small groups to identify the issues that arise for women with secondary breast cancer<TR><TD><B>12.30</B></TD><TD></TD><TD><B>One group's personal experience:</B> A short presentation by women affected by secondary breast cancer who are members of St Thomas' support group<TR><TD><B>1.00</B></TD><TD></TD><TD><B>A summary of the issues raised</B><TR><TD><B>1.15</B></TD><TD></TD><TD><B>LUNCH:</B> including a relaxation session for those who wish to participate<TR><TD><B>