n with advanced breast cancer. Many of the organisations involved in the area of breast cancer are aware of this need and are working together to expand their services. In the meantime, they offer a wide range of information, help and support to women, their partners, families and friends. Their main services are described below and details of organisations working in the area of palliative care are also given. <P>A list of books and publications is provided, some suggested by participants at the workshop, as well as those cited by Alison McCartney in her research into secondary breast cancer. <H3>Organisations</H3><P><B>BACUP</B><BR>3 Bath Place<BR>Rivington Street<BR>London EC2A 3JR.<BR>Cancer Information Service:<BR>Freeline: 0800 181199 or  0171 613 2121 (for London callers)<BR>Counselling Service: (London) 0171 696 9000 (Glasgow) 0141 553 1553<BR><I>BACUP's free Cancer Information Service offers information, practical advice and emotional support. Calls are answered by specialist cancer nurses who can explain medical terms and treatments, answer questions or tell you about local support groups and other organisations which may be able to help. The Counselling Service in London and Glasgow is free and confidential and its staff can also help you find a counselling service near to you. BACUP publishes booklets on all aspects of cancer, including </I>Understanding Secondary Breast Cancer, Understanding Chemotherapy, Understanding Radiotherapy, Coping at Home: Caring for someone with advanced cancer, Facing the Challenge of Advanced Cancer, Complementary Therapies and Cancer, What Do I Tell the Children?<I> and two booklets by Rob Buckman, </I>Who Can Ever Understand? Talking about your cancer<I> and </I>Lost for Words: How to talk to someone with cancer.<BR><P><B>Benefits<BR>Benefits Enquiry Line</B><BR>Department of Social Security<BR>Freephone: 0800 88 22 00<BR><I>National enquiry line for disabled people and their carers. Offers general advice on all benefits relating to disability, including Disability Living Allowance. Forms completion service for anyone experiencing difficulty completing forms (Freephone: 0800 44 11 44).</I><BR><P><B>Note:</B> BACUP and CancerLink also offer detailed up-to-date information on benefits. Contact their Information Services.<P><B>Breast Cancer Care</B><BR>Kiln House<BR>210 New Kings Road<BR>London SW6 4NZ.<BR>Helpline: Nationwide Freeline: 0500 245 345<BR>London: 0171 384 2344<BR><P>Suite 2/8<BR>65 Bath Street<BR>Glasgow G2 2BX<BR>Helpline: 0141 353 1050<BR><P>13a Castle Terrace<BR>Edinburgh EH1 2DP<BR>Helpline: 0131 221 0407<BR><P><I>Gives emotional support and practical information to women who have or fear they may have breast cancer. It has a Prosthesis Fitting Service in its London and Scottish offices. Helplines are staffed by breast cancer nurses, information officers and volunteers. Breast Cancer Care has 400 selected and trained volunteers with personal experience of breast cancer who will telephone or visit any woman seeking practical help or emotional support. Some volunteers have also experienced secondary breast cancer and can offer support to other women in a similar situation. The Volunteer Service has a complementary Partner Volunteer Service which provides support to the partners of women with breast cancer. Publications include free leaflets on the Prosthesis Fitting Service, the Volunteer and Partner Volunteer Services.</I><P><B>Bristol Cancer Help Centre</B><BR>Grove House<BR>Cornwallis Grove<BR>Bristol BS8 4PG.<BR>Helpline: 0117 980 9505<BR><I>Promotes positive health by offering self help and support to people with cancer and their carers, embracing holistic principles with programmes of counselling, relaxation, music and art therapy, healing and diet. All cancers are cared for at the centre.</I><BR><P>CancerLink<BR>17 Britannia Street<BR>London WC1X 9JN.<BR>Self Help & Support Service and Administration: 0171 833 2818<BR>Information Service: 0171 833 2451<BR>Asian Language Information Service: 0171 713 7867<BR>Young people's line: 0800 591 028<BR><P>Scotland: 9 Castle Terrace<BR>Edinburgh EH1 2DP.<BR>Information Service: 0131 228 5557<BR><P><I>Provides emotional support and information in response to enquiries on all aspects of cancer. Telephone information is provided in English, Hindi and Bengali. Produces a wide range of publications on emotional and practical issues about cancer, including factsheets and audiotapes. Resource centre for cancer self-help groups throughout the UK. Publishes The Directory of Cancer Support and Self Help (5) which is constantly updated and is a very useful source of information about support groups all over the country. CancerLink offers consultancy and training to groups supporting people with advanced cancers.</I><P><B>Cancer Relief Macmillan Fund</B><BR>(Head Office)<BR>15/19 Britten Street<BR>London SW3 3TZ.<BR>Tel: 0171 351 7811<BR><I>A national charity working to help improve the quality of life from the point of diagnosis for people with cancer and their families. It funds Macmillan nurses and doctors who specialise in cancer care; builds cancer care units for<BR>in-patient and day care and gives grants to patients in financial need (enquiries to Patient Grant Department, Head Office). Funds a medical support and education programme to improve doctors' and nurses' skills in cancer care and funds four associated charities providing information and support for people with cancer.</I><BR><P><B>Carers National Association</B><BR>Ruth Pitter House<BR>20-25 Glasshouse Yard<BR>London EC1A 4JS.<BR>Helpline: 0171 490 8898<BR>Admin: 0171 490 8818<BR><I>Advice and information service for all carers. Offers information, advice, publications on a wide range of subjects including welfare benefits, community care, respite, etc. Referrals to local support groups also available.</I><BR><P><B>Cruse Bereavement Care</B><BR>Cruse House<BR>126 Sheen Road<BR>Richmond<BR>Surrey TW9 IUR.<BR>Tel: 0181 940 4818<BR>Helpline: 0181 332 7227<BR><I>A national organisation offering help to all who are bereaved  young and old, men, women and children. Offers a counselling service to help with the emotional difficulties of bereavement, social support groups which offer support and companionship and information on many aspects of bereavement, including practical and financial matters. A network of local branches exists throughout the UK.</I><BR><P><B>The Hospice Information Service</B><BR>St Christopher's Hospice<BR>51-59 Lawrie Park Road<BR>London SE26 6DZ.<BR>Tel: 0181 778 9252<BR><I>Answers queries on palliative care services including in-patient units and home care services. Publishes the Directory of Hospice and Palliative Care Services.</I><BR><P><B>Marie Curie Cancer Care</B><BR>28 Belgrave Square<BR>London SW1X 8QG.<BR>Tel: 0171 235 3325<BR><I>Provides hospice care in eleven Marie Curie Centres and community nursing through more than 5,000 nurses trained in palliative care. Also funds cancer research at its Institute in Surrey and holds educational conferences and courses for health care professionals.</I><BR><P><B>Natural Death Centre</B><BR>20 Heber Road<BR>London NW2 6AA.<BR>Tel: 0181 208 2853<BR>Web site address: <A HREF="http://newciv.org/worldtrans/naturaldeath.html">http://newciv.org/worldtrans/naturaldeath.html</A><BR>e-mail:  <A HREF="mailto:rhino@dial.pipex.com">rhino@dial.pipex.com</A><BR><I>Aims to improve the quality of dying. An information pack on inexpensive green, family organised funerals is available for six first class stamps, and a set of forms including a living will, a death plan and an advanced funeral wishes form for four first class stamps. Publications include The Natural Death Handbook, Before and After and Green Burial.  Also offers a befriending network for visiting those with a critical illness at home, workshops, seminars, information on funerals without undertakers, burial on private land, nature reserve burial grounds, etc.</I><BR><P><B>The Samaritans</B><BR><I>A nationwide charity which provides 24 hour, confidential, emotional support for anyone in crisis. Wherever you are, The Samaritans can be contacted on 0345 90 90 90 for the price of a local call.</I> <BR><P><B>UK National Breast Cancer Coalition</B><BR>PO Box 8554<BR>London SW8 2ZB.<BR><I>Launched in October 1995, the coalition is a campaigning group whose aims are to ensure that all women have access to state-of-the-art treatment for breast cancer, that more government funds be made available for research into the causes, prevention and quality of life issues related to breast cancer and that breast cancer is seen as a top priority in health care with women taking an influential role in decisions regarding breast cancer issues.</I><BR><P><H2>Breast Cancer on the Internet</H2><P>The <A HREF="http://www.easynet.co.uk/aware/">Breast Cancer Awareness web site</A> is the only Internet site dedicated to providing information specifically for those affected by breast cancer in Britain. Online since October 1995, this site was featured on the Channel 4 programme Get Netted shown in May 1996. The site includes details of UK organisations which provide support and information about breast cancer, information on national campaigns and events, Book of the Month, and links to other cancer sites, including:<P><UL><LI><A HREF="http://www.pmedia.com/Avon/avon.html">Avon's Breast Cancer Awareness Crusade</A><LI><A HREF="http://www.icnet.uk/">Imperial Cancer Research Fund</A><LI><A HREF="http://nysernet.org/breast/Default.html">Breast Cancer Information</A> maintained by the New York State Education and Research Network.<LI><A HREF="http://cancer.med.upenn.edu:/">ONCOLINK</A> The University of Pennsylvania Cancer Resource.<LI><A HREF="http://www.nbcc.org.au/">National Breast Cancer Centre Home Page</A>: an Australian site.<LI><A HREF="http://www.graylab.ac.uk/cancernet.html">CancerNET UK Information Database</A><LI><A HREF="http://medweb.bham.ac.uk/cancerhelp/">CancerHelp UK</A></UL><P>The Breast Cancer Awareness site was set up and is maintained voluntarily, by Marie Nally (a woman with secondary breast cancer) and Nina Pope (a digital artist). Free space is provided by Easynet. Contributions to the site are welcome.<BR>e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:ucftnan@ucl.ac.uk">ucftnan@ucl.ac.uk</A><BR><P>There are many other cancer-related sites and databases. New sites appear continually and existing sites change regularly. For detailed medical information, the <A HREF="http://www.nci.nih.gov/">American National Cancer Institute's Home Page</A> is a useful starting point and links to NCI Online publications and Cancer Net, the latest cancer information from NCI, as well as NCI's cancer information service.<P>If you do not have an internet connection but do have an e-mail account, there are a number of electronic mailing lists to which you can subscribe. Two of these are BREAST-CANCER, and CANCER-L. The membership of these lists includes cancer patients, their families and friends and a few medical professionals. Once you subscribe to a mailing list, you will receive all of the messages that other people send to the list and you can write messages that will automatically be sent to all people subscribed to the list.<P>To subscribe to BREAST-CANCER send an e-mail message to <A HREF="mailto:listserv@morgan.ucs.mun.ca">listserv@morgan.ucs.mun.ca</A><BR>Leave the subject line blank and in the body of the message put 'subscribe BREAST-CANCER your name'.<BR>To leave the list, simply send a SIGNOFF BREAST-CANCER command to <A HREF="mailto:listserv@morgan.ucs.mun.ca">listserv@morgan.ucs.mun.ca</A><BR>To send a message to the other people subscribed to this mailing list, send ane-mail to <A HREF="mailto:BREAST-CANCER@morgan.ucs.mun.ca">BREAST-CANCER@morgan.ucs.mun.ca</A><BR><P>CANCER-L is a general mailing list for people with cancer. To join this group leave the subject line blank and send the message 'subscribe CANCER-L your name' to <A HREF="mailto:listserv@wvnvm.wvnet.edu">listserv@wvnvm.wvnet.edu</A><BR>To send mail to CANCER-L send a message to <A HREF="mailto:CANCER-L@wvnvm.wvnet.edu">CANCER-L@wvnvm.wvnet.edu</A><BR><P><H2>Further reading</H2><P>CancerLink provides specialist reading lists on topics such as breast cancer, as well as lists with suggestions for starting or expanding a group library. For further details, contact them (see details above). <P>Channel 4 published two booklets to accompany its 1995 Gimme Health programmes on breast cancer. Breast Cancer: Where to find support and information gives detailed, up-to-date information on the many organisations and groups in the UK that are involved with one or more aspects of breast cancer. Alive and Kicking, written by Alison McCartney, discusses support groups for women with advanced breast cancer. For a copy of either publication, please send a self-addressed envelope with two first class stamps (marked either Breast Cancer or Alive and Kicking) to PO Box 4000,London W5 2GH. <P><H3>Suggested titles</H3> <P><I>A Child's Grief: Coping with death in your family</I> by Julie Stokes and Diane Crossley, Channel 4, 1995, available from PO Box 4000, London W5 2GH. (Please send a self-addressed envelope, with two first class stamps.) <P><I>Cancer as a Turning Point</I> by Lawrence LeShan, Gateway Books, 1990, 6.95.<P><I>Facing Death - Patients, families and professionals</I> by A Stedeford, Heinemann Medical, 1984 (out of print, available from libraries). <P><I>Getting Well Again</I> by OC Simonton, Bantam Books, 1994, 7.99.<P><I>I Don't Know What To Say: How to help and support someone who is dying</I> by Rob Buckman, Pan Books, 1996 (new edition), 8.99.<P><I>Love, Medicine and Miracles</I> by Bernie Siegel, Arrow, 1989, 5.99.<P><I>On Death and Dying</I> by E Kubler-Ross, Routledge, 1990, 12.99.<P><I>Peace, Love and Healing</I> by Bernie Siegel, Rider, 1990, 7.99.<P><I>Special Diet Cookbooks - Cancer</I> by Clare Shaw and Maureen Hunter, Thorsons, 1991, 5.99.<P><I>The Bristol Programme</I> by P Brohn, Century, 1987 (out of print, available from libraries). <P><I>The Complete Book of Massage</I> by Clare Maxwell-Hudson, Random, 1988, 9.99.<P><I>The Holistic Approach to Cancer</I> by ICB Pearce, CW Daniel, 1989, 5.95.<P><H3>Suggestions from participants</H3>  <P><I>A Gentle Way with Cancer</I> by Brenda Kidman, Arrow, 1986 (out of print, available from libraries).<P><I>A Reckoning</I> by May Sarton, Women's Press, 1984, 6.99.<P><I>The Nature of Suffering</I> by Eric Cassell, OUP, 1994,  7.95. <P><H3>References on secondary breast cancer</H3><P>Buckman, R and Sabbagh, K, <I>Magic or Medicine: Investigations of healing and healers</I>, chapter called 'Getting better of feeling better', 1994, Pan Books, 6.99.<P>Spiegel D. <I>Living beyond Limits: New hope and help for facing life-threatening illness</I>, 1993, Vermilion, 9.99. <P>Spiegel D, Bloom JR, Kraemer HC, Gottlieb E. 'The effect of psychosocial treatment on survival of patients with metastatic breast cancer', <I>Lancet</I>, 1989:2: pp.888-891.<P>Spiegel D. 'Facilitating emotional coping during treatment', <I>Cancer</I>, 1990:66: pp.1422-1426.<P>Spiegel D. 'Psychosocial intervention in cancer', <I>Journal National Cancer Institute</I>, 1993:85: pp.1198-1205.<P><HR WIDTH=1000% ALIGN=center SIZE=3 ><P>Published in 1996 by<BR>Channel 4 Television<BR>124 Horseferry Road<BR>London SW1P 2TX.<BR>Produced by Broadcasting Support Services.<BR> <P>Editor: Paula Snyder<BR>Author: Melanie Lockett, workshop facilitator<BR>Editorial consultant: Elizabeth Sturgeon<BR>Design: Broadcasting Support Services<BR><P>Channel 4 are happy for individuals or organisations to copy the Report and distribute to their members and any other interested parties.<P>Broadcasting Support Services provides follow-up services for viewers and listeners and runs long-term helplines.<P>To help viewers follow up the issues raised by programmes, Channel 4 publishes a wide range of booklets, factsheets and edited transcripts, as well as organising telephone support services. You can also access Channel 4 programme support on the internet.<BR><A HREF="http://www.channel4.com">http://www.channel4.com</A> (go to 'Back-up' in the 'Areas' section).<BR>  <P>Channel 4's teletext service 4-Tel also contains regularly updated information for viewers. To access 4-Tel, make sure your television is tuned to Channel 4, press the text button, then enter the number of the page you want to access. The 4-Tel index is on page 300. Details of Channel 4 programme support, including helplines and booklets, appears on page 340.<CENTER><P><HR WIDTH=40% SIZE=2></CENTER><P></BODY></HTML>
