<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Travelog 1996 - Travelog itinerary 1996</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00"ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><BASEFONT SIZE=4><A NAME="TOP"><P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 CELLSPACING=1>	<TR>		<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=76><A HREF="travelog.html"><IMG SRC="smtrav.gif"ALT="Travelog home page" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=76 BORDER=1></A></TD>		<TD VALIGN TOP><P><H1><B>Travelog itinerary 1996</B></H1>		<FONT SIZE=4><P><B>This year <I>Travelog</I> runs from 3 January to 20March, taking in as usual a wide variety of destinations, from the exotic,such as Jamaica, the Azores and Albania, to the domestic (but no lessfascinating), such as Northumbria and London's canal system.		The links in this page will take you to a wealth of backgroundinformation, resources and links to other related sites. We will addadvance programme information as it becomes available, and the pages will		build throughout the series as new destinations are added. So keep comingback.</B></FONT></TD>	</TR></TABLE><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8BORDER=0></A><P><B><H2>Programme 1  (3 January, 8.30 pm)</H2></B><P>There are 97 white-bearded entrants for an Ernest Hemingway lookalikecontest when Pete McCarthyvisits <A HREF="florida/fl-keys1.html">FloridaKeys</A> for <I>Travelog</I>.  It was here, at the southernmost point ofthe United States, that Hemingway produced some ofhis best work.  For the past 15 years, Key West has been home to thefestival that celebrates his writings andhis life.  McCarthy enters the storytelling competition, and stays in anunderwater hotel in Key Largo.<P>Broadcaster Ghizela Modood discovers that many of the buildings in <AHREF="naples/naples1.html">Naples</A> are being restored to their formergrandeur.  She visits the opera house, the oldest and largest in Italy,talks to the president of the Pizza Bakers' Association and tries her luckon the lottery, which has been played in this part of the world since 1576.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8BORDER=0></A><P><B><H2>Programme 2  (10 January, 8.30 pm)</H2></B><P><A HREF="jamaica/jamait1.html">Jamaica</A> is one of the two islandsMarianne Faithfull regards as home - the other is Ireland.  The weather andlandscapes may differ,but the people share many characteristics.  Marianne Faithfull's tour takesin Port Royal, the Blue Mountains, Spanish Town, Strawberry Hill and awayside cafe, where sheenjoys a goat curry.<P>Back in England, Pete McCarthy circumnavigates London by boat,uncovering a side of the capital rarely seen. Dilapidated warehouses andwharves stand testament to the canals' former crucial role in industry, butMcCarthy finds that  <A HREF="london/londot1.html">London's waterways</A>are far from stagnant - working boats still operate and new ones are beingbuilt.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8BORDER=0></A><P><B><H2>Programme 3  (17 January, 8.30 pm)</H2></B><P>Andy Kershaw fulfils a five-year ambition to visit the  <AHREF="korea/koreat1.html">Democratic People's Republic of Korea</A> when heenters thecountry for <I>Travelog</I> on a tourist visa.  Accompanied by a directorwith a tourist's camcorder, he secures thefirst footage for a British travel programme of the country described as'the world's mostsecret society'.  Embarking on a surreal whistle-stop tour, Kershaw makesobligatory visits to the Kim Il Sungmonuments and war memorials, as well as to cement factories, the SeaBarrage dam, a brand-new American-stylebowling alley, a children's music and sports talent factory, and thehighly-charged demilitarised zone thatseparates North Korea from the South.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8BORDER=0></A><P><B><H2>Programme 4  (31 January, 8.30 pm)</H2></B><P>Featured on weather forecasts, but relatively unknown, the archipelagoof <A HREF="azores/azoret1.html">the Azores</A>is situated about one-third of the way between Portugal and New York.Pete McCarthy begins his journey on Sao Miguel, the largest of the islands,which is dotted with lakes and extinct volcanic craters, and takes a dip inthe healing waters of the hot mineralsprings.  On the island of Pico, whaling was once the main source ofemployment, and retired whalers pass the time tellingstories - including the 'true' tale of Moby-Dick.  At the end of hisjourney, McCarthy stops at the cosmopolitanport of Horta on Faial, where the Old and New worlds met as mariners passedthrough.<P>In the same programme, Richard Vaughan takes to the high seas on the RMS<I>St Helena</I>, Royal Mail ship and cargovessel.  En route to the small British dependency of <AHREF="sthelena/sthelt1.html">St Helena</A>, 1200 milesoff the coast ofAngola, he visits Ascension Island, now a US military base.  At sea forseveral weeks, Vaughan finds himselfromanced by the notion of travelling by cargo ship and revels in itsclassless atmosphere.  On St Helena he visitsLongwood House, the home of Napoleon inexile from 1815.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8BORDER=0></A><P><H2><B>Programme 5 (7 February, 8.30 pm)</B></H2><P>When Anne Applebaum first went to <AHREF="odessa/odessat1.html">Odessa</A> in the early 90s she asked people:'What do you think of the fall of the Soviet Union?'; 'What do you think ofUkranian independence?' She found that the unanimous answer was 'Who cares'. Odessa, the201-year-old brainchild of  Catherine the Great, has always existed at a distance from the rulingpowers. A cosmopolitan port city on the  Black Sea, it has long been a haven for exiles - political and cultural -and has gained  an enduring reputation for petty lawlessness and smuggling.<P>Ukrainian exile Vitali Vitaliev - a writer and columnist described by CliveJames as 'the best thing to come out of Russia since Nijinski' - declared aftervisiting <A HREF="tasmania/tasmant1.html">Tasmania</A> for <I>Travelog</I>:'I wantto be buried here.' Tasmania is an island of great natural beauty, withmany uniquespecies of flora and fauna. It is also a place of surprises.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8BORDER=0></A><P><H2><B>Programme 6 (14 February, 8.30 pm)</B></H2><P>Andy Kershaw adds another passport stamp to his collection of unchartedand unvisited republicswhen he journeys to <A HREF="albania/albant1.html">Albania</A> for<I>Travelog</I>.  He is surprised at the way in which Europe's poorestcountryhas recently adapted tothe 20th century.  Albania had no private cars five years ago; now it hasone of thenewest and largest per capita fleets of Mercedes in the world.  Inthe countryside, however, little has changed, despite the fact thatland is now privately owned.  He discovers that blood feud is a majorcause of death in Albania and goes out with those attempting to reconcilewhat are minor but bloodydifferences.<P>Steve Blacknell visits <A HREF="whitstable/whitst1.html">Whitstable</A>,a small seaside town on the north Kent coast. A far cry fromthe usual amusement arcades and burger bars, the attractions ofWhitstable have a sedate and quirkyair.  Thetown was once a conduit for contraband and has the smugglers' alleys to proveit; the harbour isstill busy supplying freshly caught fish.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8BORDER=0></A><P><H2><B>Programme 7 (21 February, 8.30 pm)</B></H2><P>Forgoing the asparagus and sauerkraut route, Pete McCarthy opts for the carpand beer festivals as hetravels through <A HREF="alsace/alsact1.html">Alsace</A> for<I>Travelog</I>.  This region has been part of Germany as well as France,which gives ita distinctive character.  On the Maginot Line, remnants of the Second WorldWar are reminders of a violenthistory, but today peace pervades the neat and prettycobbled streets.  In the home of theChristmas tree and the pretzel, food plays a major role in life, and foodfestivalsare held at every opportunity.<P>Travel writer Sheila Paine journeys to <AHREF="yemen/yement1.html">Yemen</A> with an all-female TV crew to show howwomentravellers from the West can experience the country's culture to the full.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8BORDER=0></A><P><H2><B>Programme 8 (28 February, 8.30 pm)</B></H2><P>From the television pictures of the drought, famine and war of the early1980s, many people have a negativeimage of <A HREF="ethiopia/ethiot1.html">Ethiopia</A>.  But Robert Elms, whovisits the country for <I>Travelog</I>, discovers it has areas of greatbeauty -lush pastures and lakes thatabound with wildlife. There is also awealth of fascinating historical sites.  Elms is particularly impressed bythe festival of Timkat (Epiphany) in Lalibela, a medieval village famousfor its extraordinaryrock-sculpted churches.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8BORDER=0></A><P><H2><B>Programme 9 (6 March, 8.30 pm)</B></H2><P>Overshadowed by its neighbour Toulouse, <A HREF="albi/albit1.html">Albi</A> escapes the notice of many travellers - but not that of the art critic Brian Sewell, who journeys there for <I>Travelog</I>.  Straddling the river Tarn, this largely medieval city has long entranced Sewell, not least because it is the birthplace of Henri Toulouse-Lautrec. But Albi offers diversions beyond the artistic. Sewell is excited to discover that government regulations demand that all food served in <I>auberges</I> must be home produced, and gleefully plunges into pate preparations <I>al fresco</I>. Stuffed to the gills and in search of redemption, he finishes his tour at Albi's vast twelfth-century cathedral.<P><A HREF="northumberland/norumt1.html">Northumberland</A> has been described as the last wilderness, its remote beauty often ignored by tourists travelling between England and Scotland.  Actress and writer Meera Syal discovers its hidden treasures and investigates a looming threat to its peace.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8BORDER=0></A><P><B><H2>Programme 10 (13 March, 8.30 pm)</H2></B><P>Pete McCarthy visits <A HREF="venice/venict1.html">Venice</A> during the carnival, visiting the famousDanielli Hotel, where carnival-goers minglein thefoyer and spill outside to dance, and taking a water taxi to a pre-ballreceptionattended by the &eacutelite of Venetian society. But Venice in February isn't just about carnival. Pete also gets offthe beaten track and visits the cemetery island ofSt Michel and theCannereggio area of northern Venice, the Jewish ghetto in medievaltimes.<P>Irish writer and comedian Owen O'Neill is surprised to find that<A HREF="montreal/montrt1.html">Montreal</A> ismarkedly more French than he'dexpected. He meets Pierre Brassard, the DJ well known inBritainfor his hoax phone conversation with the Queen, and the MontrealCanadians,one of the world's best ice-hockey teams.Owen visits Montreal during a particularly cold spell, and he retreatsunderground to the world's largestsubterraneanshopping mall. But bad weather is also a cause for celebration in the city'sannualSnow Festival.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8BORDER=0></A><P><B><H2>Programme 11 (20 March, 8.30 pm)</H2></B><P>Journalist and writer StephanieCalmanjourneys to <A HREF="alexandria/alexat1.html">Alexandria</A>, in Egypt, where she goes in search ofhigh society.Then, travelling east through the little-known Nile Delta, she gets aglimpse of avillage andfarming society seen by few tourists. Her journey ends in Ismailiyia, a popularholiday resort for wealthy Egyptians atthe northerntip of the Suez Canal.<P>Columnist Jon Ronson visits <A HREF="panhandle/panhat1.html">North Florida</A>, the'RedneckRiviera', which has some of America's prettiest coastline and is untouched bythe massholiday market. In Seaside, a developmentadmired byPrince Charles, Ronson hosts a barbecue for locals whopraisetheir crime-free Utopia. The 'Redneck Riviera' is a world away from Miamiand Orlando -this is truly America's Deep South.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8BORDER=0></A><P><B><H2>Programme 12 (27 March, 8.30 pm)</H2></B><P>Lao PDR stands for <A HREF="laos/laost1.html">Lao People's Democratic Republic</A> - or as Pete McCarthy puts it, "Lao Please Don't Rush". For despite being under Communist rule since 1975, the Lao way of life owes more to a laid-back Buddhism that it does to Marxist Leninism.<P>In a land almost without roads, McCarthy's journey for <I>Travelog</I> is made in wooden boats, old Russian helicopters and old Russian jeeps. In the former Royal capital city, Luang Prabang, he encounters the remnants of French colonial history - baguettes sold next to sticky rice, colonial architecture and the descendant of a French officer who has "come to die in paradise".<P>Phonsevanh, on the other hand, carries scars of Laos' unwilling involvement in the USA's "secret war" in South-East Asia.<P>Awaking from a nightmare sequence  where McCarthy envisages that Vientiane has become like Bangkok  he reassuringly finds a capital city where chickens on the street outnumber people. Now, the contemporary cultural threat is seen to come not from the West, but Thailand.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
