<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Travelog 1996 - Beijing - The gen</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><BASEFONT SIZE=4><A NAME="TOP"><P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 CELLSPACING=1>	<TR>		<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=76><A HREF="../travelog.html"><IMG SRC="../smtrav.gif" ALT="Travelog home page" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=76 BORDER=1"></A></TD>		<TD VALIGN TOP><P><FONT SIZE=6>Beijing - the gen</FONT>	</TR></TABLE><DL><DD><DL><DD>		<FONT SIZE=4><P><A HREF="#BAC">Background</A>		<BR><A HREF="#SOM">Some highlights</A>		<BR><A HREF="#CUI">Cuisine</A>		<BR><A HREF="#GET">Getting there</A>		<BR><A HREF="#CON">Contacts</A>		<BR><A HREF="#LIN">Links</A></FONT></TD>				<P><A HREF="koreat2.html">return to North Korea page</A></FONT></DL></DD></DL></DD><P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 CELLSPACING=1>	<TR>		<TD VALIGN TOP WIDTH=76><IMG SRC="koream3.gif" WIDTH=76 ALT="East Asia Map" ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0></TD>		<TD VALIGN TOP><IMG SRC="beijim1.gif" WIDTH=440 HEIGHT=326 ALT="Beijing Map" ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0></TD>	</TR></TABLE><DL><DD><DL><DD><P><A NAME="BAC"><H2><B>Background</B></H2><P>Settlements existed near what is now Beijing as long as 500,000 years ago, but the city's recorded history dates from about 1,000 BC. Being strategically placed, it became a garrison town, changing hands repeatedly as kingdoms clashed. <P>Genghis Khan stormed and razed the city in 1215, but his son, Kubla Khan, built his capital on the site. This was the city that so impressed Marco Polo, though the early years of the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644) were perhaps the city's cultural pinnacle, particularly in terms of architecture. The Forbidden City dates from this period. It survived because the Manchus, who founded the Qing dynasty (1644-1911), broke with tradition by not destroying the city they occupied.<P>In 1911 revolution ended imperial rule but not the age-old problems of feuding warlords, poverty and factionalism. When in 1927 the ruling Nationalist Party (Kuomintang) tried to unify China again by force, the Chinese Communist Party, led by Mao Zedong, began a civil war. After an uneasy alliance imposed by the Second World War, hostilities were renewed and the Communists emerged triumphant.<P>Mao redistributed land and initiated industrialisation. But the modern history of China and Beijing has been scarcely less troubled than its imperial past. The most devastating period was that of the Cultural Revolution, a 'class war' that caused appalling loss of life and left thousands of historical relics defaced or destroyed.<P>In recent years there has been a gradual trend towards modernisation and economic reform. The new policies, however, sit uneasily alongside the continuing authoritarianism of the government, as was tragically illustrated by the Tiananmen Square massacre in 1989. None the less China has changed dramatically, and nowhere are these changes so evident as in Beijing. McDonald's and MTV have a foothold, more and more people are giving up government jobs to become entrepreneurs, and there are frenzied building programmes. Beijing is becoming the centre of a new and even more powerful economic empire.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME="SOM"><H2><B>Some highlights</B></H2><P>Construction of <B>The Palace Museum</B> began in 1407 and took 200,000 workers 13 years to complete. It was home to 24 emperors through the rule of the Ming and Qing dynasties. Though parts have been rebuilt, the basic structure is unchanged.<P><B>Fragrant Hills Park</B> was a favourite hunting retreat for the emperors, many of whom made their mark by building temples or pagodas here.<P><B>The Summer Palace</B> is a vast imperial playground built in 1888 by the Empress Cixi. You can take a trip on a dragon boat, and visit the Temple of Scattering Clouds and Suzhou Street, a beautifully restored bazaar.<P>The highly stylised <B>Peking Opera</B> dates from the late 18th century and draws on several regional theatre forms. The result is a sensuous feast, though the outrageous costumes and piercing voices and accompaniment aren't to everyone's taste.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME="CUI"><H2><B>Cuisine</B></H2><P>The art of cooking is highly prized in China, and styles are immensely varied. In Beijing tourists can sample dishes from all over the country at reasonable prices. Many dishes described as 'Peking-style' derive from other parts of the country, but were perfected for the imperial court. Beijing cuisine makes liberal use of strongly flavoured roots and vegetables such as peppers, garlic, ginger, leek and coriander. Beijing's most popular street food is <I>jianbing</I>, a combination of eggs and scallions whipped up on a hot griddle, sandwiched between a deep-fried cracker and covered in a hot peppery sauce. The most famous northern dish is Peking duck. <P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME="GET"><H2><B>Getting there</B></H2><P>Capital International Airport connects Beijing to all parts of China and to many of the world's major cities. In most cases, it's cheaper to fly via Hong Kong. The airport is a 25-minute drive from the city centre. Alternatively you can travel on the Trans-Siberian Railway straight to the city centre.<P>Valid passports and visas are required for all foreign tourists. Visas may be obtained at embassies of consulates of the People's Republic of China, or through overseas offices of the state-run China Travel Service.<P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME="CON"><H2><B>Contacts</B></H2><B>China Travel Service UK</B><BR>7 Upper St Martins Lane<BR>London WC2H 9DL<BR>Tel: 0171 836 9911<BR><P><B>China National Tourist Office</B><BR>4 Glentworth Street<BR>London NW1 5PG<BR>Tel: 0171 935 9427<BR><P><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A><P><A NAME="LIN"><B><H2>Links</H2></B><P><A HREF="http://www.net.edu.cn/beijing/indexsed.html">Cernet: Beijing:</A> natural environment, history, population, nationalities and religions, people's lives, foreign relations, culture, education, science and technology, public health and sports, economy, useful telephone numbers, banks, embassies, airlines, points of interest.<P><BR CLEAR=LEFT><IMG SRC="tiantan.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=TOP BORDER=1><P><A HREF="http://www.ihep.ac.cn/tour/bj.html">Citynet guide to Beijing</A><BR CLEAR=LEFT><P><A HREF="http://www.lonelyplanet.com/letters/nea/chi_pc.htm">Lonely Planet travellers' reports</A><P><A HREF="http://metrotel.co.uk/jvt/china1.htm">Personal account of a trip to Beijing</A><BR CLEAR=LEFT><P><A HREF="#TOP"><IMG SRC="../../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0></A></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
