<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>POWER</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H2><A HREF="-mind.html">The Mind Field:</A> <A HREF="-power.html"> Power</A></H2><H3><A HREF="pow9.html" NAME="">Women</A> and power</H3>'Soft' power qualities, believes <A HREF="pow8.html" NAME="">Cary Cooper</A>, will have far-reaching implications for women and work. 'Women are more sensitive than men to people's needs, so women tend to be better people managers. The first women through the business schools were "old-style" managers, rather autocratic, trying to make it on men's terms. By these criteria, and survey results [have borne this out], this would only take them to middle management.' The next generation of women managers have a more female people-orientated management style. This, in theory at least, should make it easier for them to get to the very top and sustain positions there. <P><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
