<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>MEMORY</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H2><A HREF="-mind.html">The Mind Field:</A> <A HREF="-memory.html"> Memory</A></H2>False memory syndrome is a controversial psychological theory that suggests that adults can be persuaded to believe that childhood events happened when they did not. It has implications for court cases involving 'recovered' memories of child sexual abuse.  The recent <EM>Report of the Working Party of the British Psychological Society</EM> (1995) says that there is currently little evidence of the creation of false memories. Although memories are known to be frequently distorted or elaborated, the report continues, they are not usually completely false, except 'where there has been extensive rehearsal of an imagined event'. The report can be obtained from: British Psychological Society, 48 Princess Road East, Leicester LE1 7DR.<P><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
