<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>FEAR</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H2><A HREF="-mind.html">The Mind Field:</A> <A HREF="-fear.html"> Fear</A></H2><H3>How fear develops in <A HREF="fear7.html" NAME="">children</A></H3><UL><LI><STRONG>Age 0-2</STRONG>  Babies are born with a 'startle reflex': they will tense up and throw their arms out if they feel they're about to be dropped. A sudden bright light will make babies screw up their faces. Fast, jerky movements and looming shadows upset them. <P><LI><STRONG>Age 2+</STRONG>  They fear unfamiliar objects. Pets and people can be scary.<P><LI><STRONG>Age 3-6</STRONG>  The developing imagination can create ghosts and monsters, etc.<P><LI><STRONG>Age 7-11</STRONG>  They begin to see things from another's perspective, so start to fear what others think of them. Social embarrassment becomes one of the biggest fears, especially as adolescence approaches.  Fear of the future develops: 'Will I pass exams and please my parents?'<P><LI><STRONG>Age 12+</STRONG>  Abstract fears develop: war, ageing, dying. Existential thought develops - 'Why am I here?' - with attendant fears.</UL><P><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
