<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>get netted</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00"ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H2><A HREF="getnett1.html">get netted</H2><H3>first steps in cyberspace (back to index page)</H3></A><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"><H2><FONT COLOR="#00FF00">Introduction</FONT></H2><P><P>When we rang various groups around the country and said that Channel 4wanted to provide them with the means to explore the Internet, the responsewas swift: 'When do we get the computers?'<P>Of course, it must have seemed too good to be true. What sort of resultswere Channel 4 after, they asked - a polite way of finding out what thecatch was. I explained that in the light of all the media fuss about theInternet, we wanted to open it up to some of those who would not usuallyhave access. We wanted, I said, to find out how different groups would usethe technology. The only condition was that they would give an account oftheir experiences.<P>Over the past couple of years the Internet has gone a long way towardstransforming itself from a gimmick for specialists into a resource withwide application and appeal. Politicians have begun to talk about the needto ensure access to the Internet for all, speaking of information as thenext public utility, as if it were electricity or water. It is a sure signthat an idea has arrived.<P>But why the Internet? What's so special about this resource? The media havebeen flooded with different answers to this question over the past year orso, varying from the practical to the cosmic. The Internet, it is said,provides instant access to vast amounts of information on almost anysubject you can think of. It allows you to communicate quickly and cheaplywith people around the world. It is a priceless business opportunity, themeans by which most people will buy and sell in the future. Moreover, sayenthusiasts, it can free you from the limits of your own identity, allowingyou to be, if you wish, faceless, genderless, nationless. The Internet isgradually wiring everything up with everything else, as if we were slowlyassembling a global brain, nerve by nerve . . .<P>As the media cyber-babble proliferated, each of our six groups waspresented with a powerful computer with a built-in modem.CompuServe provided the connections. Each group  received basic trainingand some ongoing support. Two groups also began to learn how to publishmaterials on the Web. Anymaterials published by the groups will be available via<A HREF="http://www.gn.apc.org/hive/">Hive</A>, a new Website that has developed out of this project.<P>It was obvious that we needed to put the hype aside and concentrate onfinding uses for the Internet relevant to each group's specific interests.People were beginning to get worried after the first wave of enthusiasm.Several had heard dark mutterings about slow connections and poorly indexedand poor-quality materials.'How do we e-mail?' was a frequent first cry. The speed of electronic mailis something that most people can see as being useful, but some of thegroups have had bad experiences with it. The Internet is getting moreuser-friendly, but technology designed BNFN - by nerds for nerds - is stillall too common.<P>Despite this, and despite my own resolution, I find it hard at times toresist evangelising: the service we all want is still around the corner, Isay. The current Internet is merely a B-road compared to the informationsuperhighway that is coming. The copper wire of telephone lines will giveway to the optic fibre of cables, which are being laid along streetsthroughout Britain. Computers will be linked with televisions. The softwarewe currently buy and install will soon be grabbed automatically by ourmachines when we need it. Special electronic agents will trawl the Interneton our behalf, searching for what we want. We will simply open a gate inthe morning and a torrent of useful information will flow in . . .<P>However, the groups' questions bring me back down to earth. What sorts ofthings will they be able to find that are really relevant to them?<P>The experiences of our six different groups highlighted both the strengthsand the weaknesses of the Internet as it is now. They point to what isneeded if the Internet is to move on to a new phase: more high-qualitycontent; greater speed and ease of use; better, more functional design andclear signposts through the mass of information available. It may be, ofcourse, that we will only get this if we are prepared to pay for it.<P>The Get Netted project is just one small experiment in perhaps the biggestlaboratory of all time. Internet users may indeed sometimes feel a bit likemice in a maze, scurrying around trying to find a way forward. No one canpredict what directions we may take, or be led in, but one thing is certain- the journey is only just beginning.<P>My modem crackles into action. I click on my mail- box and read the firstmessage. 'I am just testing to see if my e-mail is working. Can you ring meback?' The first faltering steps in cyberspace.<P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"><B><P>Matthew Pike<P><I>Matthew Pike is chairman of the Scarman Trust, which aims to promoteactive, empowered citizenship.</I></B><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
