</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>get netted</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00"ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H2><A HREF="getnett1.html">get netted</H2><H3>first steps in cyberspace (back to index page)</H3></A><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"><H2><FONT COLOR="#00FF00">New lamps for old</FONT></H2><P><B>The arts group Welfare State International (e-mail:<AHREF="mailto:WSI104047.2252@compuserve.com">WSI104047.2252@compuserve.com</A>)has been around for more than 20 years, andmany people are familiar with aspects of its work: the giant puppets,lantern processions, shadow plays, fireworks, street theatre, paintedcoffins. Every few years the group enters a new phase, and at its base inUlverston in the Lake District it is now to build a Centre for Celebrationwith funding from the National Lottery. Visitors will have the opportunityto learn skills and find out about the festivities of other cultures aroundthe world.</B><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"><P>I am not a Luddite, but I enjoy cutting and printing woodcuts by hand witha Japanese method that is at least a thousand years old. I am concernedthat in our present high-tech culture, too many people have to sit inoffices all day under neon lights, staring at screens and overusing theirheads.<P>My nightmare is that one day we will all wither into pale limblesscreatures, fleshy heads resting on office chairs. I fear that we will cometo believe our electronic creations more real than the surface of the earthand that we will stop caring about anything outside ourselves. Eventuallythe affluent will persist in underground bunkers where the light neverchanges, where polluted air is recycled and where their navels areimplanted with transistorised nervous systems. Their narcissistic way oflife will be maintained by children and women in the Third World whomanufacture sealed circuitry in appalling sweat-shops. They will becomeslaves to video games and others will be slaves to their addiction.<P>I am pleased to say that after only one day's training in the winsome waysof the Internet and the World Wide Web, these prejudices have beenoverturned a little.<P>First we scanned some rough old woodcuts on to the screen and discoveredthat after playing with an infinite series of possible colours, a subtlepattern could be used as a background for some of our owncounter-propaganda poetry. This marriage of ancient and modern techniqueslooked good and was a healthy alternative to the rag-bag of infinitegraphic clich&eacutes offered by umpteen commercial packages.<P>Also we could drop slides of our processional lantern work on to thesebackgrounds, which looked very beautiful. Now I fantasise that we willproduce 'Travelling Light', an electronic encyclopaedia of vernacular art,an illuminated manuscript for the post-millennium, to run in parallel withhand-made printed hard copies.<P>As well as discovering a potentially brilliant and speedy communicationtool, which could broaden communities, I also discovered a network asintriguing as any celestial attic. There were/are like-minded obsessivesout there. By following Ritual to Funerals to Alternatives we came up withliteral dead-ends. But by poking, by chance, at<A HREF="http://www.echonyc.com/~mysticfire/">Mystic Fire</A> somewhere inCalifornia, we discovered a series ofpoetry videos which could bring some dead poets alive in our library.<P>Not sure I like the American jargon with its sub-military commands, or thesuperfluity of information or boy's-games stuff with megabyte tonnage, orthe sick pornography, or the lack of exercise. But the unstoppable genie isout of the bottle and if treated carefully we might get a few useful newlamps for old.<P>I'll keep looking: I guess some illumination is possible.<P><B>John Fox</B><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"><P>At our Digital Dreaming conference someone said, 'There is a lot of hypeabout artists using the Internet. Just think of it like artists using thePost Office.' It still needs imagination to make it anything more than auseful communications tool. God there are some awful Web sites about - whois it that designs clip-art?<P>The Net may be the Post Office writ large, at twice the speed of sound, buthow does anyone have the time to explore it? I've spent hours wandering incyberspace, sometimes without coming across anything remotely interesting.I now have an alarm clock on my desk to try and limit my phone bill. Ofcourse at other times you find site after fascinating site.<P>Probably the most useful links we will make in the future will be with thecompany's freelance artists. We are planning to set up a network of theartists who regularly work for the company so that we can communicate aboutprojects, hold mini-conferences about different aspects of our work, docollaborative design work, perhaps even have our own virtual gallery.<P><B>Chris Coates</B><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"><P>I had no previous experience of the Internet so it was exciting to be giventhe chance to find out what all the fuss is about, and I am pleased that Ican now translate those strange-looking e-mail messages at last! I found itfascinating to discover people corresponding on Vonnegut's short stories,sharing their interests and knowledge. I was also surprised to learn thataccessing pages becomes slower during the hours America wakes up and alsowhen many of our children arrive home from school. When my children (agedten and seven) finish school, they tend to go straight out to play!<P><B>Fiona Ogilvie</B><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
