<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>get netted</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00"ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H2><A HREF="getnett1.html">get netted</H2><H3>first steps in cyberspace (back to index page)</H3></A><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"><H2><FONT COLOR="#00FF00">The learning ark</FONT></H2><P><B>Park School in Dartington, Devon(e-mail: <AHREF="mailto:openschool@bbcnc.org.uk">openschool@bbcnc.org.uk</A>) is asmall school built out of wood, bobbing in the wake of other Utopianexperiments in education in Dartington over the last 70 years. Dartington'salternative public school fell from grace ten years ago. Park, aprogressive independent primary school, is a new start. It's unusual inthat every parent contributes some time to the school, fixing the roof orhelping out with teaching. The educational philosophy is about learning bydoing, wherever possible.<P>By good fortune the Open School next door is a world leader in using newtechnology for distance teaching, and the Park School staff were teemingwith ideas for using the Internet.</B><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"><P>Four children aged between seven and nine, along with their parents, areexploring what the Internet can do for them in a collaborative learningventure. We are not teaching the parents first so that they can teach theirchildren (or the other way round), rather we are beginning to identify andexplore topics of mutual interest.<P>In the early stages we have looked at a wide variety of things, from thesimply entertaining - the home page for<A HREF="http://www.freenet.hamilton%0D.on.ca/~aa844/Mr.Bean.html">Mr Bean</A>,for example, with lots of pictures from thetelevision programmes - to more serious areas. We have found out about an<A HREF="http://moscow.com/Education/masc/">alternative school in Moscow,Idaho</A>and we have dissected a <AHREF="http://curry.edschool.virginia.edu/~insttech/frog">virtual frog</A> online. We have started toinvestigate astronomy, for example by linking with the <AHREF="http://www.roe.ac.uk">Edinburgh RoyalObservatory</A> and looking at the <A HREF="http://www.nasa.gov">NASA</A>pages,trying to find pictures of the comet that recentlycame near to Earth. However this caused some technical problems and somefrustration, as our software could download the images but not manage todisplay them.<P>One of the most interesting areas of research was the 'McLibel' case - twoactivists who are being sued for libel by McDonalds, for distributingleaflets suggesting possibly libellous things about the company. One of thechildren and their parent had read a little about the story in a Sundaynewspaper and wanted to know more. On the Web they found the entire text ofthe original leaflet, together with a full history of the case so far. Thisinformation was provided by an Australian vegan group - much of it isn'tavailable at all easily in the UK.<P>Later the group looked for information on 'mad cow' disease, anothersubject that the many vegetarians in the school were very interested in.There was a great deal of information available, but most of it was far tootechnical and scientific to be accessible to the children - officialmaterial, reports from scientists and so on. They wanted to find somethingaccessible and interesting and were disappointed to find nothing but reamsof technical text.<P>Our final focus as a group is yet to be decided. Our collaborative ventureis consistent with our view of this school as a learning community. Ourplan is that, over time, the children will teach other children how to usethe Internet and the parents will teach other parents, so we develop acommunity resource. We also plan to download the material we find on theInternet to use in other school activities.<P>Using the Internet is consistent with our view of knowledge and learning -that all knowledge which interests us as learners is worthy of exploration,and that people of any age working together on subjects of mutual interestare likely to have something useful to offer. We do not think that learningis simply a process of transmission from those who know or who are older,to those who do not know or are younger. Nor do we think that ourunderstanding of the world should be restricted to a fixed body ofknowledge to which we should individually or collectively subscribe. TheInternet allows us to explore all kinds of knowledge together.<P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"><P><H2>Comments from group members:</H2><P><B><H3>Children</H3></B><P>'Quite good when you get on the computer; really boring talking about it!'<P>'Good fun - I want to do more.'<P>'Very interesting to be able to find out things you wouldn't be able tofind out otherwise. I thought it would be interesting going all over theworld on it, but it didn't make any difference.'<P><B><H3>Adults</H3></B><P>'Quite easy to start finding your way about, but speed and breakdowns madeit rather frustrating. Tended to confirm my view that much of theinformation is amazingly boring and repetitive - but then a real gem wouldmake up for this.'<P>'I really like the idea of children and adults working together, especiallyon something like this, where the children know at least as much as theadults.'<P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
