<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>get netted</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00"ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H2><A HREF="getnett1.html">get netted</H2><H3>first steps in cyberspace (back to index page)</H3></A><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"><H2><FONT COLOR="#00FF00">Get Letted!</FONT></H2><P><B>Letslink UK (e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:104047.2250@compuserve.com">104047.2250@compuserve.com</A>) is a UK leader - if notworld leader - in promoting a new kind of 'mutual economy': Local ExchangeTrading Schemes or LETS. Liz Shephard and Sabine McNeill explain below alittle about what LETS are and do.<P>It seemed that LETS and the Internet might belong together, and so, in someways at least, it proved. This project has suggested the potential formaking 'Green Money' - a special notional currency that can be used totrade goods and services - available globally for LETS-style transactions.The next step is to persuade big banks to take up the idea.</B><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"><P>LETS are independent local barter networks in which people trade goods andservices of any kind without the need for money. They offer communities andorganisations an effective cost-free solution to the problem of lack ofcash, and a means by which any low-income group or individual can establishtheir own local network for mutual support, economic self-help or communitybuilding. In LETS a simple accounting system records the value of servicesrendered using an interest-free, notional 'currency', which can be spent bythe recipient with any member of the network.<P>The UK has seen the most rapid worldwide growth of LETS - to around 400local networks, covering most towns, cities and rural areas. Any local areaor group without its own LETS can get guidelines and assistance fromLetslink on the most effective, easily managed and sustainable way oforganising its own local network.<P>As far as the Internet is concerned, we have only just started. We havebegun to make contact via e-mail with a number of like-minded LETS peoplewho want to work with us. We are developing a way to use e-mail tofacilitate small working groups in LETS development and to work jointly ondocuments and, for example, on the construction of magazine pages. We willalso use it to connect more closely with overseas partners and sisterorganisations, and with other organisations in the social economy andcommunity development fields.<P>Various people from out of the blue have left messages - we haven'tadvertised, so we're not sure how they got to hear about us. Word travelsfast, it seems. There have been unexpected messages from old friends, andmessages from a number of LETS enthusiasts who have never been in touchwith us before.Whether the Internet is capable of doing what we want, andin a way that is cost effective, is not yet clear. For example, we wouldlike to be able to include photographs and illustrations, but these takefar too long to download. We would like to send documents in our existingdesign format, but everything we have seen so far is in a standard font. Sofar (perhaps reflecting the limitations of the standard layout) the actualcontent of what we have seen has not been substantial enough to beinteresting. One other big drawback is that connections have been extremelyslow.<P><B>Liz Shephard</B><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"><P>User-friendly' is one of those terms you hear whizzing around the Internet,but to my mind it's all a bit of a con. Much of it seems about asuser-friendly as soap wrapped in barbed wire. Mainly I think this isbecause the overall design is so ugly! In fact the PC design seems to meutterly revolting, macho, masculine, nerdish, &eacutelitist, time-wasting . . .<P>Having said that it was exciting to switch it on the other day and discoverdozens of messages from all over the world, and to get reassurance fromvarious correspondents that we would sort out how to use it in time. Wewill see. It is early days.<P><B>Harry Turner</B><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"><P>I have been working on setting up a LETS Web site, which will include a lotof Letslink's materials, plus 'hot links' to other sites in the UK andaround the world. To build the site I had to get hold of a powerful AppleMac computer, so I have done a deal with the Cop Shop, a community computercentre at the Interchange Studios in London, using a special kind of LETSwhich can be traded across the city: Green Money. In return for my helpingthem out with Web work and tidying a small patch of ground outside theirback door, I am getting access to the computers I need.<P>I am using a programme called Web Weaver to put the text into html(Hypertext Mark-up Language). It is quite fiddlyat first, but not that difficult to master with patience.<P>The LETS materials will be part of a new Web site, <A HREF="http://www.gn.apc.org/hive/">Hive</A>, which hasdeveloped out ofthe Get Netted project. The main job over the next few weekswill be to get the structure as clear as possible, so that people arerouted quickly through to what they want to know.<P>While I have been working on the LETS site, I have also been making linkswith others in the field, such as Liz Shephard, Jan Wyllie and Mary Fee ofLondon Letslink, to talk about the idea of making Green Money availableglobally as a currency for LETS-style transactions. We have looked at theWeb sites of organisations such as<A HREF="http://www.digicash.com/shops/cybershop.html">Digicash</A> inAmsterdam,<A HREF="http://www.mondex.com/mondex/">Nat West's Mondex</A> in London and other sites using Internet-basedpayments in the USA. Through e-mail and face-to-face meetings we arebeginning to shape a plan for action.Soon everyone will be able to GetLetted!<P><B>Sabine McNeill</B><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
