<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>get netted</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00"ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H2><A HREF="getnett1.html">get netted</H2><H3>first steps in cyberspace (back to index page)</H3></A><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"><H2><FONT COLOR="#00FF00">The surfing community</FONT></H2><P><B>The Cedar Centre (e-mail: <AHREF="mailto:104047.2255@compuserve.com">104047.2255@compuserve.com</A>) isa small butvibrant community centre in the heart of the Isle of Dogs in east London -if that jostle of blue-glass monstrosities can be said to have a heart. Thedevelopment Corporation couldn't sell the flats nearby, so in the endfamilies, many of Bangladeshi and Somali extraction, found themselvesplaced in these luxurious buildings. But there are problems. For one thing,the residents need to develop new skills in order to have any hope ofgetting a job.<P>The centre has won an award for good practice in community development, andis always bursting with activity. Some of its users were enthusiastic aboutthe Get Netted project, but would the Internet 'community' really haveanything to offer them?</B><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"><P>'Do you want to be on the Internet?'<P>'The what?'<P>'You know what it is then?'<P>So began our conversation with Matthew Pike about getting on to theInternet. It so happened we were considering getting wired anyway - thiswas an opportunity we couldn't afford to miss.<P>There followed a brief honeymoon period (before the modem was bought,before the Compuserve account arrived), when several of us were runningaround the centre shouting 'We're going to be on the Internet!' to anyonewho would listen. Most people wouldn't.<P>Some young people told us that they were interested in getting informationabout homework; older people, looking for work, wondered if they could puttheir CVs on the Internet. There was a lot of interest in finding out aboutBangladesh, Somalia, Russia and China - places that some of our centreusers come from.<P>Gary, a technonerd, and old friend of the Cedar Centre, arrived in his bestanorak and started to teach Renos and Helen the basics of getting on to,into and around the World Wide Web.<P>Since then, we have had our good days and our bad days. Sometimes we can'tsend an e-mail and have to phone Gary to be rescued from our ownincompetence. Sometimes you could sort out a client's housing benefit inthe time it takes to assess information. Other days, we are surfing theInternet with such verve and style that we never get wet.<P>Renos is looking for library photographs (he's a photographer); Helen islooking for good educational software; Mel is looking for CV and jobsbulletin boards, in the hope that he can use them to help people find work.Khaleda is looking for Bangla language sites. Lofti, who teaches French,wants to find articles from <I>Le Monde</I> for his students.<P>First we visited a <AHREF="http://gpu.srv.valberta.ca/~dislamBangladesh.html">Bangladeshi site</A>. This was impressive -lots of news about Bangladesh, although, sadly, nothing about Sylhet, wheremost London Bangladeshis have their roots. We were impressed by the qualityand ease of access to information on this site.Next we visited<A HREF="http://www.cs.indiana.edu/hyplan/dmulholl/somalia/somalia.html">Somalia</A> again, an impressive amount ofwell-presented information in English and Somali. The<A HREF="http://www.vnet.org/www/Vcsmw">Vietnamese site</A> was not so good:we got there all right,but there wasn't much information. From this we deduced that a home page isonly as good as its keeper. We're looking forward to revisiting the siteswe've been to - we always leave a message if we can - and to visiting newsites. We're also keen to create our own home page on the Web.<P>The best thing about the Internet is that you can link in with groupsanywhere in the world. The worst thing is that it isn't yet user-friendlyenough for technophobes to use easily. We have access to a global librarywhich doesn't yet have a straightforward cataloguing system: in ten years'time, things will be different.<P>In the meantime, we will persevere: we want to spend some time learning howto use the Internet, because we want to communicate with other groups ofpeople who are interested in community development: not just talking aboutit, but doing it!<P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
