<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>get netted</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00"ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H2><A HREF="getnett1.html">get netted</H2><H3>first steps in cyberspace (back to index page)</H3></A><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"><H2><FONT COLOR="#00FF00">Small world</FONT></H2><P><B>Charles Wooton College (e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:ram92@dial.pipex.com">ram92@dial.pipex.com</A>) stands on its own atthe frontiers of Toxteth in Liverpool. It was established in 1974 toprovide training and educational opportunities for disadvantaged residentsof Toxteth and surrounding areas. Most of the students dropped out ofschool at the age of 14. Over the years the college has developed into awell-respected institution, which has been able to find places for studentsat universities across the country, as well as enabling people to findwork.</B><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"><P>The Internet is of great benefit to us. Itenables our students, many of whom have roots in Africa, to learneffectively about the black experience around the world. The Net also opensup lines of communication between ourselves and otherindependent/community-orientated institutions. Below is a sample of theexperiences that our students have had using the Internet.<P><B>William Ackah, Team Leader</B><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"><P>When I first heard about the Internet project, I was intrigued, because Ihave always been interested in communication via computer. Having learntthe basics, I found the Net quite easy to surf, and discovered quite a lotof useful information.<P>In my searches I was trying to get information about Somalia, my homeland.As a result of the civil war there it is difficult to get information, so Iwas hoping that the Net might provide me with some news. Although there wasnot much up-to-date information on Somalia, I did manage to download somepoetry written by a Somalian poet, and also by chance I got in touch with along-lost Somali friend of mine now resident in Sweden. He gave mepermission to use some of his poetry, which was a thrill.<P>Overall, I think that the Internet is a very useful medium. It makes theworld seem like a smaller place, and it has enabled me to revive memoriesand feelings concerning my homeland of Somalia.<P><B>Mohammed Abdisalam (computing student)</B><P><H3>Sites visited of interest:</H3><P><A HREF="http://www.cs.indiana.edu/hyplan/dmulholl/acg.html">TheAbyssinia CyberSpace Gateway</A><P><A HREF="http://reimari.uwasa.fi/~a70971/waaberi.html">Somali CulturalHome Page</A><P><AHREF="http://www.cs.indiana.edu/hyplan/dmulholl/somalia/somalia.html">Somalia Page</A>	 	<P><A HREF="http://www.vicnet.net.au/vicnet/COUNTRY/somalia/sca.htm">SomaliCultural Association Home Page</A><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"><P>In using the Internet, I was hoping to find information concerning women inslavery and women in education. After my initial training, I found itdifficult to access any useful information concerning black women ineducation - the kind of information that was available could easily beobtained from books. My search on slavery yielded a bit more information,and I found one very good article concerning slavery and the law.<P>Although my first impressions of the Internet were not entirelysatisfactory (I hope to have more time on it!), I do believe that it has agreat deal of potential as an educational tool. I am hopeful that it willenable black women in particular to share experiences and information witheach other.<P><B>Celia Granger (law student)</B><P><H3>Sites visited of interest:</H3><P><AHREF="http://www.itsnet.com/home/asumnall/africa/notes/inkiori.html">Africain World History: The Export Slave Trade from Africa</A><P><A HREF="http://tile.net/lists/slavery.html">The History of Slavery</A><P><A HREF="http://www.demon.co.uk/africa/">Africa and All Things African</A><P><A HREF="http://libfind.unl.edu:2020/alpha/Black%20Studies.html">BlackStudies</A><P><A HREF="http://the-tech.mit.edu/V113/N66/davis.66n.html">Angela Davisdiscusses issues concerning black women</A><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"><P>I have had a very enjoyable time using the Internet. I found the trainingoffered by the college useful and only wish that I had more time to surfthe Net on a regular basis. Using Infoseek, I did searches concerning blackwomen and black poetry. The sites that I visited yielded a fair amount ofinformation, and I even got a reply to my e-mail asking for informationabout 'slam' poetry.<P>Being filmed for television gave me quite a buzz, and reading poems basedon themes gathered from the Net was a great experience, particularly as oneof the poems I read was written by my uncle Levi Tafari.<P>I think the Internet is a very useful tool, and I am sure it will be ofbenefit to a lot of people.<P><B>Russell Frier (media student)</B><P><H3>Sites visited of interest:</H3><P><A HREF="http://www.netdiva.com/ourstory.html">Isis - OurStory (Women ofthe African diaspora)</A><P><A HREF="http://www.wilmington.net/arts/poets/">Poets in Person HomePage</A><P><A HREF="http://www.poetry.books.com/">National Poetry Month</A><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"><P><H2>Summary</H2><P>Though it was only about a couple of weeks' surfing on the Internet, wecertainly came to a conclusion on how much information is available outthere! Through our basic training and time spent on the Net, we were awareof its advantages (for example, communication with friends and colleaguesaround the world; tapping into information databases and librariesworldwide; retrieving graphics, documents, journals and computer programs;staying up to date with national and international news) and potentialdisadvantages (for example, access to illegal pornography; 'hacking' orgaining unauthorised access to computer systems and playing havoc withthem; the possibility of 'virus infection' through downloading programsfrom the Internet). We agree that whatever is the future of the Internet asa global computer network, it is certainly here to stay, as part of thebigger technological evolution of humans on planet earth.<P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
