<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>get netted</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00"ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H2><A HREF="getnett1.html">get netted</H2><H3>first steps in cyberspace (back to index page)</H3></A><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"><H2><FONT COLOR="#00FF00">Virtual accommodation</FONT></H2><P><B>Cae has tried his hand at a lot of jobs, but building is what he knowsbest. It's not surprising, then, that he's angry about the vacant buildingsin Manchester. Sound bricks and timber, which people on the streets couldturn into homes.<P>Cae has helped to start Surface (e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:cae@xtml.unet.com">cae@xtml.unet.com</A>), a housingcampaign that aims to squat a building soon. It's a loose butwell-organised group, typical of the new breed of campaigners, such asJustice? in Brighton, who recently started an alternative estate agencyoffering the details of every vacant property in the town. Surface are wellfocused: 'Deeds not words' is their slogan.</B><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"><P>Manchester is where we're at. It's been called many things: heart of theindustrial revolution, England's second city, 1996 tourist centre, hostcity of the Olympics, or the place that proved no matter how bad the livingconditions, people still have nowhere else to go.<P>Manchester is a city full of empty space. Sign after sign illuminates thehundreds of office developments, warehouses and shops: EMPTY, TO LET. Giventhis huge availability, isn't it remarkable that the owners of thisfantastic real estate don't seem too upset? They can wait for the next bigthing, and sell them on. The property guide to Manchester is like ashopping list, but for the exclusive property club. Many of the city'sfiner buildings have been demolished or taken into the hands of businesseswhose only aim is to make more money.<P>I ask you, what would you do? Go to the council and complain about the lackof services? Write to your MP? Write to the Queen? Pray? Leave? Or take theinitiative?<P> We've chosen to take the initiative. How can you use the benefits ofavailable resources if you can never find them or don't know they exist?Surface covers everything: use of office space, information technology,group dynamics, printing and design facilities, caf&eacute, material stores andrepair centres. We understand, learn and educate ourselves and each other .. .<P>Unfortunately, so far as the Internet project is concerned, we got off to abad start. Just after we installed the machine we were given some softwarewhich had a virus on it, and the whole thing crashed. We rang the computermanufacturer, but they couldn't give us much help. In the end Lorenzo andhis mate sorted it out, but it took about a week and half of tryingeverything. We also had problems with changing our password, so it wasn'tuntil well into April that we got going.<P>We made contact with a few groups by e-mail, such as Friends of the Earthand the Freedom Network. But it was mainly some Web sites that we foundmost useful. Frantic is a squatter site, with a load of different spaceswith themes such as Weird and Wacky, Underground and so on, each one keptby a different 'landlord'. Different individuals and groups can make use offree Web pages and get advice on getting their words up there. AmsterdamDigitalis is a really interesting exploration of what a sustainable citywith a population of ten million people would be like. The Dorsia Embassyin New York is a potential model for us - it provides a drop-in space fortraining people in literacy and Web skills. Through company sponsorshipthey have got hold of more computers and are helping lots of people.<P>Our problem is that we only have one computer. We got into somedisagreements early on because too many people wanted to play around. Forthe time being we have to concentrate on our main work. We have beeninviting different groups around Manchester to contribute pages ofinformation for our new site. We have been developing the idea of adatabase of people's CVs which we can just mail off when particular jobopportunities come up at the Jobcentre.<P>But above all we want to create a new site which will be based on thebuilding which we will eventually take over. We'll give people itsmeasurements, say where it is, what it is made of. We'll ask people toadvise us: how could we set up a wind turbine? What should we grow here?How could we become a centre for recycling, collecting paper and selling iton to businesses? How can we make the whole thing sustain itself, so itbecomes a home for the long term?<P><B>Cae, with contributions from eight other members of Surface</B><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
