<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Hidden Hands</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><P><H3>Introduction</H3><P><H2>by Waldemar Januszczak, commissioning editor, arts and music</H2><P>Modernism: it is a daunting word. It describes the century's most important art movement, and perhaps more than that. Perhaps 'Modernism' describes the most important cultural conjunction since the Renaissance. Certainly, it conjures up images of purity, coolness, progressiveness, a desire to rise above the tastes and conventions of the ordinary. Modernism was a massive revolution, a complete overthrow of the old ways of art. It is one of the century's fanaticisms. It had thousands of arms in architecture, poetry, painting, music, fiction, sculpture, theatre, cinema and photography.<P>Modernism is a huge term that embraces any 20th-century avant-garde movement that consciously and deliberately disrupted traditional forms of representation. Radical, searching, provocative, these avant-gardes were characterised by their desire constantly to find new and unfamiliar ways of representing the world, of lifting the modern age to expression. Modernism was a movement which, as its name suggests, believed in the heroic possibilities of the modern age. And, in a century during which the Western world has defined itself almost uniquely according to the conditions and discoveries of 'modernity', Modernism was destined to become its official and dominant art.<P>But for too long Modernism has been misread and misunderstood as a movement driven by theory, by a set of motivations that were intellectually rigid and entirely conceptual. We have been encouraged to believe that what the artists <I>above</I> us were trying to do - they were never <I>around</I> us, but always, seemingly, on a higher plane - was to go far beyond common concerns, to arrive at aesthetic perfection. <I>Hidden Hands</I> argues that the Modernists were, in fact, often guilty of exaggerating their intellectual aims and overemphasising their theoretical ambition. This, together with the inflated claims and often self-serving accounts of official histories of Modernism, sometimes resulted in out-and-out deception.<P><I>Hidden Hands</I> has tried to be undaunted by Modernism. The subjects of the four essays (and of the television series) might appear at first to be an extremely random selection, as disjointed as a Surrealist cut-up collage. But this is deliberate. Since comprehensiveness is impossible, <I>Hidden Hands</I> avoids the illusion of it. What it attempts to do is focus on a handful of Modernist details in the belief that they will end up speaking of much more than themselves - a process that the writer Paul Theroux used to call 'generalising on the immediate'. In fact, there is a very strong thread running through all four essays of this self-styled 'Different History of Modernism'.<P>In the first, Is Anybody There, about the influence of Theosophy and an assortment of other curious spiritualist ideas on Modrian and Kandinsky - an influence always feverishly played down by critics - we see two artists who were essentially cranky cult followers arriving at an art that has been habitually misrepresented as theoretically enlightened and pictorially perfect. But, on the contrary, Mondrian and Kandinsky were driven by murky, confused, pseudo-medieval hocus-pocus. The fourth essay, Painting with the Enemy, which contrasts Picasso's war with Matisse's, stops short of describing Matisse as a collaborator, but does accuse French art of supporting Nazi aesthetics long before war broke out. In the late 1930s, French art was already mounting its own purges of Modernism, and while Matisse was not a collaborator, he was the only major artist to broadcast on Vichy radio.<P>The two remaining essays also provide evidence of clay feet. That the CIA played a role in the spread and triumph of American Abstract Expressionism has long been suspected but never proved - until now. Art and the CIA presents the evidence. And the obsession with hygiene, with a Clean, White World, which Le Corbusier shared with Hitler, resulted in what was perhaps the ultimate Modernist architecture.<P>Perhaps we should have called these essays, and the television series,  <I>The Sins of the Modernists</I> , but that might have implied some belittling of their achievements. In being driven by motives that were often less than worthy, and sometimes plain cranky, the Modernists did not produce art that was any the less great, or inspirational, or breathtakingly beautiful: they merely proved that they were just like the rest of us. This is the revolutionary message of <I>Hidden Hands</I>.<P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
