<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Hidden Hands</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><P><H2>Modernism goes West</H2><P>On a fine April day in 1945, Soviet and American soldiers embraced on the banks of the River Elbe. They were 75 miles south of Berlin, and German defeat was imminent. Men of all ranks joined in a spontaneous celebration, toasting each other with liberated German champagne and cognac. Two months earlier, the Allied leaders - Stalin, Roosevelt and Churchill - had met at Yalta and promised the world a new and peaceful future. The Russian vodka flowed, there was some hearty back-slapping, and for a moment it looked as if they could put their vast ideological differences aside in favour of peaceful co-existence.<P>But soon the flattering speeches of Yalta gave way to mutual suspicion and distrust. Within a year, the Elbe embrace had dissolved into a snarl, and the flirtation between East and West was called off. The Cold War had begun.<P>For the impact it would have on the politics, economies and cultural life of both sides, the Cold War ranks as one of the most extraordinary and far-reaching developments in modern history. A war of ideology, it embroiled the two sides in a doctrinal struggle for over 40 years. They danced a convulsive and dissonant <I>pas de deux</I>, and Modernism, like everything else, was forced to take part.<P>The Second World War had redrawn the cultural cartography of Europe. Under the philistine jackboot of Fascism, the avant-garde had either fallen silent, capitulated or gone into exile. From the mid-1930s, a steady influx of artists had washed up on the shores of the United States, the flotsam and jetsam of Modernism's creaking vessel. <A HREF="http://archpropplan.auckland.ac.nz/People/Mat/barcelona">Mies van der Rohe</A> went to Chicago, and found his American hosts much more obliging patrons than the Nazis had been. Chicago also welcomed <A HREF="http://mitpress.mit.edu/mitp/recent-books/art/hight.html">Laszlo Moholy-Nagy</A>, who founded the New Bauhaus there. For Walter Gropius, there was a prestigious teaching job at Harvard University, and commissions to boot. <A HREF="http://pharmdec.wustl.edu/juju/surr/images/surr-imagery.html">The Surrealists</A> - Max Ernst, Andre Masson, Man Ray, Marcel Duchamp, Andre Breton, Marc Chagall - regrouped in New York and, with the help of some wild antics from Salvador Dali, were the talk of every salon. The great Cubist artist Fernand Leger also pitched up in New York; as did Piet Mondrian, who was hypnotised by the jazz, the subway, the arrangement of bottles in a bar. <P>With Europe still half-buried under rubble, its refugee Modernists were mesmerised by the United States. They found themselves in the only place where the modern age seemed able to come to terms with itself. When the American journalist Walter Lippmann announced the dawn of the 'American century' in 1946, few were inclined to disagree. 'Fate has willed it that America is from now on to be at the centre of Western civilisation rather than at the periphery,' he wrote in a Paris magazine. His declaration echoed the hopes of every ambitious politician and ideologue in the United States.<P><H2>Pollock, booze and the 'triumph of American art'</H2><P>If this was to be the new imperial capital, it needed an art commensurate with such a role. And, with war-time patriotism still in vogue, it had to be an American art. Cue <A HREF="http://www.cnam.fr/wm/paint/auth/pollock/">Jackson Pollock</A>. 'He was the great American painter,' said his fellow-artist Budd Hopkins.<P>'If you conceive of such a person, first of all, he had to be a real American, not a transplanted European. And he should have the big macho American virtues - he should be rough-and-tumble American - taciturn, ideally - and if he is a cowboy, so much the better. Certainly not an Easterner, not someone who went to Harvard. He shouldn't be influenced by the Europeans so much as he should be influenced by our own - the Mexicans and American Indians, and so on. He should come out of the native soil, not out of Picasso and Matisse. And he should be allowed the great American vice, the Hemingway vice, of being a drunk.'<P>Everything about Pollock was right. Born on a sheep ranch in Cody, Wyoming, he entered the New York scene like a cowboy - hard talking, heavy drinking, shooting his way out of the Wild West. He had the grittiness of Marlon Brando, the brooding rebelliousness of James Dean. Next to Matisse - by now barely able to lift a paintbrush, the compromised and impotent figurehead of an ageing European Modernism - Pollock was virile and had seed enough to spill. <P>He came up with a technique known as 'action painting', which involved laying a huge canvas flat on the ground - preferably outdoors - and spilling paint all over it. In the splurgy, random knot of lines which threaded their way across the canvas and over the edges, he seemed to be engaged in the act of rediscovering America. Ecstatic, loose, fuelled by drink, Modernism in Pollock's hands was a kind of delirium tremens. Although one critic described it as 'melted Picasso', most referred to it as 'Abstract Expressionism'.<P>By the late 1940s, to be an ambitious painter meant to be an <A HREF="http://sunsite.icm.edu.pl/wm/paint/tl/20th/abs-expr.html">Abstract Expressionist</A>. This was the style that would enter the official histories of Modernism as the 'triumph of American painting'. The ranks duly swelled: Robert Motherwell, Franz Kline, Willem de Kooning, Adolph Gottlieb, Mark Rothko, Barnett Newman, Clyfford Still. The painters met frequently at the Cedar Street Tavern in downtown New York, but in reality were bound more by a taste for whisky sour than by any formal aesthetic common denominator. But they were also linked by their past. Most of them had worked for the Federal Arts Program in the 1930s, producing subsidised art for the government and getting involved in left-wing radicalism. But by the early 1950s, like the America that fted them, they seemed to have come of age.<P><H2>Patriots and patsies</H2><P>This was the American decade. Post-war consumer spending put cars in every garage, meat on every table. The United States was at ease with itself, confident of economic success, proud of its international status and keen to offer the world a <I>Pax Americana</I> . <P>Chrome fin-tails, Ethel Merman, bobby socks, hula hoops, Lucille Ball, <I>Reader's Digest</I>, formica, Joe DiMaggio - in the 'Nifty Fifties', America had never had it so good. The cliche has prevailed, fed periodically by Fifties' revivals. But like all cliche, it fails to deliver the whole picture. For the United States during the 1950s was also the place of loyalty oaths, the House Un-American Activities Committee, the execution of the Rosenbergs, Commie witch-hunts. It was Senator McCarthy's decade, a time of rash accusations when conjecture and inference became impostors of fact and truth. It was a period shot through with suspicion and paranoia, divided into hunters and hunted, patriots and patsies - a place obsessed with the enemy without and the enemy within.<P>'We were traumatised not only by what we had been through and by the almost unimaginable presence of the bomb, but by the realisation that the entire mess was not finished after all,' wrote the novelist William Styron. 'There was now the Cold War to face, and its clammy presence oozed into our nights and days.' <P><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/expo/soviet.exhibit/coldwar.html">The Cold War</A> stoked the furnaces of anti-Communism in the United States until it sweated out of every pore. Hollywood made the point with a rash of films, their titles as unpersuasive as their plots: <I>I Married a Communist , I Was a Communist for the FBI , The Red Nightmare , The Red Menace , Red Planet Mars . Look </I>  magazine ran a cover story asking 'Could the Reds Seize Detroit?' The Bowman Gum Company, famous for its baseball cards, brought out a new set in 1951 called 'Children's Crusade Against Communism', with the slogan 'fight the red menace!' Captain America, the Marvel comic hero who had battled the Nazis in his strip during the war, now wielded his mighty shield at the Communists: 'Beware, Commies, spies, traitors, and foreign agents! Captain America, with all loyal, free men behind him, is looking for you, ready to fight until the last one of you is exposed for the yellow scum you are!' <P>In April 1949, <I>Life</I>  magazine ran a two-page spread attacking the United States' leading cultural figures as 'dupes of the Kremlin'. Featuring 50 passport-sized photos, this was a personal attack to accompany McCarthy's notorious blacklists. Dorothy Parker, Norman Mailer, Leonard Bernstein, Aaron Copland, Langston Hughes, Lillian Hellmann, Clifford Odets, Arthur Miller, Albert Einstein, Charlie Chaplin - all were accused of toying with Communism. <I>Life</I> was owned and edited by Henry Luce, a committed Cold Warrior, and it was on every coffee table in America. The cultural life of the nation - and the question of its integrity - was under attack.<P><H2>Advancing American Art</H2><P>Jackson Pollock had been a Communist activist in the 1930s; so had Adolph Gottlieb, William Baziotes and several other Abstract Expressionists. In McCarthy's vocabulary, these artists were patsies at best, traitors at worst. And yet none of them was included in the <I>Life </I>  magazine mug parade. Indeed, at a time when many intellectuals were being tailed by the FBI and driven out of their jobs, the Abstract Expressionists flourished. Why? Because they had a secret patron: the Central Intelligence Agency.<P>The involvement of America's spying establishment with the American avant-garde is one of the most bizarre legacies of the Cold War. Bitterly contested by most critics and historians, this liaison has long been rumoured but never really taken seriously. The CIA did back the American avant-garde, and it did so as part of an active and official Cold War policy. Indeed, the CIA played an aggressive role in the intellectual and artistic life of the 'free' West, and it did so unchallenged for 20 years. <P>But what in the name of God (and, indeed, He was often invoked by Americans during the Cold War) were the CIA doing in the business of arts sponsorship? Weren't they meant to be collecting intelligence and toppling foreign dictators? To understand how and why Modernism was secretly exploited as an instrument of US diplomacy, we need to look at the story of the 'Advancing American Art' show.<P>In 1947, the US State Department organised and paid for an exhibition of contemporary American art to travel abroad. Destined first for Latin America, then Europe, 'Advancing American Art' included leading US artists, among them Ben Shahn, Stuart Davis, Georgia O'Keeffe, Yasuo Kuniyoshi, Adolph Gottlieb and William Baziotes. Its purpose was to enhance American cultural prestige abroad, and to counter Soviet propaganda, which depicted the United States as a cultural desert. But the exhibition's public life, like that of so many other cultural and aesthetic issues of the Cold War, began and ended as a political football.<P>A small but vocal minority of Congressmen attacked the exhibition, denouncing its content and the political affiliations of some of the artists. William Gropper, Ben Zion, Stuart Davis, Yasuo Kuniyoshi and others were accused in Congress of being members of Communist-front organisations. And they were criticised for setting forth a 'distorted' and 'disfigured' portrait of the American scene, for failing to depict the nation's values and traditions in recognisable forms.<P>'I am just a dumb American who pays taxes for this kind of trash,' whinged one Congressman.<P>'If there is a single individual in this Congress who believes this kind of tripe is . . . bringing a better understanding of American life, then he should be sent to the same nut house from which the people who drew this stuff originally came.'<P>Even President Truman lent his voice to the outrage, saying, 'If that's art, I'm a Hottentot,' and mocking modern artists as 'half-baked lazy people . . . frustrated ham-and-egg men.' These attacks were to continue well into the 1950s, when yet again the theme of decadence was raised. 'The slogan of [Abstract Expressionism] seems to be: If there is any health in it, it can't be art,' said one critic. Others went even further, claiming that 'Modern art is actually a means of espionage . . . if you know how to read them, modern paintings will disclose the weak spots in US fortifications, and such crucial constructions as Boulder Dam' <I>(Art News from Los Angeles, 1951</I>).<P>The State Department, accused of sponsoring Communist sympathisers, capitulated to Congress and cancelled the 'Advancing American Art' show in mid-tour. The works were sold off at auction for 5 per cent of their purchase value. <P>The American government now faced a substantial dilemma. This cultural philistinism, combined with McCarthy's violent attacks, was deeply embarrassing. It discredited the idea that the United States was a sophisticated, democratic society capable of having a rational political or cultural debate. And it confirmed the negative stereotype being peddled by the Soviets of an America that was culturally barren. The government was eager to show the world that it had an art commensurate with the United States' greatness and freedom, but it couldn't publicly support modern art because of opposition in Congress. So it came up with an unlikely but ingenious solution: it turned to the CIA. [A]	<P><H2>Covert Institute for the Arts</H2><P>The CIA was founded in 1947 by President Truman. It replaced its wartime predecessor, the Office of Strategic Services, which was also known as the Oh-So-Social', on account of its Ivy League character. Staffed by Yale and Harvard graduates - men who collected art and wrote novels in their spare time - the CIA seemed a treasure-trove of liberalism compared to the cultural fundamentalism of McCarthy and the FBI.<P>If the government was looking for a secret arts council, the CIA was ideally suited to the task. It had the personnel, and it also had the facilities. From its inception, the Agency had begun stockpiling culture and art as weapons in its Cold War arsenal. It had a division - known officially as the 'Propaganda Assets Inventory' - that, at its peak, embraced more than 800 news and public information organisations. It also had a handle on numerous student movements and youth organisations, and counted among its contacts a youthful and enthusiastic Gloria Steinem. Unofficially, this division was referred to as 'Wisner's Wurlitzer', after Frank Wisner, first chief of the CIA's covert action staff. The idea was that, by simply pushing a button, Wisner could hear whatever the CIA was in the mood to hear across the world. <P>With the opening of another office in 1950 - the International Organizations Division (IOD) - it was clear that the Agency's cultural Cold Warriors were more than just a bit of fluff on the side. The Cold War was now being waged furiously, and in the IOD, its weapons were chosen and honed. 'The purpose of the IOD,' explains its first chief, Tom Braden, 'was to unite intellectuals, artists, writers, and musicians against what was being offered in the Soviet Union. The idea that the world would succumb to a kind of Fascist or Stalinist concept of art and literature was a horrifying prospect.'<P>To show that the United States was devoted to freedom of expression, the CIA secretly sponsored a huge variety of cultural and artistic activities. In its time, the IOD backed the animated version of George Orwell's <I>Animal Farm </I> ; it translated T. S. Eliot's <I>Four Quartets</I>  into Russian and airlifted copies into the Soviet Union; it sponsored jazz tours, opera recitals, the Boston Symphony Orchestra; it subsidised art books issued by the US publisher Praeger, Inc.; its agents posed as writers of Fodor Travel Guides; and it ran the Congress for Cultural Freedom (CCF).<P>This last was the CIA's most ambitious cultural operation. At its height, it had offices in some 35 countries and published over two dozen magazines, including Encounter in Britain   (edited by Stephen Spender) and <I>Preuves</I>  in France. Its members constituted a roll-call of the West's most notable writers, historians, poets, artists and intellectuals - Ignazio Silone, Arthur Schlesinger Jr, Malcolm Muggeridge, Daniel Bell, A. J. Ayer, James Farrell, Herbert Read, George Kennan, Saul Bellow, J. K. Galbraith, Raymond Aron and hundreds more. It was secretly paid for and controlled by the CIA, and its purpose was to protect Western culture from the contagion of Communist ideas. <P>With the Congress for Cultural Freedom in place, the CIA had the ideal front from behind which it could promote its covert interest in Abstract Expressionism. The CCF would be the official sponsor of touring exhibitions; its magazines would provide useful bases for critics favourable to the new American painting; and no one, the artists included, would be any the wiser.<P><H2>An abstract expression of the American myth</H2><P>The attractions of Abstract Expressionism to the staffers of the CIA were manifold. First, here was an all-American painting style that spoke for what America was: vigorous, energetic, free-wheeling, big. It upheld the great American myth of the lone voice, the individual statement, a tradition which Hollywood had enshrined in such films as <I>Mr Smith Goes to Washington</I>  and <I>Twelve Angry Men</I> .<P>Second, it was the kind of art that the Soviets loved to hate. Non-figurative and politically silent, it was the very antithesis of Social Realism. 'Moscow in those days was very vicious in its denunciation of any kind of non-conformity to its own very rigid patterns,' explains Donald Jameson, a former CIA officer. 'Anything [the Soviets] criticised that much and that heavy-handedly was worth support one way or another.' <P>One way was through the Congress for Cultural Freedom, which organised several exhibitions of Abstract Expressionism during the 1950s. One of the most significant of these, 'The New American Painting', travelled to every major European city in 1958-59. Other influential CCF shows included 'Modern Art in the United States' (1955) and 'Masterpieces of the 20th Century' (1952). The organisers made no attempt to conceal the propaganda value of these exhibitions. In one catalogue, the curator wrote: 'On display will be masterpieces that could not have been created nor whose exhibition would be allowed by such totalitarian regimes as . . . Soviet Russia and her satellites.'<P><H2>Millionaires in museums - MOMA and the CIA</H2><P>Abstract Expressionist works were expensive to move around and exhibit, and the Europe that they were intended to impress certainly couldn't afford them. So millionaires and museums - or rather, millionaires in museums - were now called into play. <P>The best example of the clever and subtle collusion that followed is the relationship between the CIA and the Museum of Modern Art (MOMA) in New York. The pre-eminent museum of avant-garde art in the US, MOMA had been co-founded in 1929 by Abby Aldridge Rockefeller. Her son, Nelson Rockefeller, was president of what he called 'Mummy's Museum' through most of the 1940s and 1950s. As well as being one of America's most powerful art patrons, Nelson Rockefeller was also deeply involved in overseeing foreign policy, having run the office of Co-ordinator of Inter-American Affairs in 1940, and served as Assistant Secretary of State in 1944-45.<P>Supporting left-wing artists was a familiar exercise for Nelson Rockefeller. <A HREF="http://fileroom.aaup.uic.edu/FileRoom/documents/Cases/60diegoRivera.html%0D">Diego Rivera</A>, the Mexican muralist and revolutionary, had been given a one-man show at MOMA in 1931 (only the second in its history), and had been commissioned by Rockefeller's father to paint a vast mural for the Rockefeller Center in 1932. The latter experiment turned out to be a disaster when Rivera refused to submit to Rockefeller <I>fils</I>' request that he remove a portrait of Lenin. Rivera was asked to leave, and Nelson Rockefeller had men with jack-hammers come in overnight to remove the offending figure.<P>But although this particular piece of patronage was unsuccessful, the principle it established was not forgotten. Forces of the left could be sponsored and co-opted by forces of the American right. In the process, it could be hoped that the political commitment of the artist might be diminished in the shimmer of the patron's coin. It's impossible to understand how Abstract Expressionism became an active part of Cold War policy without understanding this crucial precedent. <P>The critic <A HREF="http://Creenberg%20http://press-gopher.uchicago.edu:70/CGI/cgi-bin/hfs.cgi/99/chicago/7508.ctl">Clement Greenberg</A> - the chief proselytiser for Abstract Expressionism - set out the ideological rationale for accepting patronage in his famous article 'Avant-Garde and Kitsch', published in 1939 in <I>Partisan Review</I>. A crucial clue to the connection between Abstract Expressionism and the Cold War can be found here. Greenberg said that people working in the abstract mode need an [acute]lite to subsidise them; they need patrons, just like their Renaissance forebears. If there ever was a justification for the avant-garde being subsidised by the establishment, it was here. Incidentally, Greenberg signed up with the American branch of the Congress for Cultural Freedom, and was a committed Cold Warrior.<P>The functions of the CIA's cultural apparatus and MOMA's international programmes became increasingly similar and mutually supportive as the Cold War progressed. In one of the few articles to explore the relationship between the two institutions, Eva Cockcroft explains this symbiosis:<P>'Freed from the kinds of pressure of unsubtle red-baiting and super-jingoism applied to official governmental agencies . . . CIA and MOMA cultural projects could provide the well-funded and more persuasive arguments and exhibits needed to sell the rest of the world on the benefits of life and art under capitalism.' (From <I>Abstract Expressionism, Weapon of the Cold War</I> , Artforum, 1974.)<P>The funding was provided by the CIA's Tom Braden who, by 1950, had groomed the first generation of private sponsors to advance large sums of cash for his cultural endeavours. He had set up a Byzantine network of phoney foundations and conduits, counterpart funds and fronts, and there were few among America's great and good who did not cooperate. And there can be little doubt about Braden's relationship with the Museum of Modern Art: he had been its executive secretary in 1949, and his wife Joan worked as an aide to Nelson Rockefeller.<P>The exporting of Abstract Expressionism abroad dates almost to the same year. Willem de Kooning's work was included at the Venice Biennale as early as 1948. By 1950, he was joined by Arshile Gorky and Jackson Pollock, and for the next decade at least, the Abstract Expressionists were exported globally as the 'official' American art.<P><H2>Artists' response to the rhetoric</H2><P>But what of the artists themselves? Was the movement itself entirely passive? While there is no suggestion that the artists knew who their secret patron was, did they not object to the Cold War rhetoric that often accompanied exhibitions of their work? And was the movement entirely at odds with the social and political functions to which it was put? <P>Mark Rothko and Adolph Gottlieb both became committed anti-Communists during the Cold War. As early as 1940, they had helped found the Federation of Modern Painters and Sculptors, which started by condemning all threats to culture from nationalistic and reactionary political movements. In the following years, the Federation became an active agent for anti-Communism in the art world, seeking to expose Party influence in various art organisations. Rothko and Gottlieb led these efforts, and their dedication to the cause was so strong that, when the Federation voted to cease its political activities in 1953, they resigned.<P>Robert Motherwell joined the American branch of the Congress for Cultural Freedom, as did Jackson Pollock. But Pollock also said: 'The idea of an isolated American painting . . . seems absurd to me, just as the idea of creating a purely American mathematics or physics would seem absurd.' Willem de Kooning, too, was suspicious of 'Americanist' sentiment: 'I feel sometimes an American artist must feel like a baseball player or something - a member of a team writing American history.'<P><H2>Modernism's swan-song</H2><P>However, there was an 'American' art, and the CIA had done its part in helping to invent it. But soon the art became a bigger commodity than either the men who produced it or those who peddled it. Nelson Rockefeller had called it 'free enterprise painting', and in a way, he was right. Up, up, up went its stock; down, down, down went its value as an avant-garde style. As the movement proliferated, so it became decadent.<P>Abstract Expression was really the swan-song of Modernism. As its style became ubiquitous and standardised, a radical and subversive avant-garde found itself caught in the Catch 22 of official endorsement. Modernism - which had emerged at the turn of the century amid so much conflict and misunderstanding, and which had been subjected to suspicion and oppression by totalitarian regimes - ultimately lost its way in the corridors of official culture, seduced by reward and applause.<P>Tom Braden is nearly 80 now. He lives outside Washington in Virginia, in a house full of abstract art. He looks back on the CIA's efforts to subsidise Western culture with pride: 'If it's immoral to secretly fund something that was essential for the freedom of the world, I'm glad the CIA was immoral.' <P><H2>Further reading</H2><P><I>Abstract Expressionism: The triumph of American painting</I>  by Irving Sandler, Pall Mall, 1970.<P><I>Art-as-Politics: The Abstract Expressionist avant-garde and society</I>  by Annette Cox, UMI Research Press (US), 1982.<P><I>The Great Fear</I>  by David Caute, Simon & Schuster (US), 1978.<P><I>How New York Stole the Idea of Modern Art</I>  by Serge Guilbaut, University of Chicago Press (US), 1983.<P><I>The Liberal Conspiracy</I>  by Peter Coleman, Macmillan, 1989.<P><I>The Life and Times of the New York School</I>  by Dore Ashton, Adams & Dart, 1972.<P><I>The Paranoid Style in American Politics and Other Essays</I>  by Richard Hofstadter, Alfred Knopf Inc. (US), 1965.<P><I>Toward a New Past: Dissenting essays in American history</I>, edited by Barton J. Bernstein, Alfred Knopf Inc. (US), 1967.<P><I>Without Fear or Favour</I>  by John E. Salisbury, Ballantine (US),1980.<P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
