<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Hidden Hands</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><P><P><H2>War, flu and a new artistic imperative</H2><P>The Great War. Some called it 'the great remedy', and welcomed it as a 'cleansing' that would purge the world of its corrupt ways. Many of Europe's artists and intellectuals couldn't wait to join in. <A HREF="http://pharmdec.wustl.edu/juju/surr/futurism/1IRENA.html">The Futurists</A>, a bunch of high-octane artists mostly from Italy, set out for it on bicycles, as if they were going on a picnic. But the Great War was no picnic - it was a bloody mess:<P>'The bottom of the trench was springy like a mattress because of all the bodies underneath . . . The flies entered the trenches at night and lined them completely with a density which was like moving cloth. We killed millions by slapping our spades along the trench walls but the next night it would be just as bad. We were all lousy and we couldn't stop shitting because we had caught dysentery. <P>'We wept, not because we were frightened but because we were so dirty.' (Leonard Thompson, quoted In Peter Vansittart (ed.), <I>Voices from the War </I>)<P>The Great War was a cesspit that drowned an entire generation in mud, blood and shit. It decimated the ranks of the avant-garde and seriously dented the Nietzschean optimism that had inspired them to fight. Henri Gaudier-Brzeska, Umberto Boccioni, Charles Peguy and many other great creative talents were killed at the front. Many more died in misery from disease: tuberculosis, typhus, syphilis, cholera and dysentery - all the traditional camp followers.<P>Then, in the spring of 1918, there came the 'Fourth Horseman': a global outbreak of influenza that killed more people in Europe than the war itself. It raged out of control for a year, exacerbated by the conditions of demobilisation, and disrupted the Versailles Peace Conference. Guillaume Apollinaire, Raymond Duchamp-Villon and Egon Schiele were among the millions who died from it. <P>These two apocalyptic events - the war and the flu pandemic - ruthlessly imposed themselves on the imagination of those who survived. For the next 20 years, Modernism was to struggle with an experience that, above all, had driven dirt, decay and disease into the artistic consciousness. And in so doing, Modernism acquired a compelling new imperative: to clean up, to sterilise, to re-order, to eliminate chaos and dirt. <P>There has never been any sustained analysis of Modernism in terms of 'clean' and 'dirty', and yet, during the 1920s and 1930s, it was driven by this debate more, perhaps, than by any other. Many of the avant-garde - and especially architects - became obsessed with hygiene and cleanliness, and made it into a value system in their work. They sought a new Eden, a clean, white world blanched of the stains of the past. And they came up with a new aesthetic: hygiene. <P><H2>Shit, sex, viscera, chaos: Dada and Expressionism</H2><P>But initially, with the indescribable squalor of the war still sharp in the memory, dirt and the subject of the body became the obsessive focus of many artists. In Germany, a nation crippled by defeat, <A HREF="http://rubens.anu.edu.au//prints.xmosaic/MI/1738.JPG%0D">Otto Dix</A> and <A HREF="http://rubens.anu.edu.au//prints.xmosaic/MI2/1839.JPG">Georg Grosz</A> made wounding and mutilation the golden section of their work. They had both served at the front (Dix had been a machine-gunner, Grosz had suffered two nervous breakdowns), and for them, the clinical reality of rotting flesh and broken limbs refused to go away. <P>Alongside these images of men staring at their own entrails, war also called forth the insanity of <A HREF="http://pharmdec.wustl.edu/juju/surr/images/hausmann/hausmann.html">Dada</A>, an anarchic and motley ensemble of refuseniks who formulated another dirty Modernism based on shit, provocation and sex. Like Dix and Grosz (who was himself a Dadaist), theirs was a response determined by a view of the body - and the body politic - as inherently corrupt. 'We had no idea what we were doing,' wrote Grosz in his book <I>A Small Yes and a Big No</I>, 'but it felt to us as if we were stirring a filthy puddle with a long stick for no good reason . . . all we do is stir shit.'<P>Dada was scatological, naughty, spontaneous, carnivalesque, cosmopolitan. In its way, it embraced the dereliction of the age and danced on the ruins. Like the 'happenings' of the 1960s, it left behind little material sign that it ever existed, although the collages of Kurt Schwitters - rusty nails, old rags, toothbrushes without bristles, bicycle spokes, broken umbrellas - survive as poignant reminders of a scrap-heap age.<P>Dada had started in neutral Zurich during the war, but it flourished in the early 1920s in Germany, where military defeat and the collapse of the old political order left a situation rich in chaos and confusion. 'All values were changed, and not only the material ones,' the novelist Stefan Zweig wrote. 'The laws of the state were flouted, no tradition, no moral code was respected . . . In the collapse of all values a kind of madness gained hold.'<P>In Germany, architecture, too, was subsumed into a kind of madness. It stumbled into a response that was, at first, uncontrolled, visceral, nonsensical. Known as Expressionism, it produced some of the most bizarre architectural fantasia ever. Bernard Hoetger's war memorial near Bremen looks like a physical re-enactment of shell-shock. With its exaggerated curves and eerie protuberances, it is infected by the experience of war. Hans Scharoun's 'crystal architecture' watercolours explode with the intensity of magnesium flares - fiery shrapnel-beauty. And Hermann Finsterlin's swirling, organic drawings map out a hallucinatory state of mind.<P><H2>Le Corbusier cleans up</H2><P>One architect - Charles-Edouard Jeanneret, better known as Le Corbusier - was disgusted to see architecture in the service of such feral impulses. 'In the depths of our being,' he wrote in 1925, 'larva, toads and beasts which haunt the memories of the primordial world re-emerge again today . . . we see them in this new crisis of the spirit which followed the war: frightening dreams of Hermann Finsterlin from Bavaria, with their viscous ejaculations recalling underwater horrors, or those viscera, or impure acts of beasts. But physical matter is against it. These things can be born in a fevered head and inscribed on paper. Physical facts refuse to let them be built.'<P>Le Corbusier was to become the most influential of all Modernist architects. Son of a Swiss clockmaker, he was a rationalist and a puritan. He loathed the messiness and, above all, the impracticality of Expressionism. He believed that war had provided the occasion for a massive clean-up: enough of all this chaotic stuff; enough of this morbid concentration on collapse and decay. <P>Le Corbusier had not fought in the war, but he now began to dig a deep trench between the past and the present. 'Our world, like a charnel-house, is strewn with the detritus of dead epochs,' he wrote in <I>The City of Tomorrow</I>. 'The great task incumbent on us is that of making a proper environment for our existence, and clearing away from our cities the dead bones that putrefy in them.' The instrument of this 'great task', argued Le Corbusier, was 'Purism', an aesthetic that, unsurprisingly, emphasised cleanliness and hygiene as well as utter clarity of form and function. <P><H2>The Bauhaus and the new Age of Reason</H2><P>Purist ideas now began to assert themselves all over Europe. In Holland, the De Stijl movement exchanged traditional forms in design, painting and architecture for a style that was stripped back, geometric, simple. In Finland, Alvar Aalto began designing white buildings that were luminescent, clean, cubic. And in Germany, the escapist impulses of Expressionism soon gave way to more rational systems of architecture. The Bauhaus moved away from the superstitious crankiness of Mazdaznan to an equally convinced belief in the marriage of form and function to modern technology. Johannes Itten's departure in 1923 after a protracted power struggle with Walter Gropius meant that the Bauhaus could now position itself at the cutting edge of a new Age of Reason. As Max Bill recorded, the Bauhaus transformed itself into the temple of a new and effective <I>modern</I> faith:<P>'I see the Bauhaus as something bigger than it really is. Picasso, Jacobi, Chaplin, Eiffel, Freud, Stravinsky, Edison, etc. all really belong to the Bauhaus. Bauhaus is a progressive intellectual direction, an attitude of mind that could well be termed <I>religion</I>.'<P>Gropius himself, much influenced by the austerity of De Stijl and the writings of Le Corbusier, changed style almost overnight. In place of a cosy, gingerbread kind of architecture, he started organising buildings around strictly functional, geometric criteria. He believed that technology and industry, in harmony with art and design, could transform society and revolutionise the way people live. <P>Under the directorship of Gropius, the Bauhaus addressed itself with missionary zeal to solving the problems of a bankrupt and directionless Germany. Scarred not only by war but also by the rampant industrialisation of the 19th century, Germany's problems were particularly acute. Its cities were overhung with dust from smoke stacks, and most of the population lived in pre-war mass housing that had been badly conceived and poorly executed. Everywhere people lived in hopelessly overcrowded conditions, and disease and mortality rates soared to levels matched only by the inflated Deutschmark. <P><H2>Healthy houses: the Weissenhof Siedlung</H2><P>By 1927, Modernism had drawn up its solution. In July of that year, an architectural exhibition called the Weissenhof Siedlung opened in Stuttgart. Organised by <A HREF="http://archpropplan.auckland.ac.nz/People/Mat/barcelona/">Ludwig Mies van der Rohe</A> in the Weissenhof district of the city, the project consisted of 21 buildings set on the side of a hill overlooking the old city. <P>With prophetic insight, Mies had invited all the future leaders of Modernist architecture to take part. Included were Walter Gropius, Adolf Schneck, Peter Behrens, Hans Scharoun, Hans Poelzig, Mart Stam, J. J. P. Oud and, of course, Le Corbusier. No architectural experiment before or since had such an impact, and nowhere more than at the Weissenhof were the links between an emerging architectural style and ideas about hygiene made more explicit.<P>A poster advertising the site showed an over-decorated, gloomy apartment full of antique furniture, pictures and other objects. This photograph was crossed out in deep red. The consensus of the Weissenhof architects was that the old way of living was bourgeois and corrupt. Moreover, with its heavy drapes and stuffed armchairs, it was unhygienic, a safe haven for dust and all kinds of bacteria. In their new houses, they did away with the old plush furniture and replaced it with Bauhaus chrome chairs and tables; carpets were eliminated in favour of easy-to-clean linoleum. Down to the knives and forks, the look of the new home was bright, shining, germ-free. All ornament and frippery was abandoned. In its place was simplicity of form and a new palette: white.<P>White is historically the register of enlightenment and moral purity. But it's also the law court of hygiene, the place where dirt and disease are condemned. Correspondence and notes in the Weissenhof archives reveal the extent to which the architects were collectively motivated by issues of health and hygiene. Peter Behrens recorded his desire to 'construct a multi-storey house which could either help prevent some of the main dangers to public health or at least encourage the recovery of those who become ill'. At a time when the only recognised treatment for tuberculosis was exposure to the sun and clean air, the abundance of glass and open space at the Weissenhof was no coincidence. This was therapeutic architecture, designed to make people healthy. <P>The archives also record the persistent influence of a Dr Erna Meyer in the planning of the Weissenhof. Dr Meyer had recently published <I>The New Household: A guide to scientific housekeeping</I>, which had, according to Mies van der Rohe, 'won a lot of attention in Germany'. Dr Meyer's book presented the ideals of hygiene and efficiency, tempered with appeals to German 'spiritual' values. Mies distributed her writings to the other architects, along with a list of recommendations compiled by the housewives' organisations of Stuttgart. <P>So, it was under the guidance of the Mrs Beatons of their day that the architects of the Weissenhof came up with a prototype for the brave new world of Modernism. In all these buildings, the home was seen as the microcosm of social change, the module from which a new, healthier society would be constructed. <P><H2>New Man, New Woman, New Body</H2> <P>Contemporary black-and-white photographs did much to spread the message of this new vision. They conveyed a world suffused with light and sculpted in abstract, geometric forms. And they showed the 'New Man' - and the 'New Woman' - as a constituent part of the new iconography: sharpened and toned, improving their postures on Bauhaus reclining chairs, working out on terraces equipped with exercise bars and punch bags.<P>The punch bag was a vital accessory, and indeed, the image of the boxer was a dominant one at this time. On the terraces of the Weissenhof, in newspapers and art magazines, the boxer emerged as a new aesthetic form. This form showed the New Man - like the New Architecture - defined as a vehicle of precision, abstract logic and engineering principles. And the boxer, beating the shit out of the old culture with its romanticism and mystic hocus-pocus, represented an individual recovered from the war and ready for his combat with life. <P>Georg Grosz and John Heartfield were sparring partners; Bertolt Brecht wrote a long boxing poem called <I>Hook to the Chin</I> ; Le Corbusier liked to boast: 'Je suis un type boxer.' In one drawing, Boxing in the <I>Hanging Gardens of a Collective Apartment</I>, Le Corbusier showed a man pummelling away at a punch bag, his wife looking on admiringly as he works off his excess energy and becomes a healthy citizen of the new state. <P>By the late 1920s, the 'New Body' had become a popular obsession. In Germany, nudism - a fad previously dismissed as eccentric - now became <I>de rigueur</I>; health spas and sanatoria designed by the Modernists did a booming trade, and sports stadia mushroomed. There was even a Museum of Hygiene, built by the Modernist architect Wilhelm Kreiss. Opened in 1930 in Dresden, and sponsored by a millionaire who had made his money from Odol mouthwash, it was one of the largest and most popular museums of its day. It was known, appropriately, as 'The Temple of the New Man'.<P>Serried rows of white, cubic housing settlements, equipped with the latest sports and washing facilities, now began to crop up in every German city. People were relocated from slum housing to apartments that had electricity, bathrooms and sun terraces. Shining with sharp angles, every surface - inside and out - articulated the progressive vision of the Modernist spirit. Immaculately conceived and immaculately expressed, the new architecture was hailed as a triumph. <P><H2>The tyranny of order</H2><P>But inscribed in Modernism's triumph was its failure. There were problems, and their roots can be found at the Weissenhof. 'The doctrinaire constructivism of the Bauhaus gives these houses an oddly dry, pedantic quality while at the same time being reminiscent of some sort of provisional barracks,' observed one critic. Another, K. Dussel, commented: 'One could imagine someone wanting a room with this kind of constructivist functionality. But if so, he'd have no right to complain of being reminded of dentist's offices or operating rooms.' <P>And in a sense, Dussel was right. The deep metaphor of Modernism had become that of the operating theatre, the hospital, the sanatorium. It was antiseptic, functional, austere - and not everybody liked it. Even Le Corbusier's wife, Yvonne, complained. 'All this light is killing me, driving me crazy!' she once cried out in their apartment. When Le Corbusier put a bidet next  to the marital bed, she knitted a large tea-cosy to cover it. <P>In Le Corbusier's house at the Weissenhof, a corridor measuring 70 centimetres - the same width as the corridor of a train - made temperatures run high, as people with large beer bellies tended  to get stuck in it. This kind of architecture was clearly signed: NO EXCESS WEIGHT, NO PERSONAL  CLUTTER, NO KNICK-KNACKS. Everything, including your paunch and your past, must be left behind. <P>'There is an implicit tyranny in this view of a world which has to look the way the Weissenhof Siedlung looked,' says architectural historian Franz Schulze. 'What do you do with people who prefer to live messier lives, less ordered lives, people who are not happy living on the surface of a Mondrian painting? There's very little room made for them in the Weissenhof world. In fact, there's an irony here because, in a way, the Nazis come along with much the same view. They don't want the  diseased to be part of their world; they don't want the gypsies to be part of their world; they   don't want the homosexuals or the Jews to be part of their world. They want, in a sense, a world   that is every bit as clean in their terms as any of the Modernist architects did in theirs.'<P>This argument is highly contentious. It puts forward the theory that a sympathy of views existed between the Modernists and the Nazis. Many historians and critics dismiss this out of hand. But did their obsession with hygiene in any way link the Modernist architects with the Nazis?<P><H2>Nazism and Modernism: hygiene and the art of the insane</H2><P>When the Nazis put their theories about racial hygiene on show at an exhibition called 'The Miracle of Life' in 1935, the Bauhaus teacher Herbert Bayer designed the posters. In several diagrams for the exhibition, he adapted Modernist ideas about the body to suit Nazi propaganda. The Third Reich was conceived as a body, with Hitler as the brain. In Bayer's diagrams, the 'Body of the People' was now a total organism, functioning like a finely tuned machine.<P>And what were the blue-eyed, blond-haired, muscle-bound members of the Hitler Youth but a transformation of the ideal Corbusier type? Le Corbusier himself was much influenced by a French physician, Dr Pierre Winter, who was an energetic Fascist. Dr Winter contributed a series of articles on the 'New Body' to Le Corbusier's journal<I> The New Spirit</I>. Winter's language (and, at times, that of Le Corbusier himself) would not have been out of place in a Nazi propaganda film:<P>'We need to learn to how to be healthy . . . How to eat, how to rest, how to choose a wife, how to shape our children . . . The most formidable discovery of our era is "health", the discovery of the kind of life man can achieve if he agrees to take a bit of an interest in himself at last, to get to know his body, to concern himself with his own output and that of his race.'<P>One cannot remain deaf to the linguistic echoes between 'clean' Modernism and Fascist ideology. 'The New Man' was a phrase favoured as much by Le Corbusier as by Hitler. 'Health' and 'hygiene' were terms that acquired a political significance under the Modernists: they implied an attempt to impose order on society, to control the environment. So when Hitler referred to the Jews as 'bacteria' or 'disease', he was fully aware of the cultural and emotive weight that these concepts had. Hitler did not invent the lexicon of 'clean' and 'dirty': he simply borrowed from an existing vocabulary and then radicalised it.<P>Where the Modernists had conceived of the 'New Body' as part of a radical agenda for social improvement, the Nazis modified this idea to promote their own plans for a racially pure society. In the Third Reich, 'hygiene' was no longer a progressive concept; it became a reactionary device, an appalling stratagem for purifying the Aryan tribe, which culminated in the Holocaust. <P>But although the Nazis laundered Modernist ideas about health and hygiene, they stopped short of embracing their art and architecture. One of the main stands at 'The Miracle of Life' exhibition was organised by an architect-turned-physician, Dr Paul Schulze-Naumburg. He compared photographs of mentally and physically handicapped people to avant-garde art. His message was shockingly simple: Modernism was the by-product of insanity, and like the insane, it was a threat to the Body of the People.<P>The Nazis despised Modernist architecture as much as its art. Hitler, himself once an architect's draughtsman, favoured the chosen style of dictators - Neo-classicism. Its reference to the great civilisations of ancient Greece and Rome gave such architecture authority. It spoke the language of power, pure and simple. Projects like the Weissenhof clearly failed to fit this agenda, and to the Nazis, this white world was anything but pure. Several of the architects were Communist or Jewish, and the buildings were clearly influenced by Mediterranean and Moorish styles. With its dirty cosmopolitanism, it sullied the Aryan gene pool. In fact, the Weissenhof was depicted mockingly on postcards as an Arab settlement.<P>Despite this, many architects attempted a pact with the devil. After the Nazi occupation of France, Le Corbusier went to Marshal Petain, and tried to get commissions to build for the new Fascist state of France; he even wrote letters to Mussolini. And in Germany, Mies van der Rohe entered competitions for Nazi projects, adding a few swastikas to his designs for good measure. Gropius wrote to Goebbels and entered drawings for the Reichsbank building. Wilhelm Kreiss, Adolf Schneck, Peter Behrens, Heinrich Tessenow and many others all looked for work from the Nazis. <P>They were unsuccessful. The Nazis were too conservative to be obliging patrons of an avant-garde style. From the 'Degenerate Art' exhibitions of the 1930s, the architects should have been able to guess at Modernism's chances under Hitler. So, if the Modernists wanted work, they would have to look elsewhere. And inevitably, they turned to the United States, where many of Europe's outlawed or out-of-work artists had already been warmly received. <P><H2>Compromise and betrayal</H2><P>If there was an historic compromise, it occurred not in Fascist Europe, but in corporate America. Here, Modernist architecture was cleansed of its social and political content by a culture that was looking for a style, not a Utopian programme. 'They all ended up designing big corporate headquarter buildings, and those buildings were very severe, very reduced, and represented power,' argues the architect Charles Jencks. 'And in that sense they represent a betrayal of everything the Modernists fought for. After all, Modernism in 1910, 1920 was a spiritual movement which wanted to refound a new kind of culture in Europe, to "transvalue all values"; it was not invented to make the world safe for corporate America, for the triumph of Coca-Cola and Seagrams Whisky.'<P>The Weissenhof was heavily bombed during the Second World War, and many of its houses were flattened. Of those that remained, Mies van der Rohe's was used, appropriately, as a hospital for infectious diseases, while Le Corbusier's became a flak emplacement. The latter was extensively restored after the war, but today its whiteness seems a little faded. And if you look in the windows, you'll see interiors crammed with the kind of knick-knackery that would make most of the Modernist architects turn in their graves.<P><H2>Further reading</H2><P><I>Architects of Fortune: Mies Van der Rohe and the Third Reich</I>  by Elaine Hochman, Weidenfeld & Nicolson, 1989.<P><I>Art in the Third Reich</I>  by Berthold Hinz, Pantheon (US), 1979.<P><I>The City of Tomorrow</I>  by Le Corbusier, John Rodker Ltd, 1929.<P><I>From Bauhaus to Our House</I>  by Tom Wolfe, Picador, 1993.<P><I>Health, Race and German Politics, 1870-1945</I>  by Paul Weindling, Cambridge University Press, 1989.<P><I>The New Sobriety: Art and politics in the Weimar period</I>  by John Willett, Thames & Hudson, 1978.<P<I>A Small Yes and a Big No</I>  by George Grosz, Allison & Busby, 1982.<P><I>Storms of Steel</I> by Ernst Junger, Chatto, 1929.<P><I>Towards a New Architecture</I>  by Le Corbusier, Architectural Press, 1965.<P><I>Voices from the War</I> , edited by Peter Vansittart, Jonathan Cape Ltd, 1981.<P><I>The World of Yesterday </I> by Stefan Zweig, Cassell, 1987.<P><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line2.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
