<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Hidden Hands</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><P><H2>Painting with the Enemy</H2><P><P><H2>A war on two fronts</H2><P>There was an eerie quiet when Hitler's motorcade sped through a defeated Paris on 28 June 1940. Arriving at dawn, he spent three hours inspecting the cultural landmarks of the city while it still slept. Hitler was as swift and purposeful a tourist as he was a military commander. He spent only a few minutes at each of the sights, all of which he had studied from books when he was an aspiring architect. The Opera, the Arc de Triomphe, the Ecole des Beaux-Arts - he knew exactly what he wanted to see. As his entourage struggled to keep up with him, they were amazed at his exact knowledge of the proportions and arrangements of buildings and monuments he had never encountered before. <P>The Eiffel Tower, of course, loomed over Hitler at every turn. An essay in construction and abstraction, built for the Paris Exposition of 1889, it was the self-conscious symbol of modernity. Defying all traditional forms of representation, it was notably absent from paintings of the Paris skyline at the turn of the century, and languished for 15 years before finding its most ardent admirers - the <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/wm/paint/glo/cubism/">Cubists</A> and Orphists, who painted it again and again, contemplating its arches and angles, transforming its shape, spinning it on its axes and responding to the many questions it so bluntly posed about space and time and form and emptiness. Here was the great iconographic statement of the modern age. But of Modernism itself there was no sign in the Paris that Hitler saw. The French themselves had seen to that. <P>Long before signing the armistice with Germany in an old railway carriage on 22 June 1940, France had instigated its own campaign against the Modernists. The story of this French war against the avant-garde has long been overshadowed by the infamy of Nazi attacks on Modernism, and by the historical inhibitions that have tended to characterise the dark war years in France (the Vichy period was censored in school textbooks there until 1983). <P>But French attitudes during these years reached such a level of xenophobia, anti-Semitism and reaction that dramatic upheavals were caused in every sphere of life. In the art world, these changes signalled the betrayal of France's reputation as a haven for noisy and recidivistic avant-gardes. France aligned itself with Hitler's Germany in its intolerance of experimental art and any other kind of radical expression. It repeated the same neurotic pattern as the Third Reich in identifying Modernism with decadence and Jewishness, and it, too, sought to control artistic output as a propaganda tool of the state. <P>In the June armistice, France was divided into the occupied zone (the west and north, including Paris), and the Vichy zone, which was governed by Marshal Petain. In <I>Scum of the Earth</I>  (1941), Arthur Koestler scathingly described the Vichy government as a bunch of 'arterio-sclerotic old generals'. Marshal Petain, he said, was 'a disastrous old gaga', a 'living mummy'. 'It was an unreal drama of shadows. Racial-Fascism in Germany, Clerical-Fascism in Spain, Senilo-Fascism in France,' Koestler concluded gloomily. <P><H2>Decadence and degenerates</H2><P>This was not good news for experimental art. The Vichy government, like its Nazi masters, was quick to decry Modernism. What was needed, said Petain and his cronies, was a return to the classical, pastoral, patriotic line of French art, not all this jumbled, messy internationalism. What followed was a rampage against 'decadence'. But the reorganisation of the art world under Petain was not merely in mimicry of Nazi policy: it was responding to pre-existing tensions and contradictions in France. <P>From the Revolution to the Dreyfus affair, the obsession with decadence - and, most importantly, the perceived connection between decadence and Jewishness - was a recurring phenomenon in France. Edouard Drumont's<I> La France Juive</I>  of 1885 designated the Jew as the universal principle of disorder, while Max Nordau's Degeneration (1892) linked artistic decadence to social decay. Nordau recommended that experimental artists be given medical examinations and their family trees scrutinised. 'In nearly all cases,' he claimed, 'one would undoubtedly find degenerated parents or one of several symptoms, which put the diagnosis of degeneration beyond question.' <P>And then there was <A HREF="http://www.mi.aau.dk/~nhe/celine.html">Louis-Ferdinand Celine</A> (1894-1961), the great French novelist, who was obsessed with the biological decline of his race and the degenerative excesses of Modernism. In a letter to Andre Gide's secretary, Lucien Combelle, he once complained:<P>'You say nothing about Jews - nothing about alcohol - nothing about the vile flattery . . . of our famous "elites" [i.e. the Modernists] by the press. What an opiate! Never, in my opinion, not even under the Pharaohs, have the masses been subject to a form of treatment that is so debasing and so full of rubbish!'<P>So, the pseudo-scientific identification of aesthetic decadence with biological degeneration had already been forcefully made, in France, some time before Nazi theories were articulated. Hitler's notorious Nuremberg speech of 1935, in which he identified avant-garde art as a Jewish conspiracy, was merely a repetition of an old tune. The French critics Camille Mauclair and Waldemar George had been saying as much throughout the 1920s and 1930s, and they can only have welcomed Hitler's speech, in which he explained his principal grievance against Modernist art:<P>'Anyone who wants to excuse the paintings and sculptures of the <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/wm/paint/glo/dada/">Dadaists</A>, Cubists and <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/wm/paint/glo/futurism/">Futurists</A> has really no idea of the function of art, which is not to remind mankind of its deterioration, but rather to counter it with the eternally beautiful and healthy . . . It is not the function of art to grovel in the dirt for dirt's sake, to depict mankind in a state of decomposition, to draw idiots to symbolise the rites of maternity, and to show twisted buffoons as symbols of virility.'<P>It is impossible to escape the obsession with degeneracy that marked this period in Europe. Many intellectuals, not just in France and Germany, were heavily influenced by social Darwinism and eugenicist theories. W. B. Yeats, T. S. Eliot, Virginia Woolf, Ezra Pound - in fact, most of the principal literary Modernists - believed, like Louis Pasteur, that the masses could be compared to germs. Woolf referred to a 'vast, featureless, almost shapeless jelly of human stuff'. Pound claimed that humanity (apart from artists, of course) was a 'mass of dolts', a 'rabble', 'waste and manure', and in his Cantos, the 'multitudes' become a torrent of human excrement ('the great arsehole'). There is ample evidence to show that the intellectual context of this period was integrated with totalitarian beliefs: the masses needed to be controlled, the tribe needed to be purified. Many Modernists held this view, but under Hitler and Vichy, it backfired on them.<P>The attack on Modernism was formalised in Nazi Germany in 1937 with the mounting of the Entarte Kunst - or 'Degenerate Art' - show. This comprised 20,000 Modernist paintings, seized from galleries and museums around Germany, exhibited alongside contemptuously worded captions. The aim was to encourage the public to ridicule the excesses and distortions of this kind of art. Modern artists were described as criminals and fools; their work was juxtaposed with the works of 'primitive' peoples and the insane to undermine its integrity and authority. <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/wm/paint/auth/klee/">Paul Klee</A>, Oskar Kokoschka, <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/wm/paint/auth/picasso/">Pablo Picasso</A>, Max Beckmann, <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/wm/paint/auth/ernst/">Max Ernst, <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/wm/paint/glo/expressionism/">the Expressionists</A>, <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/wm/paint/glo/surrealism/">the Surrealists</A>, <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/wm/paint/auth/kandinsky/">Wassily Kandinsky,</A> Georg Grosz, Otto Dix, <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/wm/paint/auth/chagall/">Marc Chagall</A> and even Emil Nolde (who was himself a Nazi) were all exhibited. Most of the work was later burnt or auctioned off to foreign dealers (or disappeared into the private collections of Nazis such as Goebbels, who continued secretly to nurture a private taste totally at odds with public and official policy).<P><H2>Signing up for the aesthetic pogrom</H2><P>In the same year, an exhibition of French art by living artists took place in Berlin, organised by a branch of the French Ministry of Foreign Affairs. While Britain refused a similar invitation from the Germans, the French show demonstrated that there were plenty of artists willing to exhibit in a country where countless Jewish and other 'decadent' artists were being banned. Furthermore, the French exhibition respected the Nazi ban on Jews. So, several years before the Nazi occupation, the French signalled to the Germans a lack of solidarity among modern artists and, more disturbingly, a predisposition to sign up for an aesthetic pogrom. <P>The year 1937 was a truly bad one for Modernism. After the fall of Leon Blum's progressive government in the spring, a new right-wing administration launched a clean-up in the art world. As the Prometheus sculpture commissioned from Jacques Lipchitz that year for the World Fair in Paris was removed from the Champs-Elysees and destroyed, a violent press campaign was launched against the artist, a Russian Jew, amid an atmosphere of growing hostility to the 'international style', as Modernism was otherwise called. 'We have decided to put the label "Francais" on all our products,' declared the Syndicat des Artistes et Artisans. 'We have decided, in order to fight against unfair competition from foreigners who have settled in France, to exclude them from this organisation.' Restrictions on foreign artists, quotas, exclusions - such measures became inscribed in French law well before the Vichy government was set up.<P>When Marshal Petain summoned France to 'an intellectual and moral redressing' in 1940, he therefore knew from precedent that he could rely on the support of a core group of French artists and intellectuals. Petain advocated a kind of back-to-basics art - a return to the soil, to family values and national traditions. Art under Vichy was to be a soothing lullaby that sang the body beautiful of France. It was to offer a kind of vision of a France before the 'fall' of the complicated, dirty impulses of Modernism. <P>The application of this principle was thorough, and it produced for the most part a tract of kitsch and mediocrity that is testimony not only to Vichy's deluded ambitions but to the capitulation of some (not all) artists to those ambitions. Contrary to claims that the war years were fallow, France during the Occupation was, in fact, extremely productive. A survey of exhibitions held between 1940 and 1944 shows an enormous increase in both the number of shows and attendance figures at public galleries. Theatres, cinemas, publishing houses, music halls - all flourished. <P>For the Germans - who were, of course, fastidious censors (no more Josephine Baker, no more Revue Negre) - this sense of normality was a useful smokescreen for a host of nefarious activities, not least the deportation of Jews and 'foreigners' to German concentration camps. For those prepared to rub shoulders with the occupiers, Paris glittered under the jackboot, as Max Beckmann's <I>The Gobblers  </I>(painted in exile) shows with brutal emphasis.<P>The German advance had pushed most of the avant-garde, including Beckmann, to the edges of France and beyond. Piet Mondrian and Fernand Leger had left in 1939 for the United States, where they were later joined by Marcel Duchamp, Andre Breton, Ernst and Chagall. Joan Miro returned to Spain. Husband and wife Robert Delaunay and Sonia Terk hid in the Alps. <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/wm/paint/auth/matisse/">Henri Matisse</A> retreated to Nice. Chaim Soutine died in hiding. For the most part, the artists who remained were either second-raters or collaborators, and their work reveals a staggering level of mediocrity. Marshall Petain's idea of 'community, <I>metier</I>  [trade, occupation], humanism, roots' found its amateur apotheosis in a poor copy of German social realism - French folk art chewing the cud like an honest cowherd - and in 'l'Art Marechal', which celebrated the personality cult of Petain. There was even a retrospective celebrating the French lottery, and another of 'Famous Medical Busts'. As the underdogs of the Paris art world became the standard bearers of the new culture, France seemed to be, according to the novelist and dramatist Henri de Montherland, 'surrendering to card games and Tino Rossi'. <P>But the truth is a bit more disturbing. French artists who collaborated with the Vichy regime were not simply participating in the banalisation of art; they were actively pursuing the triumph of 'non-Jewish' art. They were complicit in the systematic 'Aryanisation' of French culture, and they promoted their own bureaucratic careers by openly sympathising with Nazi Germany. <P>In October 1941, 13 French artists accepted an invitation by the German Ministry of Propaganda to tour Germany. The trip, dubbed <I>'Le Voyage'</I>, is particularly troubling for apologists of Modernism because it included five painters once associated with the Fauve movement. When Matisse and <A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/wm/paint/auth/derain/">Andre Derain</A> exhibited their work in 1904, they had been likened to 'wild beasts' (<I>'fauves'</I>) and accused of 'throwing a pot of paint in the face of the public'. Their scandalous experiments in the fields of colour and composition were a self-conscious moment of rupture with pictorial tradition. Fauvism represented the breaking of the waters before the imminent birth of Modernism. So when Derain, together with fellow-Fauves Maurice Vlaminck, Kees van Dongen, Othon Friesz and Andre Dunoyer de Segonzac allowed themselves to be guided through Germany by officers from the propaganda and art censorship ministries of the Third Reich, Modernism seemed to be surrendering ignominiously to its worst enemy.<P><H2>Picasso: discreet resistance</H2><P>Asked later about the significance of 'Le Voyage', Picasso said that Derain should be shot for what he had done. Picasso himself was hailed after the war as a Resistance hero, and he sat on a purge tribunal responsible for dealing with artists accused of having 'favoured the enemy's endeavours'. It's reasonable to expect that the Spanish supremo would have been inflamed by Derain's betrayal. Picasso was, after all, the creator of <I>Guernica</I>  (1937), rightly regarded as Modernism's most daring counter-attack to totalitarian aggression, and the one that had the most impact. General Franco was enraged by <I>Guernica</I>, and it seems he obtained a guarantee from the Germans that Picasso would not be allowed to show or sell his work in occupied France. The Nazis, who had included Picasso in their 'Degenerate Art' exhibition, were happy to oblige the Spanish dictator.<P>When Alfred Barr of the Museum of Modern Art in New York offered to help Picasso get out of France in the summer of 1940, the artist had refused, deciding instead to return to his studio in Paris. Certainly his decision to remain when he had the opportunity to leave gave comfort to other members of the avant-garde. But Picasso, whose fame and wealth gave him some immunity, kept his own discreet counsel.<P>In the 300-400 works he produced during the Occupation, there was no repeat of the confrontational bravura of <I>Guernica</I> . To have done so would probably have been disastrous for Picasso. If it can be said that he avoided or disrupted the conditions of cultural repression, it was only by using distorted and disturbing imagery at a time when the officially accepted form was idealised beauty. As Francoise Gilot has pointed out, you didn't need to put dynamite under a train to qualify as a resister. Perhaps the only choice available for Picasso was the quiet encoding of the themes of darkness, coldness and despair in his work. But this sits uneasily with the fact that he entertained German soldiers and officers in his studio throughout the Occupation; that he did business with a dealer who was known to be trading in sequestered Jewish art; that he was unofficially tolerated because of his huge reputation. <P>Were the claims of the Americans at time of the Liberation - 'Picasso, the painter who defied the Germans, finds himself the hero of a revolutionary mood' (<I>New York Times</I> , 29 October 1944) - perhaps a little inflated? What exactly was his 'position in the Resistance movement', which Alfred Barr claimed to be 'of unique importance'? Were viewers, favourably disposed to him since the <I>Guernica</I>  episode, inclined to imbue specific images painted during the Occupation with politically subversive undertones or even pro-Resistance messages? Or was the very fact of continuing to be an experimental artist the only effective act of resistance at a time when open disagreement with the state was a matter of life and death?<P><H2>Matisse: the refuge of a dream</H2><P>Certainly there is more of the mood and tension of those years in Picasso's work than in that of Matisse, the great father of Modernism, whose work during the same period is little more than decorative. There is no sign at all of the Vichy regime or the war in Matisse's paintings. On the contrary, he continued painting the <I>belle monde</I> of France as if nothing had happened. From 1941, he lived in Nice - his chief concern, as always, the pursuit of a gorgeous aesthetic dream. <P>Matisse's wife and daughter were active in the Resistance, but he was allowed (uniquely among artists) to make broadcasts for Vichy radio. If he was sympathetic with Vichy ideology, then an interview he had given in 1924 may explain why. 'I do not consider it to be desirable in all respects that so many foreign artists come to Paris,' he had said. 'The result is frequently that these painters carry a cosmopolitan imprint which many people consider to be French. French painters are not cosmopolitan.' <P>History by hindsight is easy. Matisse can't be held to account for the fact that such sentiments were used to empower a reactionary and oppressive regime. But if the Modernists had a moral choice, only very few of them opted to question the status quo. 'Our role [as artists] . . . was to "scream out the truth",' argued the writer and Resistance worker Edith Thomas '- the yellow stars on the chests of Jews, the brutal separation of children from their mothers, the deportation towards unknown locations. That was the truth at a time when attempts were being made to enclose [artists] in a world of dream, fantasy, irresponsibility, childishness and puerility.'<P>The Vichy regime was directly responsible for the imprisonment of 135,000 people, the internment of 70,000 suspects, the dismissal of 35,000 civil servants. A total of 60,000 Freemasons were investigated, 6000 harassed, 989 sent to camps. The French governmental apparatus abetted the deportation of 76,000 French and foreign Jews, of whom fewer than 3 per cent survived. They sent 650,000 workers to Germany as conscript labour. Thousands of works of art were confiscated and destroyed, and hundreds of galleries were closed down or Aryanised. Paris lost its claim to be the cultural capital of the world, and Modernism, where it had not capitulated, was driven out of Europe to the United States. <P><H2>Further reading</H2><P><I>Art under a Dictatorship</I>  by Helmut Lehmann-Haupt, Oxford University Press, 1954.<P><I>Artists under Vichy</I>  by Michele C. Cone, Princeton University Press (US), 1992.<P><I>Life with Picasso</I>  by Francoise Gilot and Carlton Lake, Nelson, 1965.<P><I>My Galleries and Painters</I>  by Daniel-Henry Kahnweiler, Viking (US), 1971.<P><I>Paris in the Third Reich: A history of the German occupation, 1940-1944</I>  by David Pryce-Jones, Collins, 1981.<P><I>Scum of the Earth</I>  by Arthur Koestler, Eland, 1941, 1991.<P><I>Suicide of a Democracy</I>  by Heinz Pol, Raynal & Hitchcock, 1940.<P><I>Surrender on Demand</I>  by Varian Fry, Random House (US), 1945.<P><I>Vichy France: Old guard and new order, 1940-1944</I>  by Robert O. Paxton, Columbia University Press (US), 1972.<IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
