<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Cybersecrecy: A short history of encryption</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H2><A HREF="cyber000.html">Cybersecrecy</A></H2><H1>A short history of encryption</H1>The desire to communicate in private, and yet to listen in on other people'scommunications, is as old as human history, and the history of encryption isalmost as old as the history of writing itself. Cryptography is the science ofencryption, or secret writing. Archaeologists have found carvings thatincorporate a deliberate transformation of writing as early as 1900 BC in thetomb of the Egyptian pharaoh Knumhhoptep II. In ancient India, Vatsyayana's<I>Kama Sutra</I> (written before AD 500) lists secret writing as one of the 64arts that women should know and practise. <P>The Greeks are thought to have been the first to employ encryptionsystematically as a method of private state communication(<I>krupt&oacute;s</I> is the ancient Greek word for 'hidden'). As long ago asthe 5th century BC, the Spartans were using cryptography for their militarycampaigns. The Spartans developed <I>skytale</I>, an early cryptographic devicethat operated by winding a tape (usually made of papyrus) along a wooden batonin such a way that a short message could be written along the baton. Once thetape was unwound, the collection of letters appeared arbitrary and meaningless.Clearly recipients could decode the message only if they knew the technique(and had a baton of the same dimensions). Thus the Spartan leader Lysander, forexample, was able to make his all-important decision to act against thePersians on the basis of intelligence acquired via an encrypted communication.(The message, by the way, said that the Persians had betrayed Lysander and wereplotting against him.)<P>Another ancient encryption device was the so-called 'Caesar cipher'. For hismilitary and diplomatic messages, Julius Caesar used a simple system ofreplacing letters in the alphabet by letters a set number of spaces further on.Shifting the alphabet three places, for example, would transform the word 'DOG'to 'GRJ'. This simple form of encryption, though mere child's play by today'scryptographic standards, was enough to keep unauthorised persons fromeavesdropping on sensitive communications.<P><FONT SIZE=1><A HREF="cyber020.html">NEXT PAGE</A></FONT><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
