<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Cybersecrecy: Black magic and executions</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H2><A HREF="cyber000.html">Cybersecrecy</A></H2><H2>Black magic and executions</H2>There were major advancements in cryptography during the Renaisance. In 1518,Abbot Trithemius, a German Benedictine monk, published in Latin the first bookon the subject - the <I>Polygraphia</I> - which proved so popular that it wassoon reprinted in French and German. The Abbot's system involved using a simplesubstitution cipher (like the Caesar cipher) and then transcribing each newletter into a word or phrase - so Trithemius's code was actually hidden in whatappeared to be normal text. The concealing of a message in this<I> physical</I>way is called 'steganography' (secret inks and microdots are other examples).The principle behind the Abbot's system is still widely used today. However, atthe time, his work was viewed by some as evidence of black magic and copies ofhis book were publicly burned, though thankfully Trithemius himself escaped thesame fate.<P>In 1556, another encryption system was invented by Girolamo Cardano. For hissystem, he used a specially prepared grid divided into 36 squares, whichpivoted in the middle. Nine of the squares were punched out and numbered. Partof the secret message was then written through these squares, and through asystem of turns, the grid gradually built up the secret message. Fortransmission, the message was rearranged in six-letter groups, and therecipient would reverse the process, using an identical punched-out grid.Cardano's system of 'transposition ciphers' was the basis of one of the mostsuccessful British naval ciphers of World War I.<P>England came late to cryptography, but Elizabeth I's chief spy FrancisWalsingham used code-making and -breaking extensively and very successfully. In1571, when Elizabeth appointed him head of the first Englishcounter-intelligence network, England - a Protestant country in a Europedominated by Catholics - was under threat from many sides. Walsingham was nothimself a cryptographer but was able to set up a spy-ring reaching as far asthe Vatican by appointing the cryptanalyst Thomas Phelippes as his assistant.<P>Another recruit, Gilbert Gifford, was sent to spy on Mary Queen of Scots.Managing to gain Mary's confidence, he was soon appointed her messenger and, inthis role, was able to open her communications in secret, copy the ciphercontained in them, reseal the letter and promptly send the text to London fordecoding by Thomas Phelippes. It was by this method that Walsingham learned ofan alleged plot by Mary Queen of Scots and her cronies to assassinateElizabeth. The plotters were swiftly arrested and Mary sent to trial, where thecipher key and papal ciphering bureau, which had been discovered in Mary'sapartment, were presented as evidence. Mary was beheaded on 8 February 1587 inthe hall of Fotheringay Castle.<P>Mary was not the only one to lose her head because of insecure communications.Charles I was executed in 1649 after a trial partly based on his decipheredprivate letters. In 1685, the dukes of Monmouth and Argyll were both executed.Among the evidence against them was the deciphering of one of Argyll's letters,which revealed that they were plotting to overthrow James II.<P><FONT SIZE=1><A HREF="cyber030.html">NEXT PAGE</A></FONT><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
