<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Cybersecrecy: Signals over wires</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H2><A HREF="cyber000.html">Cybersecrecy</A></H2><H2>Signals over wires</H2>Cryptography's next leap forward came with the Industrial Revolution, alongwith general progress in the technology of communications. In France, duringthe Napoleonic wars, brothers Claude and Ignace Chappe invented a machinecalled the 'lightning telegraph'. This precursor of modern telegraphs and thetelephone employed wooden poles dotted around the countryside, each of whichhad an arm extension manned by an operator. The positioning of the armsindicated important information, such as whether there had been a militaryvictory or defeat, or any other message that needed to be conveyed quickly. Thesystem was primitive and insecure but a significant breakthrough.<P>The 19th century saw a range of innovations in the development of codes. In1817, a British naval officer, Captain Frederick Marryat, devised thesemaphore, a system that uses the positioning of coloured flags to sendmessages, and which was really an adaptation of the basic lightning telegraphidea. The real communications breakthrough came in 1832, when the AmericanSamuel Morse began his experiments that led to the invention of anelectromagnetic telegraph system that could send signals over wires. This wasthe first code that did not rely on the direct manual relay of messages andbecame famous as 'Morse code'. The system uses dots and dashes to representeach letter in the alphabet (and is strictly speaking a substitution cipherrather than a proper code). By 1866, the first telegraph cable had been laid onthe bed of the Atlantic - it was now possible to communicate across thousandsof miles in a matter of seconds. <P>With the invention of faster communications, new and better encryption systemshad to be developed. Now that passing confidential messages involved externaltechnology such as wires and cables rather than being directly communicatedfrom one person to another, privacy was coming under threat in a new way. Overthe next hundred years and through two world wars, the battle between thecode-makers and the code-breakers was waged as never before.<P><P><FONT SIZE=1><A HREF="cyber040.html">NEXT PAGE</A></FONT><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
