<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Cybersecrecy: Interceptions and Enigma</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H2><A HREF="cyber000.html">Cybersecrecy</A></H2><H2>Interceptions and Enigma</H2>The fight over encryption was often the key to determining success in thebroader struggle. In September 1914, at the start of World War I, the body of aGerman junior officer was plucked out of the freezing Baltic by the Russiannavy, his ship, the<I> Magdeburg</I>, having sunk a few hours earlier. Clutchedtightly in the young sailor's arms, which were frozen with ice and rigormortis, was the codebook of the doomed German ship. The discovery of the<I>Magdeburg</I> codebook was to give the British an enormous militaryadvantage.<P>Another famous incident was the interception of the 'Zimmerman telegram' by theBritish in January 1917. The text promised to give Texas, New Mexico andArizona to Mexico if that country would enter the war on the side of theGermans. The telegram was deciphered by British cryptographers and presented tothe Americans as a reason why they should enter the war.<P>In the 1920s, the Germans developed a sophisticated encryption machine calledthe 'Enigma'. The keys of its typewriter-like keyboard were interconnectedelectronically so that, by pressing, say,<I> f,</I> it would print <I>q</I>;the couplings were changed constantly so there was never any consistencybetween messages. Enigma was used to send the Third Reich's most secretinformation.<P>With the impending Nazi threat, an unprecedented act of cooperation took placein the world of cryptographers and their masters. The Poles, who had beensecretly developing a way to break the Enigma, were just a step away fromcracking the code when they were foiled by the Germans adding two more rotorsto the machine, multiplying the security of the encryption standard. In theirdesperation to stop Hitler's advancing forces, the Polish cryptographers madethe dramatic decision to share what had, until this point, been a fiercelyguarded technique using a high-speed calculating machine known as the<I>'bombe</I>'. The Poles would probably have eventually been able to crack theEnigma code, but now time was of the essence. <P>At an intelligence post deep in the Pyre Forest of Poland, the code-breakers -under Gwido Langer, head of Poland's Cipher Bureau - handed over everythingthey knew about the Enigma machine to the British and French. Within six weeks,on 1 September 1939, the Nazis invaded Poland, and two days later, war wasdeclared on Germany by France and Britain. The British carried on where thePolish code-breakers had left off, and by April 1940, the first decoded Enigmamessages appeared. The interception of Germany's communications was to play amajor role in the outcome of the war. And the process of deciphering theminvolved the construction of Colossus, widely regarded as the first propercomputer.<P>In the battle for information, the Germans were also able to intercept Alliedcommunications. In one such instance, Rommel learned of Britain's intentions byintercepting the communications of an American military attach&eacute;.<P>More recently, the use of encryption has become integral to governments inpeacetime as well as in war. After the Cold War began in the late 1940s, theBritish set up GCHQ (Government Communications Headquarters) and the US set upthe NSA (National Security Agency) with the specific tasks of code-making and-breaking. The Soviet Union and its client states in Eastern Europe establishedvirtually identical counterparts.<P><P><FONT SIZE=1><A HREF="cyber050.html">NEXT PAGE</A></FONT><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
