<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Cybersecrecy: Cracking codes</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H2><A HREF="cyber000.html">Cybersecrecy</A></H2><H1>Cracking codes</H1>There are two basic ways of cracking encrypted codes. One is by brute force -simply going through every single combination of a code or key until eventuallythe right combination is found. The other is to look for faults in themathematical logic - the <I>algorithm</I> - at the heart of the cipher, whichcan show themselves in a lack of randomness in the encrypted message. Lookingfor patterns in 'ciphertext' is notoriously mind-boggling:<P><I>Obviously staring at something which is completely meaningless and doing thatfor hours and days and sometimes weeks on end can be extremely boring. You maywell go to sleep doing it. On the other hand, you have to be alert all thetime. It's a tremendous strain, a psychological and nervous strain. You getinto the attitude where you see letters and figures everywhere and try to reada meaning into them. Car numbers. Telephone numbers. If they begin with 66 andend with 44, you think that must have some significance. It's with you all thetime. You can't escape it. It almost sends you mad.</I><BR><DL><DD>Hans Fischer, German cryptanalyst during World War II, quoted in BruceNorman,<I> Secret Warfare: The battle of codes &amp; ciphers</I>, 1990.</DD></DL><P>For well-established modern algorithms, a 'brute force' search of all possiblekeys is usually the only method. This is because modern codes are enormouslypowerful. If the algorithm is sound, the power of a code is determined by thelength of its key (since this determines how many possible combinations thereare). Cracking these can be a lengthy and involved process. Recently a FrenchPhD student managed to break a message coded with a 40-bit key in eight days,but he had to use about 120 computers to do this. Commonly used encryptionsystems might have a key length of 128 bits (binary digits, or 0s and 1s) ormore. To attack such a code by brute force, a 128-bit key length would presenta decipherer with a search through approximately <P>	1,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000<P>(one million million million million million million) possible variations. Evenwith a very large supercomputer working 24 hours a day, this task would take agreat many years.<P>The need for encryption has increased enormously with the digital age, toprotect property rights and confidentiality in digital communications. This ishighlighted by just how vulnerable unencrypted data is to 'hacking' - that is,the unauthorised entry into a computer system. However, a major impediment tothe implementation of encryption on digital systems has been the management ofsecret keys. For centuries, a code could only work if the sender had a key to'lock' the message and the recipient had an identical key to 'unlock' it. Thereare two problems with this secret key system: how do you get the key from A toB (assuming that your communication channel is bugged), and how do you create asecure 'many to many' system of communication (like the ordinary phone system)if all these pairs of secret keys have to be swapped and still be keptsecret?<P><P><FONT SIZE=1><A HREF="cyber060.html">NEXT PAGE</A></FONT><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
