<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Cybersecrecy: Public and private keys</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H2><A HREF="cyber000.html">Cybersecrecy</A></H2><H2>Public and private keys</H2>The solution to these problems came from American cryptographer WhitfieldDiffie. His invention, in the mid-1970s, of what he called 'public keyencryption' revolutionised the science and literally brought encryption to themasses. His idea was that everyone should have two keys - one public key forencryption and one private key for decryption. If person A wants to send amessage to person B, A encrypts the message using B's public key. B thendecrypts the message using his private key. Since the public key<I> is</I>public, anyone can send an encrypted message to B. But since B's private key<I>is</I> private, only B can decrypt those messages.<P>The main threats to the safety of public key systems are developments incomputing power and in mathematical theory. Computing power presents less of aproblem. It is unlikely that the speed of microchips will increase at a greaterpace than the staggering improvements that have occurred in the 25 years sincethe microchip was invented. At this pace, present codes would be safe well intothe future (especially if longer key lengths are used). Even pessimisticestimates among cryptographers tend to assume that messages encrypted withcurrent technology will be safe for around 100 years.<P>However, developments in mathematics may pose a greater threat to public keyencryption. In particular, most modern codes rely on the intractablemathematical problem of 'factorisation'. This is the process of trying to findthe two prime factors that, multiplied together, would give you a third primenumber. For example, if you take 3337 - a prime number (i.e. a number that hasprecisely two divisors) - how would you find its two prime factors? (They are,in fact, 47 and 71.) There is, at present, no mathematical theory that allowsthis to be easily worked out. If a theory of factorisation were to emerge -which mathematicians believe is extremely unlikely - codes would be immediatelycrackable.<P>Alternatively, if a computer could be built that worked in a different way topresent-day machines - one that could operate in a 'massively parallel' way (inother words, instructions are not carried out one after the other in asequential way, and the computer's 'thought process' relies heavily on advancedartificial intelligence) - such a computer may be good at factoring large primenumbers and so render codes crackable. However, such a computer would only bepossible if computing could be reduced to quantum levels, operating withphotons (the smallest particles of light). At present, scientists are onlydreaming of quantum computers, and many believe that they will never bebuilt.<P>In any case, a recent development has made such discussion largely academic.British Telecom researcher Paul Townsend has demonstrated how something called'quantum key distribution' can work over, at present, 30 kilometres (18.6miles) of fibre-optic cable. The idea behind quantum key distribution is thatperson A sends a secret key to person B using photons of light. Ifeavesdroppers intercept the message, they are unable to take fragments of thesignals involved (because photons are physically indivisible), so they musttake the whole message. However, because of the way that photons behave,interceptors are prevented from properly reading the message or indeedreproducing it to send on to the intended recipient. Even if B gets the keywithout interception, he or she has to recheck it with the sender.<P>The upshot is that quantum key distribution is physically impossible tointercept without the interceptor being found out. This means that there is analternative to the public key, which guarantees the safety of secret keys.Scientists believe that quantum key distribution, combined with a method ofcryptography called the 'one-time-pad', will soon deliver cryptography's holygrail - absolutely physically safe communication.<P><P><FONT SIZE=1><A HREF="cyber070.html">NEXT PAGE</A></FONT><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
