<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Cybersecrecy: The new information age</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H2><A HREF="cyber000.html">Cybersecrecy</A></H2><H1>The new information age</H1>The spreading use of cryptography by all sorts of people and for all sorts ofpurposes is a cause of great concern to governments, which are quickly losingtheir ability to eavesdrop on communications.<P>Communications are an integral part of everyday life in the new informationage. Telephones, fax machines, computers and the Internet all play a major partin everyday business and personal interactions. However, many companies areunaware just how insecure their data is - for instance, AT&amp;T has estimatedthat 99 per cent of all faxes from the US to Japan are being intercepted.Encryption offers the way forward for business. With vast amounts ofinformation being sent over telephone and data networks, and with interceptorslurking round every corner, it has become vital for business traffic to beencrypted.<P>All sorts of records - medical, credit, military, criminal, driving, court,employment, property -  as well as many other forms of personal information arenow kept on computers. Many of these can be accessed remotely by techniciansand engineers who need to gain entry into the networks for perfectly legitimatereasons (such as mending systems that have broken down). There are numerousexamples of how, in the past, networks have been compromised in this way, withthe information obtained being abused.<P>One way to avoid this is by the use of passwords. However, many of thepasswords used to protect data on the Internet and other networks are quiteguessable, and even a semi-competent hacker can often get in by trying a fewwell-known combinations. For instance, many people use their surnames as their'log-in' names and then their Christian names as their passwords. In fact, itis generally the person who has devised the password who is the weakest link inany network.<P>Sending data over the Internet is like sending a postcard. The data has totravel through a series of networks ('post offices') to reach its finaldestination. At any point, the unencrypted data (i.e. data 'in the clear') canbe intercepted by a hacker, systems administrator, government official orcorporate spy.  It is easy to run a program that can intercept all data goingthrough a particular network - a technique known as 'packet sniffing'. However,by encrypting the data before sending it, the contents is protected from thecasual eavesdropper.<P><P><FONT SIZE=1><A HREF="cyber080.html">NEXT PAGE</A></FONT><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
