<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Cybersecrecy: Government surveillance</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H2><A HREF="cyber000.html">Cybersecrecy</A></H2><H2>Government surveillance</H2>Encryption is the solution to the problem of corporate thieves, unfriendlycountries, curious neighbours, prying bosses and overzealous or eventotalitarian governments. But the threat of encryption has become extremelyworrisome to governments, which insist that there is a legitimate need to taptelephone and data lines for the safety of the people. Civil libertarians, onthe other hand, say that the threat is exaggerated. However, in the wake of theOklahoma bombing, the FBI successfully relaunched their campaign for strongerwiretap laws. Here in Britain, with the threat from IRA bombings only recentlylessened, the right of GCHQ to wiretap has been only infrequently questioned.<P>Government agencies already  have extensive powers of surveillance. Both GCHQand the NSA are responsible for monitoring all international communicationstraffic going through their respective country's telephone lines and satellitelinks. Both intelligence agencies use 'key words' to search for anything thatmight be of interest. These are fed into computers, which then filterconversations and log any that have featured any of the key words. These can beanything from 'submarine' or 'explosive' to 'John Major', 'IRA' or even'miners' strike'. The chairman of the US Senate Intelligence Committee, SenatorFrank Church, has said of the technological eavesdropping capability of theNSA:<P><I>That capability at any time could be turned around on the American people andno American would have any privacy left, such is the capability to monitoreverything: telephone conversations, telegrams, it doesn't matter. There wouldbe no place to hide.</I><BR><DL><DD>Quoted in James Bamford, <I>The Puzzle Palace: Inside the National SecurityAgency</I>, 1993.</DL></DD><P>The FBI recently investigated instances of its employees accessing the USCriminal Database to run checks on friends, neighbours, partners and so on.Private detectives, organised crime and corporations have also been known toapproach young computer hackers, offering them money to break into variouscomputer systems to obtain specific information on designated targets. Theimplications are frightening.<P>In the past, GCHQ was manned by a staff that would manually monitor all trafficpassing through British telephone and cable lines. Today, sophisticatedsoftware and supercomputers are used instead to monitor satellite, cellular andlined communications. This is no easy task, as the amount of data has increasedspectacularly in recent years. But since the NSA and GCHQ are highly secretive,it is difficult to get any firm information about what they are doing, or theamount of information they are analysing. There is much speculation about theiractivities without much verification.<P>MI5's function since 1952 has been the 'defence of the realm from external andinternal dangers arising from attempts at espionage and sabotage, or fromactions of persons and organisations whether directed from within or withoutthe country, which may be judged to be subversive to the state'. This directiveoffers widespread protection to various intelligence gatherers. Trade unionssuch as the National Union of Miners (NUM) and groups such as Greenpeace andCND have all come under suspicion at one time or another. Critics say that MI5is able to choose its own surveillance priorities on the basis of its ownpolitical perceptions.<P>In Britain, it is not necessary to get individual warrants for telephonetapping. A blanket tap warrant can be put into effect that covers anorganisation, and such warrants have no expiration date. The Communist Partyheadquarters have been monitored since at least the 1920s, making it thefront-runner for the honour of being subject to Britain's longest runningtelephone tap.<B><P><P><FONT SIZE=1><A HREF="cyber090.html">NEXT PAGE</A></FONT><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
