<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Cybersecrecy: Threats against private encryption</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H2><A HREF="cyber000.html">Cybersecrecy</A></H2><H2>Threats against private encryption</H2>In recent years, with the end of the Cold War, there has been a shift from thegathering of political and military intelligence to the gathering of commercialintelligence, and both GCHQ and the NSA have followed the trend. They are nowresponsible for monitoring commercial electronic traffic in order to protectBritish and American investments from foreign companies. However, GCHQ, the NSAand other similar agencies around the world have been denied access to muchvaluable information because an increasing amount of data is encrypted. Thishas led to the passing of legislation with the aim of preventing or at leastmaking very difficult the use of encryption by private (rather thangovernmental) concerns.<P>In Russia, a law has recently come into force prohibiting cryptography forprivate citizens. In France, it is illegal to make an encryption programwithout giving its key to the government, which allows them to listen in atwill. In the US, the government has passed strong laws governing the export ofencryption, to hinder its spread into private hands. Encryption there fallsunder the International Trade in Arms Regulations (ITAR) - that is, it isconsidered by the government to belong in the same category as bombs, planes,tanks and guns. The NSA and the FBI continue to lobby for stricter laws tocontrol the use of cryptography in the US and its export internationally, aswell as for laws to allow the regulation of the Internet and telephonetapping.<P>The most important government initiative against encryption has also come fromthe US. The Clinton administration has launched the 'Clipper Chip' project,which promises to standardise encryption systems for telephone and computercommunications in the US and possibly internationally. The rub is that the FBI,or indeed foreign governments if the standard becomes international, get accessto a 'spare key' to the system, allowing them to eavesdrop without having todecrypt. The American government has argued that this will assist in keepingtabs on drug traffickers, pornographers and organised crime.<P>However, critics of Clipper ask us to recall the chequered history ofintelligence agencies, which have not restricted their activities to ordinarycriminals, but have (like MI5) targeted political opponents and perceivedsubversives. Such powers of surveillance that Clipper offers could, argue civillibertarians, pave the way for totalitarian control. Critics have also pointedout that industry and commerce could be adversely affected by Clipper. Foreigncountries would think twice about buying American computers if it were thoughtthat the FBI was effectively 'inside' them. And foreign companies with officesin the US would probably be reluctant to use an encryption system that washackable by agencies whose explicit tasks include economic surveillance. To capit all, it has been argued that the supposed targets - terrorists and the like- would never dream of using Clipper to encrypt their communications,especially given that there are so many powerful rogue systems freely availableover the Internet from various sources. <P><P><FONT SIZE=1><A HREF="cyber100.html">NEXT PAGE</A></FONT><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
