<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Cybersecrecy: The Cypherpunks strike back</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H2><A HREF="cyber000.html">Cybersecrecy</A></H2><H2>The Cypherpunks strike back</H2>Despite government efforts to restrict the use of encryption, actions by suchpublic pressure groups as the <A HREF="http://www.eff.org/">Electronic Frontier Foundation</A> and the AmericanCivil Liberties Union and private citizens such as <A HREF="mailto:prz@acm.org">Philip Zimmerman</A> (author ofan encryption computer program) have striven to keep encryption in the hands ofthe private sector. In addition, various court cases are challenging governmentregulation through cryptographic export rules, especially in the US.<P>The issue in one case going through the American court system at the moment is'whether textual material in digital form on a floppy disk can legally beclassified differently, for export control purposes, from the identical textualmaterial in printed form in a published book'. Under the US State Department'srulings, material on a floppy disk has been held to be a 'defense article',while the same material in a published book has been properly held not to bewithin the Department's export control jurisdiction. <P>The material in question comes from Bruce Schneier's book <I>AppliedCryptography</I>, of which over 20,000 copies have been sold since itspublication in 1984. Initially, the State Department decided that the book wasnot subject to US export controls, and the book <I>Applied Cryptography</I> wasgranted an export licence to be sold internationally and deemed to be, as abook, in the 'public domain', even though Chapter 5 contains text ofcryptographic source code. <P>However, when a second application was filed to release the book in digitalform on a floppy disk, it was referred to the Departments of Commerce andDefense and the NSA 'for their review'. They found that the disk was subject tothe licensing jurisdiction of the Department of State and the ITAR because 'thesubject disk contains source code listings for certain cryptographic algorithmsthat would not be exportable if they were incorporated into a product.' Thisdecision was made despite the fact that the disk and the book contain exactlythe same information. In addition, this information - binary copies of thesource code - is also available at various sites on the Internet to anyone whowants it, via ftp (file transfer protocol), and on the World Wide Web. In fact,some of the sites where you can obtain this information are located oncomputers outside the United States. <P>In the case of <I>Applied Cryptography</I>, the defendants of the pendinglawsuit clearly believe that<P><I>In these circumstances, trying to prohibit the dissemination of thecryptographic algorithms in digital format on the diskette, given thewidespread availability of that information in text and digital format,reflects the pursuit of an irrational goal that bears no relationship to thereal world.</I><BR><DL><DD>From the export control appeal on the <I>Applied Cryptography</I> diskette</DL></DD><P>Even though it is illegal to export strong cryptographic algorithms andencryption programs out of the US, it is practically impossible to enforcethese laws. Cryptographers themselves have tried to make a point of this. TimMay, one of the US-based 'Cypherpunks', believes that national borders areeffectively transparent to data flows:<P><I>I recently carried seven gigabytes of data to Monte Carlo. The only question Iever got was, upon my return to San Francisco, by a bored Customs agent whoasked me what my business in Monte Carlo was. When I told him it was to discusscryptography, his eyes glazed over and he waved me through.</I><P><A HREF="mailto:mab@research.att.com">Matt Blaze</A>, the American who 'cracked the Clipper Chip', also tried to make apoint of the hopelessness of trying to control the flow of data overinternational borders. His essay 'My Life as an International Arms Trafficker'reveals the inadequacies and basic lack of knowledge on the part of customsagents trying to regulate the export of encryption.<P>These examples show the difficulty in physically stopping the flow of dataacross international borders, but what of the Internet, where data can betransferred in seconds through an infrastructure that is basically anarchistic?<P>One individual who has fallen foul of the US export laws is the aforementionedPhilip Zimmerman, the author of the controversial encryption program PGP('Pretty Good Privacy'). Once he had made PGP available over the Internet,copies of it quickly went around the world. It is known that it is now beingused by all sorts of individuals and organisations, including AmnestyInternational, Burmese guerrillas, neo-Nazi groups, trade unionists, banks,Greenpeace, pornographers and even governments. As a consequence, Zimmermann iscurrently under investigation by the FBI.<P>Other programs - many developed by Cypherpunks who are dedicated to promotingthe benefits of encryption - extend the power of encryption. One such - called'Stego' and written by Romana Machado (aka 'Cypherella') - hides encryptedmessages within other 'messages', mainly photographs and digital music. In thisway, not only can governments not read your data, they don't even know thatyou're sending an encrypted message. <P>The principle behind Stego is that randomness can be easily hidden withinrandomness. An encrypted message is powerful when it <I>looks</I> random. Indigital files that contain photographic images or music, there is a lot ofrandomness. In addition, in any word (or collection of binary digits) only thefirst few 'bits' actually do anything. For instance, in the case of a picture,only the first few bits determine the colour of the pixel (the smallest elementwith controllable colour and brightness in a video display or computergraphics). What Stego does is rip out one of the least significant bits in eachpixel and replace it with a single bit from a PGP message. The result is apicture that looks like a picture but has a message embedded in it, in such away that no amount of computing power on Earth could get it out (unless it hadthe key). <P>There is also a simple encryption default that can easily protect personal datastored on computers. When the user logs in, his/her data remains unencrypted,but when the user logs out again, the data becomes re-encrypted, so that anyonegaining access to the network under false pretences would not be able to readits contents.<P><CENTER>* * *</CENTER><P>We have come a long way from Egyptian tombs and Caesar's cipher. As the worldbecomes more dependent on computers, data and data networks, the issue ofencryption will continue to be a hot topic among governmental control freaksand anarchistic cypherpunks - and most of the rest of us in between.<P><P><FONT SIZE=1><A HREF="cyber110.html">NEXT PAGE</A></FONT><P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
