<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>FIRST SEX</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#FF00FF"><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/_gifs/4wobcircle.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD><TD><IMG SRC="/_gifs/wobcircle1.gif" ALIGN=left BORDER=0></TD></TR></TABLE><P><P><DL><DD><DL><DD><H2><A HREF="fsintro.html">First Sex</A></H2><H1>Rape on trial</H1>Controversy continues to rage over the fate of rape cases within the judicial system. With a number of high profile 'date rape' acquittals and a call for anonymity for alleged offenders, it appears the pendulum of public sympathy has swung against female victims of rape.Yet the disturbing fact remains that although reports of rapes are increasing, the number of convictions stays alarmingly low. Campaigners argue that whilst the response to women reporting rape has improved markedly, the treatment of women in the court room leaves much to be desired.As a Police Federation spokesman put it, 'They (the lawyers) virtually rape the victim in court and get away with it.'Use these pages to access<A HREF="fsrap2.html" NAME=""> facts and figures</A> that reveal the shocking truth about rape;explore the <A HREF="fsrap3.html" NAME="">reasons</A> why the victims of rape feel they are the ones on trial in court;and discover where a woman who has been raped or sexually assaulted can get <A HREF="fsrap4.html" NAME="">help</A> .<P><IMG SRC="../../_gifs/_line1.gif" WIDTH=448 HEIGHT=8 BORDER=0"></DL></DD></DL></DD></BODY></HTML>
