<HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE>Collectors Lot</TITLE></HEAD><BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#B90308" VLINK="#34821C"><BASEFONT SIZE=3><P><A HREF="../collectors.html"><IMG SRC="../graphics/logo2.gif" BORDER=0></A><P><H2>Programme 1 (Monday 13 January 1997)</H2><P><B>Collector of memories</B><BR>Whatever turns you on, just start collecting now. John Hammond started collecting trade union badges in 1984, in memory of an age he realised was disappearing. Now, he has 3,500. He runs the Trade Union Badges Collectors' Society which has members worldwide. To know more, drop him a line to 28 The Drive, Worthing, Sussex, BN11 5LL. <P><B>Child's play</B><BR>Head for Devon to take in the Whimple Dolls House and Toy Museum, The Gallery, Whimple, nr Exeter, Devon, EX5 2SL. Tel: 01404 822607. There you can view the dolls house restored for Channel 4 'Collectors' Lot'. The museum is open all year but phone for details. Twenty dolls houses from 1870 to present day, plus tin-plate and mechanical, especially steam-driven, toys. Books: by the proprietor Brian Nickolls - <I>Making Dolls Houses and Making Character Dolls Houses</I> (David & Charles, 17.99 each). <P><B>Stitching up at No.11</B><BR>While Mr Clarke counts, Mrs Clarke quilts. She introduced us to 200 American quilts from the early 1900s in the American Museum at Claverton Manor, Bath, Avon, BA2 7BD. Tel: 01225 460503. Open: 22 March - 2 November, 1997. Look for the ones with hearts on them - girls made 12 for their hope chest and then a 13th for their wedding night, adorned with special motifs. <P><H2>Programme 2 (Tuesday 14 January 1997)</H2><P><B>More than Disney</B><BR>For the 'best introduction to US culture outside the USA', take a trip to American Museum at Claverton Manor, Bath, Avon, BA2 7BD. Tel: 01225 460503. Open: 22 March - 2 November, 1997. The American Museum there has 18 period rooms from the 1700s onwards. <P><B>Girl's best friend</B><BR>We're talking diamonds. Jethro Marles says an amateur never can tell - so unless you're a zircon-collector, always get an expert's help. Costume jewellery is easier to find and afford  - age doesn't always count! So if you like gaudy 1950s paste or 1930s Bakelite brooches, go for them. <BR>BOOKS: <I>Fabulous Costume Jewellery</I> by Viviene Becker (Schiffer) and <I>Jewellery</I> by Shirley Bury, in 2 volumes, Antique Collector's club, tel: 01394 385501, 47 to buy or look in the library. <P><B>Mini-wallpaper clues</B><BR>Dolls houses were redecorated over the years just like full-size houses. So, look (carefully) under layers for original features. Graft paper on to damaged areas from places that don't show (eg, behind furniture). Brian Nickolls of the Whimple Dolls House and Toy Museum Tel: 01404 822607 is the restorer on Collectors' Lot.<P><B>What did you do in the War, Tilley?</B><BR>Roger Price is turned on by oil lamps - he has 1,500, worth from 6 for a 1950s example up to 150 for a special 1930s specimen. (Look in your loft or garage; people often kept them 'just in case'.) There's even a Historic Lighting Club of Great Britain. For details, write to 23 Northcourt Rd, Abingdon, Oxon, OX14 1PW. <P><B>Lords and ladies of the dance</B><BR>You can't go and view prima-ballerina Bryony Brind's leotards that she wore for her first rehearsal with Nureyev, or her legwarmers or her good luck mouse, but you can go to The Theatre Museum, 1E Tavistock St, London WC2E 7PA. Tel: 0171 836 7891. Fax: 0171 836 5148, where they have Taglioni dresses, some stunning photograph and plenty more on ballet. There are many books on Nureyev: <I>Nureyev</I> by Howard Brown (Phaedon Press, 1993); <I>The Nureyev Image</I> by Alexander Bland (Studio Vista).<P><H2>Programme 3 (Wednesday 15 January 1997)</H2><P><B>Flossing is fun!</B><BR>Shock the children (and yourselves) into improved dental hygiene with a ghoulish visit to the British Dental Association Museum, 64 Wimpole St, London W1M 8AL. Tel: 0171 935 0875. <P><B>Want to add to your collection?</B><BR>Robin Lindsey adds to his Minibrix collection (the rubbery forerunner of Lego, and hard to find unperished), by advertising in magazines like Collectors' Gazette and Exchange and Mart. You could try other local free-advertising papers like regional Loot in London. If you've got any Minibrix, or Bayko (a rival plastic version), and you want to meet others, there's an informal group of collectors. You can contact them by writing to Robin at 87 Station Rd, Whittlesey Rd, Peterborough, PE7 1UE. <P><B>Cunning idea - collect what no one else wants</B> <BR>Antique dealer and lecturer Robin Butler has specialist knowledge and a small demonstration collection of fakes and forgeries. He charges Antiques Collectors' Clubs 200 an hour to impart some of his secrets. If interested, phone or fax him on 0117 973 3017. <P><B>The Zandra Rhodes Collection</B><BR>She collects what she cares about - fashion. Enough to open a Zandra Rhodes Museum of British Fashion and Textiles sometime in 1997 - watch the Press for details. She's a a living antique-maker herself; you can admire her kaftan along with a Hartnell Ballgown of the Queen Mother's at the Victoria and Albert Museum's 'Cutting Edge' exhibition of British Fashion 1947 - 1997 (6 March - 27 July, 1997), South Kensington, London SW7 2RL. <P><H2>Programme 4 (Thursday 16 January 1997)</H2><P><B>Worth a packet</B><BR>In the 1890s few people knew that Marmite would still be spreading thinly into the next century. Someone, somewhere must have suspected. They kept a jar or two, so famous gatherer up of advertising and packaging Robert Opie can show us the difference between an 1890 Marmite and a 1990s Marmite. At Gloucester Docks now, Robert Opie has the world's largest collection of household items. Visit his empire at The Museum of Advertising and Packaging, Gloucester Docks, Gloucester GL1 2EH. Tel: 01452 302309. <P><B>Eric's old China</B><BR>Some people collect to preserve memories. For Eric Matthews it's teapots - red clay ones fom China which take him back to the Hong Kong of his childhood. View 500 teapots, including Chinese ones, at Bramah Museum of Tea and Coffee, Clove Building, Maguire St, London. Tel: 0171 378 0222. <P>A thing to do with a wax candle Valerie Singleton would be proud of you: just rub one along the binding parts of your sticking drawers and your dresser or chest will be re-born. <P><B>Logan's boodle</B><BR>How do you spot the antiques of the future? Same as everyone did in the past - buy what you love. Zandra Rhodes rates the jewellery of Andrew Logan (famous for exclusive works of art, including enormous sculptures), as wearable, collectable and affordable, from 50 upwards. View his sculpture - head of Zandra - at the National Portrait Gallery, St Martin's Place, London WC2H OHE. 0171 306 0055. For all sales enquiries, please make an appointment by calling Andrew Logan or 'Betty' on 0171 407 6575, The Glasshouse, Melior Place, London SE1 3QP.  <P><HR WIDTH=80%></BODY></HTML>
