<html>

<head>
<title>LBBS: The Left On Line Bulletin Board System</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFA" link="#CC0000" vlink="#000055" alink="#FF3300">
<h2><img src="../../gifs/hlbbs.gif" alt="LBBS" align=bottom width=120 height=33><img src="../../gifs/chat.gif" alt=" Online Chat" align=bottom width=175 height=22></h2>
<hr>
<p align=center><a href="index.htm"><img src="../../gifs/hlbbs.gif" alt="LBBS | " align=bottom border=0 hspace=4 width=120 height=33></a><a href="../../index.htm"><img src="../../gifs/smznet.gif" alt="ZNet | " align=bottom border=0 hspace=4 width=73 height=37></a><a href="../../whatsnew.htm"><img src="../../gifs/whatsnew.gif" alt="WHAT'S NEW | " align=bottom border=0 hspace=5 width=56 height=54></a><a href="../../help.htm"><img src="../../gifs/help.gif" alt="HELP | " align=bottom border=0 hspace=4 width=56 height=54></a><a href="mailto:sysop@lbbs.org"><img src="../../gifs/feedback.gif" alt="Feedback" align=bottom border=0 hspace=4 width=90 height=46></a> </p>
<hr>
<blockquote>
<h3>LOL Forums</h3>
<p>LOL members read and write messages which accumulate in our Forums. Forum discussions are serious, committed, and 
without flaming and other not so pleasant but typical telecommunications attributes. A particularly nice thing about LOL 
forums is that LOL lets users do all reading, writing, and searching offline, at no cost.</p>
<p>Forums are the heart of LOL. Below we include brief descriptions of some forums currently active on LOL. </p>
<p>A few of the sample of Forum names below are web links which lead to examples of forum messages. As the discussions 
are in-depth and these messages are in some cases from the middle of long running discussions, users may have some 
difficulty following the entirety of their references. Still, they give a good feeling for what goes on in LOL forums.</p>
<dl>
<dt><b>Activism</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for users to present information and reports about current activism, and to discuss activist projects and ideas. </dd>
<dt><b>Anarchy</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing anarchist philosophy and aims.</dd>
<dt><a href="azc.htm"><b>AskZ&amp;C</b></a></dt>
<dd>This forum has two respondants, Michael Albert (the Z part of the title) and Noam Chomsky (the C part of the title). 
Albert's role is to keep things moving when Chomsky is off traveling and can't respond. Generally, however, Noam 
answers queries once a week, and discussions proceed from there. </dd>
<dt><b>Campus</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing the politics of academia and of academics, and the campus experience more generally.</dd>
<dt><b>CurEvnt</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing current events and happenings of all kinds. Like current events in the fourth grade, but with a 
little more political consciousness at play. </dd>
<dt><b>CurrentZ</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing articles in the current issue of Z. </dd>
<dt><b>Ecopol</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing ecological issues and green politics. </dd>
<dt><b>ForPol</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing foreign policy issues</dd>
<dt><b>Gender</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing gender related issues of all kinds. Sexism, sexual preference, sexual practices, strategy, 
articles, books, behavior, whatever... </dd>
<dt><b>GenPhil</b></dt>
<dd>This is a kind of catch-all forum for discussing philosophical matters. There is no need for a political link. Anything 
that has general intellectual interest can be aired here.</dd>
<dt><b>Internet</b></dt>
<dd>This is a forum where people can introduce one another to internet sites and methodologies, discuss internet politics, 
etc.</dd>
<dt><b>Hello</b></dt>
<dd>This is a forum where people can introduce themselves and ask introductory questions about the use of the system. It is 
also a place to ask how to get started, and to meet other people and strike up online friendships, etc.</dd>
<dt><b>Help</b></dt>
<dd>We have various online help forums where users can get help with DOS, Windows, or Mac programs respectively, for 
LOL or otherwise, from knowledgable users. </dd>
<dt><b>Humor</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for people to share jokes, humourous material, etc.</dd>
<dt><b>Labor</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing labor and union related issues. It is open for all to participate, but we hope that union activists 
and rank and file working people will bring up and develop views on labor issues. </dd>
<dt><a href="mark.htm"><b>Markets</b></a></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing the merits and debits of markets as institutions for economic allocation.</dd>
<dt><b>MediaPol</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing mainstream media and its politics. How it works, what is going on in it, what to do about it, 
etc.</dd>
<dt><a href="movie.htm"><b>Movies</b></a></dt>
<dd>A forum for reviewing/discussing movies.</dd>
<dt><b>Music</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for reviewing/discussing contemporary music.</dd>
<dt><a href="parecon.htm"><b>Parecon</b></a></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing Participatory Economics (the non-market, non centrally planned) post capitalist economy 
proposed by Michael Albert and Robin Hahnel, as well as economic vision in general, and related strategic and 
visionary issues having to do with work, consumption, production, allocation. Albert and Hahnel participate actively. </dd>
<dt><b>PolEcon</b></dt>
<dd>A forum to discuss the political economy of the U.S. and of modern economies more generally. How do they work, 
what is the structure, what are their dynamics, and so on.</dd>
<dt><a href="popcult.htm"><b>PopCult</b></a></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussion of pop culture in general, and pop culture events as they unfold.</dd>
<dt><b>ProgPubs</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing alternative media and its politics. How it works, what is going on in it, what to do about it, etc.</dd>
<dt><b>R-Wing</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing the resurgence of right wing politics in the U.S.--its logic, dynamics, and what to do about it.</dd>
<dt><a href="race.htm"><b>Race</b></a></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing any issues bearing on race, racism, cultural visions for diverse communities, etc.</dd>
<dt><b>Religion</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing religious ideas and issues, and religion and politics.</dd>
<dt><a href="schools.htm"><b>Schools</b></a></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussion of teaching policies, public schools, education, etc.</dd>
<dt><b>SexPol</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing sexual politics, sexuality, and sexual political program.</dd>
<dt><b>Strategy</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing how to win a better world, or anything less comprehensive.</dd>
<dt><b>Youth</b></dt>
<dd>A forum for discussing issues and ideas particularly relevant to or arising from the experiences of young people. </dd>
</dl>
<blockquote>
<hr>
<p><font size=2>A Project of The Institute for Social and Cultural Communications. <br>
Updated: 17 June 1996</font></p>
</blockquote>
</blockquote>
</body>

</html>
