<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">

<html>

<head>
<title>LBBS:About</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFA" link="#CC0000" vlink="#000055" alink="#FF3300">
<h1><img src="../gifs/about.gif" alt="About " align=absbottom hspace=2 width=92 height=22><a href="index.htm"><img src="../gifs/hlbbs.gif" alt="LBBS" align=bottom border=0 hspace=8 width=120 height=33></a></h1>
<hr>
<p><a><img src="../gifs/smlbbs.gif" alt="LBBS | " align=bottom hspace=4 width=144 height=65></a><a href="../index.htm"><img src="../gifs/smznet.gif" alt="ZNet | " align=bottom border=0 hspace=4 width=73 height=37></a><a href="../help.htm"><img src="../gifs/help.gif" alt="HELP | " align=bottom border=0 hspace=4 width=56 height=54></a><a href="mailto:sysop@lbbs.org"><img src="../gifs/feedback.gif" alt="Feedback" align=bottom border=0 hspace=4 width=90 height=46></a></p>
<hr>
<blockquote>
<h3>Purpose</h3>
<p>The Left Bulletin Board System, or Left On Line ( or LOL) aims to become a continuous town meeting of large sectors of 
the progressive community providing useful information, facilitating exchange of ideas, developing new political program 
and unity, facilitating on line activism, and acclimating progressive people to new technologies. </p>
<h3>Organizational Structure</h3>
<p>LOL is a system within the ShareWorld community of online systems. Shareworld creates such systems for diverse 
progressive organizations such as The Wilderness Society (WOL), The Nation Magazine (NOL), and Greenpeace (GOL), 
among many others. ShareWorld maintains and operates the technology, handles tech support, etc. for all these systems, 
including Left On Line. The online content of LOL itself, however, is directly maintained by its sysop, <a href="../zmag/albert.htm">Michael Albert</a>, 
operating in office space donated by <a href="../zmag/index.htm"><i>Z Magazine</i></a>. </p>
<p>LOL has a diverse range of co-sponsoring organizations. Each of these help provide content for the system such as forums, 
files, etc. Each promotes the system to their constituencies. Each receives revenues for members of LOL joining from their 
constituencies. </p>
<h3>Finances</h3>
<p>Revenues to LOL derive from fees paid by users (find out how to <a href="subscrib.htm">subscribe</a>): </p>
<ul>
<li>there are monthly fees for basic use including virtually all typical functions and full internet connectivity</li>
<li>there are special fees for particular options such as taking an online course.</li>
</ul>
<p>Incoming fees pay for maintaing the system and continually upgrading it, for getting content for the system, for maintaining 
internet connectivity sufficient to usage levels, for technical support, etc. Also, a portion of fees are dispersed to 
co-sponsors in tune with the number of system users coming from their constituencies.</p>
<p>Salaries and space are currently donated. </p>
<p>Projecting revenues and costs of LOL for 1996 is virtually impossible.There are too many unknowns regarding number of 
likely members, amount of use per member, etc. But, as the year proceeds and we gain more clarity about these variables, 
we will post budget projections. </p>
</blockquote>
<p>A Project of The Institute for Social and Cultural Communications. <br>
Updated: 18 June 1996</p>
</body>

</html>
</DOC>
<DOC>
