<head>
<title>LBBS: Internet Connectivity</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFA" link="#CC0000" vlink="#000055" alink="#FF3300">
<h1><img src="../gifs/hlbbs.gif" alt="LBBS" align=bottom width=120 height=33><img src="internet.gif" alt=" Internet Connectivity" align=absbottom hspace=10 width=118 height=22></h1>
<hr>
<p><a><img src="../gifs/smlbbs.gif" alt="LBBS | " align=bottom hspace=4 width=144 height=65></a><a href="../index.htm"><img src="../gifs/smznet.gif" alt="ZNet | " align=bottom border=0 hspace=4 width=73 height=37></a><a href="../help.htm"><img src="../gifs/help.gif" alt="HELP | " align=bottom border=0 hspace=4 width=56 height=54></a><a href="mailto:sysop@lbbs.org"><img src="../gifs/feedback.gif" alt="Feedback" align=bottom border=0 hspace=4 width=90 height=46></a></p>
<hr>
<blockquote>
<h3>LOL Internet Connectivity</h3>
<p>LOL offers telnet, ftp, adjunct SLIP connectivity for WWW browsing with Microsoft Explorer (which we provide to new 
users) and/or Netscape which is available from within the system, Internet EMail in and out of LBBS is supported, as are 
links to Internet Usenet Groups, etc. </p>
<p>In other words LOL can serve as a full internet provider, with seemless connectivity to the WWW, etc. if you do not have 
less expensive local access available.</p>
<p>You can connect to LOL by telnet (if you have another internet provider), by calling long distance, or by calling local 
numbers throughout the U.S. (Our local numbers come from UUNET a major national provider.)</p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<p>A Project of The Institute for Social and Cultural Communications. <br>
Updated: 17 June 1996</p>
