<head>
   <title>ZMI Project Uncensored</title>
   <meta name="GENERATOR" content="Mozilla/2.01Gold (Win32)">
</head>
<body>
<a href="index.htm"><img src="../gifs/titzmi.gif" alt="Z Media Institute" border=0 height=95 width=121></a>
<p><a href="../index.htm">Return to ZNet Home Page</a>  <a href="index.htm">Return
to ZMI Home Page</a>  <a href="zwww.htm">World Wide Web Help</a></p>

<p><a href="zmigrads.htm">View This Page in Spanish</a> 
<hr></p>

<h1><img src="../gifs/zmie.gif" alt="Z Media Institute" border=0 height=175 width=175>ZMI
Project Uncensored</h1>

<p>
<hr>We 1995 <a href="zmicon.htm">graduates</a> of the Z Media Institute
have decided to offer a resource for gaining unknown, important information
-- this page and the paths it leads to.</p>

<p>ZMI is an offshoot of Z Magazine, and we highly recommend the experience.
It will give you a necessary new perspective on the information received
through the mass media. If you are interested in the Institute and have
questions about it, you can communicate through <a href="zmicon.htm">email</a>
with many of the 1995 graduates and some of our instructors.</p>

<p>The mass news media systems in the United States continually fail to
provide citizens with essential information about contemporary life. They
report only a small percentage of the events shaping the world. They narrow
the range of discussion, opinion and perspectives.</p>

<p>This is not too surprising, given that only 20 corporations control
the major information systems of the country. Ben Bagdikian, in his book
<i>The Media Monopoly</i>, predicts that by the year 2000 that number will
shrink to only 5 or 6. These megacorporations invest in many other enterprises
and are only interested in news media companies as money makers. Turning
a profit replaces providing the information to citizens that they need
to make rational life decisions concerning many complex problems facing
society -- like creating real democracy. When GE, which makes nuclear reactors,
owns NBC, youre not going to see any rational discussion of the dangers
of nuclear waste on that network.</p>

<p>In short, the mass media present only the perspective of the financial
elite and their corporations, depriving people of many insightful and alternative
viewpoints on what is happening and what changes in society are possible.
As a result, many alternative sources of information have been created.
These include community newspapers, alternative magazines, publishing houses,
computer networks (such as <a href="http://www.igc.apc.org/">IGC</a>),
radio stations, and networks and cable access channels. Since these alternatives
are not corporate-controlled, they dont have substantial advertising budgets
and are not widely known. We refer you to some of the many <a href="zmibooks.htm">books</a>
containing scholarly analyses of the mass media.</p>

<p><a href="zmigrads.htm">Same page in Spanish.</a> </p>

</body>
</html>
</DOC>
