<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Chomsky Comment About Nature &amp; Human Nature</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><P>
<A HREF="index.htm"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/smlbbs.gif" ALT="LBBS | " ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">

</A>
<A HREF="../help.htm"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/help.gif" ALT="HELP | " ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">
</A>
<A HREF="mailto:sysop@lbbs.org"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/feedback.gif" ALT="Feedback" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">
  
</A>
</P>
<P><CITE>
The following is a message from Noam Chomsky written for the AskZ&amp;C Forum,
responding to comments from another user.</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1>
On Nature and Human Nature... </H1>
<P>To clarify matters, two factual points. I don't accept Dewey's definition of
freedom, or any other. I don't think fundamental notions can be defined, outside
of narrow areas of the sciences, not relevant here. In large part, we try to
learn about these matters, not define words on the basis of little
understanding. Second, the figures about sharing of DNA mean little. The
evolutionary distance between humans and other primates is about 15-20 million
years (the common ancestor now assumed to be 7-10 million years ago), about the
same as the distance between cows and giraffes. The roughly 99% sharing of DNA
has to be considered against the fact that about 97% of DNA has no known
function, and that virtually nothing is known about how small changes in the
rest lead to huge changes in physical structure and behavior. Some minuscule
change might have led to emergence of human language, for example. These
calculations mean nothing, in the absence of any theoretical understanding, a
fact familiar to biologists. They are also irrelevant. Cats shouldn't be
tortured gratuitously however remote they may be from humans.</P>
<P>Furthermore, even the narrowest anthropocentric view leads to pretty much
the same conclusions you reach, if I understand you, about ecological matters.
We want a world in which our grandchildren can survive, and which they can
enjoy, a fact that suffices to ground reasonable conclusions about these
matters. It's also the case that a lot of other organisms would be better off if
humans weren't around, but the &quot;biocentric perspectives&quot; that I'm
familiar with don't seem to me to address such questions -- not trivial ones --
in any reasonable way. I frankly don't see how changes in &quot;cosmology&quot;
help in dealing with the questions we should be facing.</P>
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT23-B33-260</DOCNO>
