</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "+//ISBN 82-7640-037::WWW//DTD HTML//EN//2.0" "html.dtd">
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Albert (Z of Z&amp;C;) on Human Nature</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY><P>
<A HREF="index.htm"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/smlbbs.gif" ALT="LBBS | " ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">

</A>
<A HREF="../help.htm"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/help.gif" ALT="HELP | " ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">
</A>
<A HREF="mailto:sysop@lbbs.org"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/feedback.gif" ALT="Feedback" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">
 
</A>
</P>
<HR>
<P><CITE>
The following is a message about human nature and activism written for the AskZ&amp;C
Forum by Michael Albert, responding to comments from another user.</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1>Albert on Human Nature and Social Activism</H1>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>TW said: Now Chomsky says that human beings are not
intrinsically &quot;good&quot; or &quot;evil&quot;, but rather that they have
the capacity for both. It is a matter of setting up environmental conditions
which will bring out the best instead of the worst, that will cause people to
co-operate for the benefit of all rather than force them to compete ruthlessly.
I wonder TW&gt;whether this is possible.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Well, so far we have nothing to disagree about... Surely it is true that
humans are capable of what we generally call good, and what we generally call
evil. This isn't an open question, we can see it every day, and throughout
history. And certainly, as this is true, if we have institutions that place
people in contexts fostering/rewarding behavior we call evil, we will see much
more of it than if we have people operating in environments that foster/reward
behavior we call good.</P>
<P>Well, maybe there is a little to disagree about, because we already know for
a fact that some environments are highly conducive to evil and push people into
such quite vigorously -- for example jails (on both sides of the cells) and,
more informatively, markets. And we also know that there are other ways of
arranging our behavior that is conducive to better behavior. As bad as nuclear
families are, for example, few of us arrange to have them operate internally on
the basis of a competitive market...which is because we understand, all of us,
that different institutional circumstances are more or less conducive to good or
bad outcomes.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>TW&gt; said: I am not saying that it is not, but I am
questioning it. Chomsky is always saying that ordinary people are basically
decent and caring, while the ruling elite are a bunch of gangsters and
murderers. I wonder how it can be that this has been the case always and
everywhere, throughout history. How can it be that decent people always wind up
being ruled by gangsters, by the worst among us?</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Well, this seems obvious to me, in two senses. First, Noam isn't saying that
those at the top are one kind of species and those at the bottom are another
kind -- he is saying that whoever is at the top will wind up behaving in one
type way, while whoever is at the bottom will wind up behaving in rather
different ways, with exceptions and gradations of course. You wouldn't say about
carrots that it is strange that those in the broiler are always softer than
those in the salad. You would say it was due to their history, in the broiler.
So why should it be strange in the case of people? Those who spend time at the
top become top-people, which is none too nice.</P>
<P>The second parallel sense is if you construct society so that to get ahead
requires that people stamp on other people, well then, that trait will begin to
appear and people with it will rise. (Prison guards are often sadistic on two
counts. Sadists apply for the job. And non-sadists who apply for the job and get
it become sadistic.) And those in whom it appears will get ahead. And it
shouldn't be surprising that being a bully generally wins over being a nice
person in a head up conflict -- should it?</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>TW&gt; said: So, when Chomsky and Shalom speak of &quot;setting
up&quot; a society which will bring out the best rather than the worst in
people, I have to ask, who is going to do this &quot;setting up&quot;?</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Who is going to set up a society in which more than a few percent can read,
in which people don't eat people, in which there is no longer slavery, etc. etc.
</P>
<P>There is progress. It is almost always due to those who suffer and see
through to the causes of the suffering trying to eliminate them.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>TW&gt; said: Is it going to be a &quot;moral elite&quot; of
good people - like Plato's philosopher kings, or the Communists fancied
themselves to be? Or is it going to be an effort of the people as a whole - a
flowering of true democracy? If the latter, how is this going to happen? This
would imply that you already have an enlightened general population - which is
not what we have now. And if we had that, the problem would already be solved -
we wouldn't have to &quot;set up&quot; anything. How do we get there from where
we are now?</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>That abolition occured didn't imply that they already had enlightened
individuals (opposed to slavery, say) long before abolition. Nor does it imply
that we have enlightened individuals now (opposed to wage slavery, say) to say
that we need to win this gain. Though, in fact, we do have many such
individuals...</P>
<P>The process of winning change is generally one of getting a grip on what is
sought (vision), developing some strategy/program, trying to implement it,
learning new things and improving the vision/strategy/program, trying again,
etc. etc. including consciousness raising, institution building, attacking
existing impediments, and so on.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>TW&gt; said: I would say, that it is not that our social
institutions (capitalism?) force us to be ruthless and exploitative, but, at the
most fundamental level, it is that other people are ruthless TW&gt;and
exploitative, and this puts pressure on everyone to be so. And please note
again, I am not saying that they are totally so, totally evil - not at all - but
that there is enough of it going around to create just the conditions that
Chomsky so brilliantly delineates. If this is indeed the case, what should be
our approach to improving the human condition?</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>If the reason why there is oppression in the world is the same as the reason
why people talk or don't fly--that is, it is wired in--there would be little we
could do about it (at least in the sense most organizers mean to do something
about it).</P>
<P>(There is a caveat here, I suppose, which changes nothing however, in the
sensible approach. That is, suppose evil traits and good ones are distributed
among the population rather like tallness and shortness, say. Then what? Well,
again, isn't it obvious that if one then constructs a society with institutions
that reward the evil traits, people with those will dominate, but if one
constructs a society with the social and desirable traits, and gives nothing for
the other, you will get much better results?)</P>
<P>If anti-social outcomes in history are a result of social choices and
historical outcomes, all of which are subject to alteration via our conscious
wills and actions, then there is obviously much that might be done.</P>
<P>Now there is no conclusive evidence one way or the other. There is a very
good argument, I think, for the latter perspective, but it can't be proved.
There is not much of an argument even, for the former perspective, but it can't
be conclusively disproved.</P>
<P>So where does one come down? Well, it seems to me one either believes or
hopes or assumes (or whatever) in favor of the optimistic (we can do something)
option and then gets on about doing what can potentially help. The alternative
is, with 100% confidence, catastrophe.</P>
<P>Now my own personal view --</P>
<P>I look at history and see even one admirable person--someone's aunt, che
guevara, doesn't matter--and say that is the hard thing to explain. That is:
that person's social attitudes and behavior runs contrary to the pressures of
society's dominant institutions. If it is part of human nature to be a thug, and
on top of that all the institutions are structured to promote and reward
thugishness, then any non-thugishness becomes a kind of miracle. Hard to
explain. Where did it come from, like a plant growing out of the middle of a
cement floor. Yet we see it all around. To me it means that social traits are
what is wired in, in fact, though these are subject to violation under pressure.
</P>
<P>I look at the same history and see however many vile thugs--the neighborhood
bully, Clinton, whatever--and say, hey that is easy to explain. Those folks are
behaving exactly as their upbringing and the institutions they inhabit tend to
reward and provoke them to...</P>
<P>It is the opposite of what you see, I guess. Where you see evidence that
people are the source of evil, I see evidence they are victims of it, the source
being historically embodied ignorance and patterns of action and choice =
institutions.</P>
<P>Noam's usual answer, in fact, is to tell the tale of the person walking down
the street in hot weather and seeing a child with an ice cream cone. Does the
person take the cone, swatting the child away (assuming no one is there to have
any say in the matter)? If yes, we say the person is pathological, and that says
it all about our view of human nature, I think. But, on the other hand, if we
are talking grown-ups operating in the market, well then, of course, if the
person doesn't take the goodies that are available in a clever market
transaction, whatever the cost to others or society, it is a sign of stupidity,
or weakness, etc. And that says it all about the impact of institutions, doesn't
it?</P></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
