<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Chomsky Comment About &quot;Theory&quot;</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY><P>
<A HREF="index.htm"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/smlbbs.gif" ALT="LBBS | " ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">

</A>
<A HREF="../help.htm"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/help.gif" ALT="HELP | " ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">
</A>
<A HREF="mailto:sysop@lbbs.org"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/feedback.gif" ALT="Feedback" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">
  
</A>
</P>
<P><CITE>
The following is a message from Noam Chomsky written for the AskZ&amp;C Forum,
responding to comments from another user.</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1>
On Theory and Social Change 1</H1>
<P>I think your comments are right on target. I use the word fairly strictly.
So, a theory is different from an opinion, or a description. Something merits
the term theory to the extent that there are principles that are not entirely
obvious (typically, in terms of structures that are not directly observable) in
terms of which something can be explained, by an argument that is at least 2 or
three steps long. By that standard, theories barely exist outside the natural
sciences and a few other areas. Even within the natural sciences, understanding
and explanation tail off very fast when we move beyond the simplest structures.
Mathematics and physics, as is familiar, deal with extremely simple structures.
Standard jokes in the field are that the only numbers are 1, 2, and infinity -
maybe 3, on a good day. Beyond the level of big molecules, understanding drops
off very fast, and I'm not sure you will find a physicist bold enough to try to
work out an explicit account of how hydrodynamic principles account for the flow
of water from a tap. It turns out, for largely mysterious reasons, that in a few
areas focusing laser-like attention on very simple problems has led to theories
of extraordinary depth and insight, but for most of the problems that concern
us, that simply isn't true.</P>
<P>You're absolutely right that the general practice in the intellectual world
is quite different. The term &quot;theory&quot; is bandied about in ways that I
personally find shocking. In the social sciences (not to speak of &quot;literary
theory,&quot; etc.), there is very little that merits the term, in my opinion.
That's not a criticism of the fields; rather, of those in them who like to
inflate their self-images by posturing about their &quot;theories,&quot; which
usually turn out on inspection to be either truisms or false or worse -- or, at
least, such is my experience -- maybe I'm missing something. For example, there
is something called &quot;international relations theory,&quot; which as far as
I can see consists mostly of elementary falsehoods and partly of vacuous truths,
and doesn't contain an argument that goes beyond 2 steps (if that). Why that
should be called &quot;theory,&quot; I have no idea (or rather, I have an idea,
but it isn't flattering, so I'll keep it to myself).</P>
<P>I don't think it's been shown that it is &quot;inherently impossible&quot;
to gain more than superficial insight and understanding in the social sciences,
though it isn't easy -- in any domain where one deals with complex systems, even
complex molecules. But it's not easy, and I think one should ask, with an open
but skeptical mind, just what has been shown or is being asserted by those who
inform us grandly about their &quot;theories&quot; or their &quot;philosophy.&quot;
Maybe there is something, but I'm waiting to hear it. If all we are doing is
describing things on the basis of pretty simple assumptions, I think we should
claim no more than that -- though it's true, that's not the way to prestige and
privilege.</P>
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
