<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Chomsky Comment About &quot;Theory&quot;...</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><P>
<A HREF="index.htm"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/smlbbs.gif" ALT="LBBS | " ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">

</A>
<A HREF="../help.htm"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/help.gif" ALT="HELP | " ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">
</A>
<A HREF="mailto:sysop@lbbs.org"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/feedback.gif" ALT="Feedback" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">
  
</A>
</P>
<P><CITE>
The following is a message from Noam Chomsky written for the AskZ&amp;C Forum,
responding to comments from another user.</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1>
On Theory and Social Change 2 (plus some other commentary)</H1>
<P>Sorry we seem to be failing to communicate very well. Let me try again, and
see if we can at least move towards clarifying what we are (perhaps) disagreeing
about. I'll go through the points raised in your March 22 communication in
order.</P>
<P>1. &quot;Theoretical discourse,&quot; &quot;drawing connections between
issues in philosophy and issues in politics,&quot; etc. You say my response
didn't come to grips with the &quot;issue&quot;; it was just &quot;sound-byte
culture,&quot; etc. Putting the rhetoric aside, I basically agree with your
point: my response to your charges didn't come to grips with the &quot;important
issues&quot; you say you perceive. The reason is that I don't see what you find
important. You expressed your opinion -- in a &quot;sound byte,&quot; to borrow
your term -- and asked for a response. But there is no way to respond, apart
from expressing my own opinion, which happens not to agree with yours about the
value of the work to which you allude. Since you did not indicate in any way
what you found important, I can't comment any further.</P>
<P>Suppose Jones asks you to comment on his belief that the answers to our
problems lie in the Church Fathers, but doesn't give a hint as to why he
believes this. Your only response could be what you call a &quot;sound-byte.&quot;
Jones is asking for something impossible in principle, and if he proceeds (as
you do) to express annoyance when it isn't produced, one hardly knows what to
say.</P>
<P>As I mentioned, I've found some work in the domains to which you refer
intellectually interesting, though without any bearing that I can see on the
issues that concern me (e.g., Rawls). And I've come across plenty of the
inflated and self-important posturing that is so characteristic of intellectual
life, and found that it dissolves into truism or falsity when I take a close
look. Perhaps I've missed what's really important. That could surely be the
case. If you can direct me to what's really important, I'll be happy to educate
myself. But until you indicate what it is that you find so important, I can't
respond to your charges against me and others for failing to deal with it --
except at same level of vagueness as your expression of your opinion. Can't we
at least agree on that?</P>
<P>2. Underestimating Gingrich, Gramm, etc., -- or your example: Hitler.</P>
<P>Evidently I didn't make myself clear, maybe my fault, so let me try again.
Take your example: Hitler. Surely Hitler had to be taken seriously, but not by
refuting his Nuremberg addresses, which were just manic ravings. Similarly,
Gingrich et al. have to be taken seriously, even though -- as I said and repeat,
it is &quot;so flaky it's hard not to laugh.&quot; Again, isn't the point
obvious?</P>
<P>3. On speech and acts. You misunderstand what you call the &quot;libertarian&quot;
position. Take me. I adopt the position that you denounce (without argument) as
&quot;absurd&quot;: that the right of the Klan to speak should be defended. I
even basically agree with the 1969 Supreme Court decision on freedom of speech,
in what happened to be a Klan case. Similarly, to take a vastly more important
case that I mentioned but that you ignore, I would (if the issue arose) defend
the right of advocates of what passes for &quot;free market&quot; doctrine to
speak, though they are really causing extraordinary human misery, immeasurably
beyond the Klan, so that my position on this matter must be far more &quot;absurd&quot;
by your standards. But while taking this &quot;absurd&quot; position, I
nevertheless join everyone else in recognizing that speech is an action. That's
not the issue. If, as you assert, Fish believes he is saying something important
by telling us that actions are actions, then he's mistaken. I'd suggest that you
rethink the matter. I'm sure you have a point, but it can't be this.</P>
<P>Let me restate the same point in different terms. Take Fish. What I've read
of his views on these matters seems to me not only very poorly argued but also
pernicious. Nevertheless, I defend his right to speak this pernicious nonsense
-- to carry out these harmful acts, as I believe them to be. Furthermore, I
would passionately oppose social arrangements that provided me, or anyone, with
the authority to silence him. Similarly in your case. You haven't really stated
your views, though you have stated that anyone who disagrees with them is &quot;absurd.&quot;
But as far as I can make out, you seem to believe that some principles (that you
won't formulate) and some authority (but you won't tell us what) should have the
right to determine who is allowed to say what. I regard that general point of
view as extremely dangerous; I can't comment on specifics, because you won't
tell us what they are. But despite my feeling about the views you express in a
general and inexplicit way while denouncing those who disagree with them as &quot;absurd,&quot;
nevertheless I would strenuously oppose any attempt to silence you, and would
forcefully reject social arrangements that gave me, or anyone, the authority to
do so. All of this remains true while I of course agree with the truism that
acts of speech are acts.</P>
<P>3. Fish and legal theory. You stated that you found his work on legal theory
to be very important for us, though without giving any reasons: you expressed
your opinion, criticizing my refusal to join you in applauding this work, using
it, etc. Since again you give no indication of what you find important, I can do
no more in response to your admonition than to express my own opinion, as I did.
My opinion is that I do not find his contributions to legal theory of any
interest. Your response to this is: &quot;I'm astonished that legal theory has
nothing to do with the discussion.&quot; That's a pretty remarkable conclusion.
</P>
<P>As for &quot;legal theory,&quot; one may have this or that judgment, but you
had raised a completely different matter: the alleged importance of particular
contributions to it. You say that they are important, without giving reasons,
and criticize others for refusing to believe as you do. In response, I can only
say that I don't see what you find important. Nothing in this response suggests
that &quot;legal theory has nothing to do with the discussion.&quot;</P>
<P>4. Free trade. You state that by reporting the fact that the Republicans
advocate free trade while demanding protection and subsidy for the rich, I seem
&quot;on the face of it to advocate `really' free trade by default.&quot; That
surely doesn't follow, just as the opposite conclusion doesn't: that I'm
advocating that everyone follow their protectionist practices. The right
attitude towards free trade simply isn't addressed when someone points out that
the historic pattern of representatives of wealth and power (not just the
Republicans) is advocacy of market discipline for the poor and ample protection
and subsidy for the rich.</P>
<P>You say my &quot;empirical criticism is open to challenge on the basis that
unless [I] believe trade and markets to be inherently evil... then either some
restrictions...are needed or else it's going to be `free' and the devil take the
hindmost.&quot; I don't think the reasoning goes through. I didn't suggest that &quot;trade
and markets&quot; to be &quot;inherently evil&quot; -- or &quot;inherently good.&quot;
But I do think it is wrong to demand public subsidy and protection for the rich
while imposing market discipline on the defenseless. The rest of your comment
simply doesn't relate to this position. Furthermore, by its very logic it
couldn't be a &quot;challenge&quot; to an &quot;empirical criticism&quot; of the
double-edged market doctrine under discussion.</P>
<P>5. On free speech, you say &quot;the ball is in my court,&quot; and I must
either &quot;reject markets entire&quot; or &quot;accept markets with
restrictions&quot; as a &quot;Fabian socialist.&quot; I don't reject markets
entire, and I don't accept Fabian socialism. I've written elsewhere about what I
do think, and won't repeat it here, of course. But the alternatives you pose
don't even cover a fraction of the possibilities. As to the ball being in my
court, it's you, not I, who advocate (unspecified) restrictions on speech while
refusing to answer the simple questions posed about who is going to do the
restricting, by what authority, with what criteria, etc. The ball's entirely in
your court on this one.</P>
<P>6. On automatic parsers. You gave an example from particular efforts to
automate parsing for practical purposes -- or as you now put it, from &quot;Chomsky's
old work in computer programming&quot; -- to show how &quot;scientific speech is
constrained by class boundaries,...&quot; I responded by saying that automatic
parsers in the sense of your discussion have virtually nothing to do with
science, so whatever the merits of your position about science and class, the
example couldn't support it. You took this as an attempt to make you &quot;feel
small,&quot; the kind of &quot;elitism which drives middle-class people&quot; to
Limbaugh. I'm sorry you took it that way. It wasn't intended, and it's hard for
me to follow your reasoning, once again. How can I be trying to make you &quot;feel
small&quot; by saying that my &quot;old work in computer programming&quot;
doesn't have anything to do with science? It seems that if that's making anyone
feel small, it must be me, not you, since you feel I'm demeaning my work. That's
an odd way to drive middle class people into Limbaugh's arms.</P>
<P>For the record, I never did any work related in any way to computer
programming or automatic parsing, and the particular kind of project you were
talking about happens to be, as I said, &quot;a form of engineering&quot; --
good or bad, but not science. As I mentioned, there is other work in automatic
parsing (in which I also have no involvement, and never did) that is &quot;a
form of science&quot; -- again, either good or bad; that's a separate matter.
These are descriptions, not attempts to make you, or me, feel small or large. If
you think the descriptions are wrong, and can tell me why, I'll be glad to
consider your reasons; I'm as open-minded here as about the &quot;theoretical
work&quot; to which you allude and in which you find value that you don't
explain and that I don't see. It could well be that all of this is, as you seem
to feel, my blindness; but you aren't telling me how to relieve it.</P>
<P>I didn't follow the rest, I'm afraid.</P>
<P>7. On theory and description. You say it doesn't &quot;parse&quot; to state
that some topics are too hard for nontrivial theory, though there is plenty of
good and useful description: Newcomb's flower guide, for example, or Webster's
dictionary, or in fact most of human endeavor outside of a very few areas. I'm
afraid you'll have to elaborate. The comment you say doesn't &quot;parse&quot;
seems to me close to truism. In most areas, and almost all that involve matters
of any complexity, we have very little theory though often quite useful and
extensive descriptions. The fact that one can lie with statistics and do bad
polling has no bearing on the matter.</P>
<P>You then say that you &quot;question whether it is valueless to do theory in
the social sciences.&quot; No one would disagree. It would be extremely valuable
&quot;to do theory in the social sciences&quot; -- if anyone knew how. If you
think there is some valuable theory -- that is, some plausible principles that
go beyond the obvious and that yield consequences over some interesting range by
arguments that are valid and nontrivial -- I'll be glad, indeed delighted, to
learn about them. But what I find when I look at the &quot;theories&quot; that
intellectuals present with great self-acclaim is something quite different,
perhaps my failing -- but you aren't telling me why.</P>
<P>8. I was interested to hear about your experiences in Princeton and
elsewhere, but frankly didn't see the bearing on the issues we are discussing.
</P>
<P>9. Turning to my &quot;transgressions,&quot; you cite one: that my &quot;theoretical
work&quot; is &quot;fairly sealed off&quot; from my &quot;political work.&quot;
The nature of your charge isn't clear to me. Is my &quot;transgression&quot;
that the &quot;sealing off&quot; is a fact? That I believe it is a fact? That I
insist on it? If the first, I'm afraid I can't change facts. If the second, I'd
be delighted to be convinced that I'm wrong and that there really are
connections that I don't see and that no one has been able to find. If the
third, then that's just false. If anyone could come up with nontrivial theories
that had some important bearing on issues of human concern, I'd be the first to
leap on the bandwagon, whether they are my theories or those of others.</P>
<P>10. On the Republicans being &quot;the party of change,&quot; I gave
specific arguments that seemed to show the contrary. You refer to them, but
leave them unanswered, choosing instead to refer to Marx and 1848. I don't see
the relevance.</P>
<P>11. On my remark that &quot;I didn't quite follow the rest, I'm afraid,&quot;
you respond: &quot;Aw come on, Professor Chomsky, you are a smart man&quot; so
don't pull &quot;this trope.&quot; I'm afraid I still don't follow, despite your
admonition, and don't even understand what the &quot;trope&quot; was.</P>
<P>You've been launching all sorts of criticisms and charges, and making lots
of claims and assertions. Maybe they are justified, maybe not, but unless you
give something in the way of argument, it's impossible to tell. I'm afraid I
still don't see the basis for them. I'd be glad to find out why you think what
you do, but more of the same doesn't help; at least, doesn't help me.</P>
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
