<P><CITE>
The following is a message posted to the AskZ&amp;C Forum, by a user querying
Chomsky to initiate a new thread of discussion.</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1> A query to Chomsky re his attitude to Post Modernism, etc.</H1>
<P>Regarding the discussion of theory, I'd like to weigh in on the side of
developing it further. I, too, am interested in Noam Chomsky's views on this
matter. I have occasionally read rather brief, disparaging remarks from him on &quot;social
science,&quot; or the &quot;Paris school&quot; or the &quot;postmodernist cults.&quot;
And I am somewhat confused about several things:  1) Who is he talking about? 2)
What is it about what they say that he dislikes (beyond the pretension to being
like the physical scientists)?  3) Why is he so curtly dismissive?</P>
<P>This last point is particularly puzzling. He writes lengthy articles and
books exposing the posturing and obfuscation of the New York Times, so why not
give these other guys the same treatment? It seems to me that a lot of leftists
are impressed by some of the folks he (presumably) dismisses, so it could be a
great service to show them where they are going wrong.</P>
<P>Let's start with a Parisian writer who has impressed a lot of leftists and
who may fit in as a postmodernist (whatever that is), Michel Foucault. I find
his Discipline and Punish an absorbing and sobering study of the rise of
disciplinary mechanisms in western culture. It usefully depicts, in my view, a
great change from harsh mechanisms of repression to more subtle mechanisms by
which people come to do voluntarily, even enthusiastically, what power would
have them do. It explores carefully the minute operations of surveillance and
control.  It argues that the very discourses in which we engage become the
mechanisms by which we are controlled. All of these are important insights and
theoretical constructs which I think people must become aware of if they are to
be successful in their search for means to end oppressions. Foucault gives us a
clear view of where we start from, and he does it with an impact I haven't found
elsewhere. Does Noam think he is wrong, or useless, or posturing? Or is he
talking about someone else when he dismisses a broad group of unidentified
writers?</P>
</BODY></HTML>
