<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Albert (Z of Z&amp;C;) on Non-Violence</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY><P>
<A HREF="index.htm"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/smlbbs.gif" ALT="LBBS | " ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">

</A>
<A HREF="../help.htm"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/help.gif" ALT="HELP | " ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">
</A>
<A HREF="mailto:sysop@lbbs.org"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/feedback.gif" ALT="Feedback" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">
 
</A>
</P>
<HR>
<H1>Albert replies to query about non-violence and social change </H1>
<P>I am not non-violent. I believe that in the U.S. if you turn the other
cheek, the powers that be will just smack that one too. And if you stretch out
on the railroad tracks, they will run you over ----- unless, in both instances,
you have created a social movement which not only challenges some policy or
seeks some change, but also protects itself from crushing repression.</P>
<P>How?</P>
<P>By making the price of the act of repressing you, to elites, greater than
what they gain from it.</P>
<P>We want to change the world. Others will try to preserve it. They are not
bound by moral, ethical, or (essentially) technical limits in the degree of
lies, violence, or other steps they will take to attain their ends. They are
bound only by social and political constraints. And we have to impose those.
</P>
<P>If jailing or even killing the organizer will defeat the movement with low
or no likelihood of instead provoking a still larger movement, then that is the
tactic that the authorities will employ. But if these choices will instead
provoke a larger movement response, in part because of the groundwork organizing
the movement has undertaken, then those violent repressive tactics won't be
implemented.</P>
<P>And what is justified on our side of the equation? Well again, there are few
if any limits imposed by morality, I think, assuming we are talking about
actions that would effectively thwart oppression. But there are many actions
that we ought to rule out, not on moral grounds, but because they would not
help. These are the grounds, not a commitment to non-violence, that cause me to
rule out a host of different kinds of actions one might suggest. They would
either alienate people we need to communicate with, or they would corrupt our
own institutions and mindsets, or they would bring down force we cannot handle.
</P>
<P>How, indeed, can the issue possibly be &quot;violence or non-violence&quot;?
</P>
<P>The daily order of life in the U.S. and throughout the world is almost
limitless violence. The issue has to be smart tactics, smart program, or dumb
tactics, dumb program. The violence is there, and will be there, in degrees that
dwarfs anything we can even dream of adding to the mix, until we win.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>ML&gt; says: Further, Prof. Zinn seems to point out in numerous
places in his history that many worker's movements have been co-opted by the
political system, that when they tried to work peacefully within the system,
they lost energy and fizzled out.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Trying to transform a social system is not like trying to run a vcr machine.
You and Zinn are right, I think. The fact is that the state of mind and
emotional strength and commitment of those working for change is a very big part
of the success or failure chances of activism. And it is, in turn, very much
connected to the kinds of sentiments that are expressed and the kinds of
feelings that are cultivated and allowed and employed, etc. But the exact
translation is hard to know.</P>
<P>Yes, contouring one's posture to fit the system, so one will be respected,
taken seriously, etc. etc., is almost always a direct route to irrelevance
(though often well paid and respected irrelevance). On the other hand, irate,
outraged mayhem rarely sustains activism for long. &quot;Packaging&quot; the
kind of attitude and focus that characterizes a grassroots organizer who sticks
to it year in and year out -- well, it may be impossible, but emulating such a
person seems to me to be a very worthy pursuit.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>ML&gt; says: So, while we can easily observe, correctly, that
they have more power, isn't this exactly what we're organizing to change? And
will we ever really create change from within any currently operating
political/economic system?</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>No. That is, if our movements accept the contours of the system as the
bounds limiting their values and thought, then you are right that they will
never transform the system. But a movement guided by values other than those of
capital, patriarchy, racism, etc. etc. still most operate in the here and now...
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>ML&gt; says: Everybody wants to put a band-aid on it hoping
that it will heal up somehow beneath the bandage where we don't have to see it.
Does the Left as a movement not have the same attitude? We all can see that
things are not improving for the vast majority of beings on this planet, yet we
seem to be waiting for something or someone to make it right. I share many of
the sentiments and frustrations you raise...</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>And continues: Your reply is well considered and I presume anyone who has a
passion about justice for the masses is taking every opportunity to raise the
consciousness of others in whatever way they can. Yet there still is, or will
be, the need for action, for force, isn't there? Or do you believe there will be
some kind of &quot;hundreth monkey&quot; phenomenon where, when a critical mass
is reached, we will all be lifted to the next plane of understanding and
capitalism will simply fade from our consciousness?</P>
<P>And adds: I should re-phrase my question to read: Is there really a peaceful
way to attain our ends, and how do you feel At This Moment about our progress,
or lack of it?</P>
<P>I think of it this way, to use a catch phrase: consciousness raising,
consolidation, contestation, construction.</P>
<P>(1) We have to raise consciousness of an alternative and of means for
fighting to win it.</P>
<P>(2) We have to consolidate our own organizations, movements, means of
program development and outreach, etc. etc.</P>
<P>(3) We have to contest the powers that seek to maintain the status quo, both
institutional and, regretably, personal, for a series of changes, each making
the world a somewhat more livable place, and each creating a new stage a little
more in our favor for new struggles, until we begin to challenge basic
institutions and power structures.</P>
<P>(4) We have to construct the alternative institutions and mindsets and
behavior patterns of a new society.</P>
<P>Each phase of our effort persists during the whole revolutionary process,
and each phase both promotes and is in some sense a prerequisite for the others,
but the emphasis shifts as time proceeds, from consciousness raising, to
consolidation, to contestation, to construction.</P>
<P>We are back at (1) as the point of emphasis...though a significant amount of
attention to 2, 3, and 4 is essential not only so the process will proceed,
rather than bog down and reverse, but so that we will do our consciousness
raising well.</P>
<P>The questions for strategy seem to me to be, therefore, how do we raise
consciousness in a broad sweep of the population, how do we begin to consolidate
the existence of opposition consciousness in movements and organizations, how do
we effectively fight for non-reformist reforms, how do we begin to prefigure the
future we seek and inform all our actions with awareness of our goals.</P> 
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
