</A>
</P> 
<H1>Albert on Market Abolitionist or Not?</H1>
<P>My point wasn't that we can't and shouldn't try to conceive of reforms that
would alleviate pain and move us toward a better economy, reforms that we can
win now, while we still--quite obviously, have markets. My point was that just
as one might try to alleviate the pain of racism via a reform or the pain of
sexism via a reform, where the reforms are desirable and lead in a good
direction, so too for markets. But also, just as one would not say racism is ok,
or sexism is ok, or these are good, so long as we ameliorate their most obvious
faults, and just as one would not argue for a reform on the grounds that one
could couch it in terms of furthering the essence of racism or sexism, the same
should be true of our approach to markets. If they are abohorrent and if their
underlying logic is intrinsically counter to human fulfillment and development,
while we should recognize that they are not going to disappear soon and that we
have to operate in their context and figure ways to ameliorate current ills on
the road to a better economy, we should not make the mistake of legitimating
them, praising them, or even trying to argue for our aims in terms of &quot;market&quot;
values.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>DU&gt; says: Markets and slavery cannot simply be assumed to be
equally morally repugnant, especially when the whole purpose of the forum is to
discuss the moral worth of markets, in theory at least, with or without reform.
Slavery we will universally agree is awful--people with no rights, people as
property. If markets are the same, why even have the discussion. The analogy is
forced.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Indeed, you are quite right. It cannot be simply assumed. Which is why, for
example, I have spent endless time thinking about and analysing the situation,
as have others, and trying to formulate coherent arguments and evidence.</P>
<P>But I think the analogy, while not perfect, is not forced. You don't, and so
maybe that's the issue we need to pursue. Let's not assume they are horrible, or
that they are great, or that they are anything at all, let's discuss what they
in fact are.</P>
<P>The fact that people now universally say they oppose slavery is part of my
point, not a counter to it. This was not always so. On the contrary once slavery
was thought natural, inevitable, and in everyone's interests (including the
slaves). Right now, yes, almost everyone (who has gone though significant
schooling, in any event) thinks markets are great (not withstanding the need for
a little patching here and there). Down the road, I think, there will come a
time when people will look at those views the way we now look at earlier
generations views of slavery...</P>
<P>Anyhow, I hope we can discuss the actual issues -- do markets or don't they
have intrinsic properties which are grossly antithetical to the human welfare
and development of economic actors...</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>DU&gt; says: It also seems to me that with the Newt's Contract
on America aimed at eliminating any free market in ideas, via eliminating public
media, support for the arts, &quot;regulations&quot; requiring any sense of
fairness, and avoidance of campaign finance reform (institutionalized
corruption--i.e. control by the rich in our plutocracy), we need to talk more of
free markets at least in that realm.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>We disagree strongly here. Yes, he is a gargantuan hypocrite (or rather,
machiavellain manipulator) and pointing this out can help to reveal his true
motives. But to argue that what we want is free markets or free competition in
some realm is to (a) be confused, and (b) legitimate a rhetoric and a value
system contrary to what we really seek. Why confused, well take your above
paragraph. I'm sorry, but Newt is far more correct than you. When he says slash
PBS in favor of privatization he is implementing free market rhetoric. When you
say maintain government subsidy of PBS, or whatever, in pursuit of more arts
(and claim this is also implementation of free markets in ideas) you are
twisting words to fit your own meanings.</P>
<P>You could urge trust busting, monopoly breaking, etc. as desirable reforms
in a market context, though it may be that serious regulation and more power to
workers in such units would be a better path of reform to pursue. But when Newt
talks about free markets he doesn't in fact mean perfectly competitive markets
in which no actor has more power than any other, he means economic markets, plus
private ownership, operating free of government intervention. And, yes, he only
invokes it when it suits his real aims, not universally (and that is the
hypocrisy part we can point out).</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>DU&gt; says: The spiraling control by the right is scary.
Goebbels may soon seem rather unsophisticated by comparison.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Indeed, there is a serious problem in the land... And, Goebbels is already
quite unsophisticated by comparison. But the comparison is to Clinton and the
mainstream establishment, not Newt. Newt, if anything, is beginning to remove
much of the sophisticated apparatus which is why he scares many with wealth and
power as well as you and I.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>DU&gt; says: This bulletin board itself is a positive step. The
right might claim that by leaving the media in private oligopolistic hands they
are DU&gt;promoting free markets. The need for market reform here at least is
key to achieving anything else we might theoretically debate to achieve the
goals of greater justice, the pursuit of happiness, and the alleviation of
suffering.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Well, the Internet was created by the Govt, and sustained by it. This is not
a market history, so to speak...</P>
<P>Free markets, again, don't mean for Newt markets plus a state to ensure that
no market actor gets inordinately powerful. It means markets without a state to
interfere in the machinations of those who are most powerful. Actually, this is
the liberal agenda as well. The difference is that the liberals realize that
capital in the large needs state intervention to regulate the system, curtail
actions detrimental to broader interests, etc. etc.</P>
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
