<P><CITE>
The following is a message about markets written for the Markets Forum by
Michael Albert, responding to comments from another user (BM&gt;) criticizing
the market abolitionist stance developed in earlier posts.</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1>Markets and Democracy</H1> 
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>BM&gt;You showed how a market economy would pervert democracy.
This raises, for me, the most basic of questions. If the market system you spoke
of not only allowed but encouraged people to indulge themselves in greed and
competition, could the fault be as much in the people as in the system?</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Suppose I made a beehive that fostered bees making honey. So, yes, the
structure I imposed on them pushed honey-making, but this was also a natural
outgrowth of their own natures.</P>
<P>Is this a possibility regarding markets? Yes, if I demonstrate that markets
not only promote but literally compel competitive, anti-social, egoistic
behavior -- might it not be the case that this is also what comes naturally to
people? Sure. But it doesn't seem to me that it is, at all.</P>
<P>It seems to me, on the contrary, that it takes a lot of pressure and
prodding and constraining to get humans to act as badly as we all do. And even
with it all, most of the time, we don't act that way.</P>
<P>In any event markets do things like mispricing goods, etc., which would be
bad even if humans were hyenas (you know what I mean).</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>BM&gt;Would certain people find a way to manipulate ANY system,
no matter how egalitarian? Are there safeguards which could make even a market
system more fair? Or, are these &quot;darker&quot; qualities just less likely to
proliferate in a system which encourages qualitatively different objectives?
</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>I believe parecon is close to immune to this type manipulation. It is nearly
impossible, I think, short of outright robbery, etc., to aggrandize oneself by
behaving in anti-social ways. And even if you are willing to overtly steal, it
is hard to get much out of it, without it being evident, etc. Will there still
berobbery? I don't know. I suppose so. But the point is the defining features of
a parecon, and the defining ubiquitous behavior and attitudes of people in it,
will, I think, be in close conformity, emphasizing such values as equity,
solidarity, diversity, self management, etc.</P>
<P>Sure, there are lots of ways to improve outcomes in a market economy -- in
essence any reform that empowers working people and reduces the relative power
of capital (or coordinators, for that matter) will tend to improve matters, as
will any reform that ameliorates ills produced, such as a minimum wage or
progressive tax, etc., or laws constraining the options capitalists have, taxes
to moderate the pricing errors, and so on.</P>   
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
