<HR>
<P><CITE>
The following is a message about markets written for the Markets Forum by
Michael Albert, responding to comments from another user (BM&gt;) criticizing
the market abolitionist stance developed in earlier posts.</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1>Markets as Neutral?</H1>   
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>BM&gt;If pressed on this now, I would say that it makes sense
to consider a &quot;system&quot; to be inherently neutral, but it certainly
seems that different systems encourage different human propensities. Maybe
that's not neutral, after all. But, if the propensity for competition or greed
or personal advancement at the expense of others is in us somewhere, might it
not surface no matter what the system used? Why could we not be discussing, &quot;People
-- good or bad?&quot; as easily as markets?</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>I think it makes no sense to consider systems neutral. Is slavery neutral?
Is monarchy neutral? These are social institutions, with roles, etc. So are
markets. Such systems can be studied and in most instances be shown to have
in-built dynamics that yield predictable outcomes for different constituencies
of people. How is any of this neutral? An institution or set of institutions
would be neutral if it didn't by its intrinsic nature impose any biases or
directions on those partaking of it. This is not true of the institutions
mentioned here...it may not be true of any institutions, arguably. So why not
opt for ones that facilitate outcomes we deem desirable?</P>
<P>If markets inexorably bias information so that it is impossible for actors
to do other than make choices that yield a trajectory of ever more individualist
consumption and ever less public goods consumption, how is this neutral? And so
on.</P>
<P>Could we be talking about humans: good or bad? Lots of people always seem to
want to. I never understand it, myself. Do you think you are bad, at root? I
never met anyone who thought that about themselves, so I don't understand why
there is really an issue. Do we have the capacity to do bad things? Obviously.
Will there be a higher likelihood of these things occuring if we exist in a
context that makes other behavior difficult if not impossible? Seems so to me.
Is the only chance for greater justice and sociality, etc., therefore, that we
alter social relations and structures to foster these and impede their opposite
(whatever might ultimately turn out to be the truth about &quot;people&quot;)?
Seems like this folows to me...</P>
<P>So one discussion, about institutions (including markets), is fruitfull, and
we can actually discern enough to engage in it with some hope of insight and
clarity--and of finding out things that can help us eliminate oppressions and
attain conditions suitable to liberation.</P>
<P>Whereas the other discussion, about humans, beyond some broad arguments,
doesn't really get anywhere much, and has few implications in any event, that I
can see. We have to seek desirable institutions in any event.</P>
<P>On the other hand, in my experience an underlying prejudice (I hesitate to
even call it a belief) that human nature is basically greedy malevolent and
otherwise horrible seems to be an important obstacle to people becoming radical.
When I try to talk with people about the efficacy of resistance and the
possibility of improving society, as the ultimate last line of defense I almost
always run into this view: People shit, therefore there is no point.</P>
<P>So I do think that organizers need to be able to address this in convincing
ways.</P>
<P>I have a few approaches I try, sometimes with some success--</P>
<P>I use Chomsky's example of the person walking down the street and coming
upon a child with an ice cream cone. And it is hot, and the person would like a
cone. And does the person just swat the kid away after grabbing it. No.
Virtually never. And we would call such a person pathological. Yet this seems to
me to be precisely what would occur if people were, in fact, greedy avaricious,
anti-social, etc.</P>
<P>Or, given that the basic defining institutions of society are all conducive
to gross behavior, how is it that there are so many good people, and so much
good behavior. Where does it come from, against all these institutional
pressures, if it isn't natural to us? In other words, one Che (or nice uncle) is
harder to explain in history than is Hitler or war, etc. etc., unless we
dispense with the idea that humans are innately crappy.</P>
<P>Or, how come people leave tips at restaurants?</P>
<P>And so on.</P> 
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT23-B33-270</DOCNO>
