<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Markets and Social Change...</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY><P>
<A HREF="index.htm"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/smlbbs.gif" ALT="LBBS | " ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">

</A>
<A HREF="../help.htm"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/help.gif" ALT="HELP | " ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">
</A>
<A HREF="mailto:sysop@lbbs.org"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/feedback.gif" ALT="Feedback" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">
 
</A>
</P>
<HR>
<P><CITE>
The following is a message posted to the Markets Forum, by Robin Hahnel,
continuing and enlarging a thread of discussion.</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1>Hahnel replies to additional comments about markets and social change</H1>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>GW&gt; says: 1. Markets seem natural to me. I imagine most any
group, maybe above a certain size, would come up with its version of a market
after a while.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>I don't believe this is historically true. Most human societies have not
seemed to &quot;spontaneously&quot; gravitated toward free markes as the basis
for allocating resources, assigning people tasks, and distrib- ting goods for
consumption.</P>
<P>But, even if this were the case, I wouln't be in favor of markets. Just
because a behaviour pattern is the easiest to lapse into doesn't meant it the
best. Lots of couples and lots of siblings most easily gravitate toward
interactions that are far from optimal. Frequently a little fore thought of
consequences and planning and structure can generate much improved outcomes. I
see participatory planning in that light -- knowing how badly market
interactions will end up, can't we agree to a different set of procedures for
communicating our economic desires and arriving at an equitable and efficient
pattern of coop- eration?</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>GW&gt; says: Trading, earning, and competition, though wildly
out-of- balance in our big-money-dominated consumer economy, don't strike me as
fundamentally bad or unfair.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Precisely &quot;trading and competition&quot; DO strike me as second best,
at best -- even if the participants are more or less evenly matched initially.
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>GW&gt; says: A farmers' market would be an example of a market
that works, as would the markets I've seen while traveling in less
industrialized countries. </P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>These examples are among the LEAST pernicious -- of course. But would you
feel as comfortable about these markets if I convinced you that they were bound
to be very inefficient unless they were accompanied by labor markets in which
people with greater talent and or training, but who made fewer sacrifices than
others, got 10 times as much income?</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>GW&gt; says: In the US our markets are so distorted by
disparities of size, power, and political access as to not really be markets at
all, in the Adam Smith sense. The invisible hand is bought and paid for.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>And adds: To function properly a market system would have to allow all
sellers equal access to buyers, the distribution system, advertising (or some
way to tell people what's being offered), etc.</P>
<P>Even if a market system did this -- and none can, or could for long -- it
cannot provide a way for people to express social desires as easily as private
desires. There are many decisions that we all have to live with in the sense
that we are all affected to some extent. Markets force us to approach these
decisions as individuals without any means of working out jointly agreed
arrangements. Everyone is given the following choice only: Buy the good or
don't. Sell the good or don't. But what if when I buy something others will
benefit (or suffer) too? There is no way for me to get them to pay for part of
the good if they benefit and no way for them to get me to compensate them for
the damage if they suffer. So, under market procedures we get too much of goods
whose consumption generates negative external effects for others and too little
of goods whose consumption generates positive external effects for others. The
reason there are external effects to the market decision making process is that
only individual buyers and sellers make decisions under those rules.</P>
<P>Participatory planning changes the rules and procedures so that more than a
single buyer or seller can be involved.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>GW&gt; says: A &quot;perfect&quot; market still wouldn't be
good enough, though, unless the effects of externalities were adjusted for.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>They can't be through markets.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>GW&gt; says: Any growth economy, socialist, market-based,
parecon, etc., will eventually destroy the world, as expanding human activity
exceeds carrying capacity.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>I believe this is an inevitable consequence of the major form of incentive
in a market system -- competition. So yes, I agree with you here.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>GW&gt; says: So a workable economy must be capable of
functioning without exponential growth or development. Our current economy
depends on continual growth, and looks down on stable non-growing enterprises as
&quot;stagnant.&quot; </P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>And adds: Then there are the functions of society that markets aren't
suitable for - health care, assistance to poor or dependents, environmental
protection, police and fire departments, libraries, road maintenance, policing
financial markets, etc. etc. To allow markets to function properly in a mass
society - if any system can work in a mass society - market participants have to
accept responsibility for these &quot;public good&quot; areas the markets can't
handle.</P>
<P>The problem is that to some degree almost all economic decisions have some &quot;public&quot;
effects. So when you finish the list of decisions that should not simply be
turned over to the market, it includes almost everything!</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>GW&gt; says:2. I'm not one who believes all people should be
rewarded equally for different outputs, types of work, etc. Equal opportunity
makes sense to me, guaranteeing equal satisfaction, rewards, jobs, does not.
Some people work harder, or smarter, than others. Some people don't try very
hard.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>In a market economy people who work harder, try harder, and sacrifice more
frequently get less -- because they are less talented, less well trained, or
less well equipped with the best available tools than others. In a participatory
economy all would be rewarded according to effort or sacrifice -- provided the
effort were efficiently directed.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>GW&gt; says: 3. I don't trust anyone else to make decisions for
me. In a non-market economy, it seems to me, some group must arise to make
decisions. I don't want any council - even if I'm a member - deciding what job
or &quot;job complex&quot; I'm allowed to do.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>If you work in a group someone else will have some decision making power
over what job complex you can do -- unless you are the dictator of the group and
decide what they will do. I don't think there is any kind of economy that can
prevent that. The issue becomes if job complexes are designed fairly and if
people are free to apply and be considered without bias for whatever complexes
they want. I think parecon meets those criteria. Certainly private enterprise
and labor markets don't.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>GW&gt; says: Our current market economy is arranged to make the
rich richer, maintain the &quot;world order,&quot; marginalize dissent,
homogenize the world, etc. Why not design a &quot;guided market&quot; system
that would reward initiative, encourage real equality of opportunity, protect
Nature, and discourage the concentration of power? We won't get perfection, but
it wouldn't be hard to come up with some real improvement.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Of course we could get a lot of improvement within a market environment. Who
argues differently? And of course we should support these kinds of reforms. Has
anyone suggested differently? But that doesn't answer the question of whether or
not markets are compatible with equity, democracy, efficiency, and environmental
sustainability over the long haul. And it doesn't answer the question of whether
market dynamics obstruct our goals and tend to undermine our reforms. Those of
us who call ourselves &quot;market abolitionists&quot; do so because of what we
believe are the truthful rather than mythical answers to those two questions. It
is no joy to arrive at the conclusion that something that is pervasive and with
us for a while longer is necessary to replace and exerts a pernicious influence
in the mean time. </P> 
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
