</A>
</P>
<HR>
<P><CITE>The following is a message posted to the Markets Forum, by Robin
Hahnel, continuing and enlarging a thread of discussion.</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1>Hahnel replies to additional comments about markets and social change</H1>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>TO&gt; says: I think markets or market-like mechanisms can be
useful and fair when conditions of reasonably equal power, information,
resources, and consequences of action hold for all of the participants.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Markets will do better under the circumstances you stipulate than when
participants have unequal power, information, or resources. No disagreement
here.</P>
<P>But, even when people have equal power and information I believe that
markets are NOT the most desirable means of coordinating our related economic
activities because they do not provide people with the kind of information
needed to cooperate equitably, and they provide powerful incentives, or
temptations if you will, for people to try and benefit at others expense. The
most powerful incentive to do just this is knowing that markets make it highly
likely that others will try to take advantage of you if you don't &quot;do unto
them&quot; first. Markets put people who otherwise might be perfectly happy to
engage in equitable cooperation with one another in the position of having every
reason to fear that if they try to procede in this manner they will end up being
taken advantage of. Nobody likes to be the fool.</P>
<P>I don't think one can get around this problem no matter how &quot;fair&quot;
you make the &quot;fight.&quot; Since participatory planning provides self-
management opportunites while people work out an equitable system of cooperation
I can see a better alternative to markets.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>TO&gt; says: I don't think markets should be privileged as a
form of social decisionmaking, but I think as a process capable of dispersing
information, choice, and power widely, and thereby promoting democracy, they
shouldn't be dismissed.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Over the long haul markets concentrate information, subject the majority to
the &quot;choices&quot; of a few, and generate growing disparities in people's
power. By concentrating economic wealth and power, markets also contribute
toward undermining political democracy if what that means is equal opportunity
to influence political choices. I know mainstream ideology tells us 100 times a
day that markets are forces that promote decentralization, democracy, and
individual choice, but I believe that is one of the biggest lies and hoaxes
going today. It is analagous to beleiving the Defense Department is designed to
defend our security because someone named it the Defense Department instead of
the War Department. </P>
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
