<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Markets and Social Change...</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY><P>
<A HREF="index.htm"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/smlbbs.gif" ALT="LBBS | " ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">

</A>
<A HREF="../help.htm"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/help.gif" ALT="HELP | " ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">
</A>
<A HREF="mailto:sysop@lbbs.org"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/feedback.gif" ALT="Feedback" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">
 
</A>
</P>
<HR>
<P><CITE>
The following is a message posted to the Markets Forum, by Robin Hahnel,
continuing and enlarging a thread of discussion.</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1>Hahnel replies to some comments about markets and social change</H1>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>JM&gt; says: Abolishing markets would require a violent
revolution.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>I don't concede this point at all. It seems to me that major social change
can occur peacefully or violently, quickly or over a long period. What
determines these things is mostly the organization and values of those who want
to make the change AND the organization and values of those who do not. One of
the terrible facts of history as I read it is that no matter how broad based,
democratic, and peaceful the forces that want change may be, it is possible that
those who support the status quo can create a situation where those who want
change must either give up their hopes and acquiesce to the status quo or be
entangled in violence. Of course, it is also possible that those who want change
are more than willing to engage in violence.</P>
<P>Why changing from market based allocation to participatory planning should
require violence any more than any other progressive social change is not
apparent to me.</P>
<P>In any case, we're a long way from having established a majoritarian
concensus against markets and for participatory planning, and since
participatory planning is impossible unless there is a strong concensus for it,
it seems to me we are not close to facing the issues of violence and transition.
I agree with you completely that violence should be avoided. Innocents always
pay 99% of the price of social violence.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>JM&gt; says: Establishing an simultaneous alternative system is
preferable. If co-operatives could be given an opportunity to grow, they may
counter some of the negative facets of the present system without having to
storm the Bastille again, and again...
</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>I favor cooperatives and all economic institutions that foster greater
equity and participation in decision making since they all make economic life
more bearable in the short run and are part of a transition to an economy fully
capable of delivering equity and democracy in the long run. HOWEVER, I think we
are well advised to examine carefully HOW A MARKET ENVIRONMENT WILL LIMIT AND
SUBVERT REFORMS WE STRUGGLE FOR AND WIN, and that includes cooperatives. It is
pointless to be naive or fool ourselves about the ways in which markets subvert
equitable and participatory reform impulses since we need to understand this
dynamic in order to combat it, AND we need to understand it in order to build a
concensus for replacing markets in the long run so our progress toward equity
and economic democracy will no longer be obstructed.</P>
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
