<P><CITE>
The following is a message posted to the Movies Forum, continuing and enlarging
a thread of discussion.</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1>
More on Gump and Movies Generally
</H1>
<P>In the aftermath of the &quot;Forrest Gump'' Academy Award landslide, I
think it's worth noting once again the political and cultural void we're facing
right now. It was 20 years ago when Robert Altman made &quot;Nashville'' and &quot;One
Flew Over the Cukoo's Nest'' won the best picture Oscar. American films were
breaking new ground both politically and artistically -- reaching new
generations of filmgoers by challenging American jingoism and institutional
oppression. The years of 1968 to 1977 remain one of the most exciting and
fertile decades in American film because young visionary directors had something
real and urgent to say -- something about life outside the theater doors.</P>
<P>Twenty years later, most movies have not only abandoned that &quot;goal''
but have done an about-face and are being rewarded for doing so. Instead of
challenging institutional propoganda -- instead of challenging ANYTHING for that
matter -- &quot;Forrest Gump'' embraces a hodge-podge of revisionist history
that asks only for complacency and comfort and throws any kind of dishonest crap
on screen in order to obtain it.</P>
<P>I have talked about some of the political implications of the film with
people who outright dismiss that kind of analysis. They only want to know if the
acting is good and whether it's amusing and entertaining.</P>
<P>Why there has not been more outrage over the blatant misogyny of &quot;Forrest
Gump'' is still beyond me. Some say there is little place for this kind of
discussion which to me is like saying it's OK to review &quot;Birth of a Nation&quot;
without addressing the racism in the film.</P>
<P>I would argue that it is impossible NOT to talk about the regressive
politics of &quot;Forrrest Gump,'' not to see &quot;Forrest Gump'' as a
disturbing extension of both politics and culture in this country right now.
</P>
<P>Along the same lines, it's no wonder that Sherry Lansing was the only
high-ranking executive female involved in &quot;Forrest Gump.'' Lansing has
spearheaded one anti-feminist film after another (including &quot;Fatal
Attraction''). In Susan Faludi's &quot;Backlash,'' the author questions Lansing
about her carrer.</P>
<P>&quot;I think the biggest mistake filmmakers can make is to say, okay, we're
only going to show women who are together and stable and wonderful people,''
Lansing says in the book.</P>
<P>&quot;In late '80s Hollywood, however, there didn't seem much danger of
that,'' Faludi responds. &quot;Asked to come up with 'together and stable and
wonderful' single women in her films, Lansing says, 'Oh, I've made plenty.' Such
as? 'I'm sure I've shown characters like this,' she repeats. Pressed once more
to supply a specific example, she finally says, 'Well Bonnie Bedelia in 'When
the Time Comes' was just this functioning, terrfic Rock of Gibralter.' But
Bedelia was playing a young woman dying of cancer -- another Beth of 'Little
Women.' Lansing's example only underscores the point driven home in the final
take of 'Fatal Attraction.' The best single woman is a dead one.''</P>
<P>While American film is in such sorry shape today, the level of acting is
still as good as ever. That's why it's such a shame to see hypnotic actresses
like Susan Sarandon and Jodie Foster perform in movies not worthy of them. There
are few female roles in American film that call for strong women who develop and
grow in challenging and mature ways. While Hollywood sexism is clearly on view
in award winning movies like &quot;Forrest Gump'' and popular pictures like &quot;True
Lies'' and &quot;Indecent Proposal,'' it also presents itself through the movies
Sarandon and Foster and so many other fine actresses are not ABLE to make.</P>
<P>Along the same lines, it's interesting who was not nominated for Oscars this
year. Not nominated for best actress were Crissy Rock in &quot;Ladybird,
Ladybird'' or Rena Owen in &quot;Once Were Warriors.'' One film is from England,
the other from New Zealand. They were clearly two of the most powerful pieces of
acting of the year and reflected the kind of work -- the kind of depth -- that
is seldom seen in roles played by American actresses today.</P>
<P>Some may argue that both characters present two more &quot;victim roles''
for women. That's a point to be sure but both movies accurately portray these
women as victims of an exclusionary system where institutional hurdles confront
them every step of the way. Their growth in both cases requires insight and
deeper understanding; they become politicized by the experiences they have to
endure.</P>
<P>Unsurprisingly, both movies went unnoticed by the Academy and received
little attention from American audiences who hardly had the chance to see them
in the few theaters where they played.</P>
<P>How depressing it is to have reached a time when &quot;Forrest Gump'' is not
only held up as the pinnacle of American cinema but that there is no real dialog
about what it champions. The rightful outrage over &quot;Hoop Dreams'' not being
nominated for best documentary should stand side by side with outrage over a
1995 &quot;best picture'' that embraces xenophobia, misogyny, glibness, and the
heroic ability to move through life completely unaware of anything going on
around you.</P>
<P>The Academy delivered a definitive but unsurprising declaration Monday
night: Wecome to what American movies in the '90s are all about. ---</P>
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
