<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Participatory Economics</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY><P>
<A HREF="index.htm"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/smlbbs.gif" ALT="LBBS | " ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">

</A>
<A HREF="../help.htm"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/help.gif" ALT="HELP | " ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">
</A>
<A HREF="mailto:sysop@lbbs.org"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/feedback.gif" ALT="Feedback" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">
  
</A>
</P>
<HR>
<P><CITE>
The following is a message posted to the Parecon Forum, replying to a request by
a new user to provide a summary of some key features of participatory economics,
the system about which the forum focuses...</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1>Starting a New Thread About Parecon</H1>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>GH&gt;You said something about a week or two ago about starting
some new discussions about ParEcon concepts rather then specifics.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Don't remember, but it sounds like a good idea.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>GH&gt;The present discussions about Insurance companies and
injury compensation are interesting, but are getting more into the details of
ParEcon, rather than the general principles.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Quite true, and not too useful for new people checking in for the first
time, I suspect. Although very interesting for those of us who have had some
time to think about the underlying issues, and therefore quite worth pursuing...
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>GH&gt;I was wondering if you could write a brief summary of
ParEcon for people who haven't read the book(s) and may be less familiar with
the concept than others. I would like to understand ParEcon but feel somewhat
alienated by the technical discussions routinely going on here.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Ok. I will try. But, without it sounding (I hope) too commercial or
self-serving, while this is a great place for debating attributes and the logic
of the system, for a variety of reasons it can't begin to compete with reading
Looking Forward (from South End Press) for getting a good grip on what the model
in fact is. And I would be very interested in your reaction to that book, if you
can find the time to give it a look.</P>
<P>Participatory economics is a vision for how an economy might be organized.
It aims to establish ways of organizing how we work and our workplaces, how we
consume, how our incomes are established, and how allocation (the determination
of who does what, how much is done, and where everything winds up) is carried
out--all in ways that promote some guiding values--solidarity, equity,
self-management, and diversity.</P>
<P>While any economic vision is going to involve a great many features and
aspects that need to be described for full comprehension, more so as the vision
varies greatly from familiar systems, which parecon does, still, there are bound
to be some centrally defining features that quickly give a feel for the main
logic of any vision.</P>
<P>So at the risk of giving too partial a picture, let me dwell on a couple of
centrally defining features.</P>
<P>(1) Our circumstances in the economy should be just in the sense that
material incomes AND the daily life circumstances and responsibilities we have
are fairly distributed. Thus there should be no hierarchy of rewards or of our
conditions of economic life--that is, no class divisions.</P>
<P>As a result, in parecon incomes are a function of effort and sacrifice,
only. And, also, jobs are defined so that people's circumstances at work are
fairly apportioned and in tune with everyone being empowered to participate in
making decisions. That is, each person has an array of responsibilities, tasks,
etc., whose overall implications for quality of life while one is working, for
fulfillment and boredom while working, and particularly for the degree to which
one's work empowers one, are balanced with all other jobs.</P>
<P>(2) People should have a say over the decisions that affect them to the
degree they are affected by those decisions. Outcomes (ranging from what I will
consume, or what job I will take, or the character of products, or techniques
used in producing them, or the amount produced, or how my neighborhood will
organize itself or whether it will opt for a park, to what the overall level of
work and leisure will be in society, etc.) should be decided in ways that
manifest the wills of all those affected, in proportion as they are affected.
</P>
<P>As a result, we need a means of allocation that lets each actor make
responsible decisions about their preferences, in light of full knowledge of the
social costs and benefits of competing options, and that somehow sums all these
expressed preferences into a decision, according each person's preferences a
proper degree of influence.</P>
<P>There are other themes defining and driving the definition of parecon, but
the above are arguably paramount, and could take us a long way, I think, to
clarifying its character and seeing why and how it is so different from
capitalism, social democracy, and centrally planned and market post capitalist
alternatives (sometimes called socialism and market socialism, but better
labelled centrally planned and market coordinatorism, I think).</P>
<P>So here is the rough overarching grand sweep picture --</P>
<P>In a parecon there are many workplaces and housesholds and other consumer
units. These are all linked by a system of participatory planning. Within each
site there are balanced job complexes so that every actor has a mix of
responsibilities and tasks whose overall impact is comparable to that of every
other actor.</P>
<P>Income, from which we determine how much of the social product we can each
have, depends (unless we are unable to work, etc., in which case we just get the
average income by right) on the effort and sacrifice we contribute while working
to produce the social product. Since we all work at a balanced job complex,
essentially equally demanding of effort and sacrifice, a good rough measure of
how much we have worked is just how long we have worked.</P>
<P>The planning process is one in which each unit and each actor assesses
possibilities and offers choices among them. These preferences for consumption
and production options are compiled for the whole economy, and then made
available for a new round of choosing. The process continues until there is a
mesh or fit between what people (in their role as consumers) want to have, and
what people (in their role as workers) want to produce.</P>
<P>The details of the system are of course critical -- such as, how do jobs get
balanced, what is the impact of balanced jobs on efficiency and quality of
economic life and work, what is the impact of the criteria of earning
(remuneration), how do people arrive at their preferences about what they want
to consume, how much they want to work, what investments they want to see made,
etc., and how do their choices get conveyed to one another, and then what
facilitates the mesh or fit between demand and supply esential to the system
working properly. What kinds of information are communicated as part of the
decision process and what structures and mechanisms facilitate democratic and
participatory decision-making at each level, from the individual, through
workgroups to neighborhoods and workplaces, to regions and industries, and to
the whole country. And what kinds of special institutions and job roles are
required to facilitate this type of workplace organization and economic
allocation, and so on.</P>
<P>I think, insofar as people are interested, we can get into the details after
we deal some more with whether the guiding concepts have any merit.</P>
<P>To start (Gabe, you asked me to ask some questions to organize some
discussion, though, of course, anyone can pursue any other avenue)...</P>
<P>Do we think that the idea of remuneration according to effort and sacrifice
only (and not the amount of output we are responsible for) is just, desirable,
workable?</P>
<P>Picasso and Harvy Artist (not so productive) and Einstein and Jill Physicist
(again, not so productive) and Paul Bunyon and Roger Tiny (also not so
productive) and Michael Jordan (and whoever) all earn the same income due to
working the societal average at a societally balanced job complex, or maybe
Harvey or Jill or whoever work a little a overtime and earn a little more...
Does this make moral sense, economic sense, incentives sense?</P>
<P>And:</P>
<P>Do we think that having job complexes balanced for circumstances and
empowerment effects is just, and is necessary for self management, or that it
has problems that impede attaining these or other aims?</P>
<P>The same array of people discused above all work at balanced job complexes.
Picasso and Einstein and Paul and Air himself are not freed from the requirement
of doing an array of tasks that sum to a balanced job complex. Nor is anyone
else. Do this make sense? Is it just? Does it get the best for each actor, for
all actors, for the whole economy? Or is it a ludicrous bit of PC nonsense that
wastes talents and underutilizes skills and forces people to have to do things
they would rather not, and so on? </P>
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
