<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Participatory Economics</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY><P>
<A HREF="index.htm"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/smlbbs.gif" ALT="LBBS | " ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">

</A>
<A HREF="../help.htm"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/help.gif" ALT="HELP | " ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">
</A>
<A HREF="mailto:sysop@lbbs.org"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/feedback.gif" ALT="Feedback" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">
  
</A>
</P>
<HR>
<P><CITE>
The following is a message posted to the Parecon Forum, continuing a thread of
discussion focused on the idea of balanced job complexes as one component of
participatory economies.</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1> More discussion of Job Complexes</H1>
<P>There is nothing about parecon that says there are never decisions, never
rules, never norms to be respected. Nor is there anything whatsoever that says
everyone just does whatever the hell they want.</P>
<P>Workplaces have standards for jobs. Applicants must meet them, and, for that
matter, be hired in the first place, which, depending on the job in question,
often includes meeting certain standards, etc.</P>
<P>There is an array of job complexes. People in a work place generally do the
job they did last year. Sometimes there is a desire to change. Or sometimes
technical or social innovations lead to some redefinition of the available jobs
as tasks are eliminated from the work process, or added to it. When someone
wants to change a job, if this can work good, if not, then it won't happen. On
what grounds might it not happen? The person wanting a job is not able to
actually do it. Someone else already has the job. And so on.</P>
<P>Who figures out job complexes? Who handles job assignment requests? Who
handles job applications? Well this will likely vary from workplace to
workplace, at least somewhat, consistent however with the norms of balanced job
complexes, self management, etc. But think of it as a personel department. Who
works in it?</P>
<P>Well, people who wish to, as part of their job responsibilities. They also
have other responsibilities. We all have tasks that involve some power, and
tasks that involve carrying out some rote functions, etc. These tasks are
structured so people can't personally aggrandize themselves, etc. (There is much
on this in the book Looking Forward, but it is too detailed for here, I think.)
</P>
<P>If your question is, however, does job balancing preclude or take the place
of trying to actually get jobs done in a sensible and fulfilling fashion that
includes minimizing waste, utilizing talents, etc. etc., the answer is no. There
is no reason that it needs to, and the requirement that workplaces function
efficiently (as they must within the norms of the planning process) militates
against such possibilities.</P>
<P>On the other hand, you might be feeling that the job balancing somehow gives
us an array of jobs, or an assigning of people, that fails to utilize skills
properly or comprehensively. Is that what you are getting at? Are you thinking
that this approach will under utilize the skills a person who wants to be (and
has the skills to be) a doctor has, or will demand too much of some other
people?</P>
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
