<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Participatory Economics</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY><P>
<A HREF="index.htm"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/smlbbs.gif" ALT="LBBS | " ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">

</A>
<A HREF="../help.htm"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/help.gif" ALT="HELP | " ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">
</A>
<A HREF="mailto:sysop@lbbs.org"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/feedback.gif" ALT="Feedback" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">
  
</A>
</P>
<HR>
<P><CITE>
The following is a message posted to the Parecon Forum, continuing a thread of
discussion focused on the idea of balanced job complexes as one component of
participatory economies.</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1> More discussion of Job Complexes</H1>
<P>I am glad you are taking issue with the balanced job complex conception of
parecon. It is certainly controversial. And so good to discuss. My views on it
are quite strong, however, and I hope I don't offend by my answers...</P>
<P>You say:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>IB&gt;I agree with the objection to parecon you have raised,
that parecon assumes that it is possible to divide tasks according to whether
they are desirable or undesirable, empowering or disempowering. for one, some
folks find picking up garbage quite rewarding. What's so demeaning about keeping
things neat and clean?</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Nothing, at least in a good economy. Assuming a fair distribution of
responsibilities...and income.</P>
<P>I think there is a basic confusion of levels, here, so to speak. Society
might judge that the social costs and benefits of drum sticks versus those of
hand made violins yields one ordering of their value. You personally might,
however, have no use for a violin at all, valuing it at zero, and be quite fond
of drumming... This difference between social value and ones personal taste for
something applies not only to consumption but also to jobs.</P>
<P>Society inevitably offers us a variety of work options. Regarding jobs,
there will be a &quot;menu&quot; of offerings. Each will have a variety of tasks
within its range of requirements. We will choose among this menu, presuming that
we aren't just forced to do a job by some economic dictator. This much is true
in any economy.</P>
<P>So one important question to ask is what should characterize the menu of
offerings we all choose from. Of course we are each going to look at the
offerings and find one that particularly suits our personal tastes and
preferences. But when we look at the whole array of offered jobs, will we be
happier, so to speak, if what we see before we make that personal choice is job
after job which we have collectively agreed with others in society represent to
the best of our judgement a fair share of pleasant versus unpleasant, desirable
versus less desirable, versus undesirable--and especially empowering versus
unempowering components? Or will we be happier if we look and see a menu of jobs
which array on a scale of desirableness and empowerment, from much to little,
with a few at the top, and many more at the bottom?</P>
<P>If you want to say that you think there is no such thing. That a job is a
job, well, I guess you are entitled to your opinion. But it seems outrageous to
me.</P>
<P>If you want to note that in a good economy the way we view all work will
change, and the respect we give to all effort and sacrifice at work will be
comparable, no matter the task, I agree, sure. This is one reason we make the
changes in the first place. But there is a difference between saying that doing
a task like sweeping is dignified, and contributes, and is important, all of
which is quite true, and saying that it is fulfilling or empowering in the way
that many other tasks are.</P>
<P>If you want to say that for reasons of productivity, or training
requirements, or whatever else, while it would be more just to have balance, we
have to forego it--I can understand that argument and we then have to determine
if, indeed, we gain in productivity or training or whatever, by opting against
balance...</P>
<P>You say:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>IB&gt;For another, if there is a task that is so onerous that
no one wants to do it, perhaps it simply does not need to be done. Presumably,
if we moved to parecon, we would not simply rethink the allocation of tasks, we
would also rethink what tasks are performed at all.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Absolutely. And the nature of parecon is such that tasks will be eliminated
from work complexes due to innovations, changes in what people decide to
consume, etc., for precisely these reason. And it will make everyone's work life
better off, because the overall balanced job complex will get a little better
with each such change. But to presume that we will switch to a good economy and
all work will all of a sudden be intrinsically desirable and pleasurable, much
less equally so, or intrinsically empowering, much less equally so, seems to
have no justification whatsoever. And as long as the differences exist, there is
the issue of how to pack the different tasks into jobs...</P>
<P>You say:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>IB&gt;Given that, I see no reason to toss out the division of
labor and specialization based on an unsubstantiated assumption that there is
some line to be drawn between the desirable and undesirable job.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Well, who has tossed out a division of labor? And who has tossed out a
degree of specialization? No one. You do not do everything, nor do I. So there
is a division of labor, to be sure. And you do not become skilled in all things,
or in no things, but in those areas that you choose to pursue. There are still
people who become expert in fields.</P>
<P>It doesn't do to create a straw position here. You can develop and utilize
surgeon skills, or chemist skills, or music talents, or whatever else you might
wish in parecon. What you can't do is have a job that is disproportionately free
of onerous or rote work, or is disproportionately empowering. And this
constraint is imposed on grounds of equity and of solidarity, and of ensuring
that formally democratic decision procedures are not subverted by lack of
participation by most and domination by a few (due to unequal work situations re
empowerment effects).</P>
<P>Make it simple, for the sake of argument.</P>
<P>Suppose there are three categories of task in the economy: desireable,
neutral, and undesirable. And suppose within each category no further
differentiation can be made. And suppose the total time throughout the economy
that must be applied to each category of task throughout the economy, to
complete all work, is equal for the three classes.</P>
<P>So, on average, the job complex, if we took the parecon approach, would be
neutral.</P>
<P>Now suppose we divide up the jobs so that some people have only desirable,
some only neutral, and some only undesirable, on the one hand.</P>
<P>Or suppose we divide up so that everyone has a mix so that on average each
available job complex comes out neutral.</P>
<P>Of course there are thousands of different jobs, tens of thousands, indeed
millions, depending on the economy. And each individual will prefer some to
others, due to the individual's personal tastes.</P>
<P>It seems that what you and some other critics want me to believe is that the
balanced complex model will be oppressive to some people because they will not
be able to find a job that has a neutral mix which they like as much as jobs
that they would be able to find in the other society, in the undesirable
category.</P>
<P>I find this to be an incomprehensible claim. It says that if you give such a
person a job in the undesirable category and say to them, would you like to
trade any of your tasks for tasks in the neutral or desirable category, they
will say no.</P>
<P>Even presuming that they have received a wonderful education, etc. etc. etc.
and we are not talking about taking jobs that oppress others, and so on.</P>
<P>I don't believe it, for an instant. The fact that it may be true now, for a
relatively few people, perhaps, tells us nothing useful about equitable
circumstances, if it is true now because of habit, lack of training,
intimidation, etc. etc.</P>
<P>On the other hand, if you tell me that people in the first economy who have
jobs that are entirely composed of desirable tasks and empowering ones, might
say, hey (assuming there is no social onus and no loss involved) I would rather
keep these tasks than have to trade away any for undesirable or even neutral
options, I would say yes, I believe that that could be so, but I don't care.
</P>
<P>To me it is no different, in kind, than saying that capitalists would rather
not give away their capital...</P>
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
