<HR>
<P><CITE>
The following is a message posted to the Parecon Forum, pursuing a detail of
participatory economics--how to deal with insurance and claims and lawyers...
</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1>A Comment in an Extended Sidebar Discussion about Insurance and Law in
Parecon</H1>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>RH&gt;If producers in parecon delivered products to consumers
that caused injury I'm not sure that society would simply pick up the tab for
the damage. Hopefully this would occur much less often in an economy where
consumers federations were checking out products as well as workers federations,
and where the worries and concerns of consumers federations would be taken
seriously by workers federations and then communicated by the workers
federations to individual workers councils where they would also be taken more
seriously. Also, where there was no more to be gained by the workers from
producing a quality product that was safe for which they would be paid the full
social cost than from producing a shoddy product, there shouldn't be an
incentive for producers to cut corners at consumers' expense. BUT, there
presumably would be some friction from time to time over whether or not what was
delivered was up to expectations -- and every once in a while it would be
discovered after the fact that something was not, in fact, safe. Then the
question is who should be compensated by whom. </P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Let's take the case of a new (medicinal) drug. Studies are done on its
safety before it is produced for the public. But a year after it's &quot;on the
market&quot; it turns out that there is a unanticipated adverse reaction when
the drug is taken after having eaten asparagus and mushrooms. The person who
consumed this unfortunate combination gets seriously ill.  What do we do?</P>
<P>Obviously the person who got sick gets all the necessary medical care.</P>
<P>Obviously the warnings on the drug label will be changed.</P>
<P>Obviously if it is discovered that the drug produces adverse reactions in a
whole lot of cases, cases that are not so rare as the asparagus- mushroom
situation, we might decide to stop producing the drug (presumably balancing its
benefits with these dangers and taking account of the alternatives, etc.).</P>
<P>Less obviously, but I agree with you, in calculating the social costs of
production of drugs, we will want to include some equivalent of insurance which
is just another way of saying that we expect some unexpected adverse reactions
that society will have to pay for, and more for drugs than for, say, books.</P>
<P>But none of this seems like it would require trials with any sort of
punitive damages.</P>
<P>Sure, if it was thought that someone at the drug company purposely falsified
the safety studies then you'd want a trial -- though, as you point out, the
motives for wrong-doing of this sort would be minimal in parecon (maybe a
Columbo-type murderer knows his/her victim loves asparagus and mushroom
casserole...) Or maybe there was &quot;criminal negligence&quot; -- the people
in charge of the safety studies skipped work the day the asparagus and mushroom
tests were supposed to be done and were out skiing.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>RH&gt;I'm not so sure that the basic idea of insurance is so
bad. Suppose the federation of auto makers provided malpractice insurance to
auto maker councils. That is, in addition to the social costs of workers' hours,
steel, rubber, pollution, etc. the indicative price of a car included the
insurance premium the auto makers federation charged its members in case one of
them produced and delivered faulty cars that exploded on rear end collision. If
this happened the consumers federation would complain to the auto makers
association. There would be a kind of grievance procedure. If the car were
faulty the auto federation would agree to pay damages to injured consumers out
of the premiums they collected from all auto makers.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Let's take the following case:</P>
<P>The production process for manufacturing steel for cars produces faulty
steel in one out of every 100,000,000 cases. This being parecon, all safety
studies are public information, so presumably all consumers are aware of the
risk they take when they buy a car. (I ignore the question of whether cars make
sense in a decent economy.) The production process can be changed to make the
likelihood of faulty cars only 1/100,000,000,000 but this would raise the price
of the car 10 fold and it has been decided in some democratic way that it is &quot;worth&quot;
using the first process. I am injured in an accident because my car was faulty.
</P>
<P>a. Is the decision to use the first process conceivable under parecon? (I
assume so.)</P>
<P>b. I assume that my medical bills are covered. Are they covered by society
or by the automobile industry's &quot;insurance.&quot;</P>
<P>c. Am I entitled to damages for my injuries given that I read the warnings
and knowingly bought the car? Are monetary damages the way to compensate me for
being partially paralyzed, etc.</P>
<P>d. Because I am paralyzed from the waist down, my lover has suffered from my
injury. Does my lover receive any compensation? From whom?</P> 
</BODY></HTML>
