<HR>
<P><CITE>
The following is a message posted to the Parecon Forum, pursuing a detail of
participatory economics--how to deal with insurance and claims and lawyers...
</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1>A Comment in an Extended Sidebar Discussion about Insurance and Law in
Parecon</H1>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>SS&gt;RH&gt;I'm not so sure that the basic idea of insurance is
so bad. Suppose the federation of auto makers provided malpractice nsurance to
auto maker councils. That is, in addition to the social costs of workers' hours,
steel, rubber, pollution, etc. the indicative price of a car included the
insurance premium the auto makers federation charged its members in case one of
them produced and delivered faulty cars that exploded on rear end collision. If
this happened the consumers federation would complain to the auto makers
association. There would be a kind of grievance procedure. If the car were
faulty the auto federation would agree to pay damages to injured consumers out
of the premiums they collected from all auto makers.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>I have to say, this can be fun on St. Patrick's Day. </P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>SS&gt;Let's take the following case: The production process for
manufacturing steel for cars produces faulty steel in one out of every
100,000,000 cases. This being parecon, all safety studies are public
information, so presumably all consumers are aware of the risk they take when
they buy a car.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Their consumer federation would try and make them aware -- more than anyone
does in present economies -- but I don't read all my mail. So presumably some
people would be buying the car unware that part of the reason it didn't cost
more was that it was not 100% safe.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>SS&gt;The production process can be changed to make the
likelihood of faulty cars only 1/100,000,000,000 but this would raise the price
of the car 10 fold and it has been decided in some democratic way that it is &quot;worth&quot;
using the first process.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Exactly. I think this is an important point to recognize. It isn't always
the best choice to eliminate all risk of hardship, and if parecon was incapable
of making these choices correctly there would be a problem.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>SS&gt;I am injured in an accident because my car was faulty.
</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>And you did read your Consumer Federation newsletter with the featured
article on car saftey -- that told you a) that they were only x-degree safe, and
why that was the best choice since it wasn't worth the extra cost to make it
safer. Also -- so glad it was you not me.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>SS&gt;a. Is the decision to use the first process conceivable
under parecon? (I assume so.)</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Yes. And as I said there would be something wrong with parecon if it was
not.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>SS&gt;b. I assume that my medical bills are covered. Are they
covered by society or by the automobile industry's &quot;insurance.&quot;</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>That's the point I originally responeded to. I think it is best if the auto
industry insurance pays you because the reason it was best to produce the less
safe car more cheaply was that when we fully compen- sated damaged individuals
the social cost of making slightly less safe cars and compensating victims was
lower than the social cost of making more safe cars with fewer victims to
compensate. This being the case we want to auto industry to make the payments
and collect premiums from auto makers from which to do so so we will have an
accurate measure of the social cost of making the car.</P>
<P>Suppose we made the right choice -- to make the less safe care and
compensate victims -- but didn't have the auto industry pay the victims, instead
paying them out of a general insurance fund. Then the full social cost of the
car wouldn't be reflected in the price and consumers would be responding to
false signals when they decided whether to buy a car or not.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>SS&gt;c. Am I entitled to damages for my injuries given that I
read the warnings and knowingly bought the car?</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Sure, why not? You bought a car paying the full social cost which included
the cost of compensating any who were unfortunately injured by imperfections.
Since you turned out to be one, you should be compensated -- whether or not you
read the fine print.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>SS&gt;Are monetary damages the way SS&gt;to compensate me for
being partially paralyzed, etc.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Now I'm not so sure about compensation above and beyond medical and
disability payments. I originally said that parecon should only pay medical and
allow people consumption rights during disability -- which might be permanent.
But there are social costs in excess of this when an injury occurs, and I think
these as well as medical and disability expenses should be included in the price
tags on different things. So maybe damage estimates based on lost life
satisfactions SHOULD be paid by industry insurance funds when their products are
the cause -- for efficiency reasons.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>SS&gt;d. Because I am paralyzed from the waist down, my lover
has suffered from my injury. Does my lover receive any compensation? From whom?
</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Again. My original answer was &quot;no.&quot; Now I'm inclined toward &quot;yes&quot;
-- from the auto industry federation insurance fund.</P>
</BODY></HTML>
