<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Participatory Economics</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY><P>
<A HREF="index.htm"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/smlbbs.gif" ALT="LBBS | " ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">

</A>
<A HREF="../help.htm"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/help.gif" ALT="HELP | " ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">
</A>
<A HREF="mailto:sysop@lbbs.org"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/feedback.gif" ALT="Feedback" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">
  
</A>
</P>
<HR>
<P><CITE>The following is a message posted to the Parecon Forum, pursuing a
detail of participatory economics--how to deal with insurance and claims and
lawyers...</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1>A Clarifying Summary Comment Clarifying an On-Going Discussion about
Insurance and Law in Parecon</H1>
<P>So what the hell is all this tort stuff about, anyhow?</P>
<P>Well, it seems to me that there are a few core issues, or ideas, involved.
And I want to try to tease them out, if I can.</P>
<P>First, there is the issue of what it is just to do in the event that someone
suffers an unexpected claamity of some sort or other.</P>
<P>Second, there is the issue of how the just treatment of the &quot;victim&quot;
should be organized and paid for.</P>
<P>Third, there is the slippery slope (or profoundly insightful) issue of what,
in fact, constitutes a problem to be addresses by some sort of redress in the
first place.</P>
<P>And what have we arrived at -- mostly Steve Shalom and Robin Hahnel -- so
far on these issues?</P>
<P>Well, non-controversially, when someone suffers an accident, or disease, or
hurt that involves costs they would not otherwise have had (such as for medical
care, rebuilding a destroyed house, etc.) in an even remotely good economy they
should not have to pay themselves, out of their budget, but should get the extra
funds required from an insurance pool of some kind.</P>
<P>And where should this insurance pool come from?</P>
<P>Well, Robin points out that it is not such a good idea to have it be just a
piece of the whole social product, available indiscriminantly for all
emergencies. It is important, instead, that the costs of illnesses and
particularly accidents be taken into account in economic decisions (for example,
about how much effort to take to make cars ever more safeor what the price of
cigarettes should be) and therefore these costs (in human harm) need to be
accounted to the relevant production processes.</P>
<P>[Note: When the national government bails out California residents over and
over, we have a problem. The whole country is subsidizing these people's choices
to live in a dangerous place. If, instead, the insurance fund were derived
entirely from California housing taxes, the price of living there would be much
much higher, in tune with the actual social costs and benefits of choosing to do
so. Similarly, if a national insurance fund pays all the insurance claims of
people suffering broken limbs in some industry, the industry never &quot;registers&quot;
the true social costs and benefits of its investment choices. Which is not good.
</P>
<P>Robin has made this point very clearly, but I am not sure that he and Steve
have as yet figured out the best way to solve the matter, pazrticularly in a
parecon.</P>
<P>Now there arises the question of lost pleasures. Not new costs one needs to
pay--which are covered uncontroversially. But other kinds of pain. For example,
as Steve notes, does the accident victim get lifelong remuneration to offset the
pain of on-going loss of a limb, say, or of other bodily functions...</P>
<P>The underlying impetus is a kind of equilibration of outcomes of pleasure.
And Steve takes it right to birth, saying if I am born with some attribute that
limits my future pleasures, why shouldn't I be provided means to offset that
loss?</P>
<P>I think this line of thinking, which probably takes us to the revolution
after the revolution to create a new feminist, multi-cultural, parecon, etc.
society, does, however, emerge from parecon type considerations.</P>
<P>Thus, if we argue that people shouldn't benefit from luck in the genetic
lottery, doesn't the next step arise immediately, that is, that people shouldn't
suffer due to bad luck in the genetic lottery?</P>
<P>And, similarly, if we argue that the inputs and outputs of all production
processes include human traits and qualities and conditions, and that these are
part of the true social costs and benefits that must be accounted for in
sensible and humane decision making, then doesn't it follow that we have to pay
attention to the effects of economic accidents and choices on people's abilities
to have pleasure and fulfillment?</P>
<P>This is what took Robin to the position that perhaps, yes, insurance ought
to pay people (to the extent that society isn't able to reduce accident induced
pains by its just and humane construction) for things like lost pleasure. And
Steve will undoubtedly come back with, well then why not for genetic
disabilities...</P>
<P>And that, I think, is where the discussion is at, and I certainly look
forward to its next installment.</P>
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
