<HR>
<P><CITE>
The following is a message about the 1994-95 Baseball Strike written for the
Popular Culture Forum, responding to comments from another user.</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1>On the Baseball Strike </H1>
<P>I've been reading the discussion about the baseball strike with a keen
interest. Since I cannot follow spring training with any interest and will not
follow it because of ethics, I like having some &quot;real&quot; time connection
with the game rather than be confined to my library for sustenence. One thing
that I think we are demonstrating (and the we here seems to be largely confined
to men) is how thoroughly sports are woven into our own popular subcultures even
as self-proclaimed leftists. The significance of this is certainly worth
pondering especially given the nature of the contemporary sports spectacle.
However, that discussion is tangential to this thread, so I won't pick it up
right now. Here I want to offer a few reflections that come out of the exchange
between Egniles and Michael, and exchange that touches on the complexity of the
issues surrounding this strike. In some ways the labor and management issues
that are present in most if not all strikes have been magnified in the baseball
strike due to the obviously large amounts of money involved, the publicity the
media have given to the events, the notariety of the players (and the anonymity
of most of the owners), and the perception of involvement held by a significant
portion of the general population (fans).</P>
<P>I think Egniles and Michael are talking from two different contexts. 
Egniles speaks about a current reality, while Michael speaks about a vision of
more equitable work place relationships. True, these relationships may well
exist now in some places, but I think of these occurances as being rare. In this
Popcult forum I think we need to concern ourselves primarily with conditions as
they exist now while keeping an eye on what it is we want in the future, while
attempting to understand how we build on and transform the present we understand
so as to make the future we desire.</P>
<P>The issue of advancement through merit rather than through what is generally
understood as privilege is a central myth of this country. No matter how much
factual evidence we find and reveal to the contrary, the myth persists. In a
sense baseball (and sports in general) has filled an important conservative role
by continually reinvigorating this myth through the iconization of its stars.
The celebrity of Babe Ruth is often cited as a prime reason baseball survived
the Black Sox Scandal. What isn't often considered is how the Babe diverted
attention from and covered up the issue of inequitable economic relations
between players and owners in the game and also between workers and owners and
between poor and rich in the society at large. These issues were at least as
pressing in the game and in the society during Ruth's heyday. As for how the
strike informs this issue, I think Egnilges is correct in pointing out how
little respect the owners have for the abilities of the players. In these
actions they clearly reveal the true nature of the relationship between them and
the players, a relationship that if based on the same principles as in the
society as a whole: power, as Michael so correctly points out.</P>
<P>As Michael also points out, the players and their union have demonstrated
(at least I haven't heard about their having demonstrated) any class solidarity.
All the public utterances I've heard have been pretty offputting like Brett
Butler saying that the Minor Leaguers have to &quot;pay their dues&quot; before
they can enjoy the privileges of Major Leaguers (this against the background of
strike rhetoric that says the central issue is not money for current players but
the bargaining position of future players) or Tom Glavine's declaration that the
issue wasn't money, that he would gladly play for $3 million a year. There are
at least two points I want to make about this. </P>
<P>First, here is yet another demonstration of a union failing to educate its
members to class issues and failing to be aware of need and value of uniting
with other working folks. In this strike there is a perfect tie in with the
umpires who are also without a contract and are on strike.  How many people
remember that? In addition, why hasn't the union worked to organize the Minor
Leagues?</P>
<P>Second, there is the unequal coverage of the strike by the media. Much of
what I see here in Seattle is heavily biased toward the owners. The owners of
the Mariners have such confidence in their position that they are demanding that
the region build them a new stadium (for an estimated $250 million) or they will
&quot;be forced&quot; to move to another city. They even sent solicitation
letters to some folks (including me of all people) to ask us to pressure elected
officials on their behalf. This biased coverage may not be surprising to those
of us who have paid any attention to labor politics in the US or who have been
involved in labor actions, but many people still hold to the idea of an
impartial press. This strike presents us with an opportunity to talk about an
issue in which many people have an interest, and to talk about it from a left
political perspective with the hope of actually having a conversation.</P>
<P>I think this thread is far from talked out.</P>
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
