<HR>
<P><CITE>
The following is a message about popular culture and corporate culture, and
their connections and relations, written in the Popular Culture Forum,
responding to comments from another user.</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1>Pop and Corporate Culture </H1>
<P></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>MT&gt;There is no popculture; popculture is popular culture in
short hand. What this forum really talks about is corporate culture. It
self-evident that what we are watching is corporate; all decisions made by a
centralized elite in a boardroom. They make the decisions; the we have remote
but they control all the avenues, all the cables, the and all towers. Very
little on 'popcult' reflects what people think.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>I think corporate power wants to control the products and tries very hard to
do so, but it is not entirely successful. In pop music, for example, over 60% of
CDs issued sell virtually no copies, and over 80%, I think, fail to recover
their costs. The point is that the culture moguls don't know what will sell, at
least in times when tastes are changing. So they have to issue quite a lot of
stuff, much of it beyond the category they would think of as safe. If some of
those things begin to sell, they will often pour money into promoting them as
potential blockbusters, reluctant and uneasy as they may be about certain
aspects of the work. Nor is it an easy thing to control rock bands.</P>
<P>Movies may be more controllable, but books and magazines are less so. 
Communication through electronic means, also a popculture phenomenon, is even
more difficult to control. So I think we need a more sophisticated analysis of
the various areas and products of popculture. We can't just say that they are
controlled by the corporationa and hence suck.</P>
<P>As for reverence for the clearly corporate products, my own is based at
least partly on a notion of struggle for meaning. That is, the managers may
control the product, even in considerable depth and detail. But they cannot
fully control what we as individuals make of the products and, even more
importantly, cannot control how we as groups deal with them (for example, in
places like LBBS). How we take things is, I think, very important. Mickey Mouse
may be a symbol of oppression, while Bugs Bunny can be a symbol of resistance,
the undermining of the established order. Seeing both qualities has liberatory
potential.  NYPD Blue can simply involve allowing ourselves to be conditioned by
authoritarian images, or it can involve looking at how such conditioning is
done. Either way it can be absorbing.</P>
<P>So I don't take so negative a view of popculture as you seem to take. I
certainly regard it warily, and I'm sure it has effects on me that I don't even
suspect. But I do like a lot of what I find there, and am not particularly
troubled by that fact.</P>
<P>I certainly have no objection to looking at alternative, non-corporate
channels of culture. But it seems to me the corporate stuff is there in an
undeniably big way, it reaches lots of people, and it behooves us to pay
attention to it.</P> 
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
