<HR>
<P><CITE>
The following is a message about popular culture and corporate culture and their
relations, written for the Popular Culture Forum, continuing an on-going
exchange.</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1>More on Relating to Cultural Options</H1>
<P>Regarding my comments concerning the possibilities of valuable work being
done within areas of popculture that are corporate-controlled, you express
considerable skepticism, to put it mildly. I don't have much sense that you've
understood what I have been saying, but it is quite possible that you would
reject it even if you did. And, quite possibly, you would be right. But let me
try again to lay out the categories of this argument, and if we don't seem to be
getting any closer to understanding each other, well, we can just drop it.</P>
<P>We can agree, I think, that there are at least four categories of material
that corporate record companies, film companies, publishers and others can find
themselves dealing with: 1) material that they like enthusiastically because of
its messages and effects and that sells (or is likely to sell) well, 2) material
that they like enthusiastically because of its messages and effects and that
doesn't sell (or is unlikely to sell) well, 3) material that they hate and that
sells well (or would if they were willing to offer it), and 4) material that
they hate and that doesn't sell well. In addition, I am arguing that there are
at least two more categories: 5) material that they are uneasy about because of
its messages and potential effects but that might sell well if they were to
offer it, and 6) material that they are uneasy about but that won't sell well in
any event.</P>
<P>We can argue about what falls within each of these categories, but that is
not too important. What is important is whether these categories exist. I agree
with you that the corporate managers will concentrate on finding stuff in the
first category and will look to the second in hopes that it will sell. I agree
that they are unlikely to offer for sale anything from categories 3 or 4, though
they will look longingly at category 3 to see if they have misjudged the effects
or if there is some way those effects can be contained. I agree we can forget
category 6.  But I think there is a substantial amount of material that will
fall in category 5, and that the corporate managers will attempt to sell,
because they cannot get enough sales from just the stuff they like.</P>
<P>Or, to look at it another way, the stuff they like will not occupy and
pacify certain groups, so the managers will not be carrying out their function
well enough. In other words, Pat Boone may be a great guy who has recorded reams
of wonderful music, but there is a limit to his audience. People like you just
won't listen to him, although people like me are very tempted by his engaging
covers of Little Richard. So we've got a problem: people like you represent an
untapped market, and we have not got you listening to something that will keep
you out of trouble.</P>
<P>So what do we do? We (corporate managers) look to category 5, stuff that
makes us uneasy, but that we think may appeal to people like you and so may make
us a lot of money. We don't understand it exactly, we don't particularly like
the performers or their messages, but it doesn't preach outright revolution and
doesn't seem to expose anything too fundamental or at least too contemporary, so
we give it a shot.</P>
<P>That category of stuff, I am arguing, is a realm of uncertainty for the
corporate managers, a realm of relative freedom for us. Yet when I have pointed
to the existence of such a category, you say it doesn't exist  because there is
no progressive TV talk show, because rap is basically groin-scratching music, or
because the corporate managers control all the levers, anyway, so it couldn't
possibly exist.</P>
<P>Listing examples has gotten me in trouble with you in the past, but let's
try it again. Some category 5 TV shows: The Simpsons, Roseanne, Northern
Exposure, Michael Moore's TV Nation, Geraldo Rivera's interviews with Gerry
Spence. Some category 5 movies: Apocalypse Now, One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest,
The Godfather, The Player, Shortcuts, Taxi Driver. Some category 5 music:
Nirvana, Rage Against the Machine, Nine Inch Nails, Public Enemy, Jane's
Addiction. Most of this is hugely popular stuff, the effects of which are
unclear, but which the corporate managers are willing to push because it sells.
They are certainly not enthusiastic about the messages.</P>
<P>So what do we do? We (ordinary folks) promote category 5 stuff, talk about
it to our friends, make its messages clear. If we have access, we try to produce
stuff within this category. Of course, we're not limited to this. We can also
talk about stuff from all the other categories, making clear their messages and
effects and explaining why they are being produced and sold. The audience is
huge, and they are already familiar with much of this stuff. We only have to try
to change (expand, really) their take on it. Then, I'm suggesting, we may have
some effects in terms of changing people's consciousness, perhaps starting
dialogue and movement toward other things.</P>
<P>PK&gt; Just as in punk rock, grunge and rap have contradictory themes, but 
PK&gt; most of it is about how we aren't gonna take what the rulers of  PK&gt;
society are pushing on us, society is a mess, etc. </P>
<P>Just a note: Pearl Jam (the biggest grunge group, I think) did a
semi-underground broadcast that was on multiple stations a while ago, playing
lots of cool stuff (in the little part that I heard), including audio of Chomsky
from Manufacturing Consent. It was out of Seattle, broadcast live on at least
three stations simultaneously here in the Bay Area. I thought it was an
underground takeover, especially since the people doing it were total amateurs
(band members &amp; friends I guess).  Unfortunately I didn't get a chance to
record any of it.</P>  
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
