<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Race in Fact and Usage</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY><P>
<A HREF="index.htm"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/smlbbs.gif" ALT="LBBS | " ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">

</A>
<A HREF="../help.htm"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/help.gif" ALT="HELP | " ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">
</A>
<A HREF="mailto:sysop@lbbs.org"><IMG
SRC="../../gifs/feedback.gif" ALT="Feedback" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0" HSPACE="4">
  
</A>
</P>
<HR>
<P><CITE>
The following is a message posted to the Race Forum, by a user continuing a
thread of discussion.</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1>A Comment Answering the Question: What Is Race?</H1>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>PB&gt; says: People's perceived &quot;race&quot; affects every
part of their daily existence as well as the direction of U.S. society, this is
as true for &quot;whites&quot; as it is for &quot;Blacks&quot;, &quot;Latino/as&quot;,
Native Americans, etc. Are you saying it is invalid for PB&gt; oppressed groups
to organize themselves to challenge oppression, that they are therefore
defending racial divisons. I don't agree. Moreover, it does not deal with the
reality of a very segregated society in many spheres of people's lives, and a
culture and PB&gt; ideology where only &quot;white&quot; is considered the norm.
</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>I think, actually, that many of the groups that exist ostensibly to
challenge racism have arisen, understandably, out of a defensive posture among
people who feel memberships in racial classes. However, by adopting the
oppressor's definitions of race, the oppressor was able to build the field of
conflict. No matter who gets affirmative action, for example, it's still
predicated on perceptions of race and difference. So while I agree that
oppressed people can and SHOULD organize for their rights, I think many groups
that exist are inherently ineffectual since they rely on a race-based victim
status for privileges, rather than opposing race-based oppressor status.</P>
<P>(NB: in a society with so much reinforcement for the self-image of northern
european-American straight young thin people, it may be important for a long
time for people to organize into groups with affinity groups of like skin,
weight, sex, gender, sexual orientation, age, or whatever, just to help
themselves get mentally healthy. This does not necessarily translate into ethnic
nationalism, however. Healthy people are not intimidated, nor do they
intimidate.)</P>
<P>On the other hand, there are groups that are inclusive of all colors,
backgrounds, all members of the human race. Roots Against War was a
poor-neighborhood-based anti-war group during the Persian Gulf Massacre. They
never said &quot;We're a Black anti-war group.&quot; Instead, they defined
themselves as opposing war and embracing roots. Any roots were allowed, although
there was a distinct emphasis on leadership by people with third-world roots.
</P>
<P>I saw a big hint to the solution of race divisions on a health insurance
form the other day. It asked if I was &quot;African American, Native American,
Eskimo (sic) or Aleutian Islander, Samoan, Polynesian, Chinese, Japanese,&quot;
and the list was forty items long, with &quot;White&quot; thrown in. Well I tell
you. There are ethnicities galore, but the undying socially constructed race is
not Black (despite Newsweek's cover story, &quot;What Color is Black?&quot;) but
White. Blacks have mostly adopted African-American as a term. They are accepting
their ancestry, but not their &quot;race.&quot; Whites, however, have yet to
give up White Privilege. They can't be northern European-American,
Middle-Eastern-American (that's what I am), because it would mean sacrificing
their hard-won racial identity. </P>
<P>Fifty years ago, White was a much more rarified group, and more so a hundred
years before that. It didn't include Jews, Catholics, or people who ate garlic.
(No kidding: an anti-abortion tract from 1876 wrote of the threat to the white
race by the immigrating unclean hordes, their breath still reeking of garlic.)
Nowadays a lot more people claim whiteness. In this sense, it's like &quot;middle
class.&quot; </P>
<P>Many people won't tear down the edifice from the outside because they hope
to get in, and won't do it from the inside because it's just too cozy. But only
by punishing any oppressive behavior, refusing white privilege when it's
offered, and acknowledging that everyone's a minority, can we hope to eliminate
the ugliness called racism once and for all.</P>
<P>I recommend a magazine out of Harvard U. called &quot;Race Traitor:
eliminate the white race by any means necessary.&quot; I'll post the address
when I find it.</P>
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
