<HR>
<P><CITE>
The following is a message posted to the Race Forum, by a user initiating a
thread of discussion.</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1>A Query about Dealing with Racism?</H1>
<P>My thoughts on the subject of race are plain-spoken mostly due to my recent
experience on the subject and I would like some clarification on the most
rudimentary elements. I have the unique oportunity of working with co-workers
who have very strong feelings about reasons for the current postition of
African-Americans. First, a little background. I live in one of the most
segregated cities in America (Sarasota,Florida). I work in an emergency room of
a public hospital where at least 15% of the patients are Medicaid recipients.
I've been discussing with one co-worker the reasons for the current postion of
African Americans, with her reasoning going as follows: &quot;Blacks think we
owe them something. well we're sick of that. They've had plenty of time to pick
themselves up and find jobs and decent livings. Blacks always think they can use
that slavery issue as a crutch when the simple fact is they're lazy and don't
wan't to work&quot;. And she's not alone in her thinking. Just the other day
another co-worker said, &quot;Blacks have more opportunities now than whites do.
If a white and a black were to be picked for a college, the black would get in
just because he's black. They have all these oportunities being given to them
and they still do nothing with them&quot;. And in two seperate conversations
with other co-workers, there was this strange notion that &quot;blacks even have
an oportunity to go to college. Look at the United Negro College Fund. Blacks
can go to college free if they want, but do they? No!&quot;etc.... Finally, just
yesterday, yet another co-worker (all co-workers with these opinions are white
by the way) said,&quot;I really think blacks are taking seriously what Martin
Luther King said about 'We shall overcome!' I think Black people are trying to
overcome whites....I think they should be limited to having 2 kids per family&quot;.
I could go on. There's a lot more where that came from. And I feel like I'm
fighting a losing battle. The more I argue against this kind of thinking which I
thought was long long behind us, the more I feel they are more firmly committed
to their beliefs. I feel as though the debates I have with my co-workers just
further solidify their prejudices. Racism is quite alive and well in America.
And since I'm so outnumbered I feel like I'm losing my perspective. Could
someone just give me some nice, solid facts to begin countering this most basic
racist thinking?</P> 
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
