<P><CITE>
The following is a message posted to the Race Forum, by a user continuing a
thread of discussion.</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1> A comment on Race and organizing</H1>
<P>I certainly don't want oppressed people to stop organizing to end their
oppression. I do think they will have more success if the different groups unite
to combat their common oppression.  In a recent post by Cecilia Rodriguez, the
U.S. representative of the Zapatistas, she made an offhand comment that it was
so hard to keep the racial/cultural groups' preferred names straight, and that
she hoped she hadn't left any group out. She then went on to decry the state of
a movement in which every &quot;typographical error is assumed to be a political
statement&quot;. She says, and I agree, that all the self-identified
racial/cultural subgroups would do well to unite to accomplish certain really
important goals together.</P>
<P>My father and mother were anthropologists, and the term &quot;race&quot; has
had a special meaning in anthropology. Most of my parent's colleagues agreed
that race was a cultural construct, and that the culture that bound together a
self-perceived racial group was the primary thing. Some, like the late Carleton
Coon, were so blinded by 19th century racial dogma that they felt they had to
claim race was purely biological, and that the four major races sprang from
fourt totally separate non-human species. When I think of the concept of race, I
think of this indefensible argument first.</P>
<P>I am also painfully aware of the problems some of my friends have had
because of their racial/cultural backgrounds. Four of my cousins have married
outside their &quot;racial&quot; group, and their children look like belong to
one group while they identify with another, more complex family. This has led to
problems ranging from embarrassment, to job discrimination to arrest and
beatings. Racism is a cultural artifact of the dominant white civiliztion which
has roots in the outdated concept of race but has grown into something
intolerable and all-pervading. Of course people who are oppressed by racism need
to organize and become stron enough to fight against it. And of course, members
of the dominant white culture need to learn how evil racism is and stop
purveying it.</P>
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
