<P><CITE>
The following is a message posted to the Schools Forum, by a student continuing
and enlarging a thread of discussion.</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1> A Student talks about High School</H1>
<P>Hi,</P>
<P>I am Heather Brutz, Philip Brutz's daughter. I, too, am a ninth grader who
reads Z. I agree with you. Many subjects in school would be far more interesting
if alternative views were taught. The school I am going to now is pretty good
about providing a variety of views on most subjects. Most schools, however, do
not. Most schools only provide the views of those in power at that particular
school. In many cases, this is a capitalist, conservative, white view. In the
case of the school I used to attend, it was a black view. The school I used to
attend was all black. I was THE white student. It was a unique position.</P>
<P>There were (as there are in most things) positive things and negative things
about my old school. On the positive side, you never heard any white,
capitalist, American propaganda. You very rarely heard America glorifed. The
same went for most of the standard good ol' American heroes. Columbus wasn't our
hero. Martin Luther King and Malcolm X were our heroes. They were the ones we
learned about. Similarly, you only occasionally heard the American capitalist
system glorifed. More often, you heard about how the system is racist and
oppressive. Another positive thing I was often exposed to was black pride.
Obviously, the message of &quot;pride in your beautiful skin tones and your rich
African heritage&quot; was not a message that ever had any relevance to me, but
it was still an important message and one that had to be said. </P>
<P>Truthfully, the few problems with my old school that were related to race
had to do with things being taken too far. There would often be negative remarks
made about ALL whites. Usually, when the speaker realized that I was in the
room, they would apoligize and say that of course they didn't mean me, but that
wasn't the point. Remarks should never be made against all people of a certain
race. Another thing that was occasionally taken way too far was religion,
specifically Christianity. The churches in our areaworked really hard to support
our school. That was good. I had no problem with that. The thing I had a problem
with was a tendency for these churches' laeders to give prayers at school
assemblies. These were distinctly Christian prayers, full of &quot;The Lord
Jesus Christ's&quot; name. There were a considerable number of Muslims at my old
school, who shouldn't have been forced to listen to Christian prayers. 	</P>
<P>The absolute biggest problem I had at my old school was totally unrelated to
race and it is one I believe permeates teenagers across the country. It can be
summed up in a single word, &quot;nerd&quot;. </P>
<P>&quot;You read Z?!? You mean, you like read at all? Oh my God. You're a
Socialist? You mean, you have an interest in politics?!? You have straight As?
You mean, you actually think?!? You have concerns beyond just partying?!? Oh my
God, you are such a nerd!&quot; 	If you are a nerd, you will be cruelly taunted.
You will be told that the only sexy part of your body is your brain. You will be
dateless. The few friends you do have will be other outcasts. This happened at
my old school. I have heard from other people that it happens in most schools to
some extent. It doesn't occur too much at the school I am currently going to.
That is probably because the school I am currently going to is an elite, highly
academic, private school where most doctors and lawyers send their kids in the
hopes that their children will receive the education necesary to ensure that
they will be as &quot;successful&quot; as the parents are.</P>
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
