<P><CITE>
The following is a message posted to the Schools Forum, by a recent student
continuing and enlarging a thread of discussion.</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1> On High School and Dropping Out</H1>
<P>While I didn't actually state this, I don't believe, in my original
presentation of this idea, I am an advocate of dropping up of high school.</P>
<P>What I definitely did not make clear is dropping up does not mean not
getting a diploma (GEDs are simple to acquire, relatively speaking). Nor does it
mean stopping learning. As a recent ('91) HS grad, I can attest to the fact that
there is not a single thing that could be more uneducating than attending high
school, especially in a public school. While some alternative HSs seem to be
great, the factories the state calls institutions of learning are a total joke.
They are institutions of programming, and besides basic math and science they
teach no skills of any value, for the most part. Getting out of school is a
positive thing. Not continuing your education is quite negative, of course.</P>
<P>I am presently working with activists at encouraging teens to drop up. We
are organizing provisions for alternative learning methods, living arrangements,
etc. We have intentions of forming education groups consisting of young people
who will perform the tasks of teaching each other and themselves, free from
adult influence. Besides liberating the curricula, this will hopefully serve to
escape the environment of fascistic authoritarian structures (the
structure/nature of schools is even more authoritarian and top-down than
corporations); it will also provide an environment free from adultocratic
dominance, free from state coercion, free from capitalist and statist influence
(recruiters from colleges and military, etc.), free from drugs, etc.</P>
<P>The idea, as Sysop mentioned (presumably he knew me well enough to assume I
wouldn't advocate dropping out for the sake of, well, dropping out), is to
create alternative institutions whereby young people can obtain the best
possible education. I think this must happen in the absense (largely) of adults.
I think this must happen in the absense of authoritarian structures. Schools are
so antidemocratic, no wonder young people graduate thinking they have no right
or responsibility to take charge of and participate in the management of their
own lives and society. When hierarchy and centralization are removed from school
administration, only then will education have the potential to take place in a
liberatory manner. </P>
<P>For Heather and others, I think it is important to remember that while some
students (evidently yourself included) tend to perform well under the conditions
of mainstream schools, most do not. Perhaps what they require is an alternative
educational apparatus. Indeed, maybe even students who perform well in
present-day mainstream institutions would show an improvement under alternative
conditions.</P>
<P>I have plenty of theory to back this up. And there are plenty of examples as
well. There is a booklet by Grace Llewellyn called _Real Lives: Eleven Teenagers
Who Don't Go To School_ which is about success stories. And I know some myself.
</P>
<P>And to clarify the idea of me and others counseling young people to leave
school -- we do not do this in all cases. Only those who have the potential, due
to astuteness, will, ingenuity, etc., to accomplish great things while surviving
without high school. Indeed, many young people -- perhaps most -- are sadly
dependent on the system that was established for the purpose of molding them
into servants.</P>
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
