and enlarging a thread of discussion.</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1>Another High School Student comments</H1>
<P>Heather, well I guess I'm not the only ninth-grader in the country who reads
Z but I wouldn't bet you could fill a classroom with all the people under 16 who
read Z. Your situation in your old school sounds very unique indeed. Personally
I would much rather be taught the views of Malcolm X and Martin Luther King, as
opposed to Columbus and our Founding Fathers. However I would definately have a
problem with christianity being forced into my life. </P>
<P>It sounds as though most of the views taught at your old school contained
more truth than most views taught in other schools today. However the statements
made against all whites or all blacks, or all whatever, have no place in any
education teaching that racism is bad.  It is understandable that people who are
constantly being oppressed would feel the need to blame someone, although it is
still inexscuable rascist behavior. I wounder whether the black teachers who
taught that capitalism was bad would still teach these views if the situation
were reversed and they were suddenly to find themselves the beneficiaries of our
current economic system. </P>
<P>I haven't really had a problem with being called a socialist, as most young
people don't even know what a Socialist is. And as to being branded a nerd, I
don't really feel this - although I do always get straight A's. I think the
reason people call someone else a nerd is based on several factors: 1) there is
probably a fear of anyone who cares about understanding why the world is so
messed up and 2) in general society portrays anyone who doesn't fit any
description of &quot;normal&quot; as a freak, or a nerd. For one thing my
appearance isn't what most people think of as a &quot;nerd&quot;. Although I
look fairly normal these days I had longer than average hair for the first
semester at school, thus I was probably branded as a freak or &quot;headbanger&quot;
although I was indeed the same person as I am now. Its unfortunate that people
constantly label everything in thier lives. And people here are no exception as
most of them often refer to themselves as leftists.</P>
<P>Indeed one option to get a &quot;quality&quot; education is to go to an
elitist school but personally I'm much happier in a public city school with a
fairly even racial mix of people. Hopefully some time in the near future courses
will be offered which specifically teach leftist (another label) views.  --Gabe
</P>
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
