<HR>
<H1>Another User Comments re High School</H1>
<P>Heather, I very much liked your answer on dropping out of school.</P>
<P>I think it's a bad idea, even if it the intentions are quite right, for
another reason.</P>
<P>In the current context any such trend would not be a trend toward furthering
education, toward pursuing curiosity, etc. but, I think, would be part and
parcel of the anit-intellectual fever among the children of working people and
poor people.</P>
<P>Also the few who drop out will be those who, with their parents, might best
wage a battle to improve the schools.</P>
<P>But, I wonder. Suppose, for the sake of argument, that there were
substantial and growing social movements and that they began to offer some sort
of collective home schooling for young people...or counter schools. Not dropping
out, then, but intensifying and altering the school experience.</P>
<P>Perhaps that is what Brian had in mind, anyhow, more than the image of the &quot;dropout&quot;...
</P>
<P>What would you think about that?</P>
</BODY></HTML>
