<HR>
<H1>And Another User Replies re High School With a New Slant</H1>
<P>I read your post, Heather, with a great deal of interest about many of the
points raised. But one thing, in particular, struck. And I think it is
exceptionally important for people to face it and try to figure how to do
something about it.</P>
<P>It was your description of the way that young people react to reading,
thinking, having opinions, caring about knowledge.</P>
<P>It is a remarkable fact, I think, that this society has managed to get poor
people and particularly black and latino people to actually decry knowledge.
</P>
<P>I think I can understand the &quot;positive&quot; basis for it. Somehow
reading and writing is seen as the preserve not merely of nerds, but of those
who are hated, those who dominate. And there is much truth in this. The trouble
is, of course, that the strategy of devaluing knowledge and thinking leads to
the one tool which people on the bottom of every hierarchy can't have taken from
them, their minds and thoughts, literally being jettisoned by the suffering
people themselves, as a sign of achievement, no less.</P>
<P>This is truly horrible.</P>
<P>One of the heroes you mentioned, Malcolm X, was an absolute master at
confronting this kind of self destruction.</P>
<P>Others need to have the same courage he had to tell these young people that
they are violating themselves, literally playing a game their oppressors have
designed for them, a losing game...</P>
<P>And the thing that infuriates me the most about this whole thing is that
there are many on the left, who talk about the ills of rationality, who actually
play into this horribleness...</P>
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
