<P><CITE>
The following is a message posted to the Schools Forum, by a user redirecting a
thread of discussion.</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1>And a High School Teacher Replies re High School</H1>
<P>I'm glad to see this lively debate around dropping out of school. I haven't
had time to respond to all the interesting ideas and arguments but here's my two
cents as a long-time teacher in a dysfunctional urban public high school, the
parent of a soon-to-be freshman, and an education activist </P>
<P>I think dropping out of high school means totally different things for those
who have a realistic (not just theoretical or potential) alternative routes to
getting an education. For some bright, priviliged or resourceful kids I can
imagine it making sense to bail out of lifeless high schools and finding an
individual, or the (very rare) &quot;alternative school&quot; path to acquiring
academic skills, knowledge and intellectual growth. </P>
<P>But for the great majority of kids dropping out of high school is a road to
educational oblivion. Few poor students of color or working class kids are going
to find the resources or support they need to sustain their education within
their own families or communities. It reminds me a little of the &quot;free
school movement&quot; in the 60s when some students and teachers, who saw quite
clearly how bad and authortarian traditional schools were, opted to drop out and
form &quot;free schools&quot; or &quot;alternative schools.&quot; They
undoubtedly helped some kids survive (mostly in privileged communities that had
the resources and &quot;comfort levels&quot; to give such efforts room to
experiment) But they also took some of the best and most critical energy out of
the public system, and they didn't survive very long or reach large numbers of
kids.And they didn't have a lasting impact on the schools left behind.</P>
<P>I think the public education system sucks. But it's still the only
alternative for the majority of young people. And it's one of the few remaining
places where the population comes together for a common purpose. It's also under
attack as a &quot;socialist monopoly&quot; by forces who want to privatize and
dismantle it. I don't have any argument with someone who finds an individual
path out of his/her own school nightmare. But as a social strategy, I think
students should make demands on and help transform the public system rather than
abandon it, especially where's there's a critical mass big enough to organize
walk outs or protests. Let's face it, the right wants to give up on public
education because it doesn't want an educated population. We need to claim
public schools for ourselves and make them more democratic, more effective
arenas of struggle.</P>
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
