<P><CITE>
The following is a message posted to the Schools Forum, responding to comments
from another user.</CITE></P>
<HR>
<H1>
A School Founder Replies to Views about Schools in Society</H1>
<P>I very much appreciated your post on alternatives to public schooling and
the necessity to invest energy in public schools themselves. It was both
realistic and optimistic. With another personal story, I wanted to illustrate
some of the limits of opting out of the public system.</P>
<P>About ten years ago, I worked with a number of parents and teachers to set
up a local, alternative school in our city (Rochester, New York).  Stan, you may
even be familiar with the school, Cobblestone School, for we worked with Doug
Noble, who I believe has spent some time recently working with you. Setting up
the school was an enormous amount of work, demanding much parental involvement
on all levels. Our initial budget was miniscule, and the various regulatory
bodies that looked at us were doubtful we could succeed for this reason. But it
got going, in a somewhat dark church basement, with three teachers and twenty
students.</P>
<P>The place was a jewel. It was probably the most full-of-life, joyful
environment I have ever been in. My kids (three of them) blossomed in the
several years each of them spent in that lively, child-centered, non
hierarchical place. Students were a mixed lot, many races and classes, primarily
coming from families where parents were much involved with their children,
though not well-to-do. The kids came to love learning, to understand a great
deal about their own interests, and to interact with adults in ways that were
helpful to them, rather than through submission and obedience (or revolt against
those things). They left ultimately because the school's program got too small
at the upper grade school levels, and they seemed to need more social
interaction with peers.</P>
<P>The school has since grown to be fairly large (150-200 students, 15-20
teachers) and now occupies a beautiful building. But the atmosphere of those
early years has dissipated, parents are no longer involved in the same ways, and
the students now come from largely white, upper middle class backgrounds. The
pressure for that change, I think, was largely financial. Teachers needed more
to live on, everyone sought some degree of security for the school, wealthier
parents could pay more, parents finding a good alternative by looking around
(rather than creating it) may be less motivated or trained to be involved in the
same ways, and so on. Also, I guess, success of this sort is a kind of American
dream. But in the last years we had a kid there, my wife and I (and other early
parents) came to feel rather out of place in what came to seem a fairly
yuppified, homogeneous atmosphere. It is still a better alternative in many
respects to some public schools, but worse in others (mixing of classes and
races, for example). I'd have to say that, after these ten years, it doesn't
look so different from the private schools that existed at the time it was set
up, and which we felt were inadequate. There are people there who are concerned
with the present state of things and wish to make changes, but this is ironic.
</P>
<P>I'm not saying that, had we involved ourselves in public school reform, we
would have had any more lasting impact. There have been similar attempts to set
up new public schools here, and over time as the original parents and teachers
leave the scene, the places have changed. I guess I'm suggesting that all of
this reform is temporary, at least under present conditions, that what you have
left after many years is an institution that still needs to have people go into
it, of go after it, to make it responsive to their needs. As our kids have gone
on in the city public schools, we have been much impressed with some of the
people they have encountered, and believe that there is a considerable reservoir
of people who are interested in humane change in the schools. One of the things
we did, in addition to creating a fine school for our kids for a few years, was
to take a good pocket of activist people away from that reservoir. If those
people stayed involved in public schools, well, who knows? Personally, not being
a teacher or having young kids anymore, I'm more inclined to leave schools to
someone else now, and work for more fundamental economic and political changes
that might permit schools to be good in the first place.</P>
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
