<title>Hooked And Wired 1</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#F8F8F8" link="#001F76" vlink="#001F76"
alink="#001F76">

<blockquote>
    <h2>from the pages of<img src="../../gifs/oldsmzma.gif"
    alt="../" align="top" hspace="4" width="108" height="37"> </h2>
</blockquote>

<hr>

<blockquote>
    <h1 align="center">Hooked and Wired 1 </h1>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><em>Michael Albert </em></font></p>
    <p align="center">&nbsp;</p>
    <blockquote>
        <p>There is no point ignoring real and unstoppable
        trends. Telecommunications is not a fad. It is not going
        away, Telecommunications is, instead, primed to become as ubiquitous
        as television and telephones. It is plausible that shortly
        there will be more telecomputing than desktop computing.
        Communications-related software may be used more often
        and more widely in the home than any other kind. And, if
        even a fraction of this happens, where will the progressive
        community fit in the evolving equation? </p>
        <p>Many commentators have pointed out one grave danger--commercialism
        leading to exclusion. In this scenario, as with TV
        bandwidth, room on the communications highway, and
        certainly the opportunity and space to provide serious
        offerings will be prohibitively expensive. Huge corporations
        will dominate the definition and tone of what is now
        called cyberspace. Barriers to entry in the area of
        provision will be great. Limits on the range of material available
        will be severe. Users will easily receive ream upon ream
        of information--for example, catalogs, order forms, info-tainment--but
        will have very limited ability to put information into
        the system, much less really interact with others
        throughout their communities and society. Content, much
        less dissident content, will be excluded or disappear into
        the margins. </p>
        <p>I have nothing much to add to the discussion of the potential
        commercialization and monopolization of the means of
        telecommunications. I hope the nightmare vision can be averted,
        and believe it may well be. What I want to suggest is
        that commercialization, from the top down, is not the
        only problem leftists face along the communications
        highway. It is a rock we might get crushed against, but
        there is also a more subtle, though interrelated, hard place
        that could wreck our hopes. </p>
        <p>Suppose the Internet remains largely uncommercial and, even
        more to the point, decentralized, and that it continues to
        attract new users at a fantastic rate, thereby remaining the
        largest and most diverse telecommunication option available.
        And suppose also that we progressives and leftists do our
        homework well and learn how to work efficiently and economically
        with Internet technology. What pitfalls nonetheless
        remain? </p>
        <p>The first thing to consider would be cost. Perhaps,
        though formally free to participate and make our views
        available, the technology will be too costly. This is
        possible, but doesn't look likely. The price of required
        equipment is already relatively low and is dropping steadily,
        with no end in sight. The tools required to prepare
        information for even the fanciest presentation on the
        Internet have modest cost, even compared to the kinds of
        equipment leftists already regularly use in print work.
        It can be accomplished at a typical contemporary desktop
        computer, with free shareware. Even purchasing and
        setting up a full scale communication site, able to
        provide Internet connectivity to thousands of subscribers
        and to present special and diverse progressive
        telecommunications options of its own, is not oppressively
        expensive, though staffing it can get costly, as with
        staffing any extensive project. </p>
        <p>No. These are not the concerns I want to address.
        Instead, I worry about a primary virtue of telecommunications, because
        I think it may also be telecommunications' most daunting weakness.
        What I am referring to, ironically, is the effect of
        making information and material available for free and
        the most natural ways of dealing with the problems that
        free availability creates. </p>
        <p>First, why is free availability of
        information--whether articles, reports, discussions,
        photos, other graphics, live talk shows, recordings of
        public speeches, etc.--a virtue in the first place? Well,
        by making these resources available at no cost beyond
        that of owning telecommunications equipment, we can make
        it as widely available as possible. No fees means maximum
        distribution and makes it easy, for example, for local
        activists and others to get as much of whatever is made
        available as they want. More, people who aren't sure what they
        want, can try out dissident offerings at no cost, and, if
        they like it, get a steady dose, again at no cost. </p>
        <p>So what is the problem? Well, the thing to think
        about, it seems to me, is excessive unmanageable volume,
        on the one hand, and declining quality, on the other. </p>
        <p>If it is cheap or free to place information into a
        system from which it is also cheap or free to withdraw
        it, the amount of information made available is likely to
        become astronomical. More, it will be presented without
        much differentiation as to source or quality. The user
        will therefore have to find those items of particular
        import for him or her, among all the rest. More, if there
        are no revenues from which to pay people producing
        information (photos, articles, whatever) it becomes very
        difficult for people to do that work in a sustained
        manner, to devote themselves to it, and the quality of
        the product therefore declines as more and more of it is
        hobby output, or late night output, etc. So we have more
        and more stuff, with less and less quality. Each user has
        to search for the worthy amongst the uninteresting or
        useless. The time involved in this endeavor starts to be
        oppressive. The need to wade through masses of material
        begins to curtail participation. </p>
        <p>Consider a few examples. Suppose progressive political photos
        are made available free online. What happens to Impact
        Visuals, an organization that sells progressive photos?
        You might say, OK, it disappears, but there is a better
        system in its place. That's progress. But the thing is, Impact
        Visuals isn't an unnecessary rip off. It funnels fees to
        photographers enabling them to go out and get equipment
        and to go places to take the needed shots. Also, people
        at Impact Visuals, editors, take the time to pick and choose
        among possible shots those to actually offer, so that when
        a periodical asks them for photos on Timor, or homelessness,
        or whatever, and receives a packet, it is already a
        selected set of quality offerings to choose from. The
        freeness, in place of Impact Visuals, enhances distribution,
        but if Impact Visuals is replaced by generalized posting
        of progressive photos, then in time the quality of the
        photos available to be posted declines, and, as well, the
        time required for the organization or periodical that
        wants to get photos, doesn't decline, but increases,
        supposing they can find anything worthy at all. </p>
        <p>Or consider David Barsamian's remarkably useful
        efforts traversing the country and assembling great and
        useful interviews with progressive folks, and then making
        them available. What happens to that? First his
        interveiws start to appear free, which seems like a big
        plus because many more people get them, and hear about
        David, which we all want. But then David's revenues dry
        up because everyone is getting his stuff free, he can't
        go out and do interviews anymore, and so his interviews
        are available in lesser numbers, and finally not at all.
        Other interviews appear, you might say, but without
        revenues to fund interviewers able to do hard work, they
        are everything from interviews with neighbors to , far
        less often, valuable ones. And where is the source that
        distinguishes the wheat from the chaff, at least
        reasonably well, so we don't all have to spend the time
        looking through masses of material to find what we want?
        What prevents the decline in quality, the inappropriate
        growth in volume? The same thing can be said of Z. Make
        all the articles available free. Make the free digital offerings
        steadily more and more like those in the magazine, with
        graphics and all. At first it is great. New people see
        the material and perhaps also contact Z. But in time,
        print subscriptions begin to decline, as people get it
        digital representations free. There is still a flood of digital
        articles, but not the ones Z's existence previously made
        possible. And there are no filters to help users easily access
        quality material. Revenues becomes less and less available
        to help writers find the time to prepare quality pieces,
        and so on. After a while, Z as a print media institution,
        and others like it, become impossible. </p>
        <p>Are there answers to these fears, admittedly
        exaggerated for emphasis here? I think so. I think it is
        possible that we can create telecommunications
        institutions that make the dissemination of information
        and materials easier, less expensive, and more
        effective--at the same time as we preserve or enlarge a
        flow of revenues able to sustain writers, photographers, interviewers,
        etc., and institutional sources of prefiltered material
        (publishers) both for digital and other forms of media.
        But it won't happen if we just lumber along with the info-current
        without thinking about these dynamics carefully and
        figuring out how to operate so as to avoid difficulties,
        yet also gain the benefits of telecommunications. </p>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
</body>
</html>
