content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="Author" content>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Catch 22s -- Labor's Choice</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<ul>
    <li><ul>
            <li><ul>
                    <li><ul>
                            <li><h1 align="center"><font
                                color="#FF0000"><b>Catch 22s</b></font> </h1>
                                <div align="center"><center><address>
                                    <font color="#FF0000"
                                    size="4"><b>by michael albert</b></font><font
                                    size="4"> </font>
                                </address>
                                </center></div><p><font
                                color="#FF0000" size="6"><b>O</b></font>ne
                                of the ways that an oppressive
                                society regulates dissent is by
                                structuring our lives so we are
                                always choosing the better of two
                                options neither of which are
                                actually in our interest. We work
                                at Stop and Shop or Ford. choose
                                Coke or Pepsi, vote or refuse to
                                vote, learn to endure boredom in
                                school or to hustle and fight on
                                the street. Even if we opt for
                                whichever choice makes us a
                                little happier relative to the
                                other, it nonetheless helps
                                reinforce our ultimate
                                subordination. Bad or less bad. The
                                origin and purpose of some of
                                these Catch-22s are easy to see
                                within society&#146;s defining
                                institutions. In other cases, the situation
                                is a more subtle. </p>
                                <h2>Labor&#146;s Choice? </h2>
                                <p>If you are a union official,
                                what is your agenda? On the one hand,
                                the union&#146;s mandate is to
                                serve its members. This entails a
                                host of activities, ranging from
                                providing various services and support systems,
                                to dealing with grievances and
                                trying to win better pay and
                                conditions. On the other hand,
                                however, what about the
                                union&#146;s overall ability to
                                do these things, as opposed to
                                how well it does them given its
                                current capacity? Is the overall
                                capacity increasing or declining
                                and what should you do about
                                that? </p>
                                <p>From inside the unions&#146;
                                staff and leadership structures,
                                the situation has the appearance
                                of a rock and a hard place. Your position
                                in the union, your income, what
                                good you can do for other workers,
                                and what pleasures you have at
                                work and in your life due to your
                                income and status, all depend on
                                doing a good job for your current
                                constituency, the workers now on
                                the job and already in the union.
                                This constituency feels, first
                                and foremost, the attention given
                                to their job situations and grievances.
                                So if you work on this, they are
                                pleased and you can continue your efforts.
                                On the other hand, for every
                                dollar of union resources that
                                you apply to enlarging the union
                                by doing outreach to build
                                membership, each current member
                                of the union gets less immediate
                                return on their dues. If average yearly
                                dues in the labor movement are
                                $250 per member, let&#146;s say,
                                do you spend all of it, most of
                                it, some of it, or little of it serving
                                the existing membership? </p>
                                <p>If you spend the whole $250 on
                                existing members, you protect your
                                job in the union by fulfilling your
                                mandate, but you do nothing to
                                guard against decline much less
                                to increase labor&#146;s options
                                in the future. On the other hand,
                                the more resources you put to
                                getting new members in new workplaces,
                                the more you enhance the future
                                potential for assisting all
                                members, but at the expense of
                                present services and therefore at
                                risk of your position. </p>
                                <p>The Catch-22 that you feel is
                                that your immediate constituency, which
                                empowers and in essence employs
                                you at the standard of pleasure
                                and income you now enjoy, wants a
                                clear return for their dues, but
                                the size of your constituency,
                                and also whether you can deliver
                                much to it in the long run depends
                                on how much of their dues you
                                take from immediate services to
                                them and allot to signing on new
                                members at new sites, setting up new
                                locals, and so on. As to how the
                                choice is actually made nowadays,
                                one union organizer recently told
                                me that defending the status quo,
                                even while watching it slip-slide
                                into decay and oblivion for want
                                of efforts to grow, was still the
                                agenda for all but a tiny handful
                                of locals. To put it in stark
                                terms, to get a new member may
                                cost $1,000, on average. So if
                                you lose 10% of your overall
                                membership yearly, you would need
                                to allot 40% of your union budget
                                to organizing, just to keep the
                                union&#146;s size from declining.
                                But what is the average allotment
                                to organizing? I&#146;ve been
                                told the best estimate is from 2%
                                to 3%, surely not much more. </p>
                                <h2>Activism&#146;s Aims? </h2>
                                <p>Suppose you are a leftist
                                activist/organizer building a new institution,
                                running for office, or speaking
                                widely across the country,
                                choosing your modus operandi.
                                Perhaps you are part of an institution
                                that does good&#151;a publishing
                                project, a clinic or community
                                center, a national environmental
                                or women&#146;s organization,
                                etc., or a progressive candidate,
                                or perhaps a &quot;left intellectual&quot;
                                who speaks and writes widely,
                                organizing by that means. Again,
                                do you orient your daily choices
                                to delivering what the people who
                                have been relating to your work
                                expect, and are perhaps paying
                                for, or do you risk what exists
                                in pursuit of something larger?
                                Do you defend your niche and its
                                opportunities for doing good, and
                                the returns to you in pleasures
                                and income that it affords, or do
                                you risk that niche in trying to
                                increase your future impact and
                                that of your organization or
                                project, or constituency, or
                                related organizations? Is the
                                agenda to work on only stability,
                                or on a risky effort at growth
                                which allots some resources from
                                tried and true avenues to innovation?
                                For example, do you allot all resources
                                to improving publications, or
                                serving members, etc. or do you
                                channel some resources into
                                trying to grow, or trying to set
                                up new projects and institutions?
                                Do you go only for immediate
                                votes, or try to build
                                infrastructure to help in future elections?
                                Or, as a noted speaker, do you go
                                out and deliver what people
                                expect and ask for, or do you
                                bring along neophytes with
                                potential, introduce them to
                                audiences, give some of your time
                                for them to speak, etc.,
                                increasing future potential in
                                your field by training and promoting
                                new speakers, but at the expense
                                of immediate quality and
                                satisfaction of your audiences? </p>
                                <p>As with the labor case, the
                                bias in movement projects, candidacies,
                                and speaking engagements is also
                                on preserving what is, not on
                                trying to enlarge and diversify
                                future options. Most movement projects
                                achieve some level of operational stability,
                                often taking huge and courageous
                                chances to succeed to that point,
                                but then sit pat, ever after
                                minimizing chances of failure by
                                eschewing risk and innovation
                                lest what has been accomplished
                                is lost. Precisely as in the
                                union example, above. </p>
                                <p>So what can we say about all
                                this? Well, from the outside I think
                                it is pretty obvious that if the overarching
                                agenda is to improve
                                people&#146;s lives and life
                                circumstances there has got to be
                                a greater orientation toward
                                growth, diversification, and innovation,
                                rather than mere holding actions.
                                More, the holding actions not
                                risk decline, they make it almost
                                inevitable, in the long run, anyhow.
                                All of us can see this looking at
                                the &quot;other&quot; person&#146;s
                                or organizations behavior, but
                                not so easily looking in the
                                mirror. Yet we are on a
                                historical treadmill, right now,
                                that makes standing pat a recipe
                                for sure decline. I think we therefore
                                need to figure out how to operate
                                so that we can shift at least
                                somewhat from trying mostly to
                                preserve past accomplishments to
                                trying to attain new victories.
                                Radical means not only trying to
                                get to the heart of issues, but
                                also trying to win. While not
                                overextending or losing touch
                                with the exigencies of the
                                reality we must today endure,
                                still, being radical means, as
                                best we can, refusing to settle. </p>
                                <p>Consider this passage from
                                Virginia Woolf as a possible
                                guide to radical attitude:
                                &quot;Behind us lies the
                                patriarchal system; the private
                                house, with its nullity, its
                                immorality, its hypocrisy, its servility.
                                Before us lies the public world,
                                the professional system, with its
                                possessiveness, its jealousy, its
                                pugnacity, its greed. The one
                                shuts us up like slaves in a
                                harem; the other forces us to circle,
                                like caterpillars head to tail,
                                round and round the mulberry
                                tree, the sacred tree, of property.
                                It is a choice of evils. Each is
                                bad&#133;. Break the ring, the
                                vicious circle, the dance round and
                                round the mulberry tree, the
                                poison tree of intellectual
                                harlotry.&quot; </p>
                                <p>Why can&#146;t labor develop a
                                union structure and ethos that
                                makes immediate service and
                                future growth mutually supportive
                                and seen by all as mutually
                                necessary? Why can&#146;t
                                movement activists, candidates,
                                and speakers see and help their constituencies
                                see that unless one is enlarging
                                and innovating, one is declining.
                                I suppose another relevant quote,
                                this time from my favorite bard,
                                is, &quot;He not busy being born
                                is busy dying.&quot; </p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </li>
</ul>
</body>
</html>
