<title>Of Wishes and Bitches </title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#F8F8F8" link="#001F76" vlink="#001F76"
alink="#001F76">

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<blockquote>
    <h2>from the pages of<img src="../oldsmzma.gif" alt="../"
    align="top" hspace="4" width="108" height="37"> </h2>
</blockquote>

<hr>

<blockquote>
    <h1 align="center">Of Wishes and Bitches </h1>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><em>Lydia Sargent </em></font></p>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><em></em></font>&nbsp;</p>
    <blockquote>
        <p>Welcome to Hotel Satire where gals are serving up the
        cocktails and canapes for their men, who are back to
        being forceful and manly again, after years of suffering
        the feminist terrorist Democratic regime led by Hillary
        &quot;the Bitch&quot; Clinton. Ya gotta love this new
        atmosphere where we can slur blacks and gals and
        &quot;First Ladies&quot; without getting jumped on by
        terrorists (i.e., lesbians); where revolution (i.e. a
        return to the good old days of 1830 or so) is in the air. </p>
        <p>In the spirit of the new contract with America, the
        gals here at the Hotel are also thinking creatively about
        what we want for America. After hours, weeks, months of
        deliberation, we realized Newt's contract with America
        isn't about thinking, much less creatively. It's about
        trashing certain points of view on grounds of
        authoritarianism, then proposing a list of absolutes,
        based on hate, with no basis in fact, that promote
        classic neocolonialism and quasi fascism, and
        subsequently presenting these as revolutionary ideas,
        promoting liberty and justice. In this new spirit of
        autocratic liberation, where we can freely jettison a
        large portion of the population, here's what I want (and
        know I'll get) in 1995. If any of this disagrees with
        Newt's wishes, please disregard what I want, as there's
        no sense in having more than one point of view in this
        great democracy of ours. </p>
        <p>(1) Can we please have much, much more of Newt. Five
        photos a day in the newspaper is just not enough.
        Likewise can we have more of Newt's mom? On TV. In the
        news. At the mall. We want more of Newt's mom so we can
        find out what Newt thinks about everything, but most
        particularly his views on other prominent gals (i.e.,
        lesbians) who are terrorizing our great country, not just
        Hillary, the First Lady to you lefties, a bitch to the
        rest of us. </p>
        <p>(2) There is nothing so moving, inspiring, and just
        plain right as front page photos of white guys like
        Clinton, a Cardinal or two, and Jerry Falwell as they
        emerge from policy meetings dealing exclusively with the
        topic of gals' gynecology. Who would know better about
        birth, birth control, children, parenting, and gals'
        crotches and wombs than three white guys, one of whom
        took a vow of chastity; all of whom hold power in the
        patriarchal state and church? </p>
        <p>(3) That leftie mag Time declared the Pope as Man of
        the Year for 1994. Finally, they got it right. Who better
        to lead the post-triumph of democracy era than someone
        who claims divine right (along with property and other
        stuff valued in the millions) and absolute power over
        people's spiritual and sex lives, not to mention the
        subservience of gals in the most effective and complete
        patriarchy known to man? The image of the Pope travelling
        throughout the world in that nifty bullet proof,
        rehabilitated armored vehicle,while people worship and
        kiss his ring, sets just the right tone for emerging
        democracies, don't you think? </p>
        <p>(4) The other day, I saw a newspaper photo of Hillary
        calling a Bingo game. How beautiful she looked. When she
        talks of things like universal health care, she looks so
        silly. When she calls out I-25 and B-14, she looks so at
        home, so right. That's what we wish for for all those
        gals who have gone astray and wandered away from their
        kitchen duties or had a thought or two--a chance to call
        out letters and numbers in a game that takes no skill,
        creativity, intelligence, or effort whatsoever. </p>
        <p>(5) On other gal fronts, can we have more of Winona
        Ryder, please? Here's why. In the Boston Globe of
        December 26, when being interviewed about her new movie
        Little Women, she says, &quot;I guess Jo is everybody's
        favorite character, but she's also the hardest role I've
        ever had to play&lt;193&gt;she had a lot more energy than
        I do. I was worried at first, because I really don't like
        those feisty young characters, tough cookies, ready to
        wheel into action&lt;193&gt;I insisted that she be more
        vulnerable.&quot; </p>
        <p>Gals, could you wish for anything more? If there's one
        thing we need in Hollywood and the nation it's gals who
        are more vulnerable. Let Winona rewrite all the classic
        feisty heroines, like&lt;193&gt;.uh&lt;193&gt;.Anna
        Karenina. Plus, who better to play the role of a feisty
        gal ready to wheel into action, than someone who doesn't
        like those feisty gals? </p>
        <p>(6) Can one ever have too many human interest stories
        about that hero for the 1990s, John Salvi? I can't. You
        just have to love a guy who wants, if found guilty, to be
        put to death for murder or, if found innocent, to become
        a priest. We hope he's found innocent, so we gals can
        join his parish and listen to his weekly sermons on life
        and gals' gynecology, something he clearly knows lots
        about. Meantimes, let's learn as much as we can about the
        man. What were his first words? Where did he get that
        cute haircut? What is his impression of Hillary? Barbara
        Walters? Connie Chung? Does he, too, think Hillary is a
        bitch? Can a murderer make a good priest? These are the
        questions we want asked and answered in the coming year. </p>
        <p>(7) Can The Lion King be the only movie that kids
        under the age of 14 get to see this year? In fact, can it
        be a key part of the curriculum in all the public
        schools, where lefties have been forcing their fascist
        humanitarian views on kids for the last 30 years? What
        better way to introduce such democratic concepts as
        &quot;king,&quot; &quot;monarchy,&quot; and &quot;bow
        down&quot; than regular showings of this great cartoon
        movie. </p>
        <p>Along those lines, we really wish that Pat Robertson
        could be the Secy of Education under the new Gingrich
        administration. Who better to break the liberal/left
        totalitarian stranglehold than someone whose job is to
        keep people on their knees and worshipping. The school
        curriculum could be all of Pat's writings, plus the Bible
        as interpreted by Pat, plus continuous showings of The
        Lion King. where all the animals bow down to a windswept
        blond-maned beast male autocratic king. Where all the
        animals of color are subservient or parasitic hyenas.
        Plus, during recess the kids could help out with Pat's
        endless phonothons to raise that crucial $250,000 needed
        to fund the next phonothon to raise that crucial
        $500,000, and so on. </p>
        <p>(8) Can we get that gal historian, Christina Jeffries,
        rehired? This is priority one. The only gal allowed to
        forego the housewife duties to write a history of the
        House of Representatives is one who thinks a history
        curriculum taught in public schools that tries to make
        kids understand the Holocaust weights schools toward
        leftism by not presenting the Nazi point of view. Can
        there ever be enough taught and said about the Nazi point
        of view? We need this gal. Not only should she write the
        History of the House (and kudos, Christina, for including
        your husband in this project), but of America, making
        sure to balance the Nazi point of view with the Nazi
        point of view. </p>
        <p>(9) Let's have more of Brad Pitt. What more can I say? </p>
        <p>(10) Can we finally, once and for all, stop the flow
        of cash to those in need, and pick up the flow of cash to
        those who deserve it? Like me, for instance. You don't
        know how hard it is to run a household on a meager
        $500,000 a year, my hard-earned income from inherited
        stocks. Along the same lines, let's stop the flow of cash
        to anyone who might use it in a way which I find
        obnoxious, i.e., who don't keep up their end by shopping
        incessantly when they're not working 80 hour weeks. No
        money to any gal having sex without getting the ring on
        the finger and the proper sanctioning by church and/or
        state (i.e, welfare moms, teens, lesbians). If Newt's mom
        can marry at sixteen, so can the rest of you deadbeats. </p>
        <p>(11) People who come here from other countries,
        shouldn't be able to make a decent living. Period.
        (Unless they're caucasian or good at computers or
        ex-Nazis.) If these non-caucasians want to be servants or
        even slaves, they can do so. But no special treatment, as
        in basic rights to food and shelter, and definitely no
        luxuries like health care , clothing, or time off. It's
        not fair to the rest of us who were here originally
        because our ancestors came over from Europe, a civilized
        continent if ever there was one. Let's send these
        non-caucasians home or put them in jail or in a maid's
        uniform. Or, as Newt proposes, we'll finance a laptop for
        all of them, so they can have access to all Newt's
        committee meetings. Who needs basic rights or justice,
        when you can have a laptop, I've always said. </p>
        <p>(12) Let's focus the media on one thing only, that is,
        up to the minute, extensive, details on every known
        and/or possible inhumanity/horror ever committed by one
        person or group of people on another person or group.
        When we aren't hearing/seeing this stuff, let's have up
        to the minute details on every known or possible disease
        or plague or natural disaster that humans might endure,
        including dire predictions about the future of humanity,
        particularly that we will be hit by an asteroid, and
        soon. I especially enjoy all news bulletins that alert me
        to the possible dangers in my own home--bathroom,
        basement, wherever! This is important, because we need to
        be in a constant state of fear, and in constant need of
        all things pharmaceutical. There's nothing we can do
        about these things except take legal drugs and stay in
        the only safe place left--hunched in front of the TV,
        watching shows about the dangers lurking everywhere--in
        our Fruit Loops, in our Fruit of the Looms. </p>
        <p>(13) A corrolary to (12) is the conclusion that going
        outside to shop is too dangerous. So can we please have
        home shopping during our regular programs? Regular
        network advertising is too complex, I can't even follow
        what the product is in some of these ads. Plus the lag
        time between commercials and shopping expeditions can be
        over 5 hours. This is too long. I may forget how
        wonderful that car was, how delicious that food was. </p>
        <p>Let's take a tip from MTV where 800 numbers flash
        during prime time shows. &quot;Beavis and Butthead&quot;
        offered 39 different products in a half an hour. A Chevy
        Chase bank has issued a Rolling Stones Visa card so you
        can groove while you peruse. While we gals don't approve
        of and never watch MTV, we like the instant shop concept.
        In fact, why can't we please have the chance to shop and
        purchase whenever we're facing a screen of any kind?
        While at the word processor, as you enter those recipes
        or write little notes about what your husband and kids
        did that day. Also, please program continuous soaps or
        reruns of &quot;I Dream of Jeannie,&quot; with products
        and phone numbers flashing throughout. </p>
        <p>(14) While I was never that much of a fan of Muslim
        fundamentalism or Kuwait, still one has to support the
        Emir and his emerging democracy whenever possible. Also,
        I was very inspired by something that happened recently
        in Kuwait. A kind of parable for our times. It seems the
        Muslim fundamentalists introduced a bill to segregate
        male and female students in classrooms, libraries, and
        restaurants at the University. Parliament voted it down,
        after it had passed the first round and was expected to
        win. For some unfathomable reason, the Kuwait government
        doesn't want Islamic religious law to be the sole law of
        the lands, so to speak. University students were
        understandably angry over this negative vote, but
        fundamentalists promised them segregation one day.
        &quot;How can I concentrate on an exam when the teacher
        makes a female sit beside me?&quot; said Fares Inizi, 21,
        an engineering student. How indeed. </p>
        <p>We might ask and wish the same for America: &quot;Why
        should Newt, or anyone like him, have to sit next to a
        gal when he's trying to do something important, like,
        say, get rid of gals?&quot; Why indeed, Bitch. </p>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>

<hr>

<p>&nbsp;</p>
</body>
