<title>Rethinking Teacher Unionism </title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#F8F8F8" link="#001F76" vlink="#001F76"
alink="#001F76">

<blockquote>
    <p>&nbsp;</p>
    <blockquote>
        <h2>from the pages of<img src="oldsmzma.gif" alt="../"
        align="top" hspace="4" width="108" height="37"> </h2>
    </blockquote>
    <hr>
    <h1 align="center">Rethinking Teacher Unionism </h1>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><em>Stan Karp </em></font></p>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><em></em></font>&nbsp;</p>
    <blockquote>
        <p>Civil rights activist Bernice Regan Johnson,
        reflecting on the challenges of political organizing,
        once said, &quot;If you're in a coalition and you feel comfortable,
        your coalition isn't broad enough.&quot; </p>
        <p>For seven years, the National Coalition of Education
        Activists (NCEA) has been putting this idea to the test
        by attempting to build a multi-racial, grassroots network
        of parents, teachers and community activists working in
        many different ways for school change across the country. NCEA's ambitious
        goals have been to help local activists multiply the
        impact and improve the quality of grassroots work on school
        issues, and to develop a progressive agenda for education issues
        on a national scale. </p>
        <p>Seeking to build a more fully national network, NCEA
        held its conference on the west coast for the first time
        this past August. With about 350 participants, making it
        NCEA's largest conference to date, and with more than
        half coming from California, Oregon, and Washington, the session
        accomplished that aim. </p>
        <p>As has been the case for the past few years, the
        conference was preceded by several four-day institutes at which
        smaller groups dealt in depth with issues of classroom
        practice and educational organizing. This year, for the
        first time, an institute was held on &quot;Rethinking Our Unions.&quot;
        Spurred in part by the momentum of merger talks now under way
        between the two major education unions, the National Education Association
        and the American Federation of Teachers, the institute
        was also an attempt by NCEA to address the differing
        perspectives union, parent, and classroom activists bring
        to school reform issues. Often parents and community organizers
        (and at times even classroom teachers) see teacher unions as defenders of
        privilege and bureaucracy rather than as agents of change
        or allies of the communities that public schools serve.
        On the other hand, progressive union activists have argued
        that, for all their flaws, education unions are (or at
        least, ought to be) organizations that belong to teachers
        and other school staff, and that their involvement is
        absolutely crucial to any hopes for democratic school
        reform. Union activists also argue that the sustained
        crisis of public schooling and near-universal cries for
        reform have created more space for progressive initiatives inside
        both huge education unions. </p>
        <p>The institute brought together about 30 union
        activists from both the AFT and NEA, including national staff,
        state and local officers, and rank and file members from
        many parts of the country. Participants had been active within
        their respective organizations, some as leaders of large
        urban or state organizations, others as national staff
        charged with overseeing reform initiatives, still others
        as rank and file activists in stagnant locals. But there
        had been little inter-organizational exchange between progressive-minded unionists
        in the two camps, and NCEA played a useful role in
        bringing them together. The group spent much of the time critically
        measuring the practice of education unions against both
        the long-range interests of teachers and school staff,
        and the broader interests of democratically transforming
        a school system in crisis. </p>
        <p>The result was a vision of what &quot;social justice
        unionism&quot; could accomplish in education summed up in
        a draft statement to be circulated in anticipation of a
        larger institute next year. The draft calls on education unions
        to adopt a &quot;broader conception of the interests of teachers and
        of teaching,&quot; &quot;a better partnership with the
        parents and communities that need public education
        most,&quot; &quot;a new vision of schooling that raises the expectations
        of our students and the standards of our own
        profession,&quot; and &quot;a new model of unionism that
        revives debate and democracy internally, and projects an
        inspiring social vision and agenda externally.&quot; The statement
        also suggests specific ways union power and collective bargaining
        rights can be used to promote progressive changes in classroom
        practice, school governance, and other areas. </p>
        <p>The theme of the larger conference, which followed the
        institutes, was &quot;Schools and Social Justice: Organizing
        for Change.&quot; Panels were held on overcoming
        differences between parents and teachers, responding to school
        violence, and reconnecting city schools and communities.
        Other sessions dealt with sexual harassment and gender
        inequities, critical teaching practices, curriculum
        reform, student organizing, and national and
        international policy issues from privatization and school
        finance to education in South Africa and the impact NAFTA
        will have on education. </p>
        <p>Several sessions focused on anti-racist education,
        including ways to move beyond superficial celebrations of
        multicultural diversity towards systemic, whole school,
        bias-reducing strategies. A panel with anti-racist educators
        Enid Lee, Louise Derman-Sparks, and Sonia Nieto shared ideas
        and dialogue with local activists. </p>
        <p>A variety of models for how schools change were
        presented, including projects tied to national efforts like
        the Coalition for Essential Schools and those arising
        from local initiatives. Reports on organizing efforts included
        presentations on youth leadership and organizing by Asian Americans
        United from Philadelphia, on indigenous rights in
        education by Native American activists, and on addressing
        language barriers and the educational rights of
        immigrants by Latino activists. Activists from New York
        City reported on struggles for multicultural education in
        the wake of the recent controversy over the Rainbow curriculum that included
        gay and lesbian concerns. </p>
        <p>The conference, as usual, drew much of its energy from
        the networking that occurs each year as teachers, parents
        and education activists, who often feel isolated in their
        local work, come together to share their successes and
        frustrations. One of NCEA's major accomplishments has been
        connecting people to each other, helping activists to
        recharge, and tapping the network's collective resources
        and experience in ways that sustain and expand local
        efforts. At the same time the diversity of NCEA's network
        and its activist politics challenge participants to press against
        the outer boundaries of their practice and perspectives
        so that local efforts cut deeper and accomplish more. </p>
        <p>As some activists in NCEA see it, a political
        &quot;window of opportunity &quot; exists today around education issues
        and they hope the coalition can jump through it. That
        opportunity has been opened in part by the disarray of a bureaucracy
        exhausted by failure, by the brain-dead ineffectiveness
        of many mainstream reform proposals, by the growing abandonment
        of public schooling by elite interests through
        privatization and budgetary assault, and by the gap between
        this sorry performance and the pressing need people have for
        decent, effective public education. NCEA shows signs of
        assembling many of the essential elements of a progressive education
        agenda: a new vision of education, a nuts and bolts understanding
        of life in schools, a commitment to the demands of grassroots,
        multiracial, multi-constituency organizing, and an eye on
        the big picture of broadly-based social change. </p>
        <p>While making steady strides in putting together a
        network of mutual support, resources, and information, NCEA
        is still looking for the specific strategies and the
        considerable resources needed to put all the pieces of
        its ambitious political project together. Some in the
        coalition have suggested that it needs to define in some
        clear and effective way a comprehensive national campaign
        that sums up the ways in which schools must be
        transformed. Others have suggested that there is some single
        cutting edge issue, like equity in funding, or
        anti-racist education, or sharply reduced class size that
        can serve as the centerpiece for a national effort to
        promote educational justice. Still others think NCEA should
        adopt a local coalition-building strategy that attempts
        to build a grassroots base for progressive reform by duplicating
        on the local, state or regional level, the kind of barrier-breaking
        unity among constituencies and informed political discussion
        of school issues that have been attempted at its national conferences.
        . </p>
        <p>Today NCEA counts 600 dues-paying members in 30
        states. More than 3,500 activists have connected to the
        network in some way. Planning has already started for
        next year's conference, set for the Boston area next August. </p>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>

<hr>

<p>&nbsp;</p>
</body>
