<title>Dollar Diplomacy: The Debate On Intervention </title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#F8F8F8" link="#001F76" vlink="#001F76"
alink="#001F76">

<blockquote>
    <p>&nbsp;</p>
    <blockquote>
        <h2>from the pages of<img src="../oldsmzma.gif" alt="../"
        align="top" hspace="4" width="108" height="37"> </h2>
    </blockquote>
    <hr>
    <h1 align="center">Dollar Diplomacy: The Debate On
    Intervention </h1>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><em>Stephan R. Shalom </em></font></p>
    <p align="center"><font size="4"><em></em></font>&nbsp;</p>
    <blockquote>
        <p>A debate currently rages over the issue of U.S.
        military intervention abroad. Unlike previous debates on
        this issue over the past 50 years, today the Left is
        sharply divided. There have been calls for particular
        intervention in In These Times and Dissent and exchanges
        in the pages of The Nation, The Boston Review, Peace and
        Democracy News, and The Progressive. Left conferences in
        New York and Washington have grappled with the issue, as
        have many panals at the recent Socialist Scholars'
        Conference and numerous radio debates. </p>
        <p>It is somewhat puzzling why this issue of intervention
        is being raised now. Sure the world has changed in rather
        substantial ways and it would be foolish to ignore these
        changes. But it is not at all clear why these changes
        ought to revise the standard Left presumption against
        U.S. intervention. </p>
        <p>If one believed that the reason for bad U.S.
        interventions in the past was because of a paranoid fear
        of the Soviet Union, then the end of the Cold War would
        indeed mean the end of bad interventions. But Moscow has
        always served as an excuse for U.S. interventions
        motivated by quite other considerations, considerations
        of imperial domination. So when the CIA engineered the
        overthrow of the elected government of Guatemala in 1953,
        Washington used a Soviet bloc arms shipment as its
        justification, even though the planning for the
        intervention began before the arms shipment occurred.
        When the United States wanted to support death squads in
        El Salvador, it issued a White Paper falsely charging
        that the Soviet Union was a major source of weapons to
        the Salvadoran guerrillas. And when Washington wanted to
        crush the Sandinista government, it manufactured evidence
        that Soviet MiGs were being sent to Nicaragua. The United
        States was engaged in imperial interventions long before
        the Bolsheviks came to power. So the demise of the Soviet
        Union hardly means the end of interventions rooted in the
        structures of U.S. society. </p>
        <p>When the Soviet &quot;bear was on the loose,&quot; the
        Pentagon devoured about $300 billion a year; today
        spending has only gone down to $260 billion, giving some
        indication of just how little Moscow really mattered.
        Even when one corrects for inflation, Clinton is spending
        more on the military today than Richard Nixon did in 1974
        in the midst of the Cold War. The end of the Cold War
        will change the excuses that U.S. policy-makers will use
        for future interventions, but it won't end the urge to
        intervene. </p>
        <p>This, of course, doesn't explain why some on the Left,
        in particular, are urging a rethinking of intervention.
        Why does the end of the Cold War make U.S. intervention
        more acceptable? To be sure, if the Cold War had ended
        because the Left had taken power in the United States,
        our assessment of U.S. intervention would be different.
        But even if Clinton had not violated so many of his
        campaign promises, his election would not have signified
        a decisive break in U.S. foreign policy. </p>
        <p>U.S. interventions are militarily more possible today
        because there is little danger of provoking an all-out
        nuclear war. No rational person would have urged that
        U.S. troops intervene in Czechoslovakia in 1968 because
        nuclear conflagration would have been the likely result.
        But it's hard to imagine that Washington would have
        considered intervening to defend Prague's &quot;socialism
        with a human face&quot; had there been no danger of wider
        war. To put it another way, the only thing that might
        have propelled a U.S. intervention would have been the
        desire to weaken an adversary--the Soviet Union--whose
        military power placed some check on U.S. ability to
        intervene elsewhere. So if there were, hypothetically, no
        danger of nuclear war from a U.S. intervention, there
        would also not have been any incentive for U.S.
        intervention. During the Cold War, there have been many
        places where the United States might have intervened
        without any risk of nuclear escalation: to promote
        democracy, for example, in Haiti under Duvalier or the
        Philippines under Marcos, or to stop massacres, say, in
        East Pakistan in 1971 or Indonesia in 1965. But the
        United States was supporting the dictators and the
        butchers in these cases, and far from contemplating
        intervention, it refrained from even withdrawing U.S.
        support for tyranny and terror. </p>
        <p>I suspect that one reason some Leftists have become
        more inclined towards U.S. intervention is that they have
        concluded that intervention will no longer be a danger to
        movements for social justice around the world because
        such movements no longer exist. The end of the Cold War,
        in this view, has meant that the opportunity for
        revolutionaries to receive arms and aid from the Soviet
        bloc has dried up, making the prospects for social change
        more difficult than before. This is probably true,
        despite the strings that Soviet aid usually entailed. But
        that prospects are dimmer doesn't mean they are
        non-existent. The miseries of living in the New World
        Order will surely generate new struggles for social
        change, as events in Chiapas should remind us. I am going
        to argue that in general the Left should continue to
        oppose U.S. military interventions because: </p>
        <p>1. By making good interventions possible, we make bad
        interventions more likely: this is the precedent
        argument; </p>
        <p>2. Bad countries don't make good interventions; </p>
        <p>3. Outsiders are inherently incapable of bringing
        self-determination to others (as argued by John Stuart
        Mill) </p>
        <p>4. The pacifist argument that military force is
        counter-productive </p>
        <p>After elaborating the logic of these
        &quot;guidlines,&quot; I will also discuss exceptions,
        the &quot;guidelines&quot; applicability to UN as well as
        U.S. interventions, and counterarguments. </p>
        <p>&nbsp;</p>
    </blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <h3>Precedent </h3>
        <p>The precedent argument holds that even if there were a
        good intervention, it would serve to weaken the taboo
        against intervention in general. Obviously, there have
        been many other violations of this taboo before, but
        there remains a reasonably widespread presumption against
        foreign intervention. For the Left to endorse the
        precedent of interventions, even for a good cause, may
        well help open the floodgates to many other bad
        interventions. </p>
        <p>Likewise, to develop or maintain the capabilities to
        undertake good interventions, one has to build up the
        same Pentagon budget, the same interventionary weapons
        systems, and the same foreign base structure that
        facilitate bad interventions. </p>
        <p>Intervening for the good hinges on the very
        contestable notion of what is good. Once intervention for
        the good becomes legitimized, the Left will often lose
        the contest over the definition of what is good and bad.
        Allowing countries to intervene when they consider that
        certain rights have been transgressed is a prescription
        for disaster. It is better to prohibit all interventions
        than to allow the U.S. government to decide which
        interventions are good. </p>
        <p>Consider the analogy to the hate speech issue. Some on
        the Left assert that the government ought to legislate
        speech for the good. Others, including me, insist that if
        we legitimize government regulation of speech, we will
        end up making it easier for the government to ban good
        speech. It is better to establish as a principle that
        there should be no government regulation of speech and
        take the bad with the good, rather than risk having the
        government decide what is good and what is bad. </p>
        <p>&nbsp;</p>
    </blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <h3>Bad Countries, Good Interventions </h3>
        <p>Even if the United States intervenes in a case where
        the Left agrees evil is being done, the government will
        further its own interests, not those of the local
        victims. World opinion was rightly horrified by Spanish
        treatment of the Cuban people in 1898, but U.S.
        intervention resulted in a half century of dictatorship
        and U.S. domination. </p>
        <p>Let me be clear, when I refer to the United States as
        a &quot;bad government,&quot; I mean that the United
        States can be shown to be a bad government by clear
        objective measures, by looking at what the United States
        has done and is doing in the world. Consider a place
        where some 200,000 people--one third of the
        population--have been killed: namely, East Timor. Leave
        aside that in the past Washington gave Indonesia the
        green light for its invasion and provided 90 percent of
        its arms; leave aside that for years the United States
        worked in the UN to give diplomatic support to the
        invasion. Consider only U.S. policy today, while the
        killing and conquest continue. In 1992, Congress ended
        military training aid to Indonesia in protest over a
        massacre in East Timor's capital of Dili. In December
        1993 it was revealed that Indonesian soldiers were being
        trained at U.S. military bases under the technicality
        that Indonesia was paying for the training. The previous
        June, the heads of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee
        and the Foreign Operations Subcommittee had written to
        the Department of State that allowing Indonesia to
        purchase U.S. military training &quot;would be directly
        contrary to the intent of Congress.&quot; But that's
        precisely what has been going on. Note that no one is
        calling on the United States to risk the lives of its
        young men and women by invading Indonesia or bombing
        Jakarta, but even the minimal step of cutting off
        military training is unacceptable to the Clinton
        administration. And it is this administration that some
        are hoping will intervene for a good cause--sort of like
        approaching muggers on the street and asking them if they
        wouldn't mind protecting another mugging victim on the
        next block. </p>
        <p>Some reject this argument as merely pointing out a
        double-standard, which might be true but irrelevant. We
        don't, after all, reject out of hand all good actions
        that are performed by those with a double standard. But
        the point is not (just) that U.S. concern for some
        victims of atrocities is hypocritical, but also, as a
        practical matter, it is not very realistic to expect
        those who turn a blind eye to, and even participate in,
        some mass murder to become morally engaged in preventing
        some other mass murder. </p>
        <p>Obviously, if major social change took place in the
        United States so that it was no longer a bad government,
        this argument would not apply. Nor does the argument
        apply to the case of international brigades which are
        independent of bad governments. Neither of these
        considerations, however, are relevant to the current
        debate on U.S. intervention. </p>
        <p>&nbsp;</p>
    </blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <h3>Mill's Argument </h3>
        <p>Athird argument against intervention is one that goes
        back at least to John Stuart Mill. As Michael Walzer has
        summarized Mill's argument, self-determination is not the
        same as political freedom. The former term is more
        inclusive, covering also a political community's struggle
        for freedom--whether successful or not. Members of a
        political community cannot be set free by an external
        force. &quot;It is during an arduous struggle to become
        free by their own efforts that [the virtues needful for
        maintaining freedom] have the best chance of springing
        up.&quot; Mill didn't believe that intervention fails
        more often than not to serve the purposes of liberty; he
        believed that, given what liberty is, it necessarily
        fails. The internal freedom of a political community can
        only be won by the members of that community, just as in
        the Marxian view the liberation of the working class can
        come only from the workers themselves. Thus, for Mill,
        there can be evil social systems, with much oppression,
        where revolution is justified but where intervention is
        not, for the former is an act of self-determination,
        while the latter undermines self-determination. </p>
        <p>Related to this argument is another liability that
        outsiders have in bringing freedom to others: outsiders
        are often uninformed of local conditions and thus
        ill-suited to bring social benefit. Consider the case of
        Somalia. U.S. forces charged headlong into the complex
        web of Somali politics, bringing to bear their special
        blend of arrogance and ignorance. Before the U.S.
        intervention there had been signs that Muhammad Farah
        Aidid was waning in power within his sub-clan. But first
        the U.S. promoted Aidid by treating him as a key leader,
        and then it demonized him, driving even members of his
        sub-clan who disagreed with him to his support, fearing
        that they were, in the words of the Operations Director
        for the U.S.-led Command, &quot;on the edge of a clan
        eradication.&quot; Now, Aidid has become one of the most
        powerful figures in the country, which is a real tragedy,
        because he is a brutal thug. </p>
        <p>Is it contradictory to damn the United States on the
        one hand for embracing Aidid and on the other for
        demonizing him? No. The fact is that there is no easy way
        for outsiders to reconstitute Somali society,
        particularly when they disdain the opinions of Somalis.
        No Somalis were consulted before Operation Restore Hope,
        and many of the policies carried out by outsiders
        marginalized and ignored Somalis, and have bred
        dependence and demoralization. It is thus extremely
        doubtful that U.S. Marines can bring Somalia what it most
        needs, which is precisely the participation and
        empowerment of Somalis. </p>
        <p>&nbsp;</p>
    </blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <h3>The Pacifist Argument </h3>
        <p>The fourth argument against military intervention is
        the pacifist critique. Whatever one thinks about
        absolutist pacificism, there is little doubt that
        pacifists have identified many ways in which military
        action undermines the values we hope to promote: it makes
        reconciliation more difficult, it lessens the taboo
        around killing, it is almost invariably organized in
        hierarchical structures and thus undermines democracy.
        The means one uses to attain certain ends invariably
        influence the ends that are actually achieved. </p>
        <p>Moreover, military action almost never deals with the
        root causes of problems and thus using it encourages
        quick fix solutions that ignore the underlying sources of
        conflict. And because various domestic constituencies
        benefit from military intervention, there is a tendency
        to champion military action in situations where it is
        inappropriate, especially by those whose careers or
        profits or testosterone depend on war. </p>
        <p>There are also a whole host of very real practical and
        logistical obstacles to military intervention. As Richard
        Falk has reminded us, even in cases where the U.S.
        government seems to have had strong strategic motives for
        intervention, as in Lebanon in 1983, &quot;success&quot;
        from the point of view of the intervenor has been
        elusive. </p>
        <p>Precision military operations are especially
        difficult. The destructive potential of military
        technology is immense, but its ability to achieve precise
        goals are still very remote. When Marine F/A-18 planes
        attacked Serbian armored vehicles near Gorazde on April
        11, for example, two of three bombs dropped failed to
        explode and a fourth became hung up on the wing of one of
        the planes. </p>
        <p>&nbsp;</p>
    </blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <h3>Exceptions </h3>
        <p>There are exceptions to each of these four arguments
        against intervention. The precedent argument assumes that
        the clearest place to draw the line between acceptable
        and unacceptable state behavior, particularly by the
        United States, is between intervention and no
        intervention and that drawing the line anywhere else
        weakens the general presumption against intervention.
        Precedents and taboos matter: but if there were a case
        where a particular intervention seemed uniquely good,
        couldn't we educate people to see why this case was not
        like most of the other cases we rightly oppose? </p>
        <p>The argument that bad governments don't undertake good
        interventions likewise has an exception. That is, it is
        possible that the net consequence of an intervention
        might be positive even where the motives of the
        intervenor were bad. During World War II, the United
        States government did not care about the plight of
        Europe's Jews--as shown by its failure to do a number of
        easy things that could have saved thousands.
        Nevertheless, a consequence of defeating Hitler was that
        the death camps were closed down. And it is possible to
        make a case that despite all the horrendous consequences
        of World War II--the millions of lives lost, the
        undermining of revolutionary movements, the re-imposition
        of colonialism (in Vietnam, for example)--on balance it
        was still better that the United States intervened than
        had it not. </p>
        <p>Mill recognized two exceptions to his basic
        non-interventionist position, exceptions that he claimed
        flowed logically from his general argument: (1) secession
        and (2) counter-intervention. Michael Walzer suggests a
        third exception: namely, massacre. In the case of
        secession, said Mill, the political community whose
        self-determination we care about no longer exists; the
        boundary of the political community is in doubt and
        intervention might help the secessionists achieve their
        independence and hence self-determination. When an
        outside country or countries have intervened in a civil
        war, then counter-intervention might restore the balance
        so that the domestic struggle can be resolved
        domestically. And finally when widespread massacres are
        taking place, the notion of a political community no
        longer applies. </p>
        <p>There are exceptions, too, to the pacifist paradigm.
        Although the usual effects of military force are
        counter-productive, there are circumstances where human
        suffering might be substantially reduced by resort to
        arms. I doubt, for example, that there were any pacifist
        strategies that would have had much impact on the German
        Einsatzgruppen who machine-gunned hundreds of thousands
        of unarmed Jews. </p>
        <p>So each of these four basic arguments against
        intervention has exceptions, but in order for an
        intervention to be justified it has to fall under an
        exception to all four arguments. Most U.S. interventions
        historically have been objectionable on all four grounds,
        but even one ground would be sufficient for us to oppose
        an intervention. </p>
        <p>There is good reason to be very stingy with exceptions
        to non-intervention. Take Mill's exceptions: secession,
        counter-intervention, and massacre--each one of them
        involves a great many subjective judgments. Moreover,
        since almost every society has some number of individuals
        who would like to secede, some measure of intervention by
        other outsiders, and some degree of mistreatment of its
        citizens, every country could claim justification for
        intervention wherever it wanted. Where does one draw the
        line? Serbia could claim, for example, that Croatia
        mistreated some of its citizens or was preventing
        secession and that either of these justified its
        intervention. Washington claimed that its intervention in
        Vietnam was a counter-intervention to that of North
        Vietnam and that its support for the Contras was to
        protect Miskito Indians. </p>
        <p>It is true that in domestic law we don't reject, for
        example, the plea of self-defense just because it is
        often falsely claimed, but in domestic law we at least
        have some authoritative mechanisms for evaluating claims,
        namely courts of law that can hear evidence and establish
        guidelines. A world in which countries determined for
        themselves when any of these three exceptions to the
        principle of non-intervention ought to apply would be a
        very dangerous place indeed. Not everyone would invade
        everyone else (prudence would discourage the weak from
        attacking the strong), but certainly the strong would
        have a field day. For this reason, many smaller
        countries--often the victims of large neighbors--have
        taken the position that nothing justifies intervention by
        one country into the affairs of another. For example,
        Latin American nations were able to pressure Washington
        into signing a convention in Buenos Aires in 1936
        agreeing not to intervene in the region for any reason (a
        pledge, of course, broken many times). And though the
        Latin American governments that took this absolute
        non-interventionist position may have wanted to shield
        themselves from interference with their own human rights
        abuses, my guess is that democratic opinion throughout
        Latin America supported the non-intervention convention. </p>
        <p>&nbsp;</p>
    </blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <h3>The United Nations </h3>
        <p>The birth of the United Nations changes the above
        arguments in a number of respects. All countries,
        including the powerful, have, by signing the UN charter,
        given up their right to unilateral intervention. This
        doesn't mean that interventions have become less
        frequent; they are, however, more clearly in violation of
        international law. The only exception permitted by the UN
        Charter is individual and collective self-defense, though
        the latter admittedly leaves much room for manipulation. </p>
        <p>What about intervention by the UN? Here we must deal
        with the fact that the UN is not a democratic
        organization. The structure of the body puts enforcement
        power in the hands of the Security Council, which is
        dominated by rich and powerful nations. Military
        interventions by the UN are thus likely to be directed
        against domestic social change movements or selectively
        against governments that have refused to accept
        domination by the rich and powerful. </p>
        <p>The end of the Cold War has not appreciably
        democratized the UN. In recent years, the UN had been
        blocked from taking effective action against aggressors
        not primarily by the veto of the Soviet Union, but by the
        veto of the United States, which was determined to defend
        aggressors when they were U.S. allies (Israel or South
        Africa, for example) or the United States itself (as when
        it invaded Panama). So while Washington certainly faces
        less opposition in the UN than it used to, this does not
        mean that the UN has become a more principled defender of
        international justice. </p>
        <p>Thus the precedent argument against intervention would
        apply to the UN as well as to the United States. The bad
        governments argument is not quite as strong--because
        often the conflicting interests of leading bad
        governments will serve as a check on one another--but the
        rich and powerful have enough bad interests in common
        (particularly the desire to preserve an unjust world
        social order) that the likelihood of their doing good is
        not great. And the Millian and pacifist arguments against
        intervention also apply to the UN. </p>
        <p>Nevertheless, in cases where there is ongoing genocide
        or massive atrocity or where one country has been invaded
        by another, UN intervention may be appropriate if there
        is a broad international consensus. The UN doesn't
        operate by international consensus, of course, but that
        doesn't mean that we don't often know what the
        international consensus is. If states in the General
        Assembly favored a humanitarian intervention there is a
        strong likelihood that the intervention would not reflect
        simply the interests of one or a few rich and powerful
        nations. Again, there still might be reasons to refrain
        from intervention: the countries whose troops will
        actually be doing the intervening may not have the same
        goals as the international consensus or there may be a
        variety of practical considerations that will cause the
        intervention to make things worse, rather than better.
        But there will be times when intervention can accomplish
        some good. </p>
        <p>Consider a few cases. The sanctions against Iraq after
        its invasion of Kuwait, for example, had widespread
        global support, even though they were imposed by the
        Security Council. The Iraqi invasion of Kuwait was a
        clear violation of the UN charter and UN action against
        Iraq was, in my view, proper. The objection to Desert
        Storm was not that it was inappropriate for the UN to
        act, but that UN action of a different sort--namely,
        diplomacy and continued sanctions without moving to
        war--offered the possibility of resolving the problem
        without the costs that war involved: the deaths of
        innocent civilians and semi-innocent draftees; the deaths
        of Kurds in the north and Shiites in the south of Iraq
        who tragically expected that because Bush called on them
        to rise up he would protect them; the fueling of
        fundamentalism in Algeria with ominous consequences; and
        the boost given to the U.S. military and U.S. military
        bases in the Gulf that will likely be used against
        popular struggles in the future. The fact that the United
        States had to bribe Security Council members to force
        through its resolution for going to war suggests that
        world opinion agreed that, while some actions against
        Iraq were justified, going to war at that point was not. </p>
        <p>Consider now the situation of the Kurds in Iraq. In
        February and March 1991, during and after Operation
        Desert Storm, the United States urged the Iraqi people to
        overthrow Saddam Hussein; the Voice of Free Iraq--almost
        certainly a CIA-funded operation--recruited Kurdish
        exiles to broadcast calls to their compatriots to rise up
        against the Iraqi leader. When the U.S. calls were
        heeded, President Bush proceeded to turn his back on the
        Kurds. He decided to let Saddam Hussein put down the
        rebellions without U.S. intervention rather than risk the
        splintering of Iraq. Washington had warned Hussein not to
        use combat helicopters against the insurgents, but when
        he ignored the U.S. warning, the United States chose not
        to act. In fact, a White House spokesperson explicitly
        rescinded the warning. &quot;We never made any promises
        to these people,&quot; said a senior official. &quot;We
        don't want Iraq dismembered, since that would go counter
        to the reason we fought the war,&quot; commented another
        official. </p>
        <p>Only after U.S. and international opinion were aroused
        by Bush's perfidy did the president move to protect the
        Kurds. He certainly didn't act out of noble motives. In
        1975, as head of the CIA, Bush had carried out the
        Kissinger policy of betraying the Kurds and even denying
        them asylum because it suited U.S. interests. In 1988,
        when Saddam Hussein had turned his military machine,
        including chemical weapons, against his country's Kurdish
        population, forcibly relocating half a million people,
        killing at least 50,000, and wiping 4,000 villages off
        the map, there was no word of public protest from the
        Bush administration. When Bush and the Security Council
        finally acted by establishing a safe haven inside Iraq,
        they were probably trying to relieve the public pressure
        on Turkey to open its borders to fleeing refugees, which
        would have saved many lives, but was unacceptable to
        Washington's Turkish ally, a major oppressor of the
        Kurdish people. </p>
        <p>Given the likely fate of Kurds caught by Saddam
        Hussein's forces, the safe haven was, in my view,
        justified. But one should have had no illusions that this
        would provide long-term protection for the Kurdish
        people. Indeed, the protectors had no objections when
        Turkey launched major raids by its U.S.-supplied air
        force against Kurdish villages in the safe haven; nor did
        they mind that Iraqi Kurds were subjected to two
        embargoes: one by Iraq and one by the UN as part of the
        embargo on Iraq. And, of course, atrocities against Kurds
        in Turkey continue with complete silence from the U.S.
        government. </p>
        <p>Current events in Rwanda provide another example of
        possibly beneficial UN intervention, although information
        is severely limited. </p>
        <p>The people of Rwanda and neighboring Burundi have
        suffered genocidal violence over the years. Both
        countries have a Hutu majority and a Tutsi minority, the
        latter favored by the Belgian colonizers. Competition for
        land (Rwanda is the second most densely populated country
        in the world) has exacerbated ethnic tensions. In
        Burundi, the Tutsis have controlled the country and the
        army for many years, massacring large numbers of Hutus to
        maintain their dominance. Last year, the first Hutu was
        elected president of the country, only to be murdered in
        an abortive military coup; tens of thousands were killed
        in the reprisals that followed. </p>
        <p>Rwanda had been ruled for two decades by Juvenal
        Habyarimana, a Hutu whose regime had been propped up by
        French arms and advisers and ethnic incitement against
        Tutsis. Though a brutal dictator, Habyarimana, (in the
        words of the New York Times obituary) &quot;excelled at
        strengthening ties to the West and attracting foreign aid
        and investment at a time when a number of other African
        leaders were being accused of running corrupt and
        inefficient governments.&quot; In 1990, the Rwandan
        Patriotic Front (RPF); made up primarily of Tutsi exiles
        from previous massacres, launched a war to try to
        overthrow the government. In August 1993, Habyarimana
        agreed to end the civil war and set up a transitional
        government, sharing power among his group, the Hutu
        opposition, and the RPF. He delayed on implementation,
        however, and in the meantime began arming paramilitary
        thugs while the government radio issued blood-curdling
        calls for killing Tutsis. The UN Security Council, which
        had been trying to broker a peace accord, did not press
        the Rwandan government to respect human rights or curb
        its militias. </p>
        <p>On April 6, a plane in which Habyarimana and Burundi's
        leader were flying was shot down, probably by
        Habyarimana's own presidential guard, who proceeded to go
        on a rampage against all opposition figures. Fighting
        between the RPF and the army resumed. The government
        armed militias then went after all members of the Tutsi
        minority, slaughtering tens of thousands. </p>
        <p>In the United States, initial government concern was
        focused entirely on the safety of the Americans who were
        there. As Senator Robert Dole put it, &quot;The Americans
        are out. As far as I'm concerned in Rwanda, that ought to
        be the end of it.&quot; U.S. indifference to mass murder
        in Rwanda and Burundi has a long history. In the early
        1970s, the massacre of more than 100,000 people in
        Burundi elicited not a single public condemnation by the
        U.S. government, nor even a clear private approach to the
        Burundi offficials who were responsible. The threat of
        economic sanctions (the United States was the main market
        for Burundi's chief crop, coffeee) as a lever to stop the
        carnage was not even contemplated. </p>
        <p>For two weeks, the Security Council delayed on Rwanda.
        Some 20,000 Tutsis took refuge with UN peacekeeping
        troops who were in the country in anticipation of helping
        with the cease-fire between the government and the RPF.
        Human rights workers warned that, at a minimum, if the
        peacekeepers were pulled out, the people they were
        protecting would be slaughtered. African nations, usually
        very sensitive to violations of sovereignty, urged that
        the peacekeeping force be augmented. Nevertheless, the
        Security Council voted on April 20 to reduce the force
        from 1,700 (some nations had already pulled out their
        troops) to 270. The Clinton administration originally
        favored a total pullout, but was persuaded by Third World
        delegates to back the token force. No one seemed much
        interested in Rwanda. </p>
        <p>At this remove it's hard to know whether a large UN
        force would have helped. The RPF suspects the UN of
        siding with the government and insists that the UN stay
        out. (UN mediators had recommended the inclusion in the
        transitional government of an extremist group that had
        called for the extermination of Tutsis.) Since most of
        the killing is being carried out behind government lines,
        imposing a UN force between the warring parties might not
        do much to stop the carnage. But surely reducing the UN
        force sends the wrong signal. </p>
        <p>So as long as the UN remains undemocratic, and as long
        as its enforcement capability is concentrated in the
        hands of the powerful, the dangers from UN interventions
        are very real. Where there is broad-based international
        support for intervention, the dangers will be much
        reduced, though again some of the other arguments against
        intervention may still apply. </p>
        <p>There is no absolute argument against military
        intervention by the United States. But in the vast
        majority of cases there will be less human suffering in
        the long run--and often in the short run--if we oppose
        such interventions. There are exceptions to each of the
        arguments I have advanced against intervention, but it
        will be extremely rare that a situation constitutes an
        exception to all the arguments. These arguments against
        intervention apply to the UN as well, though they are
        more permissive where the world community is in agreement
        and where exceptions to the other arguments apply. In
        short, nothing in the current world situation should lead
        the Left to adopt a position generally endorsing good
        interventions. </p>
        <p>Let me now consider some counter-arguments to the
        position presented above. </p>
        <p>&nbsp;</p>
    </blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <h3>Everything is Intervention </h3>
        <p>Some argue that in the contemporary interdependent
        world it is impossible not to intervene: whether the
        United States trades with country X or doesn't trade with
        country X, it is intervening; whether the United States
        chooses to give economic aid to country Y or not to give
        aid, it is intervening. Since intervention is thus
        inevitable, we might as well make sure it is for the
        good. </p>
        <p>It's true that it is impossible to avoid decisions on
        trade, aid, and diplomacy, and so whatever the United
        States does will be an intervention of sorts. Few
        progressives, for example, supported United States trade
        with South Africa or aid to Pinochet or Duarte. There are
        thus cases where the Left endorses using U.S. trade
        policy to influence the domestic policies of other
        countries. If Washington traded with South Africa, it
        helped apartheid; if it didn't trade it hurt apartheid:
        there was no way to avoid having an impact. Therefore, in
        these cases it makes sense for the Left to push to ensure
        that the intervention be for the good. </p>
        <p>It is essential, however, that this sort of
        intervention be done consistently. What has been wrong
        with U.S. policy on trade and aid is not that Angola,
        Vietnam, or Cuba have been penalized for their human
        rights records (though I leave out here the separate and
        very real question of whether these countries might be
        owed reparations for illegal, unjust, and vicious acts by
        the United States), but that these three were singled out
        for special punishment. Surely their records in terms of
        human rights or adherence to international law have been
        no worse than those of many other countries with which
        Washington has had cozy relations. A consistent policy,
        for example, would offer most-favored-nation treatment on
        trade to any country that meets certain objective human
        rights or other criteria and deny it to those who don't.
        This has never been United States policy. </p>
        <p>Even here there is a danger that the criteria will be
        chosen or judged in such a way as to favor U.S. client
        states. The Left will have to continually struggle to
        make sure that the criterion, for example, of whether
        there are free trade unions is not just taken to mean
        free of government control, but of employer control as
        well; that the criterion of whether citizens have basic
        rights includes the rights to food and shelter, and so
        on. No doubt, the Left will lose many of these debates,
        but there is no alternative to participating in them
        since every trade or aid policy will have an impact on
        other countries. </p>
        <p>But from the fact that some sort of intervention in
        trade and aid policy is inevitable it does not follow
        that military intervention is justified. Trade, aid,
        diplomacy--these are the normal, legal practices of
        international life. Every country has the right to decide
        who it wants to trade with or aid, and in deciding it is
        inevitably rewarding or penalizing other countries. But
        sending in the Marines is not the same thing. Countries
        do not normally have the right to invade other countries
        or to engage in covert operations abroad. Generally, it
        is not intervention to fail to dispatch troops or to
        refrain from covert operations. So there is nothing
        inconsistent with a position that says that U.S. trade
        and aid policy should favor human rights, democracy, and
        adherence to international law, while at the same time
        the United States should not engage in military
        intervention or covert CIA intervention. </p>
        <p>&nbsp;</p>
    </blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <h3>The Domestic Analogy </h3>
        <p>A second objection to non-interventionism notes that
        Leftists don't refrain from calling on the police when
        crime threatens, even though the police are corrupt and
        agents of an ultimately evil state. We try to keep the
        police under adequate civilian or community control, we
        try to restrain them from abuses of power, but we don't
        reject their usefulness out of hand. Part of our
        political struggle is precisely to get the police to do
        good rather than bad. The same is true about the
        capitalist state in general: most Leftists call on the
        state to do good things, like provide medical coverage
        for the population, provide education, enforce minimum
        wage laws, enforce environmental regulations, etc. So if
        we try to use the capitalist state for our own purposes
        in domestic policy, why shouldn't we do the same in
        foreign policy? </p>
        <p>First of all, there are some cases where we most
        definitely ought to refrain from giving the government
        the power to do good domestically because this same power
        can be--and will be--used to do bad. Consider the RICO
        statute. Some progressives, particularly in the National
        Organization for Women, pushed for a Supreme Court ruling
        upholding the use of the RICO statute to prevent
        obstruction of abortion clinics. The ruling, however, is
        likely to be used most often against social change
        movements, who are liable to find themselves bearing the
        brunt of the statute. </p>
        <p>Second, usually when people on the Left talk about the
        importance of, say, minimum wage or environmental laws
        they emphasize that these are not gifts from the state,
        but the result of years of struggle by the people, by the
        working class, etc., and that the laws will only be
        beneficial so long as there is a mobilized citizenry or
        working class continually vigilant to ensure that the
        laws are equitably enforced and carried out for the
        benefit of those who are supposed to be benefited. Even
        in these times of Leftist disarray and working class
        weakness, a government attempt to lower the minimum wage
        would face immediate response. Why? Because such an
        attempt would directly hurt U.S. workers and so they have
        a powerful incentive to be vigilant. Even a public which
        is usually deceived and misinformed by the media will
        know what is going on, because what happens affects them
        directly. Bourgeois democracy is a terribly flawed
        system, but it is reasonably effective in providing
        people with a means of guarding against direct attacks on
        their immediate interests. With foreign policy, on the
        other hand, the victims or beneficiaries tend to be
        overseas. Thus, the incentive for any U.S. citizen to
        remain vigilant to insure that the government will act so
        as to benefit the intended beneficiaries is small. And
        the ability of the public to remain informed about
        government policies which impact on distant peoples in
        distant lands is minimal. If Cobra helicopters destroy a
        housing complex in Mogadishu (and no U.S. soldiers are
        killed), few American citizens are aware of what
        happened. On the other hand, if Cobras razed an apartment
        building in Chicago, we'd be much more likely to know. So
        in general there is less danger that public demands for
        domestic government programs intended to benefit the
        American people will unleash the government to do evil
        than would public demands for foreign interventions
        intended to benefit people in other countries. </p>
        <p>In addition, secrecy is a much more regular and
        tolerated occurrence in the realm of foreign policy than
        in that of domestic policy. Particularly when military
        action is involved--we are, after all, talking about
        military intervention--censorship is widespread.
        Restrictions on the media made it extremely difficult to
        monitor U.S. actions in Grenada, Panama, or the Gulf War
        and such restrictions are likely to exist in the future.
        So whatever limited democratic check may be available to
        prevent domestic abuses of power is much less present in
        the case of foreign military interventions. </p>
        <p>Finally, note that historically the nation state was
        formed and consolidated power with a military or police
        force prior to the struggles for democratization. We
        never had the choice: do we want no state enforcement
        mechanism at all or one that we can try to lead in good
        directions? If we were not engaged in revolutionary
        struggle, we had no option but to try to democratize
        state power as much as possible. In the international
        arena, on the other hand, there is no authoritative
        global military force that can intervene in domestic
        disputes. To legitimatize an international police force
        before we have even a moderately democratic control
        mechanism seems potentially dangerous. </p>
    </blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <h3>Motives </h3>
        <p>In an article last year in Dissent magazine, co-editor
        Mitchell Cohen wrote that the only questions we needed to
        ask to determine the proper response to the Iraqi
        invasion of Kuwait were (1) What danger was posed by
        Iraq? and (2) If great menace was at hand, what
        justifiable means could arrest it? Bush's motives or his
        braggadocio about the &quot;Vietnam Syndrome,&quot; said
        Cohen, were irrelevant. </p>
        <p>This argument, however, treats Iraq in a vacuum; it
        calculates moral cost and benefit without considering
        some of the major costs, without asking whether one
        approach to the Gulf crisis might be more likely than
        another to strengthen U.S. militarism in general and
        thereby make things much worse for people throughout the
        New World Order. It might be that after careful
        calculation it turns out that the dangers of setting a
        bad precedent are outweighed by other factors. But Cohen
        simply announces that he isn't going to count these costs
        at all. </p>
        <p>U.S. motives in and of themselves don't matter. But
        bad motives are relevant for figuring out how the
        intervention is likely to be carried out and what the
        consequences of the intervention are likely to be. </p>
        <p>And the bad motives of the intervenor ought to at
        least get us to look very carefully at claims of
        benevolent intentions and anticipated benevolent
        outcomes. Consider again the Somali case. U.S. motives
        were clearly suspect. Washington had been worse than
        indifferent to Somali suffering for over a decade, arming
        and supporting the brutal dictatorship of Muhammad Siad
        Barre, even when he engaged in horrendous atrocities. The
        year before the U.S. intervention, U.S. diplomats at the
        United Nations obstructed, usually on grounds of cost, UN
        efforts to deal with the impending crisis in Somalia. And
        during the peak of the famine, the Bush administration
        ignored Somalia's travail. Bush's intervention was
        designed to promote the Pentagon, not to save Somali
        lives. Nevertheless, perhaps the U.S. intervention could
        coincidentally save lives. If hundreds of thousands of
        lives were at stake, who cares what U.S. motives were? </p>
        <p>But, in fact, the intervention did not save hundreds
        of thousands of lives and there was good reason to
        believe from the beginning that it would not do so. Death
        rates had been falling dramatically before the U.S.
        troops landed in Somalia, and, as Rakiya Omaar and Alex
        de Waal of the London-based Africa Rights have noted, the
        most likely excess death estimates for December would
        have been in the range of 10,000-15,000, and these were
        deaths not due to starvation, but to disease caused by
        the previous malnutrition. Operation Restore Hope drew
        people to refugee camps where food was distributed but
        where disease was readily contracted. The U.S. Centers
        for Disease Control and Prevention found that in Bardera,
        for example, the mortality rate doubled in the first
        month of Restore Hope and quadrupled for children under
        five. Many of those who died were people who came to the
        camp already weak and near death, but the crowded
        conditions probably helped spread disease. </p>
        <p>As the New York Times reported at the end of December
        1992, &quot;it has become clear that because so many of
        the hungry died before the foreign forces arrived,
        emergency food is perhaps a less critical issue than was
        originally outlined. Just as important now, say Western
        diplomats, aid workers and Somalis, is the need for
        political reconciliation, to allow Somalia some semblance
        of normality.&quot; The crucial question, then, was
        whether political reconciliation would be facilitated or
        hindered by the massive U.S. military presence. For
        reasons discussed above, it seems likely that their
        impact was negative. </p>
        <p>Bad U.S. motives don't automatically make
        interventions harmful. But they do require us to look
        very carefully before concluding that the probable impact
        of an intervention will be positive. </p>
    </blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <h3>World War II Again </h3>
        <p>Imagine the following letter: &quot;What's going on in
        Bosnia and Haiti is appalling. I often wonder why our
        government can't intervene to stop the killing. I know
        our government isn't pure--far from it--but nor was it
        pure during World War II and I supported its
        participation then against Hitler. It's certainly true
        that in that earlier war our government didn't get
        involved out of noble motives, but the clear consequence
        of its involvement was to defeat the Nazi killing
        machine. And that was good. Today our government's
        motives are still far from noble. But is that any reason
        for us not to demand that our government intervene when
        so many lives are at stake? The human tragedies in Bosnia
        and Haiti are so profound, that surely this is a time for
        intervention.&quot; </p>
        <p>The interesting thing about this hypothetical letter
        is that it was written by one Russian citizen to another,
        and the government the letter writer is calling on to
        carry out the intervention is the Russian government.
        Should we support the letter-writer's call for Russian
        intervention? </p>
        <p>If you are hesitant about Russian Marines landing in
        Haiti or Russian tanks rolling into Bosnia, we need to
        ask why? Is it because the Russians have been
        qualitatively more aggressive in their foreign policy
        than the United States? I doubt it, and in fact, the
        current Russian government can at least say that its
        predecessor regime is on record as apologizing for its
        invasion of Afghanistan, while the United States
        government has never done the same with respect to
        Vietnam. Is it because Russian foreign policy is
        significantly less under democratic control than that of
        the United States? Again that's dubious. The foreign
        policy of neither country is under very effective popular
        control: the U.S. people did not vote on the invasions of
        Panama or Grenada or the mining of Nicaragua's harbors;
        the punishments for wrong-doing during Iran-Contra were
        barely discernible; the correlation between foreign
        policy campaign promises and later practice is close to
        zero; and, as the Somalia episode reveals, the U.S.
        public seems able to ignore the killing of large numbers
        of Somalis by U.S. troops while getting upset by small
        numbers of U.S. casualties. </p>
        <p>Now it is true that Moscow has a particular interest
        in the Balkans, and that interest might well lead it to
        behave in ways contrary to the goals of peace, justice,
        and democracy. In Haiti, of course, the Russians have no
        similar historical connection that might lead them to
        support the wrong side, but nevertheless, it is hard to
        imagine their national security apparatus not using the
        opportunity of a humanitarian intervention for some very
        non-humanitarian purposes. So what about the United
        States and NATO? Do they have particular interests that
        would make their interventions unlikely to lead to
        coincidental good? </p>
        <p>In considering first the Bosnian case, let me first
        state my view of the basic facts of the situation without
        making an extended argument. </p>
        <p>Bosnia-Herzegovina was the one constituent republic of
        the former Yugoslavia committed to a multi-ethnic
        democracy. The Muslims, as the largest group in the
        country, were largely secular, and there was much
        intermarriage and tolerance. As Yugoslavia disintegrated
        under the weight of World Bank exactions and Serbian
        dictatorial domination, Bosnia declared its independence
        and was recognized by the international community as an
        independent state. The Serbian minority in Bosnia is, of
        course, entitled to self-determination, but this does not
        include the right to claim two-thirds of the country, nor
        to set up an ethnically pure state. Given the large
        number of mixed communities in Bosnia, any Bosnian Serb
        state would have had a large non-Serbian minority or that
        minority would have to have been expelled, as has been
        going on in conformity with doctrines of ethnic purity.
        The struggle in Bosnia has not been a civil war. The
        Yugoslav army, under the control of Serbia, began the
        attack on Bosnia (just as it had on Slovenia and Croatia
        earlier) and then it armed the Bosnian Serbs and provided
        paramilitary forces and logistical support to assist
        their depredations. </p>
        <p>For me, the crucial piece of evidence for evaluating
        the likely impact of a U.S. or NATO intervention in
        Bosnia is the history of the arms embargo. The Security
        Council, at Serbian urging, imposed an arms embargo on
        all of the former Yugoslavia. Since Serbia had inherited
        the Yugoslav armed forces, one of the largest in Europe,
        with all its heavy equipment, the embargo effectively
        denied to Bosnia, the victim of aggression and
        &quot;ethnic cleansing,&quot; the right to defend itself,
        a right guaranteed by the UN Charter. The General
        Assembly has twice voted to have the Security Council
        lift the embargo, but the Council has refused to do so.
        And it is the countries supporting the embargo--Britain
        and France--who are the NATO countries that some are
        expecting to intervene to protect Bosnia. </p>
        <p>Britain, France, and the United States are more
        concerned with ending the fighting than with defending
        Bosnia, defending a multi-ethnic democracy, or defending
        the principles that territory should not be seized by
        force and that ethnic cleansing cannot be allowed to
        stand. Stopping fighting is often a very noble goal. But
        it is not a goal supported by the Bosnians. If the
        Bosnians wanted simply to end the fighting they could do
        so easily: they could accept the tiny piece of their
        territory that Serbian leaders say they're willing to
        allow them. But the Bosnians have refused to surrender.
        They have held out against tremendous odds and they
        continue to do so. They believe they can still reverse
        the effects of aggression and ethnic cleansing. Lifting
        the arms embargo can contribute to that goal. Sending in
        NATO will not. NATO troops will try to freeze the status
        quo on the ground and force the Bosnians to accept the
        Owen-Stoltenberg plan or some other partition plan that
        ratifies ethnic cleansing. And as long as the
        undemocratic and Big Power-dominated Security Council
        runs the UN, the UN is no better in this regard than
        NATO. </p>
        <p>Countries that resist lifting the arms embargo are not
        going to send in troops to push back the Serbs. French
        soldiers who stood by while Bosnia's deputy prime
        minister was assassinated at a Serbian check-point in
        Bosnia right in front of their eyes, are not going to
        roll back aggression. </p>
        <p>The Clinton administration claims that it opposes the
        arms embargo, but it has refused to put any serious
        effort into lobbying for its lifting. But though
        Washington is less enamored of the embargo than London or
        Paris, there are other reasons why it would be futile to
        expect the United States to defend what we care about
        most. NATO air-strikes may stop Serb attacks, but the big
        powers, including the United States, will then press the
        Bosnians to accept an unjust partition. The same day that
        Clinton threatened Serb artillery surrounding Sarajevo,
        the White House announced that Washington would now press
        the Bosnians to be realistic and reasonable, which is to
        say, to surrender. Foreign intervention doesn't come
        without a price tag, and when the price involves giving
        up the very thing that the Bosnians are fighting for, the
        price is too high. </p>
        <p>At an earlier time, UN intervention might not have had
        these same bad consequences, for then freezing the
        fighting and defending Bosnia were the same. But now that
        the Serbs control 70 percent of Bosnia, freezing the
        lines would mean accepting the results of ethnic
        cleansing and aggression. </p>
        <p>There is another objection to U.S. air-strikes: they
        involve the danger of over-kill. As events in Somalia
        have shown, the Pentagon is so determined to avoid U.S.
        casualties that it is willing to engage in indiscriminate
        attacks against civilians. In Bosnia (as elsewhere) this
        will not lead to very productive results: it will
        strengthen the support for right-wing Serbian leaders and
        enflame ethnic passions. </p>
        <p>I make no pretensions to moral purity here. The
        Bosnians could not survive wholly on their own; the
        no-fly zones, the arms supplies that a lifted embargo
        would permit: these are necessary in addition to lifting
        the arms embargo. But our goal should be to allow the
        Bosnians to fight their own fight, and give outsiders
        with ulterior motives as little control over their
        struggle as possible. </p>
        <p>Now consider the case of Haiti. For decades the U.S.
        has supported the status quo in that impoverished country
        because it served the interests of those who control the
        key economic and political institutions in the United
        States. When Aristide was elected, the United States did
        what it could to undermine him and to funnel support to
        the Haitian military which was Washington's main prop for
        protecting the low-wage export platform that Haiti had
        become. So now while Washington calls for Aristide's
        return, its true colors are still showing: it has been
        trying to force all kinds of concessions on Aristide that
        will in fact preserve U.S. interests at the expense of
        Haitian democracy. If the United States were to send in
        Marines, it wouldn't be so that a popular democracy could
        take root, but so that some sort of civilian cover for a
        regime serving U.S. interests could be installed. As Don
        Bacheller nicely put it, the United States might return
        Aristide to office, but it won't return him to power.
        Note: I'm not just saying that the U.S. will oppose a
        truly socialist Haiti; it will oppose even that minimal
        level of democracy in Haiti that will come into conflict
        with U.S. interests--powerful unions, severe restrictions
        on the military, and so on. </p>
        <p>Some say that nothing else will work, we have to send
        in U.S. troops. But this is nonsense. Nothing else has
        been tried seriously. As U.S. officials have now
        admitted, the sanctions have been easily evaded through
        the Dominican Republic, with the full knowledge of
        Washington. And what could be more reassuring to the
        thugs in the Haitian military command than knowing that
        the president of the United States is pushing to work out
        a deal whereby they will be able to remain in power. I
        don't know what the Haitian people are capable of doing
        on their own, but the last country in the world I would
        want to invite in to restore democracy in Haiti is that
        most consistent opponent of Haitian democracy, the United
        States government. </p>
        <p>Moreover, having the U.S. intervene in Haiti (whether
        alone or at the head of some fig-leaf coalition) is
        problematic not just for Haitians, but for all those in
        the Third World who may later become victims of U.S.
        interventionism. Two years ago there was a great deal of
        discussion of the peace dividend and of closing down
        foreign military bases; today elements of the Left are
        drawing up missions for the Pentagon that will justify a
        bloated military budget and foreign bases for years to
        come. </p>
        <p>&nbsp;</p>
    </blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <h3>Precedent </h3>
        <p>Anyone who makes an argument from precedent cannot
        avoid moments of doubt. Am I sacrificing a very real
        specific victim on behalf of avoiding some more
        generalized harm? When police obtain a confession through
        torture, it is crucial that the confession not be allowed
        to stand if we are to prevent future police abuses.
        Nevertheless, it is unsettling to have to let a probable
        criminal go free to continue preying on society.
        Likewise, to avoid the bad precedent of letting the U.S.
        determine what's just and what's not and what ought to be
        smashed through intervention and what shouldn't, we may
        allow some real evil to go unchecked. And this is never a
        fully satisfying situation. But it is important to note
        that those who favor intervention tend to be no less
        adamant about the importance of precedent: if this
        wrong-doing is allowed to stand, other wrong-doers will
        take heart and act accordingly. That is, they too believe
        that precedent matters. So let's be sure that we factor
        into our analysis all the relevant precedents that
        intervention or non-intervention establishes. </p>
        <p>&nbsp;</p>
        <h3>Isolationism </h3>
        <p>In arguing for non-intervention, we often find
        ourselves aligned with isolationists, those who oppose
        foreign adventures not because of the harm the United
        States is likely to do, but because of the costs to the
        United States and because of a basic indifference to
        foreign suffering. Though I opposed the dispatch of U.S.
        troops to Somalia, it was disheartening to read one U.S.
        citizen's argument for withdrawal, as quoted in the New
        York Times: &quot;It's really very simple. If I have to
        choose between pictures of starving Somalian babies or
        dead American soldiers being dragged through the streets
        of Mogadishu, well, I don't want to see any more dead
        Americans. Sorry.&quot; </p>
        <p>It is awkward to be on the same side of the Somalia
        intervention question as this racist. But there are no
        fewer racists on the other side, those who would
        incinerate large numbers of Somali civilians in their
        effort to capture Muhammad Farah Aidid. We need to
        distinguish our views from those of both groups of
        racists, the isolationists and the interventionists. </p>
        <p>To some extent, the peace movement bears some
        responsibility for egocentric isolationism. Too often the
        anti-war movement resorted to the opportunist argument
        against intervention--that Americans would be coming home
        in body bags. We need to be much clearer and much more
        principled: it is because we are concerned for Somalis
        that we recommended (those of us who did) against
        intervention there. It was because of our support for
        Vietnam's struggle against U.S. imperialism that we
        opposed U.S. intervention there. </p>
        <p>When we hear Americans say &quot;don't send U.S.
        troops to Haiti, who cares about them,&quot; we need to
        reply: &quot;don't send U.S. troops to Haiti because we
        do care about the struggle of the Haitian people for
        justice and decent lives.&quot; And let us do what we can
        to help that struggle and its victims. Sure it's not easy
        to help the struggle; but U.S. Marines will definitely
        not help the struggle. When we hear others say,
        &quot;Let's keep out of that Balkan quagmire where
        American lives will be lost in behalf of one crazy
        fanatic or another,&quot; we have to respond, &quot;We
        support the Bosnian struggle for preserving a
        multi-ethnic state, and that's why we want NATO to stay
        out.&quot; And let us do what we can to help that
        struggle and its victims, including working to lift the
        arms embargo. And let us also express our solidarity with
        and do what we can to support peace forces in Serbia and
        Croatia. Opposing U.S. intervention is not giving up on
        internationalism. It is almost always the best way to be
        an internationalist. </p>
        <p>Bosnia and Haiti are not the only places where there
        is rampant killing going on. In fact, there are other
        places in the world--Sudan and Angola, for example--where
        the death toll is far larger. Moreover, it is important
        to keep in mind that human suffering occurs not only
        during times of massacre. The deeply unjust status quo
        that the United States defends--militarily, but in so
        many other ways as well--takes a horrendous human toll.
        Draconian austerity measures, minuscule aid grants, free
        trade agreements, conflating the free market with
        freedom: all these have led to and will continue to lead
        to immense suffering. Millions of infants die each year
        in the Third World not because of poverty, but because of
        inequality. Millions of people in the triumphant West
        live in literal slavery. Millions of women and girls are
        forced into sexual slavery. And in many countries, the
        profound misery erupts as ethnic conflict. Just as it
        reeks of hypocrisy for U.S. politicians to decry racial
        intolerance that their domestic cut-backs have
        engendered, so too there is a strong stench emanating
        from U.S. expressions of concern for massacre victims
        around the world--who, even when not the direct victims
        of U.S. trained or armed killers, are the indirect
        victims of the unjust global order. </p>
        <p>The priority for those concerned with human suffering
        is to overturn that unjust global order, an order
        defended by the United States and other rich nations.
        That is a long-term struggle. In the short-run, we must
        do whatever we can to make interventions on behalf of the
        status quo more difficult. This doesn't mean that there
        couldn't possibly be a situation where an intervention,
        particularly by the UN, might have broad international
        support and have positive consequences. But let us never
        lose sight of our over-all objective, which is to end
        imperialism. </p>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>

<hr>

